<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON PROPELS KNICKS PAS 76ERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Waiting for Allan Houton to find his feathery
stroke can often take days, sometimes weeks. But when it finally
arrives, when the Knicks' shooting guard squares up and forgets how
to miss, there are not many prettier things to behold from New
York's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   In his most complete game this season, Houston put on a
long-distance exhibition in the third quarter Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Dueling Allen Iverson shot for shot, Houston scored 15 of his
season-high 25 points on perimeter bombs, and the Knicks held off
the Philadelphia 76ers, 78-67, at the First Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   Recovering from their most lackadaisical performance of the
two-week-old season 24 hours earlier in Cleveland _ a blowout loss
_ the Knicks played as if they cared about getting back on defense
and about moving the basketball when it mattered most against the
76ers.
</P>
<P>
   They not only improved their record to 5-3, but they also
regained the cohesion that had characterized their four-game
winning streak before they fell apart against the Cavaliers.
Philadelphia had only 11 points in the first quarter and 27 in the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson scored 29 points on 11-of-20 shooting, racking up 16 of
them in a run-gun-and-have-fun third quarter. But he had little
left in the fourth quarter, and the Knicks executed well down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing finished with 11 points and eight rebounds. Larry
Johnson, playing on a painfully sore knee, added 12 points and
seven assists, and Kurt Thomas contributed 14 points and six
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, though, was the main reason the Knicks won. He came
into the game shooting 38 percent and had missed 14 of the 20
3-point attempts he had taken.
</P>
<P>
   Against the 76ers, he was 5 for 5 from behind the 3-point line
and 10 for 17 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   At one juncture in the third quarter, he spotted up from the top
of the arc three times in two minutes. Each time, the ball went
softly through the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful it will come,'' Houston said before the game when
asked about his shooting stroke. ``That's what I do, I shoot the
basketball. To me, there's no such thing as a slump. I'm going to
continue to shoot the ball and make plays for other guys. Mentally,
there is no such thing as a slump in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   With the fans on their feet after Iverson had cut the deficit to
66-59 with a short jump shot, the Knicks composed themselves for
one last run.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing scored the most significant basket, spinning past the
portly Matt Geiger and putting in an awkward left-handed layup to
quell the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Then Houston dropped in a baseline jump shot and Charlie Ward,
making good decisions all evening, found Ewing alone under the
basket on the break for two points that pushed the lead back up to
15.
</P>
</TEXT>
