A2486 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERRY-EXECUTION20-COX     02-20 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERRY-EXECUTION20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Berry execution completed
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUCASVILLE, Ohio _ Wilford Lee Berry Jr., strapped to a gurney
with tubes in his arms, stared at the ceiling as lethal drugs
flowed into his veins, then he took three labored breaths and died
at 9:31 p.m. Friday, said witnesses to Ohio's first execution in 35
years.
</P>
<P>
   Berry was ``gasping for breath, then he took a big sigh and quit
breathing,'' said a noticeably shaken Kristy Steeves, a reporter
with WJW-TV in Cleveland, one of five media witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``His eyes never closed. When I saw him gasping for air, that's
when it hit me: This man is dying in front of my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very peaceful death'' said Cleveland private
investigator William Florio, one of three witnesses selected by the
family of the man Berry murdered, Cleveland Baker Charles Mitroff
Jr., Jr. ``I just wish Mr. Mitroff (was able) to die the way
Wilford Berry died.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 9 p.m. Friday, the scheduled execution time,
Attorney General Betty Montgomery called Gov. Bob Taft to notify
him there were no further legal motions standing in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Taft, who on Thursday announced he would not grant clemency, had
an open phone line to the warden at the Southern Ohio Correctional
Institution in Lucasville and was to give approval for the
execution to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, 36, made no last statement before officials administered
a three-part lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known precisely when the injections started.
</P>
<P>
   Media witness Michael Hawthorne of The Cincinnati Enquirer said
Berry was already strapped to the gurney with IV's in his arm when
the media witnesses were escorted into the death house at 9:22 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeared Mr. Berry was chanting something or mumbling
something we couldn't hear what he was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   The lighting was low. Warden Stephen Huffman stood at Berry's
head, a guard at his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilford Berry started talking. The warden talked back to him
and actually patted him on the shoulder. I took that as he was
comforting him,'' Steeves said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Berry's fingernails appeared bitten to the quick.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne said at 9:25 p.m. Berry took three labored breaths and
9:30 p.m. he appeared to stop breathing. A white nylon curtain was
drawn. And when it was reopened a moment later, Huffman announced
that Berry was pronounced dead by a physician at 9:31 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, his mother sobbed,'' Hawthorne said.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, 36, had chosen lethal injection over the electric chair.
He was given intravenous doses of sodium pentathol to make him lose
consciousness, pancuronium bromide to paralyze his muscles and stop
his lungs, and potassium chloride to stop his heart. A curtain hid
the electric chair as Berry was put to death.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the prison, about 250 death penalty opponents and 50
supporters were gatherered. A period of silent prayer, started
around 8:30 p.m. for Berry, his family and his victim's family, was
marred by a small scuffle, quickly broken up by state troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents responded by singing hymns, including ``Amazing
Grace,'' and ``Swing Low, Sweet Chariot.''
</P>
<P>
   Some time later, when word came of Berry's death, supporters
cheered. ``Thank you, Wilford,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   Berry was the first man to be put to death in Ohio since Donald
Reinbolt was electrocuted in the old Ohio Penitentiary in Columbus
on March 15, 1963. Reinbolt, 29, was convicted of killing a
Columbus grocer on Aug. 26, 1961, for the $60 in his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Berry got the death sentence for killing Mitroff on Dec. 1,
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Mitroff, a Cleveland baker, had hired Berry as a night porter
only days earlier. Berry and accomplice Anthony Lozar were
burglarizing the bakery when Mitroff, 52, interrupted them. Lozar
shot Mitroff in the chest and Berry shot him in the head as he
begged for his life. The robbery netted $140.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, considered the principal offender, got a death sentence;
Lozar got life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's execution leaves 190 other men on death row in Ohio,
some of whom are close to exhausting their appeals. Officials say
it's possible, though unlikely, another execution could occur this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Berry spent the day quietly in a holding cell at the death
house, a small building at the Lucasville prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been very polite, calm,'' Warden Huffman said at a 7 p.m.
press conference. He said Berry's demeanor hadn't changed since he
arrived at the prison at 8:15 p.m. Thursday. ``He slept very well,
actually,'' on Thursday night, Huffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrews, spokesman for the Ohio Department of Rehabilitation
and Correction, said Berry visited on and off since 10 a.m. Friday
with Cynthia Yost, an assistant Ohio public defender, who was one
of three people Berry choose to witness the execution.
</P>
<P>
   He also visited through the holding cell bars from 4:55 p.m. to
6:10 p.m. Friday with his mother, Jennie Franklin, and sister,
Elaine Quigley, who also witnessed the death. ``It was a very good
meeting for both sides,'' Huffman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitroff family chose as witnesses Florio, who helped to
track Berry down, and northern Kentucky police officers Charles
``Stan'' Voorhees and Duane Rolfsen, who arrested him, a few days
after the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice was served'' said Voorhees, a retired Kenton County,
Ky., police officer. ``It was a long time coming but justice was
served.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitroff's brother-in-law, Richard Bowler said he was relieved
when Florio told him by phone that the execution was over, Florio
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basics of this is, this is the end of a 10-year funeral
for them,'' Vorhees said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews said Berry neither made nor received phone calls and had
no other visitors Friday. He didn't watch television or listen to
the radio, and he read nothing but the half dozen or so cards and
letters he got in the day's mail.
</P>
<P>
   He ordered a last meal of lasagna, garlic bread, cheesecake and
cola. ``He ate some of it,'' Andrews said. Berry also showered in
the morning and afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   There was a Bible in the holding area, but Berry didn't read it,
Andrews said. Berry did not want to be visited by the Rev. David
Chase of the Columbus Christian Center, who has been working with
him the past several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He appears to continue to be pretty stoic,'' Andrews said.
``He appears to be on a pretty even keel.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase has said Berry showed no remorse for killing Mitroff, but
has made his peace with God.
</P>
<P>
   Berry was nicknamed ``Volunteer'' because he steadfastly refused
to appeal his death sentence, saying he'd rather die than spend the
rest of his life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Ohio Public Defender's Office pursued the case
in the name of Berry's mother and sister, saying Berry was not
mentally competent to waive his appeals. He was physically and
sexually abused as a child, diagnosed a schizophrenic, and made the
first of several suicide attempts at age 9.
</P>
<P>
   Various courts, however, found him competent and attempts by the
public defender to raise the question again in light of a severe
prison beating Berry received in September 1997 were ultimately
unsuccessful. The U.S. 6th Circuit Court of Appeals noted that
Berry's competency was decided before the prison beating, at a time
when he was already waiving appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
