<HEADLINE>
DEVILS WIN FIGHT BUT LOSE A HOCKEY GAME TO RED WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The days leading up to the game had been filled with
talk of retribution and retaliation. While the Devils were ready
for the task, they were unable to contend with the Red Wings in the
more basic tasks of skating, passing and shooting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One game after scoring seven goals, the Devils struggled just to
get seven shots on goal for much of the night as the Red Wings
dominated them in a 3-1 victory at Joe Louis Arena Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minutes, the crowd chanted, ``Ozzie, Ozzie,'' for
Red Wings goaltender Chris Osgood. But until those final minutes,
Osgood was hardly challenged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings entered the game with a 2-14-1 record against
teams with winning records and needed this, their sixth straight
win, to make a point. For the Devils, who hardly appeared to fit
that description , the game showed the difference between a
six-goal margin of victory over the league's worst team, the Tampa
Bay Lightning, in their last game, and facing the two-time
defending Stanley Cup Champions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were badly outplayed, managing just 10 shots on goal
through the first two periods. They had only 11 shots with 15
minutes remaining in the game until a late flurry raised the total
to 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got off to a bit of a slow start,'' Randy McKay said.
``Definitely, our best period was the third. We tried to come at
them, but down two goals you're facing an uphill battle.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, the Devils faltered, falling behind by 2-0
after a blast by Igor Larionov. Bobby Holik answered with a goal
just 21 seconds later to make the score 2-1, but he was penalized
for elbowing 10 seconds later. The Red Wings made the Devils pay,
increasing their lead to 3-1 when Steve Yzerman, the Detroit
center, took the puck end-to-end and ripped a wrist shot past Chris
Terreri for his second goal of the game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings scored first when Yzerman skated in on Terreri and
fired a shot through the goalie's legs at 15 minutes 36 seconds of
the first period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scoring seemed almost secondary to that point as the Red Wings
focused on Krzysztof Oliwa.
</P>
<P>
   In the teams' last meeting, a 2-2 tie on Feb. 1, Oliwa became
the object of the Red Wings' ire after he was involved in a series
of questionable plays. He collided into the boards with Detroit's
Larry Murphy, and Murphy, who was knocked unconscious, suffered a
concussion. The Red Wings felt that Oliwa gave Murphy an extra,
unnecessary shot on the play. Later in the game, Oliwa broke Todd
Gill's forearm when he hit him with the butt end of his stick. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the days following the game, Barry Smith, Detroit's associate
coach, called Oliwa ``an idiot,'' and the Red Wings spoke of
retribution.The Red Wings made their attempt at payback seven
minutes into the game when Darren McCarty came off the bench and
blasted Oliwa. The two squared off briefly, but threw no punches
until the officials got between them and McCarty reached over and
landed one. They were assessed two-minute unsportsmanlike conduct
penalties, but when they got out of the penalty box, they
immediately resumed the fight, this time dropping their gloves. The
6-foot-1-inch McCarty, who, with injuries to Joe Kocur and Martin
Lapointe, inherited the role of enforcer, was beaten soundly by
Oliwa, but still drew a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play hard and tough, and the guys play hard and tough
against me,'' Oliwa said. ``I don't feel like I've done anything
wrong. I just finished my check. If I don't play hard, I won't be
in the lineup. &UR; '' &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
