<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-PITCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES MIGHT BE INTERESTED IN JIMMY KEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS) 
(mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Graeme Lloyd and Homer Bush, two-thirds of the
package sent to Toronto for Roger Clemens, were luxuries to manager
Joe Torre, specialists on a roster of stars. The Yankees will win
without them.
</P>
<P>
   But sometime before the July 31 trade deadline, the Yankees will
have to replace Bush and Lloyd _ maybe with someone like Jimmy Key,
the veteran left-hander who announced his retirement late last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, the five-time Cy Young Award winner, is expected to
arrive here Saturday, perhaps in time to join his new teammates for
a workout. He will wear No. 12 and house his equipment in a locker
between Jeff Nelson and Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just anxious to have him come here so we can sit and
talk,'' Torre said. ``He's been throwing, so he'll be ready to go
when he gets here.''
</P>
<P>
   The expectations for the Yankees, now that they have added
Clemens, seem to be even greater than last year, if that is
possible. ``We snuck up on some people last year,'' said George
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner. ``The team has to be
twice as good this year as it was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. The American League contains so many poor teams,
like Minnesota, Kansas City and Oakland, that it is hard to imagine
a scenario in which the Yankees _ with a pitching rotation of
Clemens, David Cone, Orlando Hernandez, Andy Pettitte and Irabu _
will not dominate during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Games against upper-echelon teams, however, like Cleveland and
Anaheim, are usually decided in one play, one particular at-bat.
The Yankees were vulnerable in the American League Championship
Series against Cleveland until the moment Hernandez struck out Jim
Thome with the bases loaded in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   That is where specialists like Lloyd and Bush can turn a game,
and why the Yankees must replace them. Lloyd's role was to face one
or two left-handed batters in the middle innings, with his
three-quarter delivery and sweeping breaking ball; the slugger Ken
Griffey Jr. had just one hit in nine career at-bats (.111) against
Lloyd, Rafael Palmeiro only three hits in 19 at-bats (.158). If an
opposing left-handed batter came up in a crucial situation in the
sixth inning, and again in the eighth, Torre could use Lloyd early
and Mike Stanton, his other left-handed reliever, in the late
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Now Stanton is Torre's only experienced left-handed reliever,
and there are no other left-handed bullpen candidates in camp.
Torre actually has right-handed relievers who are more effective
against left-handed batters, in Darren Holmes and Dan Naulty.
Left-handers batted .245 against Holmes, right-handers .294;
left-handers have batted just .216 against Naulty during his
injury-plagued career with the Twins, right-handers .289.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees will want another left-handed reliever for
October, assuming they make the playoffs. Anaheim is stacked with
left-handed batters, in Darin Erstad, Mo Vaughn, Jim Edmonds and
Garret Anderson; Cleveland has first baseman Thome and second
baseman Roberto Alomar (a switch-hitter who is much better against
right-handed pitchers), and Texas has Palmeiro and Rusty Greer.
</P>
<P>
   There are few effective left-handed relievers available. The
Yankees could pursue Mike Myers of the Milwaukee Brewers. If the
Blue Jays fall out of the race, the Yankees could reacquire Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   An intriguing name bandied about by Yankee pitchers Friday was
that of Key, a former Yankee who others say was approached by club
officials during the off- season. Key pitched for the Orioles last
season. General manager Brian Cashman would not comment on the
Yankees' interest in Key, who held left-handers to a .237 batting
average over the last five seasons. The questions with Key are
whether he is healthy, whether he can warm up quickly enough to
work out of the bullpen, and whether he would be willing to be a
specialist for minimal pay (the Yankees' payroll may approach $90
million).
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always looking for ways to improve yourself,'' Cashman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a backup infielder, was employed as a pinch-runner in the
late innings, stepping in for the likes of Darryl Strawberry and
Chili Davis if the Yankees were behind by a run or tied and Torre
wanted to force the issue. Bush had just 71 at-bats, but he was
extremely effective as a runner, disrupting pitchers, taking the
extra base and putting pressure on the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's departure means the Yankees could carry an extra
outfielder _ perhaps Shane Spencer as well as Ricky Ledee, or maybe
Mike Figga, the reserve catcher who is out of options. Cashman said
there is a chance Torre could carry three catchers. ``We've got
some things to think about,'' Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees also must identify another middle infielder in their
organization who would be promoted in the case of an injury. Luis
Sojo is the Yankees' utility infielder, and he can play first,
second, third or short. But if the Yankees were to lose two
starting infielders to injury for a day or a week or months, they
might have to call up Alfonso Soriano, the Yankees' top prospect
and best minor league infielder in camp. Soriano, 20, played in
Japan last year, but he has only two months' worth of professional
experience in the United States. He is expected to open the year at
shortstop for Norwich, the Yankees' Class AA affiliate.
</P>
</TEXT>
