<HEADER>
A2496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS-     02-20 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORING FIRST AND OFTEN, RANGERS BURY PENGUINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yes, the Rangers were hurting, with three important
regulars injured and out of the lineup. Sure, they were tired,
playing their fifth game in eight nights. Of course they were
slumping, having lost 10 of their previous 14 games and eight of
their previous nine at home. And their guests Friday night at
Madison Square Garden were the Pittsburgh Penguins, one of the
National Hockey League's hottest teams.
</P>
<P>
   So how bad was the result? Terrible _ for the Penguins. The
Rangers scored four goals on their first 10 shots against goalie
Tom Barrasso and cruised to a 6-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The result moved the Rangers (22-27-7) from 12th place to 11th
in the Eastern Conference and left them only 4 points behind the
eighth-place Florida Panthers, who hold the last playoff berth in
the bracket. With 26 games left in their regular season, the
Rangers are within range of post-season play.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins (30-17-7) had won 10 consecutive games until they
were defeated by the Islanders, 3-1, on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The game was a homecoming for Aleksei Kovalev, the former Ranger
who was traded to the Penguins early this season in the deal that
brought Petr Nedved to the Rangers. Although Kovalev had his
entertaining moments, he finished with a minus-3 in the plus-minus
ratio. The more productive player was Nedved, who scored a
short-handed goal and added an assist. Another former Penguin,
Kevin Stevens, scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   Another star was Dan Cloutier, the 22-year-old goalie, who
stopped 32 of 33 shots but lost his shutout with 5 minutes 34
seconds remaining on a goal by Kevin Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   It was Cloutier's fourth appearance in four games this week. Two
of them were starts, and he won both. ``Obviously, I've been
feeling pretty good lately,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible he will start at least one of the two games the
Rangers play in Alberta, at Edmonton on Sunday and at Calgary on
Monday. Coach John Muckler refused to say if Cloutier would start
the next game, adding that he would decide between Cloutier and
Mike Richter, the first-stringer, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Brennan, Adam Graves and Ulf Samuelsson scored the other
goals for the Rangers, who scored three times in the second period
and eventually led by 6-0. John MacLean and Marc Savard each had
three assists.
</P>
<P>
   Samuelsson's goal was the last of the game, right after he burst
from the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had fresh legs,'' Samuelsson said. ``The guys around me were
dying, so I looked like I was flying.''
</P>
<P>
   MacLean, who missed most of the previous game with a nerve
injury in his neck, finished at plus-4 and put four shots on goal.
``It's kind of fun to be involved,'' MacLean said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens scored once at even strength and once on the power play
and has 14 goals for the season. In the final seconds, he prevented
a goal by knocking over the Rangers' net from behind when Cloutier
was facing a barrage of Pittsburgh shots. This caused a whistle to
stop play and the Penguins to argue about the sportsmanship of it
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I might as well push the net over and see what
happens,' '' Stevens said, adding that he expected Pittsburgh to be
awarded a penalty shot.
</P>
<P>
   Muckler had praise for most of his players, particularly the
five-man unit that skated against Jaromir Jagr's line. Jagr,
leading the league in points, is a top candidate for the Hart
Trophy as the league's most valuable player. ``Jagr is the best
player in the league right now,'' Muckler said. ``He's not an easy
man to play against.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ranger unit played what Muckler calls a ``shallow
forecheck,'' which looks like the neutral-zone trap. Muckler
praised his unit for ``clogging up the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Savard led frequent forechecking forays with his linemates,
Stevens and MacLean. By forcing a turnover from Darius Kasparaitis,
Savard set up Brennan's goal to give the Rangers a 1-0 lead at
11:27 of the first period. ``We talked about putting pressure on
their defense,'' Savard said. ``We jumped on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the game over all, Savard said: ``We were smiling on the
bench, and we were kind of pumped. We want to get something going
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Muckler called it ``our best game at home in a long time; a
super effort from the time they dropped the puck till the end of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to recent criticism of Nedved _ from the coaching
staff, fans and members of the news media _ Muckler said: ``Petr is
aware of the criticism. In some cases, it's fair. The last two
games, he has worked very hard. He did a great job.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers played without Todd Harvey, their aggressive right
wing, who was scratched after warm-ups because the fractured bone
in his right thumb prevented him from shooting. Harvey, who
returned from a knee injury on Feb. 12 and injured his thumb that
night, has been playing, often well. He also pulled a hamstring on
Wednesday night during a 6-3 loss to the Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Beukeboom, the big defenseman, will miss at least two more
weeks with the aftereffects of his second concussion of the season.
Beukeboom missed his fourth consecutive game Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also played without Peter Popovic, another big
defenseman, who missed his third consecutive game because of blood
in his right eye, a result of a puck hitting it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
