<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BLACKHAWKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO'S HAT TRICK LEADS STARS' VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ So much for Mike Modano's tired legs.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' leading scorer bounced back from his worst game of
the season last night with one of his best, scoring three goals and
leading the Stars to a 5-1 thrashing of the Chicago Blackhawks at
Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not surprising,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``He
has a lot of pride as a player. It just shows how far Mike Modano
has come.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Modano's second hat trick of the season and the sixth of
his career. More importantly, it was a sign that Wednesday's
stumble against the Florida Panthers was more of a hiccup than a
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a player who plays that well for that long, we
take that for granted sometimes,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano scored twice in the second period and once in the third
to help the Stars stretch a 1-0 first-period lead provided by Brett
Hull's power-play goal. It was the kind of killer instinct
Hitchcock said the Stars have been lacking in previous games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a game in which, as a team, we went out and extended a
lead,'' he said. ``That was important.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory moves the Stars' NHL-best record to 35-10-8, good
for 78 points _ 10 points ahead of the Phoenix Coyotes in the
Western Conference. It also was the fifth consecutive victory for
the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in a stretch like this, you just want to keep
playing,'' Hitchcock said. ``This is just like it was earlier in
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are 8-1-1 in their past 10 games, a similar run to the
15-game unbeaten streak the team experienced earlier in the season.
Last night, they buried a Blackhawks team that is last in the
Western Conference at 16-34-8.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's power-play goal was a blast from the left circle off a
cross-ice pass from Sergei Zubov, giving the Stars an early lead.
Joe Nieuwendyk set up the power-play opportunity when he drew a
tripping call from Ed Olczyk.
</P>
<P>
   Modano then put the game away in the second period, sandwiching
a power-play wrister and an even-strength slap shot around Brent
Severyn's first goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   While Modano would push his goal total to 20 on the season and
Hull would pick up his team-leading 24th, the loudest cheer was
reserved for Severyn. The tough guy, who typically has to fight to
get into the lineup, blasted in a rebound for his first goal as a
Stars player.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the game was out of reach. The Stars were beating the
Blackhawks to loose pucks, keeping them away from goalie Ed Belfour
(who pushed his record to 25-9-6 and lowered the Stars'
league-leading goals-against average to 1.98) and delivered the
kind of performance Hitchcock has been seeking.
</P>
<P>
   All four lines played well, with the Nieuwendyk line providing
energy, the Modano line providing scoring and lines led by Tony
Hrkac and Dave Reid providing consistent pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, nobody looked tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a team with controlled emotions and it takes us a little
time to get revved up,'' Hitchcock said of the Stars' current
string of playing every other night. ``That's why I feel confident
in the playoffs we'll be a good team, because you're playing every
other night then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
