<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSTY WALLACE RETHINKS PIT DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKINGHAM, N.C. _ NASCAR Winston Cup star Rusty Wallace says
that if he had it to do over, he would do it over and pit for four
tires and fuel in the waning stages of the season-opening Daytona
500.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had new tires ... I could have made more aggressive
moves,'' Wallace said as rain washed out the first round of
qualifying for tomorrow's Dura-Lube/Kmart 400 at the North Carolina
Speedway. ``And the fuel in the back \Rof his Ford Taurus\S would
have kept the car running lower. So, if you're asking me would I
change my strategy again now looking back, yeah _ I would have
pitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at that particular point it wasn't even a consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and crew chief Robin Pemberton have been second-guessed
since Sunday for their decision to retain track position when the
race's fourth and final caution flew on lap 174 at the 2.5-mile
Daytona International Speedway. Wallace and Penske-Kranefuss
teammate Jeremy Mayfield eschewed pit stops while running first and
third, respectively. Jeff Gordon and Dale Earnhardt _ who finished
first and second _ led a group of drivers who opted for four fresh
tires and fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who led a race-high 104 laps, eventually was shuffled
out of the draft after the restart on lap 179 and finished eighth.
Mayfield cut a tire on lap 192 and finished 20th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daytona is behind us. It's over with,'' said Mayfield, who led
both practices yesterday on the 1.017-mile oval and posted the top
hot lap at 156.965 mph. ``All we can say is we shoulda, woulda or
coulda.''
CUP SCHEDULE REVISED
</P>
<P>
   Cup teams were scheduled to run two laps yesterday to determine
the top 25 starters for tomorrow's race. But rain washed out the
session in mid-afternoon, and NASCAR has rescheduled qualifying for
all 43 positions today. Teams are scheduled for a 45-minute
practice this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Single-lap qualifying is booked for 9:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   If that session is rained out, the order will be set by
car-owner points from last season for the first 30 spots. The
remainder of the 43-car field will be filled by postmark on the
official entry blank.
</P>
<P>
   The final 1998 owner points were led by Rick Hendrick (5,328)
and Jack Roush (4,964). That means if Cup qualifying is rained out
today, reigning series champion Gordon will claim the pole (for the
second consecutive race) and Mark Martin will start No. 2.
BUSCH LINEUP SET
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR had hoped to squeeze in qualifying for today's Alltell
200 Busch Grand National Series race late yesterday, but the rain
persisted and forced officials to set the lineup by car-owner
points from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Reigning BGN series champion Dale Earnhardt Jr. will start from
the pole and be joined in the front row by 1998 points runner-up
and defending race champion Matt Kenseth. The first 33 positions
were filled via owner's points. The 34th spot was awarded to Cup
regular Johnny Benson on a past BGN champion's provisional, with
positions 35-43 determined via entry postmark. Texan Bobby Hillin
Jr. will start 27th based upon points.
</P>
<P>
   The list of 14 drivers who missed the race was topped by rookie
Adam Petty, who finished sixth in the season-opening NAPA Auto
Parts 300 at Daytona. But his new team, owned by father Kyle, has
no car-owner points to fall back on.
JARRETT BACKS IRWIN
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett says teammate Kenny Irwin Jr.'s third-place finish
in the Daytona 500 has been overshadowed by the 12-car pileup Irwin
inadvertently touched off on lap 135.
</P>
<P>
   And Jarrett, whose car actually triggered the crash in Turn 3
after it was nudged by Irwin from behind, said that is not right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing about the whole situation is Kenny is not
getting to enjoy his best run as a Winston Cup driver,'' said
Jarrett, who is Irwin's stablemate at Robert Yates Racing. ``He did
a tremendous job and put himself in a position to win the Daytona
500, and people aren't letting him enjoy that. He's having to
answer questions about whether or not he hit his teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did touch. Yes, that did happen. But it was racing and it's
as much as my fault as anybody's. I put myself in a position for
something like that to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
