<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELE, HELLING NOT RANGERS' STAFF ANCHORS ... YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Rangers' failure to land Roger
Clemens or Randy Johnson has them still searching for that elusive
No. 1 starter.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Kevin Appier ends up being the answer, the burden will
fall on Rick Helling or Aaron Sele. That might not be a bad
alternative, especially because it doesn't involve the completely
insane idea of trading away outfielder Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Helling and Sele aren't considered true No. 1 starters on
anybody's list, but consider their credentials from last season.
</P>
<P>
   Helling won 20 games, which is usually a prerequisite for being
a No. 1 starter. He was also 5-0 with a 2.76 earned-run average in
September at the height of the pennant race, including a huge
victory at Anaheim in the final week.
</P>
<P>
   Sele won 19 games and was selected to the American League
All-Star team. He also was superb in the pennant race, going 3-1
with a 2.40 ERA in September.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important was a Sunday afternoon in May against the
Cleveland Indians. The Rangers had lost two consecutive at Jacobs
Field before Sele took the mound and held the Indians scoreless
through eight innings in a 1-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, at least, he showed the grit of a No. 1 starter.
</P>
<P>
   But one game or one All-Star selection _ as Roger Pavlik proved
_ does not put a pitcher in the same league with Clemens or
Johnson. If Helling and Sele were, then the Rangers wouldn't have
had to trade for Todd Stottlemyre midway through last season.
</P>
<P>
   It does, however, give the Rangers reason to hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing a Clemens does or a Johnson is he gives you a
track record,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``Helling and
Sele don't have the track record, but who's to say they won't win
39 games again this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were a betting man, who would you say would win more
games this year, Clemens or Helling? Obviously you'd say Clemens
because he's done it so many more times. But who knows? Ten years
from now, Rick Helling may be looked at as a No. 1 starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling and Sele had considerable help last season. The Rangers
scored 6.7 runs per nine innings when Sele pitched and 6.1 for
Helling, the fourth- and fifth-best run support for any American
League pitcher. That kind of offense played a big part in those 39
victories, and No. 1 starters must have better than the 4.41 ERA
that Helling finished with or Sele's 4.23 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to be considered up there with guys like
Clemens and Johnson,'' Helling said. ``I've had just one year in
the big leagues as a consistent starter. I'd have to do what I did
last year for four or five years to be considered that caliber.''
</P>
<P>
   A pitcher still has to start somewhere, and last season was
Helling's first full season as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux was 6-14 with a 5.61 ERA in his first full season,
and Johnson was 7-13 with a 4.82 ERA. Tom Glavine went 7-17 with a
4.56 ERA for the Braves in 1988. Curt Schilling was a middle
reliever his first two seasons in the big leagues, and the Rangers
know better than anybody it took Kevin Brown several seasons before
emerging as the big-time ace he's considered today.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of No. 1 starters are Cy Young-type of candidates, and
you just don't think about Helling and Sele like that at this stage
of their careers,'' Melvin said. ``But I think that through
consistency, they're young enough to where they could establish
themselves like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
