r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NISSAN-LADN     02-20 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LATER THE BETTER FOR ESTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just when it started getting crowded atop the
Nissan Open leaderboard, Bob Estes passed the pack.
</P>
<P>
   A first-round co-leader with David Duval at 5-under-par 66,
afternoon starter Estes was toiling on the course Friday as first
Ernie Els (66), then qualifier Alan Bratton (67), Rick Fehr (66)
and Davis Love III (65) moved to the front of the field at 8-under
134.
</P>
<P>
   Estes zipped past all of them with two birdies on his final six
holes to finish with a 66 at the par-71, 6,953-yard Riviera Country
Club. His midway total of 133 left the former University of Texas
star clear of the field but hardly in command of his hot-shooting
pursuers, who included 41 second-round scores in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing I've got a short game,'' said Estes, who
scrambled to save par four times after missing greens. ``But that's
what I do best.''
</P>
<P>
   He called his five-birdie round of 67 more solid than stellar,
especially after he recorded seven birdies in the opening round.
But workmanlike is the name of the game for Estes these days as he
tries to upgrade his wood play to the level of his greenside
brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   His second straight blue-collar effort left Estes leading many
of the world's most notable golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Defending Nissan champ Billy Mayfair, the 1995 Tour Championship
winner, was tied with Kirk Triplett and Greg Chalmers at 136. Tiger
Woods and Duval _ ranked No. 1 and No. 2 in the world _ were in an
11-way tie at 137. Two-time PGA champion Nick Price was deadlocked
with seven others at 138. And past major winners Steve Jones, Mark
Brooks, Fred Couples and Bob Tway were at 139, part of a 12-man tie
that included former Cal State Northridge star Bob Burns.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors' 1990 NCAA Division II champion joined that select
company with a flourish, knocking his tee shot into the cup for a
hole-in-one on the 155-yard 16th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see it,'' said the 1998 Nike Tour champion and money
leader. ``(The crowd) gave a roar and a sign that it went in. I hit
a six-iron into the wind. It's really about the only thing that
went in today. I didn't have a lot of luck on the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns' luckless play on the greens concluded with a double-bogey
on No. 18, but he made the cut by three strokes and will have a
favorable early tee time today (8:37 a.m.) to punctuate a happy
homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, who grew up barely 20 miles from Rivera, is playing in
his first Nissan since losing his PGA Tour card at the end of the
1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton is another who can appreciate playing in the big time.
The 1994 college Player of the Year at Oklahoma State, he has
labored four years in golf's minor leagues, playing on mini-tours
and failing PGA Tour qualifying school three times before finally
passing in November.
</P>
<P>
   But Bratton isn't exempt for every event, and he puts in his
share of playing in qualifying tournaments, as he did Tuesday at
Los Serranos North, where he shot 6-under par 66 then won a playoff
in gathering darkness for the final Nissan berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I always wanted to do,'' Bratton said after
rolling in five more birdies Friday. ``I felt like I could play
with the guys out here. I was going to keep trying until I made
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Els, the 29-year-old South African who has already won two U.S.
Opens, continued his solid play in his first PGA Tour event of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to playing the weekend,'' he said after
rolling in seven birdies. ``It's always nice to play well at
Riviera.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Fabel, looking for his first victory in his 15th year on
tour, got into position at 137 with a 7-under-par 64 that was the
best round of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove the ball well today and that's the key to this
course,''he said. ``The fairways are so good you can do what you
want to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval and Woods, the marquee names in a tournament filled with
exceptional talent, remained in contention to make weekend pushes
that have become expected. Woods included three birdies in a
bogeyless round of 68, while Duval shot 71.
</P>
<P>
   Estes, for sure, was aware of their presence, as well as the
potential for many others to close fast in a field spiced by the
proximity to next week's World Match Play Championships at La
Costa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be leading after 36 holes, but even leading after 54
holes is not that much,'' he said. ``We all remember what Duval did
at the Hope (a final-round 59 to win from seven strokes off the
pace).''
</P>
<P>
   Woods demonstrated similar late fire last week with a
third-round 62 that brought him from back in the pack to win the
Buick Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Estes didn't think a 59 was probable at Riviera but said, ``I
think a 62 or 63 is reasonable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
