<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN ACTS RODMAN-LIKE ON TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Dennis Rodman spent 30 minutes on national
television Friday but offered more insight into his sex life than
into his career intentions, or the status of his negotiations with
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, wife Carmen Electra sometimes calls him
``Daddy,'' and Rodman enjoys having sexual relations with her very
much. As for playing for the Lakers, it's still anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview on ESPN, Rodman said he's ``nowhere near close
to signing with the Lakers,'' yet called the opportunity ``a match
made in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing black sunglasses, a floppy, blue-and-green floral tam
and piercings in his ears, both nostrils and his lower lip, Rodman
said he would make an announcement Monday morning. He has called a
press conference for Monday in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson, for one, is sick of waiting. In a break from the
team's party line, Johnson ripped Rodman and said the Lakers should
cease attempts to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of this. I am,'' Johnson, a Lakers vice president
and part owner, said on Thursday's David Letterman show. ``It's
like a circus now. We are a first-class organization. We do things
the right way, and right now, he's like trying to hold us hostage.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``He's driving me crazy because he's hurting the team, he's
hurting the organization, so I would love us just to say forget
it.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove Johnson's point, Rodman spent Friday's interview
ducking questions about his intentions, said he's still interested
in signing with the Miami Heat as well and contradicted himself
several times. He said the decision wasn't about money, then railed
against the NBA's new labor agreement, which limits the Lakers to
paying him just $12,195 per game _ millions less than he's earned
the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't about Dennis Rodman trying to be greedy, its not
about that,'' he said. ``They've put me in a bind where I can't do
anything but make the minimum. . . . I'm the most popular and most
recognized individual aside from Michael Jordan in the world today,
and I can't get but (the minimum). I think that's unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, who has advocated signing the Worm, had no
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't have retired then. He should have forced a trade
(from the Bulls, who held his rights),'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers owner Jerry Buss personally invited Rodman to join the
Lakers about three weeks ago. Reports of Rodman joining the Lakers
began a week ago and Rodman himself was quoted Thursday saying he
would sign a deal by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's targeting Monday morning for a decision, saying he
needs the weekend to ``put my mind at ease and at peace.''
</P>
<P>
   He also is aiming for more money, despite the Lakers'
constraints, and appeared to be lobbying the NBA for a special
salary-cap exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came to Michael Jordan, the league literally stood in
line . . . and everybody just kissed his (rear),'' Rodman said. ``.
. . So I should stick my (rear) out there and somebody can kiss my
(rear) now and say, `Great, Dennis, thanks for giving us all this
enjoyment.'. . . They should make an exception for Dennis Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   He did offer praise for Buss, calling him ``a cool son of a
(gun). He is one of the coolest owners in the business today. . . .
He's proven time and time again that he's taken care of his players
and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman said Buss regrets not being able to pay him his market
value and according to Rodman, went so far as to say, ``If I was
you as a businessman, I would say don't play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
