<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2530 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     02-20 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF NOWHERE BUT GOING PLACES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Where did HE come from?
</P>
<P>
   When the morning's upstart co-leader is a pleasant, fresh-faced
young Texan named Alan Bratton, there is no short answer to that
question.
</P>
<P>
   He came from the Lone Star Tour.
</P>
<P>
   He came from the Nike Tour.
</P>
<P>
   He came from Singapore, Malasia, Indonesia, India, Japan, South
Korea, Thailand and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   After one winless but lucrative spin through the Asian Tour not
long ago, Bratton flew home with earnings of $17,000. That was the
good news.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news was that the Asian Tour paid its players in cash.
So Bratton got on the plane with 1,700 $100 bills strapped to his
nervous stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet I took it out and counted it 20 times,'' he said. ``It's
amazing I didn't get robbed.''
</P>
<P>
   The indignities pile up when you're a one-time College Player of
the Year who scratched and scrambled and swam professional golf's
backwaters before passing the PGA Tour qualifying school on the
fourth try.
</P>
<P>
   __ The announcer on the first tee at Riviera Country Club, home
of the Nissan Open this week, butchers your name as ``Brayton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've mispronounced it every week,'' said Bratton, who is
playing the fourth tournament of his rookie season. ``Last week I
think I was `Branton.' ''
</P>
<P>
   __ Your fellow members in the exclusive PGA Tour fraternity
wonder aloud who you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a `Hey you!' guy,'' said veteran Brad Fabel, who has
never met the 27-year-old. ``Does he have his (Tour) card?''
</P>
<P>
   __ And dismissive talk like that is your !ital!reward for
gritting your teeth for four rough years while amateur
contemporaries like Tiger Woods, David Duval, Justin Leonard and
Phil Mickelson made headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played against all those guys in college (Oklahoma State) _
and successfully,'' said Bratton's wife Gretchen, an eighth-grade
teacher in Fort Worth, Texas, who is using a week off to follow him
at Riviera. ``It's been kind of a hard rock to swallow for him to
not be out here.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's top college golfer in 1994, Bratton has won nothing
bigger than a couple of mini-tour events since then.
</P>
<P>
   He finished 19th in the PGA Tour qualifying tournament at La
Quinta in November, making him one of 35 to receive Tour cards.
</P>
<P>
   But after missing the cut in Hawaii, tying for 25th at Pebble
Beach and tying for 60th at Torrey Pines, he came to Riviera
without a guaranteed spot in the 144-man field. He had to beat a
16-year-old in a playoff in the near-dark in the Nissan qualifying
event in Chino Hills on Tuesday to secure the last entry.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back-to-back 67s at par-71 Riviera, good for a
second-place tie with two major-event winners, indicates he belongs
in the big leagues. Even if he's almost invisible in the
early-season Tour statistics, ranking 123rd overall, between
who-theys Mike Brisky and Barry Cheesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played well in college against these (PGA) guys,'' said
Bratton, son of a Texas A&AMP;M professor. ``I wasn't intimidated by
them.''
</P>
<P>
   So why did he fall behind the twentysomething Tour hotshots the
past few years?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew,'' he said good-naturedly, ``I guess I would've won
a major too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably lucky,'' he added quickly. ``If I had gotten my
card right away, I probably wouldn't have been as prepared as I am
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the Asian Tour meant packing his own American food,
28-hour plane trips and long bumper-to-bumper bus rides.
</P>
<P>
   Not that this week is a lot different in the traffic department,
since he and Gretchen are staying with his college roommate in
Orange County, forcing Bratton to get up at 5:30 a.m. to be sure of
making an 8:30 tee time.
</P>
<P>
   He began the breezy day in a five-way tie for third, a stroke
off the pace. Then, with the help of former Riviera caddy Jose
Luis, he sank birdie putts on four of the first six holes to put
``BRATTON'' at the top of the leader boards.
</P>
<P>
   Early-arriving fans followed the lanky player in the fresh
haircut and Gap clothing even though his first name remained a
mystery to most.
</P>
<P>
   At the eighth green, a woman groaned in disappointment when
Bratton's wedge shot landed 15 feet below the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Family? somebody asked her.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's just fun to see how well he's done,'' she said. ``I
really don't know who he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 0122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
