<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2531 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-NORTH-TEXAS-BOISE     02-20 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NORTH-TEXAS-BOISE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH TEXAS CLINCHES DIVISION TITLE ON DAY COACH'S FATHER DIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho _ North Texas pulled off the biggest victory of
coach Tina Slinker's career _ on maybe the worst day of her life.
UNT clinched the Big West Conference Eastern Division title with a
56-50 victory against defending champion Boise State. Slinker's
father had died earlier in the day; he had suffered a massive heart
attack in New Mexico earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not anything we could have done better for her,'' said
senior guard Teri Gunnels, who scored 10 points. ``When something
like that happens, you can't put it behind you. There was a lot of
emotion, and we just tried to turn the negative into a positive. ''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles (17-6, 9-2 in conference) overcame a sluggish start
and early rebounding dominance by the Broncos (13-11, 7-5) to win
their seventh consecutive game. UNT shot just 25 percent from the
field in the first half, but still took a four-point lead into the
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a pretty good spot,'' said junior Empress Drane,
who scored nine points _ including five in a row during a stretch
late in the game _ and grabbed eight rebounds. ``We weren't
shooting the ball, but we were still up. We just had to be patient
and put that behind us. That shows the character of our team that
we were able to pick it up in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   UNT had to pick it up without freshman Jalie Mitchell, who
scored 13 points but had to sit for an extended stretch in the
second half with four fouls. In her absence, Drane's five-point
sequence and a 3-pointer by Nicole Thomas helped UNT finally break
away.
</P>
<P>
   Boise State's biggest weapon was Crista Peterson, who came off
the bench to score a game-high 17 points. However, no other Broncos
player scored in double figures as UNT held Boise to 29 percent
shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Slinker won't be with the team for tomorrow's game at Idaho, but
she said she felt obligated last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where he would have wanted me to be,'' Slinker said.
``And this team did the best thing they could have done for me
personally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
