r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-PISTONS-AZR &LR;      02-20 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-PISTONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS GO UP IN SMOKE  
 FIRE MISSING IN SLOW-STARTING LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It was enough to make the NBA lockout look like the
good old days.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns and the Detroit Pistons played a version of basketball
Friday night that belonged back under lock and key.
</P>
<P>
   There were missed shots, errant passes and inconsistency at
almost every stage of Detroit's 101-93 victory. It's a problem
throughout the league, everybody in the NBA keeps saying.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is.
</P>
<P>
   But at America West Arena, it was definitely a problem for the
Suns, who managed to do almost everything other than issue a
drop-dead date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got outhustled, it's that simple,'' Suns Coach Danny Ainge
said after his club fell to 2-3 at home.
</P>
<P>
   Boil the game down to its first 15 minutes, and, yes, it was
simple in stark terms. The Pistons hit their first six attempts
from the floor and grabbed a 17-point lead before most of a late
arriving, capacity crowd of 19,023 settled into its seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest factor is the way they came out,'' Ainge said of
the Pistons, who snapped a five-game skid. ``They came out with
more urgency, more toughness, more energy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's anybody's guess as to why the Pistons seemed to have more
energy at tip-off. They arrived in the Valley in an apparent
decline. They lost their third game in three nights to Miami on
Wednesday night. But the loss came at home.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Suns won their third in three nights over San
Antonio. On the road.
</P>
<P>
   All the usual, tried and true signs pointed to two teams headed
in opposite directions. But nothing about post-lockout basketball
is usual, much less tried and true.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, not even Ainge, can get a fair reading on what his team
or any other will do next. Through nine games, it's been tough to
recognize the Suns from quarter to quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it looked as though the Pistons had delivered an early
knockout blow, Team Schizo suddenly revealed another side.
</P>
<P>
   Within 3:13, the Suns outscored the Pistons, 17-0, late in the
first half. They wiped out a 14-point deficit and led by three
during an explosive run that included two three-point goals by
Clifford Robinson, two by George McCloud, one by Jason Kidd and a
beautiful sequence that ended with a twisting, left-handed layup by
Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   A restless crowd was suddenly inflamed. But, as it turned out,
there was more smoke than fire.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns trailed by as many as four and never fewer than three
until midway in the fourth quarter, when the Pistons went on a 10-2
run that was capped by a slam from Bison Dele, an ex-University of
Arizona center formerly named Brian Williams.
</P>
<P>
   It was over. Detroit's bull market trampled the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you can spell harmony, you have to spell harm,'' Dele
said as he talked about a renewed sense of camaraderie in the
Detroit dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   Before you can understand that bit of Bison, you probably need
tea leaves. Nevertheless, the Suns understand harm after losing
their first game against an Eastern Conference team.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration was especially evident in the face of Rex
Chapman, who continues to search for some long-lost shooting
accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Pistons, he was 3 for 10 from the floor. When he
missed, he would clench one hand into a fist and cast his eyes
toward the ceiling, as if pleading for help from a higher source.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his struggles, there has always been a moment when it
appears he is about to rediscover his touch. With 1:52 left, he
sank a three-pointer that drew the Suns within six. You could
almost hear the crowd murmur in unison:
</P>
<P>
   Finally.
</P>
<P>
   But the old game-saving jumper is still missing. In some ways,
Chapman's struggle sums up the Suns. There are a few brilliant
moments, but never enough of them to erase signs that the Suns
could be in for a mediocre season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about Rex,'' Ainge said. ``In time, he'll be
back. But I can see the concern in his eyes, and that concerns
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapman was somewhat mystified by what Ainge meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got to continue playing and working at it without
much chance at practice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Concern? It's just another word. You can find it any old
dictionary. Chapman is looking for his shot, and for now, it is
buried in a well-read book that applied to a game before the
lockout. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
