<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-WOMEN'S-REPORT-TE     02-20 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WOMEN'S-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS COACH-PIONEER EARNS RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, Kansas coach Marian Washington ran practice at
the same time every day. At the same time, construction crews would
turn on their jackhammers and saws to continue refurbishing Allen
Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   After each practice, Washington went home and stewed. What was
it going to take to earn respect?
</P>
<P>
   It was going to take the same thing Washington has done
throughout her career: fight. Fight for what she believes in, for
change, for what she knows is right. And fight to let people know
that she cares.
</P>
<P>
   This was not something new for the woman who took over a
go-nowhere Kansas team in 1973, the same woman who earned $15,000
to be women's director of athletics, coach basketball and founded
the track and field team in 1974. This was the same person who
helped put Lynette Woodard on the map.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do care about people and I work hard to see the best in
everybody,'' said Washington, one of the pioneers in women's sports
in the 1970s. ``I wanted people to respect and appreciate women in
sports. I learned some time later the attitudes won't change, and
there were some years I was so tired and sick of it only those
close to me knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six years later and one win away from career victory No.
500, it has paid off. She has made an impact in her world. Women's
salaries, academic resources and facilities are equitable. For
years, Washington was at the forefront of those fights.
</P>
<P>
   And for a long time, there were people in her own athletic
department who wished Washington would just take her tiny lot and
play happy with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you think about people who are willing to give back and
make a difference, Marian has done that,'' Tennessee coach Pat
Summitt said. ``I know from recruiting against her that kids like
and respect her, and I have a lot of respect for what she has done
throughout her career.''
</P>
<P>
   What's left for Washington is to enjoy this. Enjoy the plush
office. Enjoy the nice salary. Enjoy the wins and seven consecutive
NCAA Tournament appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would be here, and I can't help but not
think about it now because everyone else is,'' said Washington, who
will try for the milestone tonight against Oklahoma. ``This
embraces the efforts of a lot of players and coaches who have been
a part of my program that's kept me going. This isn't about
gloating, it's about being thankful.''
CULTURAL GAP CLOSING FOR REBELS' FROEHLICH
Nevada-Las Vegas' Linda Froehlich had more than a few adjustments
to make when she left her native Germany this summer and headed for
Elvis's Playground of Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   There was the American culture, the difference is schools, the
difference in competition and the difference in basketballs,
literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball they use here is smaller,'' Froehlich said. ``In
Germany, we play with a men's basketball. There I play against
women; here I play against girls my age. It's all very different
and exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Froehlich adjusted quickly. She is the nation's sixth-leading
scorer, averaging 23 points and nine rebounds per game in her
freshman season with the Lady Rebels. She has led the team in
scoring 20 times this season and has been named the Western
Athletic Conference player of the week twice.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some Europeans who come to America to play for a season
and return home, the 19-year-old plans to return to Germany this
summer and play for the national team and then return to UNLV in
the fall. It's a good thing. After winning seven games the past two
seasons combined, Froehlich is a major reason UNLV is 15-8 this
season.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 20 points in a losing effort at TCU on Thursday,
TCU coach Mike Petersen summed it up best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, she's big time.''
QUICK HITS LOCAL CONFUSION
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the Western Athletic Conference, TCU and SMU have
been travel partners. No problem, right?
</P>
<P>
   The people in Fort Collins, Colo., don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   After the Horned Frogs played at Colorado State on Feb. 11, the
Mustangs played there two days later.
</P>
<P>
   During player introductions for the SMU game, the public address
announcer said: ``And from Fort Worth, it's the SMU Mustangs.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, after the game the box score had TCU's record
rather than SMU's. The next day the local newspaper attributed SMU
coach Rhonda Rompola with a quote.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad TCU coach Mike Petersen said it.
MOVING ON
</P>
<P>
   After the suicide of former Stephen F. Austin star Katrina
Price, SFA lost consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the Ladyjacks have gone on to win five
consecutive games and six out of seven. This season, however,
likely will not be measured by ``Ws'' or ``Ls''.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put on a good face, but we have daily reminders of
the things that we have gone through and we will carry those
remembrances for the rest of our lives,'' SFA coach Royce Chadwick
said. ``Our biggest foe right now is our minds and focusing on what
we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   SFA is 12-10 and 9-5 in Southland Conference play. SFA must win
the conference tournament to keep its string of 11 consecutive NCAA
Tournament appearances alive.
A HUSKIES FIRST
</P>
<P>
   Svetlana Abrosimova's jump shot in the second half of
Connecticut's 88-53 victory against Providence on Thursday was
significant for two reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One, it was her 22nd and 23rd points, and coach Geno Auriemma
sat her down the rest of the game. Second, she became the first
UConn sophomore to reach 1,000 career points. At this point in her
Huskies career, she has more points than Nykesha Sales, Rebecca
Lobo and Jennifer Rizzotti did at the same time in their respective
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play again, but it's senior night,'' Abrosimova
said. ``It wasn't a problem for me to sit on the bench.''
BYE-BYE, STEPHANIE
</P>
<P>
   The first home sellout for a women's game at Mackey Arena
(14,123) was also Purdue senior Stephanie White-McCarty's final
home game. The Boilermakers defeated Ohio State, 88-58.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see the place packed took my breath away,'' White-McCarty
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before she came to Purdue, the Boilermakers were averaging 4,664
fans. This season, that number has reached 9,307.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because of Steph,'' Purdue coach Carolyn Peck said.
THE MOVIE WAS BETTER
</P>
<P>
   At one point during Tennessee's 113-39 victory over Memphis on
Tuesday, Tigers coach Joye Lee-McNelis called a timeout to pose an
introspective question to her team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked had they ever watched the movie ``The Bad News
Bears,'''' she said. ``I told them that's kind of what we looked
like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
