<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIDDEN BLESSING IN NOWHERE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There is a tattoo on his chest. A black panther. A
vision Jason Kidd has carried around for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sleek animal,'' he said. ``Fast. Powerful. The kind of
animal that can do anything it wants.'' He smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out it was a little bit tough to own one, so this is
the next best thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Friday night, and all around the budding superstar, there
is the silence of failure. Tom Gugliotta is in a corner, face in
his hands. Chris Morris is leaning back, arm resting on a vacant
chair. And Rex Chapman . . .
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to feel for Rex Chapman, whose game is a casualty
of the shooter's domino effect. Sore hamstring hinders conditioning
which limits legs which kills jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   And it's hard to find an identity, a pulse, something which
defines this 5-4 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know what it is,'' Chapman said. ``Hard to get
a handle on it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a 101-93 loss to the Pistons, we know a few
things:
</P>
<P>
   These Suns are not short on guts, and there will be times when
pride alone leads them to the winner's circle. But they are no
longer glamorous, only gritty. No longer sure-footed, but
resiliently awkward.
</P>
<P>
   You can't count them out, but you can't count on them for much
else.
</P>
<P>
   As stated before, the only dramatic statement the Suns can make
next season is through their two draft picks, the consolation for a
season that looks rather shaky. But there is something else, and
it's happening now, before our eyes.
</P>
<P>
   With Kevin Johnson drifting out of memory and Antonio McDyess
hiding under security blankets in Denver, there is nothing but room
for Jason Kidd. Room to grow, explode, to take over a team crying
for leadership.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, his line was nice, but nothing like his two
triple-doubles earlier in the week. Nothing like that amazing night
in San Antonio when he put a team on his back. Like superstars do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the difference,'' Kidd said when asked if he's
crossing the bridge. ``My job is to win ballgames, help the team
win. It's up to you guys to label us as bad, good or super.''
</P>
<P>
   You want to know how Michael Jordan became a superstar? He
played on a lot of bad teams, ones that needed his talents to be
extraordinary just in order to compete. And they did. With an
enormous leash, Jordan's game sprouted in all directions. And once
he became an expert jump shooter, he was there.
</P>
<P>
   The path is starting to look familiar.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, on a Nike tour of Japan in 1996, Kidd requested an
audience with Jordan. Kidd was dealing with all that chaos in
Dallas and needed some help. They sat down, and Jordan patiently
answered all his questions.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing you should know: There are players Jordan liked as
friends and players Jordan respected, ones he deemed worthy of his
knowledge. Jordan already sensed that Kidd fit in the latter
category, so he continued talking. For 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was giving me advice,'' Kidd said. ``I was soaking it up
like a sponge.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to think of Kidd as an NBA veteran. It is his fifth
year in the NBA, but it has been only seven years since he left
high school. In contrast, this is Tim Duncan's second year in the
NBA, but his sixth since entering college.
</P>
<P>
   It's also Kidd's first year in Phoenix without the lengthy
shadow of KJ.
</P>
<P>
   It is simply Kidd's time, finally his team. And the climate is
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect KJ,'' Kidd said. ``When I was traded, the biggest
thing I didn't want to do was step on his toes. It could've gotten
ugly, me coming in, saying I wanted the ball. But I'm not that kind
of player. I'm not that kind of person.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the midst of an ugly season, he is on his way. With room
to grow, on a team that needs him to do everything. And in the end,
it could be another blessing from a season going nowhere. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
