<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-LIGHTNING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES SPIRAL DOWNWARD  
 `DISORGANIZED' TEAM LOSES TO LIGHTNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ When one of the NHL's supposedly elite teams plays the
woeful Tampa Bay Lightning, a tie is considered a loss.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, how can the Phoenix Coyotes' 4-2 loss
Friday night to the Lightning before 11,057 stunned fans at the Ice
Palace be categorized?
</P>
<P>
   Rock-bottom is good.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the Lightning _ which registered just its 12th win
of the season while snapping a 10-game winless streak _ started a
goalie, Derek Wilkinson, who hadn't played in the NHL in more than
a year and had a career NHL record of 2-7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Rock-bottom is perfect, considering the Coyotes, who have lost
three straight games, also lost center Juha Ylonen to a knee injury
in the second period. His knee will be evaluated today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's rock-bottom, but the last three games we
haven't played playoff-caliber hockey,'' said Coyote Rick Tocchet,
who scored both Phoenix goals to raise his total on the season to
20. ``The way we're playing, we're not even a playoff-caliber team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disorganized and not helping each other out. That
happens to teams that don't make the playoffs. We are within
striking distance of Dallas for first in our division. You'd think
we'd be playing together, but we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it time for an air-clearing, players-only meeting?
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be a good idea. It's tough to say anything after a
game like this,'' Tocchet said. ``It's better to sleep on it
first.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the setback more disappointing is it was the
designated ``confidence builder'' to kick off a seven-game trip
that progressively gets tougher, with stops in Florida tonight,
Pittsburgh Monday, then Washington, New York (Rangers) and New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing our best hockey and haven't been for
awhile,'' said Coach Jim Schoenfeld, whose team has lost four of
its past six. ``The biggest trademark of our team early on was we
played the game for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had adversity, and we've forgotten that's what we need
to do to win. We have to get back to playing unselfish hockey and
playing for the guy next to you instead of for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes outplayed the Lightning for the first period and
much of the second but still entered the third period tied at 1,
thanks to Wilkinson's heroics. Then they simply allowed Tampa Bay
to dominate the game.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest killer was the Coyotes' power play. They now have
scored just three times in their past 35 power plays, coming up
empty on five attempts Friday. Worse, during a pair of third-period
advantages, the Lightning equalled the Coyotes' scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had more odd-man rushes against us than we usually have in
a month,'' a disgusted Schoenfeld said. ``We didn't score on the
power play. When you get opportunities, you need to score.''
</P>
<P>
   really going to cost us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes only had three penalties, but two came on Gerald
Diduck's boarding and game misconduct, which left Tampa Bay captain
Darcy Tucker with a cut above his eye. It also led to a five-minute
Lightning power play that veteran Wendell Clark cashed in for a
game-tying goal at 7:50 of the first period to offset Tocchet's
first goal at 4:13.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gratton's goal at 17:15 of the third period proved to be
the game-winner. Benoit Hogue also cashed an insurance goal at
18:28 and an empty-netter at the final buzzer. In between, Tocchet
made it 3-2 after Nikolai Khabibulin was pulled for an extra
attacker at 19:00. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
