<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CATCHERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE OFF D-BACKS CATCHERS  
 STINNETT, MILLER HAVE SLOTS LOCKED UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Catcher Damian Miller was rummaging through his
locker recently when he heard a small voice behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Miller, I thought we traded you,'' said 7-year-old Nathan
Showalter, the son of Miller's boss, Diamondbacks Manager Buck
Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   Miller chuckled and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez, is my spring starting out good or what?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Life is better than you might think for Miller and fellow
backstop Kelly Stinnett as they prepare for another long, grueling
trek through the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, both were battling for roster spots, as were most
players in the club's inaugural camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really no pressure now. We both know we're going to
make the club. Now we can get our work in,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was one of the final cuts of the spring, went to Tucson
and was recalled for good May 6. Stinnett began the season as the
No. 2 man behind Jorge Fabregas, got some starts when Fabregas went
down with an ankle injury and then got a lot of starts after
Fabregas went with right-hander Willie Blair to the New York Mets
in a July 31 trade for outfielder Bernard Gilkey and right-hander
Nelson Figueroa.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stinnett is expected to be the primary starter,
Showalter said Miller will get a large share of time. Stinnett hit
.259 with 11 home runs and 34 RBIs in 92 games and had a
club-record 13-game hitting streak. Miller hit .286 with three
homers and 14 RBIs in 57 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a `I hate you, I hope you do poorly' relationship. We
support each other. We talk to each other. We even go out to eat
together on occasion,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough not to respect those guys after the job they did
for us last season,'' Showalter said. ``They give us depth. We're
going to try to alternate whenever we can, but if one guy gets hot
(offensively), it will be hard not to ride that horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with a new stable of veteran pitchers will help the
catchers do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like us, we can't complain,'' Miller said. ``These guys
know what they're doing. Having worked with the pitchers last year
and the experience of the new guys, we're in more of a comfort
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett said, ``It makes you want to work harder. There's more
of a swagger around here, not in a cocky way, but in a confident
way. There's more of a chance that we're going to be in every
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching coach Glenn Sherlock took the six catchers in camp off
to a side field Friday and worked for more than an hour on blocking
pitches, fielding bunts and catching foul pop-ups, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   The other receivers are non-roster invitees Rod Barajas, Marcus
Hanel, Ramsey Koeyers and Izzy Molina. The emergency catcher will
be Greg Colbrunn, who signed as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But the focus remains on Stinnett and Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly and Damian have really developed into solid receivers,''
Sherlock said. ``Their main responsibility is to handle the
pitching staff, and they've both done that. They block pitches
well, they call a good game, and they prepare well. It's no secret
that the catcher is there for the pitcher, and communication is the
key.''
</P>
<P>
   Electricity already is moving through the wires. Stinnett began
working with left-hander Randy Johnson about two weeks ago at Bank
One Ballpark in Phoenix and worked again with him during Thursday's
first workout.
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett's eyes lit up when asked about Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw his fastball and change-up but no slider, but that
will come,'' Stinnett said. ``I put the glove up and he kept
hitting the spot. It will be even better when the season starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller had a session Friday with another new starter,
right-hander Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be able to work with these guys, learn how they
like you to set up back there, get a better idea of what they
throw,'' Miller said. ``I'm glad they're on my side, that I don't
have to face them. They'll save me a few strikeouts and a few
points on my average.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett is limiting the wear and tear on his knees by using
``knee savers,'' pads strapped to the calf area. When he squats
behind the plate, he more or less ``sits'' on the pads.
</P>
<P>
   He said the knee is a bit sore ``but will work itself out when I
get into baseball shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Colbrunn was allowed to show up early to get acclimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to feel like a fish out of water,'' said
Colbrunn, who caught part of one game with the Colorado Rockies in
1998 before going to Atlanta in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's shaken the cobwebs off, and he seems to fit perfectly.
He's a bulldog,'' Sherlock said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
