<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BROWN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN CLOSE TO RE-SIGNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Cardinals offensive tackle Lomas Brown said on
Friday he expects to re-sign with the team by the end of the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking, and we're just trying to finalize
things,'' said Brown, whose agent, Lamont Smith, met with Cardinals
executive Rod Graves Friday at the NFL scouting combine in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have (agreed) on numbers and everything. We're just waiting
for approval (from team ownership).''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the two sides have talked about a two-year deal, but
he wouldn't give any details.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had talked to Brown in December about a one-year
contract worth about $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who will be 36 next season, recently completed a
three-year deal that averaged $3 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Brown around the league has increased the past few
days. The expansion Cleveland Browns and Washington Redskins asked
about him.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Cardinals acknowledged that they had talked to
free-agent offensive tackle Wayne Gandy, formerly of the St. Louis
Rams, in case Brown didn't re-sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Cardinals offensive line coach George Warhop) called me to
tell me about them talking to Gandy,'' Brown said. ``He said the
only reason the whole thing came about was because (Gandy) played
for him in St. Louis, but that they wanted me back.''
</P>
<P>
   If Brown does re-sign, the Cardinals might be hard-pressed to
also re-sign outside linebacker Jamir Miller, considered one of the
NFL's most attractive free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have said all along they wanted Miller to return,
but they didn't know if they could afford him. They have only about
$5 million to spend on free agents to stay under the $57.2 million
salary cap for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Jamir back,'' Brown said. ``We're a better team with
Jamir.''
</P>
<P>
   One source close to the team said the only way the Cardinals
could sign both players was if some veterans were asked to
restructure their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The source said the most likely candidate would be cornerback
Aeneas Williams, who is scheduled to earn $3.4 million each of the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   It is not believed the Cardinals have asked Williams to re-do
his contract. &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Chargers have shown interest in Cardinals safety
Kwamie Lassiter, an unrestricted free agent, who had four
interceptions against them last season. Lassiter, who has been
offered a three-year deal by the Cardinals, is expected to visit
San Diego on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the Fiesta Bowl scheduled for Jan. 2 at Sun Devil Stadium,
the Cardinals will have to finish their regular season on the road.
The league's regular season is scheduled to end that weekend. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
