<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE MAKES STATEMENT WITH VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Jelani Gardner and Kelvin Gibbs. What a pair.
As they go, so goes the Pepperdine men's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Last week they stunk and so did the Waves. But Friday night,
with the best team in the West Coast Conference as the opponent,
Gardner and Gibbs were back to their old ways.
</P>
<P>
   Their timing was perfect. The duo combined for 40 points and the
Waves snapped a two-game losing streak with an emotional 75-70 win
over Gonzaga in front of 2,685 at Firestone Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine, riding the bubble of a possible NCAA Tournament
at-large berth, improved to 9-4 in the WCC, 18-10 overall. The
Waves could make it a moot point, though, if they win next week's
conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   A win like Friday's over the regular-season champion Bulldogs,
who dropped to 21-6, 11-2, gives Pepperdine a shot in the arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to get to the NCAA Tournament by way of the
conference tournament, you'll probably have to get through
(Gonzaga),'' Pepperdine head coach Lorenzo Romar said. ``Now our
guys know that they have a chance to beat those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs and Gardner give Pepperdine that chance.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs, a sophomore forward, scored a career-high 23 points and
also grabbed 12 rebounds. His offensive rebound and layup with 16
seconds left gave the Waves a 74-70 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs, motivated by what he said was a lot of trash-talking by
the Gonzaga players during the game, caught an airball by Tezale
Archie and in the same motion put the ball up and in with one
second left on the shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there would only be one or two seconds left,'' Gibbs
said.
</P>
<P>
   Romar said, ``Kelvin played with fury, a vengeance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner also was a motivated player; he came off the bench for
the first time in his two-year Pepperdine career. For the first
time in 54 games, he wasn't in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Romar described the move as ``a little shakeup . . . a little
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said the coaching staff put him on the bench as
punishment for his poor play last week in losses at San Francisco
and Santa Clara. Here's the kicker: Gardner didn't disagree with
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to make it a mental challenge for me,'' Gardner
said. ``I think I did well. I think I came in and was productive. I
didn't pout.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner scored five of his 17 points in a spurt that gave
Pepperdine a 72-68 lead with 2:03 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt, when Jelani Gardner is playing well we are
a better team,'' Romar said. ``He came in and was poised; he didn't
force the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves overcame a 12-0 run by the Bulldogs over a
three-minute span in the second half. Matt Santangelo's 3-pointer
gave Gonzaga its biggest lead _ 68-62. But Gibbs ended the streak
with a rebound and basket and Pepperdine regained the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The balanced Bulldogs, who had won 17 of their 19 games prior to
Friday, had four players score in double figures, but none had more
than 12. Richie Frahm, who came in averaging 14.7 points per game,
was held to just nine.
</P>
</TEXT>
