<HEADLINE>
GUGLIOTTA ON OLYMPIC TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Tom Gugliotta got the call. So far, Jason Kidd has
not.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta told ``The Arizona Republic'' he will represent the
United States at the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' 6-foot-10 forward confirmed Friday that he received a
call from USA Basketball on Thursday and accepted the invitation to
play this summer in the Olympic qualifying tournament in San Juan,
Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Those players were asked to make a two-year commitment to play
in the qualifier July 14-25 and then the Olympic Games in the fall
of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Granik, deputy commissioner of the NBA and president of USA
Basketball, which is charged with selecting the team, said nine NBA
players will be chosen. Those will be announced next week.
</P>
<P>
   He said three other players will be chosen from the collegiate
ranks, the Continental Basketball Association or Americans playing
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   But those three will not compete in the Olympics. The Olympic
roster will be filled out with three more NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd has not been contacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have my address,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If he isn't among the first nine selected, he still could be
among the three players added next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking for a two-year commitment,'' Granik said. ``It
wouldn't be fair for a player to say, `I only want to play in
2000.' The understanding is, unless there are unforeseen
circumstances, if a player agrees to play this summer in the
qualifying tournament, they will be on the Olympic team in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, we need a good team this summer. We can't afford
not to qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the top two teams in the 10-team qualifier will advance to
the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, players who were selected for last summer's World
Championships team, which did not compete in Greece because of the
NBA labor lockout, were to get first crack at the nine spots.
However, Granik said that is not the case, but ``when the smoke
clears, you'll see a lot of those names.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta was chosen for that team, which later was filled
mostly with Continental Basketball Association players.
</P>
<P>
   Center Luc Longley of the Suns is expected to compete for the
host Australians in 2000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
