<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPNOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKS ODD MAN OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The numbers finally didn't add up for veteran
point guard Scott Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   The former UC Irvine star, who's been down since injuring his
right knee in an exhibition game against the Los Angeles Lakers, is
out. On Friday's mandatory cut-down day, the Los Angeles Clippers
reached the 12-player limit for their active roster by waiving
Brooks and moving two others to the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-11 Brooks had been attempting to make his seventh NBA
team in 11 seasons. He averaged a career-high 6.3 points per game
for Houston during the 1992-'93 season, and played for the NBA
champion Rocket team the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks has been on the injured list since hurting his right knee
in a collision with Lakers rookie Ruben Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Even with perfect health, he would have been the fourth option
in a crowded point-guard stable that includes Darrick Martin,
Sherman Douglas
</P>
<P>
   and Pooh Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things are difficult,'' Elgin Baylor,
</P>
<P>
   the Clippers vice president of basketball operations, said of
waiving the popular Brooks. ``He's a real professional, and a great
person to have around.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 players who had been on the team payroll, the only
Clippers without guaranteed contracts were Brooks and rookie free
agent Tyrone Nesby.
</P>
<P>
   Nesby has become part of Coach Chris Ford's
</P>
<P>
   rotation, and is 10th on the team in minutes played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the guy has played very well,'' Baylor said of Nesby.
``His first step is as quick as anybody. He certainly has a
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining rookie Brian Skinner
</P>
<P>
   on the injured list are veteran center Stojko Vrankovic
</P>
<P>
   (back spasms) and seemingly healthy second-year guard Charles
Smith
</P>
<P>
   (shin splints). Smith hasn't missed a practice, but has yet to
make his first appearance in a regular-season game this season.
</P>
<P>
   IS TONIGHT THE NIGHT?
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Mavericks were beaten in seven of their first eight
games. When they meet the Clippers tonight at the Sports Arena, it
will be their third road game in four nights.
</P>
<P>
   Are they ripe for defeat?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even begin to think about that,'' said Ford, who has
yet to experience the thrill of victory this season. ``We're never
gonna have an easy night, so we just have to go out there and play
hard for 48 minutes - or more. I never assume it's going to be
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, coach. So, with one overtime defeat and another loss
achieved in double-overtime, does Ford ever sit back and ponder
what might have been?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have those little dreams,'' he said, ``but then
it's reality time. Hopefully, the tides will turn for us.''
</P>
<P>
   During the low tides of 0-6, the Clippers have yet to produce a
solid effort in most phases of the game. They were pounded on the
boards against Chicago, but Ford seems to have fixed the rebounding
problem. In Tuesday's double-overtime loss to Vancouver, they
out-rebounded the Grizzlies, 60-48. But in the same game, the
Clippers missed half of their 32 free-throw attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice,'' Ford said, ``if we started making open
shots and foul shots.''
</P>
<P>
   He also would prefer a better start than Tuesday's 0-13 opening
against Vancouver. To help prevent a reprisal of that performance,
Ford anticipates a change or two in his starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL REPORT
</P>
<P>
   Off-guard Eric Piatkowski,
</P>
<P>
   whose sore right ankle prevented him from working out with the
team Thursday, participated in Friday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas also practiced, but continues to nurse a slight pull of
the left groin that occurred in Tuesday's game with Vancouver. His
availability remains in question, but if he can't play, his minutes
will go to Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner also practiced Friday, and may be able to return to
action within a week. A knee injury has kept the power forward from
Baylor on the sidelines since the end of training camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
