<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-COHN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVADA INTER ESTED IN NAU'S HOWLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - After distinguishing himself at Northern Arizona the
past five seasons, it's time for Lumberjacks Coach  &UR; Ben Howland to
move on, knowing he left a program in far better shape than he
found it.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Nevada apparently think so, too. Howland has
emerged as a top candidate there.
</P>
<P>
   NAU is tied for first place in the Big Sky Conference after
winning the regular-season titles the past two seasons (and almost
beating Cincinnati in the first round of the 1998 NCAA Tournament).
Howland immediately was mentioned in Reno after  &UR; Pat Foster
resigned as coach of the Big West school on Feb. 1, effective at
the end of the season. Since then, Athletic Director
 &UR; Chris Ault has been considering other candidates, ``but I'm sure he
(Howland) is going to get looked at,'' a Nevada official said.
</P>
<P>
   Also under consideration, among others, are Gonzaga Coach  &UR; Dan
Monson and Utah assistant  &UR; Donny Daniels. But is it really a step
up for Monson, who might be waiting to see what happens at
Washington State? As for Daniels, Utah head Coach  &UR; Rick Majerus,
who presumably would endorse Daniels, is a close friend of
Howland's.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada, a former Big Sky member, has been a graveyard for
coaches. No Wolfpack coach has ever moved from there to another
NCAA Division I job. Also, Ault is known to be a tough AD to work
for.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe it's never had the right coach. In terms of facilities
and money, and even the fact that an airport is nearby, the
potential at Nevada is greater than at NAU.
</P>
<P>
   Howland, who perhaps lobbied too hard for the Cal-Santa Barbara
job last year and didn't get it, is maintaining a low-key posture.
Contacted in Portland, before the Lumberjacks lost to Portland
State in overtime on Thursday, he acknowledged ``it's flattering to
be considered by schools,'' but said his main concern is getting
his team through this season.
</P>
<P>
   An even better opportunity for Howland might be at San Diego
State, where
 &UR; Fred Trenkle, mired in a 2-21 season, also has announced his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The school has a first-class arena, more visibility than Nevada,
and a commitment to upgrade from Athletic Director  &UR; Rick Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned. &QL; 
Sound familiar? &QL; 
Name a large university located in a warm-weather metropolis with a
transient population base and numerous entertainment options,
including professional sports, which has a good college basketball
program that can't attract fans.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. And Miami (Fla.), too.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of its most successful season ever, the NCAA
Tournament-bound Hurricanes are averaging a paltry 5,200. The main
reason seems to be Miami Arena, where the 'Canes play their home
games. It's a dump located about 25 minutes from campus in an area
with a high crime rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people just don't want to go there,'' an assistant
athletic director told Bloomberg News. ``It's hard to blame them.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's ``your'' excuse, ASU fans? &QL; 
Andre the giant &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who's the better point guard, Utah's  &UR; Andre Miller or Arizona's
 &UR; Jason Terry? First-year San Jose State coach  &UR; Phil Johnson was an
assistant at UA, so he knows all about Terry. He learned about
Miller first-hand last year, when Miller went for a triple-double
in Utah's NCAA Tournament win over the Wildcats. Now Johnson knows
even more about Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best defensive guard in America, along with Jason
Terry,'' Johnson told the ``Salt Lake City Tribune.'' And this was
``before'' Utah's 71-49 win on Thursday. ``They'll be the top two
guards taken in the NBA draft. Andre will be the first. He's really
good because he's so strong and physical for a guard.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 0139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
