r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA-OREGON-AZ     02-20 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-OREGON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA'S ANDERSON EMERGING AS SHOOTING GUARD  
 EFFORT LANDS HIM IN STARTING LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Rick Anderson seemed to be the least likely candidate
to claim the shooting guard spot for eighth-ranked Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   He had played exclusively in the low post, roughing up a lot of
California high school talent as a 6-foot-8 center and earning
nomination for McDonald's All-American.
</P>
<P>
   While 6-8 is a tall high school center, it doesn't project at
the collegiate level. Anderson isn't a bruising 6-8, either. He
weighs 198 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   He realized that to make it in college, he would have to play on
the perimeter facing the basket. He had to develop new skills and a
new level of endurance. Wing players don't camp out.
</P>
<P>
   So before stashing the surfboard and loading up for the drive
from Long Beach, Calif., to the desert, Anderson consulted a good
authority on what it would take to make the transition for Coach
Lute Olson: Anderson's dad, Gary, a former coach at Long Beach City
College and a player for Olson at Long Beach City College in the
early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad said, `Rick, this is going to be the biggest challenge of
your life, but if you want to make it, you have to run the lanes
and attack,' '' said Anderson, the first former player's son that
Olson has coached.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has taken his father's advice to heart. His consistent
progress surprisingly has elevated him into the lineup for Arizona
(19-4, 10-3) for the Pac-10 stretch drive that begins this
afternoon against Oregon (14-9, 6-8).
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was the last player signed in a heralded freshman
class.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Anderson played like a real shooting guard, blossoming
in an 89-72 rout of Oregon State. He shot 50 percent, almost 20
percentage points better than anyone else who played the position
this season, making two three-pointers and scoring a career-high 14
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure didn't shoot threes in high school,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More impressive to Olson was Anderson's defense. With his long
arms, Anderson prevented Beaver guards from making entry passes to
their big men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Olson has taught me a lot about playing the guard
position,'' Anderson said. ``I've learned team defense, where to
be, and how one mistake can make the whole concept fall apart. It
was hard to adjust, but I didn't rush it, and now it's just kind of
flowing. I knew at first I wouldn't do too well, not knowing how to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The original plan was to redshirt Anderson. That changed when
fellow freshman Luke Walton, son of Hall of Famer Bill Walton,
suffered a foot fracture similar to the one that stymied his dad's
pro career.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson moved into the lineup Thursday, following a strong week
in practice. He was further buoyed in the rotation while freshman
guards Ruben Douglas and Traves Wilson served disciplinary
benchings.
</P>
<P>
   That's the opportunity he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can take it now,'' he said of holding the job
through the NCAA Tournament. ``It's up to Ruben and Traves, too.
It's about who wants to work the hardest.''
</P>
<P>
   On that, Anderson is the leader of the pack, according to UA
point guard Jason Terry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should see how hard Rick practices, how he beats everybody
to the hoop,'' Terry said. ``I saw this ability in him a long time
ago. I was just wondering when Coach Olson was going to see it,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson said he saw it a while ago, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said from the day we signed Rick that before he's through
here, he is going to be a great player,'' Olson said. ``He's the
best communicator we have at the defensive end. He gets pieces of
passes with those long arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands the game. The biggest thing now for him is
conditioning. We've got to get him out after four or five minutes
and get him a blow. But the thing I love is that I haven't once
heard him make an excuse all year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
