<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ASU-OREGON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANS: SUN DEVILS CAN'T WORRY ABOUT POSTSEASON 
</HEADLINE>
 ST.-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Barring some sort of wacky miracle, Arizona State
is no longer playing for an NCAA Tournament invitation. Not after a
disgraceful performance for 23 minutes Thursday against Oregon,
which led to a 76-75 loss on its home court.
</P>
<P>
   So what are the Sun Devils playing for, starting today at Wells
Fargo Arena against Oregon State? An NIT bid? Pride?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still battling, we still have five games left,'' ASU
Coach Rob Evans said. ``We've got to continue to try to win every
basketball game we can and see where we land.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to finish off winning. We want to finish playing hard,
executing, just like we want to do every game. Nothing changes for
me. You have goals, and if your goals start slipping away, you've
got to re-establish. But you've got to continue to play hard. And
you've got to continue to execute. It's an assignment we have, and
every assignment we want to do the best we can at.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans will bounce back, and his team might, too. But for the
first time all season, he looked whipped, watching his Sun Devils
display an inept, lackluster effort for more than a half against
Oregon. Evans sat on the bench, not quite sure what he was seeing,
with even less of a clue as to why it was taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Evans is up and out of his chair, standing or crouched
on the sideline, barking at his players and working the officials.
But there was little of that. The fog the Sun Devils were playing
in had engulfed their coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd tell them a play,'' Evans said, ``and then they'd not
execute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, after trailing by 15, the Sun Devils finally seemed
to figure things out. They even tied the score with 37 seconds left
when Mike Batiste, who started on the bench, hit a three-point
basket.
</P>
<P>
   What if Batiste had been out there at the start? What if he made
that shot, or just a regular two-point basket in the first four
minutes instead of sitting out? Maybe ASU wouldn't have lost by a
single point or started as slowly.
</P>
<P>
   A senior, Batiste was benched for a couple of transgressions. He
failed to show up for study hall and a meeting with an academic
adviser. So did some of his teammates. As punishment, they were
summoned to run five miles at 5 a.m., which Evans refers to as ``5
at 5.'' This time, Batiste was the only no-show.
</P>
<P>
   The only way Batiste got to play at all was by participating in
5 at 5 twice, the second time the day of the game. But the damage
had been done, a needless distraction for a team supposedly focused
on finishing the season big.
</P>
<P>
   Off for a full week since an intense effort against Arizona in
Tucson fell just short, the Sun Devils looked rusty. ASU pretended
to run an offense against an aggressive man-to-man defense, and the
result was predictable. And deadly.
</P>
<P>
   After making two of their first three shots, the Sun Devils
stood around and missed the next 15. They played hurriedly instead
of quickly, and only because of repeated trips to the free-throw
line and Oregon's own raggedness did they trail by just 10 at
halftime. They made 4 of 22 shots and turned the ball over 11
times.
</P>
<P>
   Starting out the second half the same way, ASU fell behind by 15
with 17:17 left. That seemed to wake the Sun Devils up, and they
spent the rest of the game clawing back but came up short. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 0141EST &QL; 
