<HEADLINE>
DEAL WITH PIRATES HAS 1 MORE STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 and DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ The much talked-about trade between the
Diamondbacks and Pittsburgh has cleared all but one hurdle and
could be announced today.
</P>
<P>
   The trade, which will bring outfielder Al Martin and infielder
Tony Womack to Arizona in exchange for outfielder Bernard Gilkey
and cash, needs only the approval of the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   It's so close to being consummated that Martin did not board a
flight to the Pirates' spring training facility in Florida on
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reluctantly, I was going to get on a red-eye flight, but now
it looks like things took a turn for the better,'' Martin said from
his Scottsdale home. ``Hopefully, I'll just have to drive to Tucson
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The holdup is the amount of money the Diamondbacks will pay for
the remainder of Gilkey's contract. Because Arizona will pick up
more than $1 million of the deferment, and possibly as much as $6
million, the deal requires the approval of the commissioner's
office, where vice presidents Bill Murray and Sandy Alderson
red-flagged the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks managing general manager Jerry Colangelo, however,
has summoned the help of Commissioner Bud Selig to approve the
trade, which is not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finished with the Pittsburgh part,'' Colangelo said.
``He won't get that money for a long, long time. Why they took that
position with us, I don't understand.'' &QL; 
D-Backs sign Korean &QL; 
Korean native  &UR; Chan Ho Park has developed into one of the top
pitchers in the National League for the Los Angeles Dodgers. The
Diamondbacks can only hope their latest acquisition does the same.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona announced the signing of 20-year-old right-hander
 &UR; Byung-Hyun Kim of Korea, the club's first Asian player. Monetary
terms were not announced, but a source said the figure was in
excess of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kim was scouted by  &UR; Clay Daniel, Arizona's international
scouting coordinator. In 1998, Kim, 5 feet 11, 175 pounds, pitched
for the Korean National team and struck out 15 members of the U.S.
Olympic team in 6 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks decided to make a play for Kim after seeing
tape of Korea's gold-medal performance in the Asian Games, when he
struck out 12 during six perfect innings against China in the
semifinals. He had eight consecutive strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   By winning the gold medal in the Asian Games, Kim and his
teammates became exempt from military service.
</P>
<P>
   If Kim were eligible for baseball's amateur draft, Diamondbacks
Manager  &UR; Buck
 &UR; Showalter is certain he would be a first-round pick. Showalter said
the team was in a three-way race for Kim with the Dodgers and New
York Mets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
