A2557 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-WALTRIP-AZ     02-20 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-WALTRIP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
0 FOR FOREVER, BUT NOT GIVING UP  
 MICHAEL WALTRIP NEEDS 1ST WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it will happen Sunday. Or maybe two weeks from now.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe it won't happen at all.
</P>
<P>
   Not tomorrow, not next month, not even next year.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe never.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Marcis last visited victory lane in 1982. At least he got
there.
</P>
<P>
   Not Michael Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip is 0 for forever.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike older brother Darrell Waltrip, who is tied with Bobby
Allison at No. 3 on the all-time list with 84 career NASCAR Winston
Cup wins, the younger Waltrip never has finished higher than
second, and he did that just once _ 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no wonder Michael Waltrip barely batted an eye after
finishing a creditable fifth in last Sunday's Daytona 500, even
though the finish was his first top-five in three years (87
starts).
</P>
<P>
   When you've gone to the starting line 395 times since 1985 and
returned to the garage all 395 times without the checkered flag,
being close means nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty disappointed,'' said Waltrip, whose winless
streak is the longest among active drivers. ``I was very
distraught. Running fifth in the Daytona 500 is great. It's a good
morale booster for the team, but it wasn't the goal we started out
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to win.
</P>
<P>
   But when?
</P>
<P>
   Car owner Jim Mattei is convinced it will happen sometime this
season. So convinced is Mattei, he believes it will happen many
times over the next few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see great things out of Michael this year, and I very rarely
go out on the line that hard,'' Mattei said. ``Michael will produce
a lot of wins for us. We should have won (at Daytona), but
(Waltrip) made a mistake the last three or four laps and got out of
the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``On our computer, we were a tenth of a second faster than
(Jeff) Gordon. We feel like we would have at least been in the
hunt. But racing is 80 percent luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip's luck mostly has been bad.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip, however, also admits he's the author of some of that
luck. He's made mistakes. Many mistakes. And he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   But Waltrip, 35, also knows, as do others, that he has the
talent to touch the stars. It just hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early (1990s), I almost won a couple of races,''
Waltrip said. ``I sat on a couple of poles. I just really felt that
everything was right there for me, like I was just an inch away
from cashing in after working my whole career to get to that point.
It just got away from me. It didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from close to getting kind of away from it, (but) now
I feel like I'm close again. I guess it's been since 1990 or '91
that I've had this kind of optimism and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) when we started with the Wood Brothers in (1996), I felt
I could do some good. And we did do good. We ran good the first of
'96. We were in the top 10 in points. We had won `The Winston'
(all-star event) and we were really competitive. For some reason,
we just let that slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   The famed Wood Brothers outfit hired Waltrip to replace Morgan
Shepherd in 1996, believing they had latched on to a future
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't think (Waltrip) could win, we wouldn't have hired
him,'' Len Wood said. ``Our intention was to make a winner out of
him. We were close a number of times, but we just didn't put it all
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nobody's fault. It just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   It's happened all through Waltrip's career.
</P>
<P>
   But Mattei and Waltrip are determined to bring the mess to an
end. Especially Mattei.
</P>
<P>
   Mattei first became a Winston Cup car owner two years ago, when
he became a partner with Geoffrey Bodine. A year later, Mattei
purchased the remaining interest from Bodine, then replaced Bodine
with Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Michael's history, this is the first time he's
been teamed up with the right budget and right equipment,'' Mattei
said.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip has seen enough to fill him with hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm plenty confident, and I'm only 35 years old,'' Waltrip
said. ``It's just putting all the pieces of the puzzle together. It
doesn't matter who you are, or how good you can drive, or how good
you can set up a car if you and the team don't work closely
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really what I'm focusing in on this year, trying to
have a relationship with my crew chief and my car owner and my team
(so) we all think alike. That's the key to getting to victory
lane.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the only key.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started this season thinking this could be my last season,''
Waltrip said. ``I've got a great ride, a great team, a great
sponsor and if I don't win races and run well, I might not be able
to get a ride next year. That's a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm faced with, and I love to race cars. It's
worth listening to everybody remind me that I've never won a race
just so I can get to do what I want to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I know) I've got to win. I'll never feel like I'm accepted or
feel like I'm solid or stable until that happens.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
