<HEADER>
A2558 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  -CAR-NHRA-DUNN-AZR &LR;      02-20 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
-CAR-NHRA-DUNN-AZR  
 NHRA DRIVER DUNN SAVORS TURN AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about your good-news, bad-news seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dunn made it to four National Hot Rod Association Top Fuel
championship rounds last year, then proceeded to lose all four
races.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Dunn lost them all to one driver.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Scelzi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got beat a couple times, and I messed up a couple of
times,'' Dunn said. ``But we knew we had a team capable of
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn knew it, but still hadn't proved it.
</P>
<P>
   Until two weeks ago, when Dunn smoked the field at the NHRA
season opener at Pomona, Calif., blasting Larry Dixon in the finals
with a superb 4.522-second pass.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dunn's first visit to victory lane since the 1996 season,
and the reunion was made even more special after he set the NHRA
elapsed-time mark with a 4.503-second run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Scelzi and (crew chief) Alan Johnson are the benchmark,
even though we ran some good numbers (at Pomona) and pretty much
spanked the competition,'' said Dunn, driver of Darrell Gwynn's
Team Mopar dragster. ``But I think we have the team to get past
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have a similar year to last year, only we have to
turn some of those first- and second-round losses into wins. It's
easier said than done, but it's what we're shooting for.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn gets another chance next week during the Checker Schuck's
Kragen Nationals at Firebird International Raceway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Sportsman time trials begin Thursday, followed by pro qualifying
sessions Friday and Saturday. Final eliminations begin at 11 a.m.
on Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn can hardly wait.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn put together four sub-4.60-second runs during eliminations
at Pomona, displaying the type of consistency he lacked for much of
the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, however, always believed he would return to the winner's
circle. Then, when he put together a strong second half last
season, he was convinced it only was a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody made a bigger deal out of us not winning
than we did,'' Dunn said. ``In the earlier part of my career, I
probably would have had doubts myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I knew what kind of car I had at the end of last year, and
I knew the type of people we had. We were doing all the right
things. It just wasn't falling our way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've been around long enough to know that you've got to
keep chipping away at it. You can't get discouraged. Don't try and
set the world on fire. Just go and run your race. Then, everything
will start coming around.''
</P>
<P>
   It started toward the back half of last season, when at one
point Dunn made it to three straight final rounds. If Scelzi hadn't
been in the opposite lane, who knows what might have happened.
</P>
<P>
   The fact it was Scelzi only made Dunn and company work harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone talks about Scelzi, Cory McClenathan, Kenny Bernstein
and all those top guys,'' Dunn said. ``We want to be mentioned in
that group, too. We want to get to that next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
