A2560 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-RACING-ARMIJO-AZR     02-20 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RACING-ARMIJO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUTSY RACE COULD WIN GORDON FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For once, Jeff Gordon didn't dominate.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't lead the most laps, and he wasn't even in the top
three for much of the race.
</P>
<P>
   But Gordon still won the Daytona 500, and years from now,
stock-car historians may turn back the pages to this race and
signal it as the one that finally made believers out of so many
non-Gordon fans.
</P>
<P>
   Because, for whatever reason he is disliked, whether it's due to
his California roots or landing a dream ride with Hendrick
Motorsports without having to bust his butt on NASCAR's Saturday
night short-track circuits, no one can deny that Gordon didn't
drive the guts out of last Sunday's heart-stopping race.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Dale Earnhardt was nearly at his very best, Gordon
was better.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, Gordon was Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   When Earnhardt pressed the black Chevy Monte Carlo's grill up
against Gordon's rear end in the race's waning moments, a lot of
drivers might have panicked.
</P>
<P>
   Not Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon took one look in the rearview mirror, saw the sneering
Earnhardt peering over the steering wheel and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it's all about,'' Gordon might have been
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Gordon took the lead from a stunned Rusty Wallace with
a daring move entering Turn 1.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of move Earnhardt has made throughout a mostly
spectacular career, the kind of move all fans expect from their
favorite drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But Gordon made it and never once thought what the ramifications
might be.
</P>
<P>
   It's what all the great drivers would have done, even the
unfortunate ones who never have won the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   That Gordon did it in an attempt to capture the sport's most
prestigious winner's trophy is testament to his desire to be the
very best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have (made that move) time and time again if I had to
just because it's the Daytona 500,'' Gordon said. ``Probably in
some other races, you might not try something like that. But it's
the Daytona 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he won, Earnhardt would have said something like that. So
would Junior Johnson. And Cale Yarborough.
</P>
<P>
   But Gordon said it, and even those fans still unwilling to be
lured into his camp probably gained new respect for the driver.
</P>
<P>
   If they didn't, it's their loss, not Gordon's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I was the perfect type of driver that all those fans
out there wanted, I don't think everybody would be cheering,''
Gordon said. ``If I only won two or three races a year for the last
couple of years, and maybe one championship, I still don't think
they'd all be cheering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the alternative, and that's to go out there and win as
much as I can. . . . Whatever comes with that comes with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that my fan base continues to grow. I'm sure it even
grew after (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   Even rival car owners appreciated Gordon's late-race savvy and
his post-race accolades directed at Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell anybody who will listen to me that (Gordon) is a
legend, even at his age (27),'' said Jim Mattei, whose driver,
Michael Waltrip, finished fifth. ``He's done more for this sport in
this decade than any single person. He's what the future of NASCAR
is, and I'm one of his biggest fans.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday, I'll bet a lot more fans are saying the same
thing. &QL; 
No sale &QL; 
Three-time Formula One champion Jackie Stewart recognized Gordon's
talents early on and actually tried to hire him several years ago
before he turned to the NASCAR Winston Cup circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have been the first of the international bunch to see
the potential in him,'' Stewart said. ``I guess one day I`d like to
see him sitting in an F-1 car and maybe give him a test and let him
have a drive around. In fact, I spoke to him several months ago and
offered him that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's clearly an enormously talented driver. (But) I think,
unfortunately, he is making so much money now in his own little
area that it would be difficult for him to see the logic in leaving
that guaranteed marketplace and going into (F-1) racing.'' &QL; 
Mark Armijo can be reached at 602-444-8323, or at
mark.armijo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 0147EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
