<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ In a joint news conference with
President Chirac of France, President Clinton declared that Serbian
leaders will be ``held accountable'' if peace talks on Kosovo
collapse and a NATO bombing campaign is needed. By Elizabeth
Becker. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MOOD (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ As the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, pondered the West's threat of air strikes and
rebuffed a visit from a U.S. envoy, Christopher Hill, U.S. and
Western diplomatic and aid workers began to leave Yugoslavia in
preparation for potential NATO bombing in the event the Kosovo
peace effort fails. By Steven Erlanger. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KURD-MANHUNT (Washington) _ The United States worked for four
months to help Turkey hunt down Abdullah Ocalan, the Kurdish rebel
leader, U.S. officials said on Friday. U.S. diplomatic pressure
backed by intelligence-gathering helped drive Ocalan into an
increasingly desperate search for refuge, the officials said. By
Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   KURD-GREECE (Athens, Greece) _ Since Turkish security forces
seized Abdullah Ocalan in Nairobi, Kenya, where he had been hiding
in the Greek Embassy, and triumphantly hauled him, blindfolded, to
Turkey for trial on charges of terrorism, Greece has been nurturing
a deep identity crisis. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BADGEMAKER (JINXIANG, China) _ From this remote coastal
town Chen Jiashu's influence spreads all over the world. Chen is
the owner of China's biggest manufacturer of badges and pins, a
world leader in the field. ``In recent years,'' he said, flipping
through books displaying his products, ``we've been making insignia
for Ford, badges for the U.S. police forces, emblems for the U.N.
forces and, I'm pretty sure, for the U.S. military, too. Though I'm
not really sure which is which, of course, since I can't read any
of them.'' By Elisabeth Rosenthal. With map.
</P>
<P>
   SAIPAN-WORKERS (Saipan, Northern Mariana Islands) _ Saipan is a
curious halfway point between the United States and China, most
clearly reflected in the disparity between the ambitions of Chinese
workers and the objections of American lawyers. Work conditions and
pay scales on Saipan are clearly better than in China, but fall
short of American standards. The contracts that workers sign before
they leave China include promises _ not to strike, not to discuss
problems with outsiders, not to become pregnant _ that are
acceptable to Chinese workers, even though they shock American
investigators. Such contracts are illegal in the United States, but
are signed in China. By Seth Faison. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-PENALTY-BIAS (Lincoln, Neb.) _ An American Indian who was
adopted by Quakers and then killed two people and who now faces the
death penalty has become a national cause for Quakers who want his
life spared. He has been granted a stay of execution under a recent
amendment to the Nebraska constitution guaranteeing all Nebraska
citizens equal rights under the law. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-ENGINEERS (Northampton, Mass.) _ Smith College, in a bid
to help alter an imbalance and as part of its efforts to shift its
lingering white-glove image, will become the first women's college
to open an engineering department. Its board of trustees is
expected to approve the $12.5 million plan on Saturday with the
first engineering course to be offered in the fall. By Ethan
Bronner. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FLIPPER-PARDON (Washington) _ President Clinton posthumously
pardons Lt. Henry Flipper, a former slave who was the first black
officer commissioned from West Point, clearing him of court-martial
charges driven by racism. By David Stout. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-POLITICS (Hollywood) _ It's that time again in
Hollywood, when that mostly Democratic community focuses on the
potential presidential candidates who troop in almost every week to
gather support from the rich and super-rich. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OSHA-ERGONOMICS (Washington) _ The Clinton administration
promised relief on Friday to millions of workers with aching backs,
crippled fingers, sore wrists and other physical problems caused or
aggravated by their jobs. The Labor Department took the first
formal step to require employers to redesign jobs and alter work
stations to accommodate workers suffering injuries to the neck,
back, arms and hands and to help prevent such injuries. By Robert
Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The trade deficit in goods and
services narrowed in December but widened to a record level in the
full year. December's deficit shrank to $13.8 billion from $15.3
billion in November. Exports declined 0.6 percent, reflecting
weaker foreign demand for industrial supplies and auto parts.
Imports fell 2.1 percent, partly because of lower oil prices. In
all of 1998, the deficit expanded to a record $168.6 billion, up
from the previous year's $110.2 billion, in a reflection of the
dollar's strength and the domestic economy's vigor. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   RETIREES-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Retirees have always been big
travelers, but now they are showing a penchant for high-adventure
travel more typical of those half their age. These days, many older
people, even octogenarians, can be found riding elephants in India,
horseback riding in Costa Rica and bungee jumping in New Zealand.
And the adventure-travel industry is rushing to accommodate them.
By Edwin McDowell. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI-TELECOM (Rome) _ Olivetti SpA shares rose on Friday
amid speculation that a board meeting of Italy's No. 2 phone
company on Sunday would approve a bid worth at least $53 billion
for its bigger rival, Telecom Italia SpA. By John Tagliabue and
Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   G7-MEETING (Frankfurt, Germany) _ With arguments continuing
about interest rates and currency levels, the Group of 7's finance
ministers, including Treasury Secretary Rubin, and central bankers
will meet in Bonn this weekend. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NEC-RESTRUCTURE (Tokyo) _ NEC Corp., one of the world's largest
semiconductor manufacturers and an emblem of Japan's business
success, announced a broad restructuring Friday that will include
one of the most sweeping labor reductions ever undertaken by a
major Japanese company. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Burned by a searing
cross-examination of a senior Compaq Computer Corp. executive,
Microsoft Corp. and Compaq tried Friday to regain ground in federal
court, though they may have helped the government as much as
themselves. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-LANGUAGE (Undated) _ ``Off Cspring: Wuzup? Prettyfli5:
n2m Off Cspring: well g/g c ya.'' In the chat room, written and
spoken language slur together. Here, a correctly spelled word is a
sign of the inarticulate and an innovative abbreviation is prized
above all else. The protocol of informality that marks electronic
communication for Andrew Walker, 12, aka Off Cspring, and millions
of others has set off a debate about whether the Internet serves to
invigorate language or strip it of its expressive power. By Amy
Harmon. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   REGIONAL-STUDIES (Undated) _ Academic centers are popping up
everywhere to bore into the soul of the Southwest and the Great
Plains, the South and New England. The study of regional culture
and politics, folkways and eccentricities, long dismissed as the
minor leagues of academic scholarship, is fashionable at American
universities as it has not been since at least the 1930s. Still,
amid the celebration of regional distinctiveness, a nagging
question persists: are there still distinctive regions to
celebrate? By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Washington) _ As Kenneth Starr conducted his
relentless investigation of President Clinton, many Americans were
troubled. ``What can we do about it?'' they asked in frustration.
But they could do nothing, because Starr was not accountable to our
political process. By Anthony Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ARATON-COLUMN (Tampa, Fla.) _ A Sports of The Times column
that looks at the most recent Yankee madness _ the blockbuster
trade involving Clemens and Wells _ through the eyes of a new
member of the team, left-hander Ed Yarnell. The former Mets
prospect said his first day with the Yankees was an eye-opener. By
Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-PITCHERS (Tampa, Fla.) _ Graeme Lloyd and Homer Bush,
two-thirds of the package sent to Toronto for Roger Clemens, were
luxuries to manager Joe Torre, specialists on a roster of stars.
The Yankees will win without them. But sometime before the July 31
trade deadline, the Yankees will have to replace Bush and Lloyd _
maybe with someone like Jimmy Key, the veteran left-hander who
announced his retirement late last month. By Buster Olney. With
photos.
</P>
<P>
   BOX-WHITAKER-TRINIDAD (New York) _ Pernell Whitaker believes he
has turned back the clock some 14 years. He believes that when
Felix Trinidad steps into the ring against him Saturday night at
Madison Square Garden, Trinidad will not be facing a 35-year-old
boxer who has not fought in 16 months. By Timothy W. Smith. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
