</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLIB-CLINTON-KOSOVO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-KOSOVO: `HARE-BRAINED CHATTER OF IRRESPONSIBLE FRIVOLITY'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent, provocative 1,075-word ``separate buy'' article is
from the current (week beginning 20 Feb. 1999) Economist
magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: THE QUOTE IN HEADLINE IS BY BENJAMIN DISRAELI)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Saturday, the day after his acquittal in the Senate, it was
glibness-as-usual for Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week,'' he said in his weekly radio address, ``the
warring parties in Kosovo have been meeting at a 14th-century
castle in France in search of 21st-century peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Savoring the rich sweep of the past, the president proceeded to
enunciate two lessons from history. First, ``World War II taught us
that America could never be secure if Europe's future was in
doubt.'' Second, ``Bosnia taught us...(that) violence we fail to
oppose leads to even greater violence we will have to oppose later
at greater cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of these two lessons, the president explained, America
should intervene in Kosovo, though there should of course be ``a
clear and realistic strategy to allow us to bring our forces home
when their work is done.''
</P>
<P>
   These standard phrases constitute pretty much all Clinton has to
say about his decision to commit troops to Kosovo as part of a NATO
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, to be sure, that no such force will be
assembled: at midweek the Serbs and the ethnic-Albanian Kosovars
remained some distance from a cease-fire, without which
peacekeepers will stay at home.
</P>
<P>
   But, even if the two sides opt to keep on fighting, it is worth
pausing to consider the manner in which Clinton declared himself
willing to risk American lives for Balkan peace. It was not all
that impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Take, first, the ``lesson'' that America must intervene in
European conflicts early on. If this is really so obvious, why did
Clinton not intervene when the Kosovo bust-up began a year ago?
After all, America had long ago promised to jump into Kosovo at the
first sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush warned Serbia's dictator, Slobodan Milosevic,
that America would punish Serbia if it used force against Kosovo's
Albanian majority, and Clinton officials have echoed this threat
loudly and repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, for example, Madeleine Albright, the secretary of
state, promised that ``we are not going to stand by and watch the
Serbian authorities do in Kosovo what they can no longer get away
with doing in Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Albright also said, that same month, ``The time to stop the
killing is now, before it spreads.'' Yet Clinton, like America's
allies in Europe, dithered.
</P>
<P>
   Second, consider that cozy phrase in the president's Saturday
address about a clear exit strategy. He has ample political reason
to promise one of these: whenever an American president sends
troops abroad, critics accuse him of marching into a Vietnam-style
quagmire, so those critics have to be anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, at the same time, the president's talk of an exit
strategy is dishonest, and consciously so. He knows perfectly well
that no date can be set in advance for the withdrawal of
peacekeepers: in Bosnia, after all, a deadline of one year was set,
but American troops remain in place three years after the Dayton
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday Mrs. Albright appeared on television to explain that
no deadline would be set in the case of Kosovo. So much for an exit
strategy, if Clinton meant a pre-timed one.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Kosovo address also failed to explain the general
principles that determine when intervention is advisable.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past six years, the president has intervened in
Somalia, Haiti and Bosnia. But he has also declined to intervene in
places beset by equally serious wars, such as Chechnya, Liberia,
Sudan, Angola, Burundi, and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of these instances, America had plausible cause to
intervene: it might have felt some moral responsibility to quell
the humanitarian disaster in Liberia, a country invented by America
as a home for its ex-slaves; or in Angola, where America's
ex-Cold-War friend, Jonas Savimbi, is responsible for much of the
current carnage. But no intervention was forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plainly feels that European wars threaten American
interests more than far-off African ones; not least because they
worry his European allies, whose cooperation he wants.
</P>
<P>
   In his radio address, he made the point that violence in Kosovo
might spread into the neighboring countries of Albania and
Macedonia, pouring fresh poison on the relationship between Greece
and Turkey (now rendered even murkier by the Ocalan business),
which are both NATO members.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton's critics, such as Senator Kay Bailey Hutchison of
Texas, retort that European wars should be fixed by European
powers. Even if the Hutchison idea is not entirely practical, it
has some political force.
</P>
<P>
   But, rather than tackling it explicitly and head-on, Clinton
brushed past, talking soothingly about how America can ``make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's glibness on Kosovo is not an isolated case. It is the
hallmark of his foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, the president has spotted a tough issue, taken
an admirable position on what should be done, and then failed to
implement it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton believes in freer trade, but lacks the perseverance to
build a constituency for it. He wants to pay America's debts to the
United Nations, but has not persuaded Congress to go along with
this.
</P>
<P>
   Just at the moment, Clinton is preparing to deploy an
anti-missile defense system. But he has not publicly explained why
he has dropped his old opposition to this scheme, or what he means
to do about the Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty, which is relevant to
the nuclear balance with Russia and which may now have to be
renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is a brilliant student who thinks he can succeed by
pulling an all-nighter at the last minute. This is not the best way
to conduct American foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   But, even though the Kosovo example is typical, it stands out
for its seriousness. If a NATO force is sent to Kosovo, it may well
have a difficult time: hard-liners on either side will resent the
cease-fire deal, and may take out their frustrations on the hapless
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Ivo Daalder, a former Clinton official now at the Brookings
Institution, worries that Kosovo might turn into a Somalia-style
mess: American troops will get killed, triggering a hasty
withdrawal and undermining American internationalism for a good
while thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are always risks in peacekeeping. America is
strong enough to take these risks on _ provided it has a president
who explains them honestly. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: QUOTE IN HEADLINE IS BY BENJAMIN DISRAELI.) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can
also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
