<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' BOBBY AYALA WANTS TO WIN BACK THE FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ It didn't hit Bobby Ayala until this week, when
the Mariner clubhouse at the Peoria Sports Complex started filling
up.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, who lives nearby and has been working out at the complex
for months, has seen the rest of the pitching staff arrive. No
Heathcliff Slocumb. No Paul Spoljaric. No Mike Timlin. No Bob
Wells.
</P>
<P>
   That's 2551/3 bullpen innings gone from 1998. Only one reliever
who threw more than 25 innings remains.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought Ayala would be the last man standing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would be the first guy to be gone,'' Ayala said.
``It's a business, and it's kind of hard to work trades with other
teams, but personally I thought I'd be the first one.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariner executives assured fans all winter that Ayala had thrown
his last pitch for the team. Two weeks ago, in a
question-and-answer session at the Mariners Fan Fest, club
president Chuck Armstrong said, ``We think Bobby Ayala will be a
very good pitcher again _ for another team.'' The crowd went wild.
</P>
<P>
   Even manager Lou Piniella, an Ayala loyalist, conceded this
week, ``I would think that a change of scenery would do him good,
and I'm saying that on his behalf, not ours.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners simply have found no takers. Ayala went 1-10
last year with a 7.29 earned run average, and he will make $1.8
million this year. The Mariners figure they might as well see how
he throws this spring in hopes of increasing teams' interest.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala understands this, but he doesn't really want to move on.
The Man You Love To Hate would prefer to win you back.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I want) to let (fans) know I'm a down-to-earth person and I'm
capable of pitching,'' Ayala said. ``No matter what they do, boo me
or not, I'm still gonna love them. I have nothing bad to say to
them. One day, when I'm throwing the ball good, I hope they
remember what they said about me or all the boos that they had, and
hopefully they will turn them around and think different of Bobby
Ayala.''
</P>
<P>
   As his '98 season spun out of control, Ayala stopped talking to
the media, closing an outlet that could have helped him communicate
with the fans who booed him. Now, he says, opening up is cathartic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had too many thoughts about failing and not doing my job,''
Ayala said. ``There's a lot of things like that in my head, and it
builds up. I realize, hey, I can't hold all that stuff in. I just
feel more free and open _ talk and let it out. It makes me feel a
lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala felt awful after last season. He didn't analyze and he
didn't agonize. He just went home and tried to forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a terrible year for myself,'' Ayala said. ``I was
very disappointed at the year I had and the way I pitched. But when
I got home, I just sat around and got away from baseball. ... I
didn't have to worry about going out the next day and seeing what's
gonna happen if I pitched again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala didn't think about baseball until starting workouts two
months ago. He put his career on rewind, passing over his five
years with Seattle and stopping on 1992 and '93 with the Cincinnati
Reds. He remembered having success there when he started each
inning from a windup instead of from the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of workouts, Ayala told his plan to pitching
coach Stan Williams, who approved an abbreviated windup that
stresses balance, which has sometimes been a problem for Ayala.
Apart from that, Ayala plans to keep things the same _ and it might
not be a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to find anyone who thinks the 29-year-old Ayala is a
lost cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``His arm strength is fine,'' said one American League scout.
``There's nothing wrong with his arm at all. He throws hard, and
his split is still a pretty good pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only problem is his delivery's been flawed too long to be
fixed, and it's going to prevent him from being more consistent
with his pitches. But he competes well, and obviously he needs a
change of scenery.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Dan Wilson played with Ayala in the Reds' system and
came to Seattle in the same trade before the '94 season. He's not
sure Ayala has to go. Wilson said Ayala has ``unbelievable talent''
but faltered last year because he left the splitter too high in the
strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like to see anybody go, because we're all family,''
Wilson said. ``We all heard the same (rumors), but I'm glad he's
here. It gives him the chance to prove to everyone he can still do
the job.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all Ayala wants.
</P>
<P>
   A trade wouldn't surprise him, and if it happens, he said he'd
thank the Mariners _ ``They've taken care of me, big-time'' _ and
be on his way.
</P>
<P>
   But he welcomes the chance to repair his relationship with
Mariner fans. He grew immune to the jeering, he said, and even was
able to laugh about it. On the season's last day, when fans booed a
giveaway Ayala cap, he rose from the bullpen and took a bow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still can work, I believe in it,'' Ayala said. ``I'm not
going to ever let myself down and say no, that it can't work. But
if Seattle thinks different, it's their job, they own me. They're
in charge of my move.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would still like to pitch here and prove to them that I
am still capable of pitching the way Bobby Ayala can pitch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
