u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     02-20 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS TRADE A LESSON FOR MARINERS ON HOW TO PLAY AN ACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Kingdome people, nearing the end of a nice run,
have mailed out special hankies. Mine is a cheery square of bright
white cotton bordered with tiny red hearts.
</P>
<P>
   There is an inscription: ``Wave goodbye to the Kingdome.''
</P>
<P>
   It is good to see someone in this city has a sense of humor. The
end is near. And maybe not just for the Kingdome, either.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Roger Clemens-to-the-Yankees-for-David Wells
post-trade pity party, Mariners style.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the pledge of optimism offered here just a week ago
when the Mariners convened their pre-spring training media briefing
and offered hope that this year's club will contend for the
American League West Division title?
</P>
<P>
   Forget about it. There is a time for the heady relief of
optimism and then there's a time to stop acting like a fool.
</P>
<P>
   It is time to get out the rye bread and mustard. Mariner
watchers have just been grand salamied.
</P>
<P>
   As the new ballpark gets trimmed in retro-look brick, as the
fences get moved in so the left-center power alley doesn't make
Alex Rodriguez and Edgar Martinez nuts and as plans for the
Kingdome's implosion are being made, the good ol' Yankees have
rained on our parade.
</P>
<P>
   So have the Blue Jays, who took one look at what kind of trouble
a sourpussed power pitcher can mean for the emotional well-being of
a ballclub and decided, unlike the Mariners a year ago, to ship
their malcontent out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Jays got something out of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse us, Woody Woodward and any of the 16 headless-horsemen
owners in charge of Mariner payroll and trades, but doesn't this
blockbuster deal make you squirm, even just a little?
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, it appears the baseball people in New York
and Toronto are allowed to make critical baseball decisions, which
is something we can't say for sure is happening in this city.
</P>
<P>
   Does this spring training kickoff/kick-butt trade not involve a
certain New York baseball club that, in the winter of 1997-98 when
the M's said they would not offer Randy Johnson a contract
extension, was ready to send Wells plus closer Mariano Rivera to
the Mariners for that 6-foot-10, scraggly-haired pitcher whose
strikeout power still exceeds his ability to pout, whine and go in
the tank under emotional duress?
</P>
<P>
   We believe it was the Yankees who were looking to make a deal,
only someone, somewhere in the Mariner organization decided no go,
just as someone, somewhere decided no go on a later Johnson deal
with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, now is the perfect time for some hand-wringing. We
believe Wells, who hurled a perfect game last May and was the
starting pitcher in the Yankees' 1998 World Series whipping of San
Diego, could have been a Mariner.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go to the videotape in the Mariners' archive of infamy:
</P>
<P>
   Instead of getting something huge out of the Johnson debacle _
and the beer-quaffing Wells is huge _ the Mariners were backed into
a humiliating deal at the stroke of the July 31 trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a Cy Young winner and franchise saver, for three
minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   You better believe Mariner skipper Lou Piniella is down in
Arizona right now, touting second baseman Carlos Guillen as the M's
opening day leadoff hitter despite Guillen's 25 percent propensity
to strike out.
</P>
<P>
   You better believe right-handed pitcher Freddy Garcia is one of
the highly anticipated prospects in Mariner camp.
</P>
<P>
   Freddy and Carlos. Guillen and Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly names that take the sting out of losing Johnson. Not
the way Wells, Graeme Lloyd and Homer Bush take some of the sting
out of the Blue Jays losing Clemens and the two Cy Youngs he picked
up in Toronto to display alongside his previous three.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Mariners see it, their two former Astro farm hands
can't make a name quick enough, because until Guillen is the second
coming of Chuck Knoblauch and until Garcia wins 20 games, strikes
out 280 and wins a Cy Young, the Johnson trade will still leave a
stench.
</P>
<P>
   The Wells-Clemens deal does nothing but remind us again of one
certain fact: The Mariners failed to secure a top-notch starter
this offseason. They failed to fill a major hole on a club that has
too much talent to waste. And they have arrived at this juncture
because for the past 18 months or more, no one stopped to think
what it would be like to open the new stadium with Butch Henry or
Billy Swift on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   No offense to Jeff Fassero and Jamie Moyer, but in the absence
of the skid-stopping Johnson, it would have been nice to have had a
guy like David Wells to lean on.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's shoulders were pretty broad. But Wells' gut is
broader, which can only be expected from a man who David Letterman
said last spring celebrated his perfect game by setting down 27
consecutive Heinekens.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, citizens of Marinerville can't drink to that.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
