<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HOUNDING HILLARY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gotham reporters have missed a few big stories over the years.
They still haven't figured out, for instance, that Bruce Wayne is
Batman.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in every story about Hillary Clinton running for the Senate
here, it is suggested that she might be scared off by a howling New
York press pack that relishes asking the unaskable.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Breslin rolled out the welcome mat in Newsday, writing
that the First Lady would face questions like: ``Is your husband
going to come here with you so the two of you can mortify the whole
city when he cavorts with young workers?''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Newfield, a columnist at The New York Post, visualized a
Hillary campaign for ``Nightline'': ``She is going to be sitting in
Katz's Delicatessen with her mouth full of knish and 30 guys are
going to be yelling at her to explain the $100,000 profit she made
in the commodity trade in Arkansas in 1979.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to conjure up tabloid headlines: ``Hillary to Israel:
Drop Dead.'' And you can almost hear the reporters raucously
calling out: ``Hey, LA-DY, First LA-DY, over here, you, Hill!''
</P>
<P>
   Some speculate that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has broken the spirit
of the New York press corps _ blocking attempts to fathom the
health of his marriage. Even a few pressies wonder if their
reputation for ferocity may be overdrawn. ``I don't know if we're
dogged bloodhounds as much as sniping chihuahuas,'' says Andrew
Kirtzman, the host of ``Inside City Hall'' on New York 1.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's tete-a-tete with Sen. Pat Moynihan about his
seat only ratcheted up the frenzy. In case this is more than an ego
trip for Mrs. Clinton, I called some media big shots to ask what
they would ask her if she runs. Here are their questions:
</P>
<P>
   Eric Mink, New York Daily News: ``In 1992, you and your husband
made a joint appearance after the Super Bowl on `60 Minutes.' The
interview in which your husband denied having had an affair with
Gennifer Flowers was credited with salvaging his primary campaign.
Exactly six years later, you sat with Matt Lauer of the `Today'
show and declared there was no substance to the allegations about
your husband and Monica Lewinsky. Don't you think, Mrs. Clinton,
that you have to acknowledge that you were made to look completely
ridiculous?''
</P>
<P>
   Don Imus: ``Do you realize that New York City is not the capital
of New York state? How will your whole Palestinian state deal fly
with all these New Yorkers? And what about your close friendship
with Mr. Hymietown, try to explain that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennet Conant, Vanity Fair: ``Do you have to bring Bill?''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Sheehy, Hillary biographer: ``I've been told by a White
House press secretary that you think that any questions about
feelings and motivations are psychobabble and yucky. New Yorkers
want to know: What do you have against therapy?''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Barrett, Village Voice: ``If you were a member of the
United States Senate, would you have voted for the welfare reform
bill that targeted women and their children? Did you kick his
(deleted) for that?''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Kolbert, The New Yorker: ``How many counties are in
New York?''
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Molloy, gossip columnist at The Daily News: ``How did you
feel the day the president said, `I'm sorry, Monica'?''
</P>
<P>
   James Stewart, author of ``Blood Sport'': ``When billing records
documenting your work on the McDougals' Castle Grande trailer park
development were discovered in the family quarters of the White
House, you said you had no idea how they got there. Do you have any
idea now?''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Johnson, Page Six, New York Post: ``What would you say
to the conspiracy theorists who believe you had Vince Foster
killed?''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Isaacson, managing editor of Time: ``Why, after all this,
would you want to be in public life?''
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Pressman, WNBC: ``To be a junior senator, are you willing
to forsake the insulation of the White House to deal every day with
people like me peppering you with questions you may not want to
answer?''
</P>
<P>
   Dominic Carter, New York 1: ``I would really press her: Do you
plan on being the first woman president?''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Dicker, New York Post: ``In which month does the northern
zone deer-hunting season open?''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dwyer, New York Daily News: ``Pick one for your team.
Sprewell or Oakley? Clemens or Wells? Donna or Rudy?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
