</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DON ' T WORRY, SPORTSMANSHIP WON'T BE CATCHING  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A team turned back a victory the other day. Said they just did
not want to win that way. Thanks but no thanks.
</P>
<P>
   The wonder is that the incident happened in professional sports,
where sportsmanship seems to come along once a millennium. We are,
after all, in a world in which Pat Riley fines his basketball
players for helping an opponent off the floor, and football teams
keep victories even if they involve fifth-down touchdowns or gross
officiating mistakes at the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but the gesture of sacrifice and fair play also
took place in English soccer, which is inhabited, as all we smug
Americans know, by thugs and hooligans, on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it happened. Arsenal of London did not accept a
2-1 victory over Sheffield United eight days ago because the
winning goal was tainted by an apparently innocent breach of
ethics.
</P>
<P>
   There was no mistake by the official, just a violation of
sporting behavior that players themselves have evolved. Yes, I
know, these are the same mugs who spend much of their time fouling
and diving for every millimeter of advantage on the field, so it is
a shock when sportsmanship shows its tender little face.
</P>
<P>
   It was that noble impulse that led Alex Radulescu of Germany to
concede a let at 4-4 in the fifth set to MaliVai Washington during
a Wimbledon quarterfinal match in 1996. (Washington swept the last
two games and lavishly praised his opponent afterward.)
</P>
<P>
   Other tennis players have been known to call a let against
themselves, giving up, after all, only one point, not a precious
soccer goal or a hard-fought football touchdown. There is also an
assumption that you can trust just about any pro golfer to report a
violation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mass amount of faking and diving, in the past decade
soccer players have refined the tactic of kicking the ball out of
bounds to stop play if they see somebody down with apparent damage
to the head or a broken bone. They take the chance of being
hoodwinked, but they use their own judgment _ and the system works,
due to old-fashioned respect between opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In this Football Association cup game at Arsenal's field, a
Sheffield player went down, and the Sheffield goalkeeper kicked the
ball out of bounds, a normal tactic.
</P>
<P>
   After the player was treated _ nothing serious, as it turned out
_ Arsenal put the ball in bounds with an overhead throw. Normally,
the ball would have been allowed to bounce directly to a Sheffield
player, but this time it was intercepted by Nwankwo Kanu, a young
Nigerian substitute just acquired by Arsenal. Not grasping the
significance of the soft inbounds toss, Kanu kicked a crisp pass to
Marc Overmars, a seasoned Dutch teammate, who instinctively banged
the ball in the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheffield team went nuts, and many of the Arsenal players
were openly unhappy, but the referee did not nullify the goal
because there is no rule governing it. If he had been thinking
quickly, the referee could have waved off the goal, saying he had
not yet adjusted his watch, or some other fiction, but he counted
the goal, and the game ended at 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately afterward, the coach of Arsenal, the Frenchman
Arsene Wenger, announced that he was declining the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I offered the replay because it wasn't right to win that way _
it wasn't Arsenal,'' Wenger said, adding, ``The best we can do is
offer to replay the game here against Sheffield United.''
</P>
<P>
   The game will be replayed on Tuesday, at Arsenal's field, with
ticket prices cut in half to avoid any suggestion of chicanery to
set up an extra payday.
</P>
<P>
   English soccer referees are sputtering that the game is being
taken out of their hands, and many soccer buffs are fretting about
a dangerous precedent.
</P>
<P>
   My theory is, Sheffield deserved a second chance at the upset,
particularly because the players have arrived at the injury timeout
through their own wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, this is not going to start any worldwide Oprahfest of
athletes rushing to confession. We are not going to see Pakistani
and Indian cricket players making decisions against themselves. We
are not going to see Tour de France cyclists turning themselves in
for receiving blatant pushes by the crowds who line steep inclines
in the Pyrenees. We are not going to see hockey goalies admitting
the puck slipped over the line.
</P>
<P>
   In our own bloated and tedious sport of American football, let
us harken back to last December, when the Jets received a gift
victory because officials mistakenly ruled that Vinny Testaverde
had crossed the goal line. I never expected kindly Bill Parcells to
say, ``Hey, we don't want to make the playoffs because of some
mistake by the refs.''
</P>
<P>
   The last refusal of a touchdown may have taken place in 1940
when Cornell gave back a 7-3 victory over Dartmouth after
rudimentary game films proved the touchdown had come on a fifth
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't made that decision, we'd have been explaining
that game as long as football has a place in intercollegiate
athletics,'' said Edmund Ezra Day, the Cornell president.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, in more cutthroat competition, Notre Dame in 1961
and Miami of Florida in 1972 and Colorado in 1990 all had chances
to turn back officials' mistakes, but declined _ respectfully, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are part of the game. I never expected the Kansas City
Royals to come rushing on the field and admit Jorge Orta was
clearly out at first base in the play that turned around the 1985
World Series. I'm not holding my breath for Houston's Hakeem
Olajuwon and Scottie Pippen to say they got the superstar benefit
of chicken fouls in New Jersey on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Au contraire. Athletes are conditioned to fool the officials, to
stumble backward and draw the foul, to elicit sympathy. Arsenal
does not survive near the top of the Premier Division without its
share of discreet hackers and flailing divers.
</P>
<P>
   But here was a case in which the players' own code was violated,
probably by accident, and the players and coaches corrected the
error, before it was etched in the record books.
</P>
<P>
   My advice to nervous officials and twittery purists in England
is to chill out. The lads were surely hacking and diving all over
that green and pleasant land Saturday. Gamesmanship lives. I
reassure everybody that this is not the start of some fearful
epidemic of sportsmanship.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
