u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LEFTHANDER-SHORTA     02-20 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEFTHANDER-SHORTAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFTHANDED PITCHERS HAVE (AS LONG AS THEY CAN PITCH) JOB SECURITY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Clemens and Mark McGwire have job security. So do Greg
Cadaret and Tony Fossas.
</P>
<P>
   With pitchers and catchers in spring training, Cadaret is in the
Los Angeles Dodgers' camp and Fossas is in the Texas Rangers' camp.
They do not have quite the same security Clemens and McGwire have;
nor do they have the salaries those stars earn. But they and their
fellow left-handed relief pitchers hold a position other players
envy. Jobs always seem to be available to them; barring injury, no
matter what their age is, teams are always ready to sign them.
</P>
<P>
   Every team would like to have a Clemens or a McGwire but cannot.
Every team makes sure it has that commodity known as the
left-handed reliever.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have them,'' said Doug Melvin, the Rangers'
general manager, who last season employed both Cadaret and Fossas.
``You always need them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're left-handed,'' Kevin Malone, the Dodgers' general
manager, said, ``you've got a chance probably to pitch five years
longer than one might expect. There's a real need for left-handed
pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Cadaret and Fossas are always employed. That is why
teams keep taking chances on Norm Charlton. That is why Dan Plesac
continues to work years after he lost his effectiveness as a
closer. That is why Jim Poole epitomizes the itinerant worker,
moving from team to team but never lacking a job. That is why
Graeme Lloyd is a valuable inclusion in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't necessarily need them as the closer,'' Melvin said.
``But you need them in the fifth and sixth or sixth and seventh for
one or two batters because your starters don't go very far anymore.
I think they're valuable to get one hitter out. Tony Fossas
pitching for us last year gave up one hit in 16 at-bats against
left-handers.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams do not place the same emphasis on getting right-handed
relievers as they do on left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's focused on as much because right-handers
seem to be more plentiful,'' Malone said. ``They're more available,
so it's not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Even beyond availability, though, managers seem to place more
emphasis on having a left-handed specialist to pitch to a
left-handed hitter than summoning a right-handed reliever to face a
particular right-handed hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Assenmacher has made a long and profitable career out of
coming into a game, pitching to one or two left-handed batters,
then leaving. In the past three years, while Mariano Rivera of the
Yankees has pitched 240 2/3 innings in 181 games, Assenmacher has
pitched 142 2/3 innings in 207 games for Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But why the greater emphasis on the need of lefty vs. lefty than
righty vs. righty?
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective is to at least take the power away from
left-handed hitters,'' Melvin said. ``Most left-handers are
breaking-ball pitchers. The ball moves. You don't want to give up
that two, three-run homer. You still may give up a hit, but you try
to take the power away.''
</P>
<P>
   When Malone was assistant general manager in Baltimore, he said,
the Orioles were fortunate to have ``one of the best in the
business,'' Jesse Orosco, who has pitched in the major leagues for
18 years and will be 42 years old three weeks into the season.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Orosco gave up two home runs to left-handed hitters
but held them to a .205 batting average. He is not strictly a
specialist, though, and did a pretty good job against right-handed
hitters, too, registering a .232 average. ``Left-handers get better
with age,'' Malone said. ``With the experience, they become more
effective to get left-handed hitters out. They are part of a
quality bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how often they are released, left-handed relievers
find jobs. Fossas pitched for the Mariners, the Cubs and the
Rangers last season, Cadaret for the Angels and the Rangers,
Charlton for the Orioles and the Braves, Poole for the Giants and
the Indians, Alan Embree for the Braves and the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   This spring Fossas is with the Rangers, Cadaret with the
Dodgers, Charlton with the Devil Rays, Poole with the Phillies and
Embree with the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Teams prefer older, more experienced left-handers like Fossas
(41 years old) and Cadaret (37) to younger pitchers who are not
battle-tested. Occasionally, a younger left-hander becomes
attractive. Ricardo Rincon, 27, is one such reliever. Left-handed
hitters batted .131 against him and hit no home runs last season
when he played for Pittsburgh. The Pirates since have traded him to
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was after him,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Some left-handed relievers belie their role. Dennis Cook of the
Mets, for example, was more effective last season against
right-handed hitters than left-handers, giving up 29 hits,
including two home runs, in 97 at-bats to left-handers (.299) but
only two more hits and one more home run in 56 more at-bats to
right-handers for a .203 average.
</P>
<P>
   Xavier Hernandez, on the other hand, is a right-handed reliever
who was almost as effective against left-handers (.213) as
right-handers (.203). ``But,'' Melvin said, ``would you bring him
in to face Tino Martinez with the bases loaded, or Fossas?''
</P>
<P>
   Being left-handed, though, doesn't guarantee immortality.
Sometimes the arm, even the left one, just gives out.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bailes reached the majors at age 23 in 1986, pitched for
the Indians for four years, worked for the Angels for three more,
then pitched briefly in the minors in 1993 before retiring for
three years. Then the Rangers, in the typical never-ending search
for left-handed relievers, located him and dragged his 34-year-old
body off the scrap heap.
</P>
<P>
   For the first four months of the 1997 season, he pitched in the
minors. Then he joined the Rangers early in August and relieved in
24 games for them. Last season he relieved in 46 games. But his
shoulder bothered him all season, and he had rotator cuff surgery
in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``His shoulder hasn't responded very well,'' Joe Bick, Bailes'
agent, said. ``He's been throwing the vast majority of the winter
and he hasn't been feeling real good. He has not formally announced
his retirement, but that's what he's going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Give Bailes another year or two, though, and someone else may
come calling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
