</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the Numbers and the Shrills
</P>
<P>
   In complaining about the Yankees' still growing payroll, other
teams point to the salaries given players like Bernie Williams and
the team's willingness to add players like Roger Clemens. But an
even more telling barometer of the Yankees' spending style is the
$3.4 million salary Joe Girardi will have this season as their
backup catcher. Thirty-three catchers caught more games than
Girardi last year, and only six will have higher salaries this
year: Mike Piazza, Ivan Rodriguez, Javier Lopez, Charles Johnson,
Dan Wilson and Chris Hoiles.
</P>
<P>
   The number 125 has become imbedded in mantra-like recitation as
the number of games the Yankees won last year. But only 114
victories appear on their record because that is how many games
they won during the season. If people continue to cite 125 as the
number, they will have to revise the history of other years and say
that the 1906 Chicago Cubs won 118, the 1986 Mets 116 and the 1970
Baltimore Orioles and the 1975 Cincinnati Reds 115 each. Teams can
win more games now, of course, because of the extra post-season
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   At Derek Jeter's salary arbitration hearing last week, his agent
introduced a newspaper comment made by Tim Raines to show the
shortstop's popularity with fans: ``With the way women scream in
high-pitched voices, it's like he's the second coming of the
Beatles.'
</P>
<P>
   Some Team Styles Are Relaxed
</P>
<P>
   Last week was a momentous week for baseball and not because the
Yankees got Roger Clemens. One team, the Cincinnati Reds, and one
manager, Buck Showalter of Arizona, eliminated their rules banning
beards and mustaches. Greg Vaughn (Reds) and Randy Johnson
(Diamondbacks) were responsible for inducing the enlightened
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some day Showalter will even be able to acknowledge that
he was off base several years ago when he criticized Ken Griffey
Jr. for wearing his cap backward during batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch Money Lures the Best
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers enraged other teams by giving Kevin
Brown $105 million for seven years. The signing confirmed the worst
fears that some other owners and officials had when Peter O'Malley
sold the Dodgers to Rupert Murdoch. But Murdoch money has been
flowing freely, too, in not so public ways.
</P>
<P>
   An executive of an American League club said Kevin Malone, the
Dodgers' new general manager, called people from other clubs during
the winter and said, ``I struck an oil well out here; are you ready
to leave?''
</P>
<P>
   Malone used Murdoch oil to lure Ed Creech away from St. Louis,
where he had been scouting director, to become the Dodgers'
director of scouting operations. Within a couple of years Creech is
expected to double his Cardinals' salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to deny him permission to talk to them,'' Walt
Jocketty, the Cardinals' general manager, said. ``If I had, we were
going to have an unhappy employee. We couldn't compete with those
salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone also hired Bill Geivett from Tampa Bay, where he had been
assistant to the general manager, to become assistant to the
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Teams that feel they cannot compete with wealthier clubs for
high-priced players tend to emphasize scouting and player
development. But they feel they will begin to lose out there, too,
if teams like the Dodgers are going to use money to hire the best
people away from them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
