<HEADER>
A2623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      02-20 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WATER'S FINE, BUT THE SALMON ARE LACKING  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By NICHOLAS KARAS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sergei Sokalov lay on his side on the sloping bank of the
Varzina River near Murmansk, his feet toward the water, body
propped up on his left elbow, and the ever-present burning
cigarette dangling from between his fingers. For the moment, it was
difficult to imagine that he was once a Soviet biathlon athlete. A
lot has changed in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   He watched as I cast a large Mickey Finn streamer across the
current. The river was full but clear, slightly above its banks.
Its force straightened the line, pulling the red and yellow fly in
a large, sweeping arc until it rigidly faced upstream. During the
next five minutes, I swung the rod tip back and forth across the
river's surface to make the fly swim in, then away, from the
boulder-strewn bank.
</P>
<P>
   Hitless, I lifted the fly rod tip to begin still another cast.
As the fly rose upstream, then to the surface, and just before
becoming airborne, a salmon engulfed it. A few minutes later, a
spent grilse came protesting toward the guide's landing net. It was
the fifth grilse I had landed in as many hours of fishing. A grilse
is a precocious salmon, between 15 and 18 inches, that returns to
its brith stream after but a year at sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a good sign,'' Sokalov said in English. ``This is
the best week of the season. The river should be filled with
salmon. It was last year.'' Grilse don't count in the angler's
book. Most are released. To be called a salmon, it must weigh seven
pounds or more and have been at sea for three or more years before
their first return to their natal stream.
</P>
<P>
   I was alone on Finn Pool, one of a dozen named pools on the
Varzina, and was about to cast again when I heard the roar of a
converted Russian military helicopter. It was flying downriver at
tree-top level, to return us to the lodge a mile downstream. As I
stepped out of the river, some 50 feet away, near the opposite
bank, a salmon jumped clear of the water. It was a bright fish,
fresh from the sea, about 15 pounds, with a blue back, and white
sides and belly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Varzina was the hottest salmon river on Russia's
Kola Peninsula, which is shaped like a thick thumb and is 160 miles
wide and juts 250 miles eastward. It is washed by the White Sea on
the south and east sides, and by Barents Sea, an arm of the Arctic
Ocean, on the north. Most of the Kola, the heart of Lapland, is
above the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   When I fished it last July, daylight lasted 24 hours. From its
interior flow 80 rivers, 60 of which contain Atlantic salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Its most famous is the Kola River that flows north through its
isthmus to Murmansk and the ocean. For centuries, Kola's rivers
were the exclusive realm of czars and kings. During the last 70
years, they were the private property of Communist officials. It
wasn't until 1987 that several Americans and Erro Pettersson, a
Finn, established permanent camps. Today, 15 are on as many rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular and first developed for sport fishing was the
Ponoi, an east-flowing river of gigantic magnitude. The first men
to open salmon fishing for foreigners were Gary Loomis of Seattle
and his partner Bill Davis. Their camp manager and logistics whiz,
which in Russia can challenge the most cerebral person, was
Pettersson. His newest camp is on the Varzina. It opened in 1997
and its largest salmon was a 35-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   A surplus of military helicopters and cheap kerosene has made
recreational fishing a reality. However, salmon fishing anywhere is
not inexpensive. The cost of a week on the Varzina, including
traveling from Murmansk and back, ranges from $3,850 for the first
and last four weeks of the 14-week season, that begins June 13, to
$6,950 during the last week of June and the first two in July.
These three weeks are considered the best on the Varzina as well as
other Kola rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Varzina River Camp (fax: 358-9-452-4314) supports 14 rods
with two anglers per guide. When I fished, three guides were
Russian and four were Finns. All spoke English. No angler
monopolized a pool. Rods and guides were taken out each day and
evening to different pools that were rotated among the fishers.
Anglers were also flown to the nearby Penka and Sidrovka rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The best pools proved to be Golden Pool and nearby Home Pool, at
the foot of the lodge built on a high glacial plateau. The lodge is
at the head of tidewater, four miles from the Barents Sea. A mile
north of the lodge is the abandoned settlement of Varzino. It
consisted of two dozen houses and was populated by a mixture of
Laps and Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the peninsula and its Atlantic salmon are the last
vestige of a wholly wild land and fish. No roads or permanent
settlements are on any river except Murmansk, at the mouth of the
Kola river. While every salmon river in North America and Europe is
polluted, the Kola's waters are pristine. Despite the Varzina's
virgin condition, the July run last year was disappointing. That
month, there were 75 percent fewer salmon than the previous July.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian meteorologists believed one factor was the
aftereffect of El Nino. It caused one arm of the jet stream to
cross from the United States into eastern Canada and across the
polar cap, bringing cold, damp weather to the Arctic coast of
Russia. In the six days we fished, three were fog shrouded. We were
told, snow fell twice on the river the previous week. During the
week, 18 salmon and 30 grilse were landed. Most grilse were
released. The salmon ranged from 7 to 22 pounds. The 22-pounder was
a hen taken by Kristian Marinovik of Santiago, Chile. He and fellow
Chilean Gonzalo Cortes also caught the most grilse.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost the summer that wasn't. By mid-August, a rush of
hot, humid weather finally caused reluctant salmon milling about in
the frigid waters of the Varzina's fjord-like estuary to re-enter
the river and trek upstream. ``Fishing recovered quickly,'' said
Pettersson, ``but some fish must have decided to spend another year
at sea. Our final tally was three-quarters of what it had been the
year before. I know El Nino is gone, and that La Nina is wet and
warm. She is just what we need this year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
