u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT &LR;      02-20 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLOT THICKENS FOR AMERICA'S CUP TV  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA LLOYD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It appeared last month that a competing sponsorship deal might
force ESPN to drop its plans for televising the 1999-2000 America's
Cup races. But the cable sports network now says it has a new
contract in the works that would allow the show to go on.
</P>
<P>
   What had given ESPN pause was an agreement negotiated by Young
America, the New York Yacht Club's cup syndicate, that could
potentially flood ESPN's screen with advertising logos on its sails
from Fox Sports Net. That sports network is ESPN's staunchest rival
in cable television.
</P>
<P>
   The battle may seem to be no more than a tempest in a television
teapot. But in fact, the heart and soul of America's Cup as a
global event hangs in the balance. If ESPN pulls out of the deal,
as it has threatened once before, it could jeopardize fund-raising
for most cup syndicates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any international team sees the United States as a huge
market,'' Bob Billingham, chief operating officer for the America
One challenger in San Francisco, said. ``Television is one of the
biggest things you sell to sponsors. They look for their branding
on the sails and boats. It's very important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Glover, executive vice president of programming for ESPN,
said late Friday that his organization now expects to receive a
clean feed _ no Fox ads _ from the America's Cup races. The
competition is to be shown on ESPN for viewers in North America
beginning in October, when the cup trial races begin off Auckland,
New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   By ``clean feed,'' Glover means TV footage void of any competing
network verbiage or logos. In its independent deal with Fox, signed
last month, Young America agreed to allow Fox to attach corporate
logos to Young America's yacht and sails as it races against other
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The group representing the competition's 15 teams, the America's
Cup Challenge Association, confirmed that a revised contract with
ESPN is scheduled to be signed February 22 despite the Young
America deal.
</P>
<P>
   David Elwell, chairman of the challenge association, said late
Friday that the challenge group is ``extraordinarily happy that
ESPN is doing the television feed. We feel they're the best in that
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Elwell said that America's Cup 2000, the event organizer in New
Zealand, also has agreed to the tentative new ESPN contract. Final
approval, however, hinges on 100 percent approval by the 15
challenge teams, including Young America.
</P>
<P>
   Basic to the new deal is that all 15 challengers must agree not
to allow any sponsors to put signage on their boats if the
corporation competes with ESPN. Glover conceded that the rule opens
up a gray area as to which advertising ESPN might oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Like two planets moving in opposite directions along the same
orbit, that means the competing networks _ ESPN and Fox _ may still
be on a collision course. It appears that Young America remains
knee-deep in a pricey $2.5 million sponsorship deal with Fox _ all
signed and sealed _ that says Fox can advertise on the Young
America yacht as much as it wants within event rules.
</P>
<P>
   John Marshall, the president of Young America who also helped to
negotiate his syndicate's deal with Fox, declined to comment
Friday. But it appears that the agreement he crafted still stands
as written last month. ``We have a sponsorship with Fox, and that
has not changed,'' Jane Eagleson, a syndicate spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the sphere of contract rights is the New York Yacht
Club, which sources say is unhappy with its charge, Young America.
At a board of trustees meeting about two weeks ago, executives of
the club reportedly told the syndicate that it needs to undo the
Fox contract.
</P>
<P>
   Since about 90 percent of the syndicate's operating funds - so
far, about $24 million - comes from club members and affiliations,
the syndicate clearly is between the proverbial rock and a hard
place.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, for one, is unlikely to let Young America off the hook. Its
rivalry with ESPN is well-known within the industry. In a show to
be aired Monday night on HBO's ``Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel,''
David Hill, president of Fox Sports, takes on ESPN about its
America's Cup broadcast rights:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it could be a very clever marketing ploy, don't you?''
Hill said to Steve Bornstein, ESPN's president.
</P>
<P>
   Bornstein replied: ``It'll never get on our air. We're not in
the business of televising our competitor's logos.''
</P>
<P>
   Vince Wladika, a senior vice president at Fox Sports, said that
Hill was not available for comment Friday. ``There's really nothing
to talk about until a deal has been signed,'' Wladika said about
the revised ESPN contract.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
