<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: OLD, AND SOMETIMES SENTIMENTAL  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ ``I'm getting old,'' George Steinbrenner is
saying, around the corner from the Yankees' clubhouse here at
Legends Field, away from the cameras, apart from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of those big-news days that Steinbrenner lives for,
that for more than a quarter century he's been able to invent.
Roger Clemens is here, being welcomed into the Yankee family. It is
a day to feel the limitless possibilities of an unborn season. But
these days, Steinbrenner talks about getting old. At 68. A tanned
and rested 68.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' he says, ``that's getting old.''
</P>
<P>
   Old, and sometimes sentimental, but the Boss wants to make one
thing perfectly clear. He is not, in his ``getting old'' years,
going soft.
</P>
<P>
   He makes this point, unwittingly perhaps, by snapping at a
clubhouse kid wheeling a laundry cart through the narrow corridor,
pinning us against the wall. ``That can't wait?'' he asks. The kid
shrugs, pushes on. He does not get fired. Maybe he is getting just
a bit soft, around the edges, like an aging bear.
</P>
<P>
   I ask about his displays of public emotion, the crying game
during the clubhouse celebration after the clinching game of the
World Series in San Diego last October. On my television screen, he
looked close to tears several times at ESPN's annual awards show
last week in New York, especially when Joe Torre raised a trophy to
Steinbrenner in the audience and thanked him, poignantly, for being
the best Boss.
</P>
<P>
   A Boss increasingly in touch with his inner self, like Vincent,
on HBO's mafia series, ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not choke up at the ESPYs,'' Steinbrenner says, shaking
his head. ``No...no. I was happy for Joe, for my players. To be
named the best team of the year, going against the Chicago Bulls
and the Denver Broncos? That's an accomplishment to be proud of.
But I can tell you that I did not choke up at the ESPYs.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the World Series, yes, I was very choked up because I
worked harder on that team than any other I've had, and because
right before we got up there, I had been in there with Bud Selig,
and we'd been talking about all we'd been through together, as
owners, and now with him being commissioner. And then when he
handed us the trophy ...''
</P>
<P>
   The Boss lost it, right in front of Nielsen Nation, and then
came the speculation that this was the signal that a quarter
century run as the country's most prominent sports franchise owner
might be over. The sale of the team to Cablevision's Charles Dolan
was coming. Steinbrenner was going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said this before and I'll say it again,'' he said.
``Whatever is worked out, I'll be here. I have a son and a
son-in-law who want to take over, and will. The Yankees and the
Steinbrenner family will be together for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The family business. It still comes first. It came before
whatever sentimental attachment Steinbrenner had formed for David
Wells, who won 18 games last season, lost 4, pitched a perfect
game, won the swing game, Game 5, of the American League
Championship Series. He became a true Yankee character, a New York
folk hero who stood on that same ESPY stage last week and spoke of
his love for his ``new home.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words rumbled through Steinbrenner's mind earlier this
week like a subway train. There were, he admitted, moments when he
had second thoughts after his baseball people had unanimously voted
to make the deal. How could he trade David Wells, he asked himself?
A few times he could feel himself wanting to reach for the phone;
he could feel the urge to overturn the vote. But that, he said,
would've been letting his emotions run wild at the worst of all
times, in the middle of a business deal. That, he said, would've
been soft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started thinking about how they crucified me when I let
Jimmy Key go and decided to sign Wells,'' he said. ``Then I said to
myself, `My God, how could you not want a Roger Clemens on your
team?' This is business, this is baseball. I've never been an
Eisenhower. I'm a Patton.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs and says, ``Howard Cosell called me that.''
</P>
<P>
   The blue shirt he is wearing is a gift that was presented to him
the night he made his peace with Yogi Berra by visiting the Berra
Museum in Little Falls, N.J. When Darryl Strawberry walks by, they
joke around, and half embrace, which apparently means that
Strawberry is forgiven for missing an autograph session last week
at the Florida State Fair without a note from his Boss.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner even admits he is interested in the publicized
efforts of his friend, Congressman Charles Rangel, to seek federal
aid to redevelop the Yankee Stadium area, and would strongly
consider, under such terms, keeping the team in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not a kid anymore,'' he says, ``you do care a
little more what people think of you. But, you are who you are. I
still love being able to do what I do, to go out and make Yankee
fans happy.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ``getting old'' age, he shook up his 125-victory
defending champions and reeled in Roger Clemens. When everyone
thought he was going soft, he cried no tears over David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything,'' he says, ``I still love being the
Boss.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
