<HEADER>
A2638 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEDERAL-POLICE-REVIEW     02-20 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDERAL-POLICE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEDERAL CASE: PILING IT ON TO THE G-MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There was a time when G-men wore fedoras and hunted
down bank robbers, kidnappers and spies. Now, in addition to all
that, federal law-enforcement agents are being asked to track down
carjackers, wife beaters, drunk drivers and low-level drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The change in responsibilities has prompted some legal experts
to warn of the emergence of a national police force. It has also
raised a more prosaic issue.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen if the federal agents really got serious?
</P>
<P>
   Last week a special task force of the American Bar Association,
headed by former Attorney General Edwin Meese, issued a strongly
worded warning about the trend in Congress to federalize crimes
that are traditionally handled by state and local authorities.
Calling the trend ``misguided, unnecessary and even harmful,'' the
panel said, ``It reflects a phenomenon capable of altering and
undermining the careful decentralization of criminal law authority
that has worked well for all our constitutional history.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been so eager to be seen as tough on crime that it
has enacted a host of laws in recent years making crimes like
carjacking and drive-by shootings federal offenses. In fact, more
than 40 percent of all federal criminal statutes enacted since the
Civil War were placed on the books after 1970.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of the chest-thumping surrounding the passage of new
federal criminal laws, the panel said, the federal government does
little to protect Americans from crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of feel-good legislation,'' said Meese, who, had a
tough-on-crime reputation when he was attorney general during the
second half of the Reagan administration. ``It's passed because
it's politically popular or because a particular crime gets a lot
of media attention. But what we found was that the new laws aren't
utilized very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Of nearly 60,000 criminal cases filed in federal courts in the
1997 fiscal year, 164 were carjackings. There were no drive-by
shooting or domestic violence cases, crimes that got much media
attention when they were included in a major crime bill passed in
1994. Even in crimes like drug trafficking and possession _ an area
where the federal government has been quite active _ only 1.5
percent of the more than 1 million drug arrests in the country in
1997 were prosecuted by federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increased federalization is rarely, if ever, likely to have
any appreciable effect on the categories of violent crime that most
concern Americans,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The legal scholars who made up the panel suggested that if
federal courts become overwhelmed with these criminal cases, they
may be prevented from handling antitrust, civil rights and other
civil matters that state courts cannot hear.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all they warn about what they see as a trend toward a
national police force, an issue that so concerned the framers of
the Constitution that they forbade the use of the military to
enforce domestic laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 1218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1021 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEDERAL-POLICE-REVIEW     02-20 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDERAL-POLICE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEDERAL CASE: PILING IT ON TO THE G-MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There was a time when G-men wore fedoras and hunted
down bank robbers, kidnappers and spies. Now, in addition to all
