<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-CHANGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON DECK FOR YANKEES: CRASH COURSE IN INTENSITY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ A clubhouse full of pinstriped pitchers eagerly
awaited the arrival of Roger Clemens here Saturday. To rookie Ryan
Bradley, to long-time pitcher David Cone, Clemens is seen as a
great store of knowledge. Clemens will be asked questions and
watched closely, the way a former president might if he were
teaching a college course after leaving the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's probably the best pitcher in the game, and there
are a lot of people in here who are going to learn from him,'' said
the reliever Jeff Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   When club officials determined to trade for Clemens three days
ago, they assumed the five-time Cy Young Award winner would provide
more than just a well-pitched ball game every fifth day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is someone who has incredible presence,'' Cone said. ``He
has Paul O'Neill-type intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone does not freely throw around comparisons to O'Neill, who is
said to set the tone for how the position players on this team
focus deeply on each at-bat. O'Neill's inner rage is unique, and
similarly, Clemens' approach to his work is legendary: his workouts
between starts, his intense approach to each game, the detailed
notes he keeps on hitters and umpires. Yankees pitchers will watch
and learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if he's in a trance on the day he pitches, from what I
hear,'' Cone said. ``That's something I'm kind of anxious to see.
He's almost unapproachable _ you don't even want to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to compare notes with him. Once the young guys get
over their awe of him, he'll be able to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte had a poster of Clemens on his wall when he was a
teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, the Yankees' best pitching prospect, has always seen
Clemens as his idol; the Yankees played the Blue Jays shortly after
Bradley was promoted last year, and as the Yankees worked out,
Bradley could hardly contain himself from rushing to the other side
of the field just to get a look at Clemens, in the flesh. He wanted
to meet him and shake his hand, but never got the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bradley and Clemens will share the same field, the same
clubhouse, the same mounds, at least through spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best,'' said Bradley. ``I love the way he pitches,
the way he goes up and in on hitters, the way he does things. I'd
love to learn some stuff from him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee pitcher whose stuff most resembles that of Clemens is
Hideki Irabu, who also throws a fastball 95-96 miles an hour, with
a diving split-fingered fastball. But Irabu already has been put on
notice by Joe Torre in the first days of camp, the manager
indicating that Irabu needs to start preparing with more purpose,
and not take his job for granted.
</P>
<P>
   What could Irabu learn from Clemens?
</P>
<P>
   ``Work ethic,'' Torre answered, quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of last season, opposing pitchers had been
throwing inside to Yankees' hitters, knocking them down; Pettitte,
in particular, did not retaliate in a game against Seattle, and
that led to a team meeting. Earlier in spring, Nelson suggested
that the starting pitchers had to take more responsibility in
protecting the hitters, that the Yankees' relievers always had to
do the dirty work of knocking down or hitting opposing hitters,
when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   That won't be an issue with Clemens, the game's most
intimidating pitcher. In the parlance of the old Western: there's a
new sheriff in town.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens twice was involved in beanball incidents with the
Yankees last season, when he was pitching with Toronto. After Irabu
hit Blue Jays shortstop Alex Gonzalez in the head, Clemens
immediately hit Derek Jeter in the side, and the message was clear:
you hit our shortstop, and I'm going to drill your shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Sept. 11, the Yankees were taking healthy full swings
against Clemens, and Clemens responded by drilling Scott Brosius in
the back.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' penchant for pitching inside, said the Yankees catcher
Joe Girardi, makes him very uncomfortable to bat against.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said: ``You hated the way he did it when you were on the
opposing side of the field. But now he's with us. Instead of having
the relievers going out and protecting hitters, he will do it. He
has no problem doing in. In fact, he gets away with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason why the other pitchers shouldn't be picking
up a lot of stuff from Clemens. I mean, he's a Hall of Fame
pitcher.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
