<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      02-20 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS SACRAMENTO STILL IN THE LEAGUE? VERY DEFINITELY  
 FEERICK IS HISTORY  
 STOCKTON TO PAYTON TO KIDD  
 RODMAN'S DECISION  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danny Ainge emerged from his first practice session as a
Sacramento King more than a decade ago and heard the sound of
shotguns outside Arco Arena, the team's home facility that was
built in the middle of the sticks, north of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on?'' Ainge inquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duck season,'' he was told.
</P>
<P>
   As the losses piled up, there were more than enough rustic
stories to go around about the town and the team _ one of the
National Basketball Association's perennial sad-sack franchises
since it moved west from Kansas City in 1985. They were called the
Sacrificial Kings and worse.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help when they finally lucked out on the No. 1 draft
pick in 1989 _ and promptly chose Pervis Ellison.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' last winning season was 1983 and they have one
playoff victory to their credit in the past 13 seasons. The last
time the franchise won a playoff series, Ernie Grunfeld was in the
backcourt. But the jokes and the futility are gradually coming to
an end.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber is now dunking back missed shots for the Kings, the
rookie point guard Jason Williams is freezing Gary Payton before
going by him, and Vlade Divac's behind-the-back passes are finding
cutting teammates rather than fans in the fourth row.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings moved to 5-3 on Friday night with a victory over
Charlotte. Williams' flair, Webber's force and Divac's craftiness
are pushing Phoenix, the Lakers and Minnesota, whom the Kings play
Sunday afternoon, for the title of America's Highlights-at-11 team.
Whether or not they advance to the playoffs, the Kings represent
the best off-season makeover of a lottery team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a different type of team a year ago, where it was
basically Mitch shooting the ball all the time,'' said Geoff
Petrie, the Kings' general manager, referring to the former
All-Star guard Mitch Richmond. ``Now, Mitch is a terrific player,
but the passing and ball movement we have is something that's made
this team exciting. They play very unselfishly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings went into Friday night's game as the only team in the
league averaging more than 100 points. They are second in assists.
Webber, who was traded in the off season for Richmond, and Divac
are two of the better interior passers.
</P>
<P>
   The brand of ball they play _ essentially an end-to-end,
church-league scrimmage _ is reminiscent of the Golden State
Warriors' style of nearly 10 years ago. Petrie is the architect,
but he has had some help.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective owners and brothers Gavin and Joe Maloof, who
will take over the team in July, made their presence felt
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   They flew to Little Rock, Ark., in a tornado to convince Corliss
Williamson and his agent to play for a meager $500,000 so salary
cap room might be cleared for Divac's six-year, nearly $60 million
deal. Williamson kept his Larry Bird rights, meaning he can command
a much better deal after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Petrie pushed hard to draft Williams at No. 7, in spite of the
fact he flunked two drug tests at the University of Florida.
Williams, a point guard, has brought flair and fire to the
position. Petrie also spent considerable time in Greece the past
two years, swaying the team's 1996 draft pick, the 6-foot-9-inch
Predrag (Peja) Stoyakovic, to finally join the team.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the 21-year-old Yugoslav, perhaps the best
player to come out of Europe in the past year, helped his fellow
countryman Divac to leave Charlotte for the Kings. Tariq
Abdul-Wahad starts at shooting guard, while Stoyakovic comes off
the bench. The Kings also acquired the seldom-used Laker guard Jon
Barry for less than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Though Webber has said he is merely making the best of his
situation _ Sacramento might as well have been Siberia for him
after Washington jettisoned him _ he is playing some of his most
inspired basketball.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, with the new collective bargaining agreement, the
Kings can keep Williams for up to four years before he pursues free
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally convinced there's a young nucleus here that with
maturity and experience can be something much, much better than
we've ever had before,'' Petrie said. ``Whether it happens this
season or down the road, I don't know. It's hard to ask patience
and perseverance from the fans of such a long-suffering team, but
we may have to. What you can say is, we're potentially pretty good
here now.''
</P>
<P>
   Feerick Is History
</P>
<P>
   John D. Feerick was quietly released from his duties last week
as the grievance arbitrator under the collective bargaining
agreement. The league, not the union, asked for the dismissal of
Feerick, the Fordham Law School dean who ruled in the Latrell
Sprewell case.
</P>
<P>
   Feerick was thrust into the spotlight last March when he sharply
reduced the penalty handed down by the NBA and Golden State after
Sprewell choked Coach P.J. Carlesimo in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After a much-publicized hearing, Feerick ruled that Sprewell's
contract with the Warriors would be reinstated, and that
Commissioner David Stern's yearlong suspension would be trimmed to
the end of last season. Sprewell lost 68 games and $6.4 million _
the longest and most costly nondrug-related suspension in league
history.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Feerick was roundly criticized. Even Stern got into the
act, saying that Feerick's decision essentially said it was all
right to choke your boss if you play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no ill feelings,'' Feerick said on Thursday. ``I feel
terribly privileged to have had the opportunity to work as a judge
in a great American sport. I will always feel grateful for that. I
can understand the need for change, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The league and the union will have to agree on the appointment
of a new grievance arbitrator to decide disputes that arise from
the new agreement. But they will be hard-pressed to find one with
not only impeccable integrity and credentials but also one as
philanthropic.
</P>
<P>
   Feerick worked 250 hours on a guaranteed contract case between
July and September, in which he earned an $88,000 fee. He is going
to use that money to establish a scholarship at Fordham to assist
law students from the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time he has dedicated the fruits of his
arbitration work to worthwhile causes. He took the entire $98,000
fee he would have earned from the Sprewell arbitration and gave it
to a grammar school in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, he did find it somewhat amusing that Sprewell landed
in New York. ``I've gotten a lot of comments,'' Feerick said,
laughing. ``Suffice to say, nobody has given me any free tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I wish him well.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton to Payton to Kidd
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton is still the most productive and dominating point
guard in the game, having taken over the unofficial title from John
Stockton about two seasons ago. But you wonder how long he can hold
onto the crown. One player has had two triple-doubles this season,
and it's not a power forward or a shooting guard. Jason Kidd
erupted for 28 points, 11 rebounds and 13 assists against Denver
last Monday and followed up with 14 points, 15 rebounds and 10
assists on Wednesday against San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's Decision
</P>
<P>
   It's nice of Dennis Rodman to finally make up his mind about his
plans for this season. Rodman is holding a news conference Monday
at a very discreet location _ Planet Hollywood in Beverly Hills. If
he decides to play, he'll have cost himself about $150,000 in
prorated salary by waiting until the season was in its third week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 1223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2649 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRAY-DOGS-2nd-take-L     02-20 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAY-DOGS-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: increased costs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Knapp is asking City Council leaders to increase
his budget from $8.2 million to $11.9 million in the coming fiscal
year _ a $3.7 million increase. He's asking for an additional $1.6
million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Knapp said his agency now operates in perpetual crisis mode.
Forty-five animal control officers police a city of 3.8 million
people, 3 million cats, 760,000 dogs, and an assortment of
chickens, pigs, goats and other livestock.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, three officers and a supervisor were devoted to
tackling the stray dog problem. But it was too little, too late.
Last year, the city took in 33,000 stray dogs. Animal control
officers caught 7,581 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the problem increases exponentially on the streets.
Spay/USA, an animal overpopulation awareness group, estimates one
female dog and her offspring can produce 67,000 dogs in six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just snowballs,'' Bernstein said. ``They're not spayed or
neutered so they're just making more. It fuels overpopulation.
Getting the strays off the street would stabilize the population.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan's office said the stray dog task force
will get special attention when his final budget request is
submitted on April 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question that the city budget remains tight,'' Deputy Mayor
Noelia Rodriguez said. ``However, this issue is a priority for the
mayor because it affects the quality of life for our residents on a
number of levels from public safety to the atmosphere of the
community. It's not good for the two-legged Angelenos as well as
the four-legged Angelenos.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem calls for a grim solution. Most strays are not
adoptable. They're too skittish, diseased or old, so they're killed
instead. L.A. Animal Services euthanized 35,522 dogs and 17,604
cats last year.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents are not sorry to see the stray mutts go to an
uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad you all are catching all of them,'' resident Eric
Allen told animal control officers. ``Every day, every night
there's dogs running up and down, up and down. This place round
here is pathetic with dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time, I had to come out here with my bat. This Dalmatian
was jumping on this little girl. She was crying, her parents were
yelling, so I came out and started slugging.''
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, a dog pack has lived unhindered so long the
alley is thick with dried feces. Residents named one alley dog
``Fleabag.'' The dog had limped around the neighborhood for two
years after it was hit by a car. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The dogs are not to blame. The root of the problem goes back
to irresponsible pet owners who don't spay or neuter their dogs and
let them wander the streets _ which can lead to a $76 ticket if an
officer has time to write it. Unwanted animals are turned out on
the streets or dumped into already overcrowded shelters where most
are killed to make room for an endless tide of neglected animals.
Only 11,000 dogs were adopted at L.A. shelters last year.
</P>
<P>
   Grim, overcrowded conditions at California animal shelters led
to the Hayden bill, which may have the unintended consequence of
increasing animal euthanasia. The law requires longer holding
periods for sick or injured animals, which means adoptable animals
will have to be euthanized to make room for a new surplus of dogs
and cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animals that are sick, injured or have behavioral problems
tend to die quickly in shelters. Adoptable animals occupy shelter
space longer,'' said Gini Barrett, western regional director of the
American Humane Association and a member of the city's animal
regulation board. ``But there is so much protection in this bill
that the ones we will have to euthanize first are the happy,
adoptable ones _ the ones we used to keep the longest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 1223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
