u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOY-FAIR-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-20 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOY-FAIR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYLAND 1999: SHUT THAT THING UP! 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Remember Giga Pets? Not long ago, the little
hand-held computers that children fed, watered and nurtured by
pressing buttons were all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to imagine how a toy company could top that
craze, but get ready for Giga Monsters, designed for ages 5 and up.
Here the object is to make the virtual pets die.
</P>
<P>
   The persnickety monsters keep coming back to life as the
diligent child tries to hasten their destruction. They live in tiny
coffins, or ``uniquely stylized cabinets,'' in the words of the
toy's creator, Tiger Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost enough to make one nostalgic for the days when toys
died because they ran out of batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The Giga Monster was but one of many startling items on display
last week at the 96th American International Toy Fair in New York,
where 1,700 exhibitors gathered to peddle their wares to 20,000
buyers. Most of the toys and games haven't hit stores yet. Some are
still prototypes and failed in demonstrations; others succeeded in
demonstrations and will still fail in stores.
</P>
<P>
   In the game of Conscience _ ``The fun way to learn right from
wrong'' _ players travel through seven zones: violence, drugs,
crime, character, charity, education and sex. (Sex is optional, and
parents can remove or add this zone at will.) Winners earn gold
stars. Losers collect black marks and wind up in the principal's
office, detention center, jail or the morgue. Players get on the
wrong path if they ignore their homework, for example, or
``associate with druggies.'' The board game has been designed by
GoRu Products for ages 8 and up, but comes with a simplified
version that 5- to 7-year-olds can enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Checkers, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Children are certainly capable of dealing with morality,
character or crime _ after all, they encounter such issues in fairy
tales and in the schoolyard. And, of course, classic games have
always tackled the big themes: Chess explores war, Monopoly takes
on greed and in many games players meet their metaphorical deaths.
But the latest toys tend to be more literal, making announcements
like, ``Your toy just died.''
</P>
<P>
   The new heavy-handed gadgets, plus Jerry Springer board games
and Rock-'n-Roll Elmo, are part of a $20 billion-a-year industry.
Even Bill Gates has gotten in on it. Anyone who thinks Microsoft or
the Teletubbies are intent on world domination will be alarmed to
hear that they have forged an alliance. Microsoft Teletubbies
ActiMates are dolls that a conspiracy theorist could love.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who believes the purple Teletubby is secretly gay
obviously did not attend this year's toy fair. Secrecy and subtlety
were not at a premium: Toys for 1999 tell about themselves in
painstaking detail, and they won't shut up. They will tell you if
they are dead or alive or sad. The Kissy-Kissy Baby, courtesy of
Irwin Toy Ltd., will pucker if you kiss her mouth, will say ``Kiss
my boo-boo better'' if you kiss her hand and ``I love you, Mommy''
if you kiss her cheek. Her responses are ``moisture-activated.''
</P>
<P>
   Even lipstick gets a word in. Funrise Toy is offering electric
lipstick equipped with a sound module that says things like ``You
go girl!''and ``Looking Good!'' The lipstick presumably provides
the encouragement that young girls may not otherwise be getting.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of the sound chip, toys can broadcast all kinds
of messages out loud. Girls' white shoes, for example, could once
connote innocence, or summer, or membership in the wedding party.
But now tots with marital ambitions can slip on a pair of Funrise's
Sound Shoes without any ambiguity. The shoes play ``Here Comes the
Bride'' as the girl walks.
</P>
<P>
   But in a stride against blonde stereotypes, Mattel's Chatty
Cathy now comes in new hair and eye colors. The doll, who
incessantly says things like ``Please carry me,'' can now be a
brunette, too.
</P>
<P>
   Technology also allows toys to relate to one another. According
to Plato, Aristophanes suggested that human beings were once
two-headed creatures, then were split in half and condemned to
spend the rest of their lives seeking to re-attach to their
original mates. Dubbels, a toy by Rumpus, uses the latest
recognition technology chips to prove Aristophanes right. Somewhere
out there, the perfect mate awaits each L-shaped bean-bag creature.
They just need to be fit together.
</P>
<P>
   If two incompatible bean-bags join, the toy will complain,
``You're cute, but you're not my Dubbel.'' The crestfallen child
will then probably demand that another $5.99 be invested in the
Dubbel's search for romance. The payoff comes when it finds its
bean-bag fantasy mate and announces, ``Baby I've been waiting for
you my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   With recognition technology this advanced, subliminal messages
are unnecessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 1224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2652 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAW-BOOKS-LADN     02-20 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAW-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEY-AUTHOR COLLECTS COMPELLING ARGUMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DON HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. -- After dropping out of high school at age 17,
Michael Lief has piloted submarines for the Navy, conducted
research at the United Nations, edited a newspaper and graduated
from law school.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 35-year-old Ventura County deputy district attorney is
trying on a brand-new role: popular author.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and Gentlemen of the Jury'' _ his compilation of
notable closing trial arguments _ has raced through four printings.
He recently sold the British rights, and the book will soon be
published in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   There's even talk of an audio book and a documentary series for
cable.
</P>
<P>
   Lief, an affable man with a quick wit and a ready laugh, said
the book has all the fascination of a potboiler blended with modern
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans love crime, as you can tell by the success of shows
like `Homicide,' `The Practice' and `Law and Order,' '' Lief said.
``It's compelling, and it's dramatic. We're dealing with issues
here ranging from genocide, assassination, murder, the nuclear
power industry. So these deal with compelling issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``And nothing is more compelling than crime or genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   Published by Scribner, the 400-page book covers the most
eloquent closing arguments in 10 notable trials _ most from this
century. Defendants include the Nuremberg Nazi war criminals,
Charles Manson, the Chicago Seven and Lt. William Calley, involved
in the 1968 My Lai massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Among Lief's favorites is a closing argument by Clara Shortridge
Foltz, California's first female attorney. Although the 1890 trial
centered on an Italian immigrant charged with arson, prosecutor
Thetas Stonehill set his sights not on the defendant, but on Foltz
and the idea of female lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is so quick-witted, so sarcastic that I found several
times I laughed out loud while reading her summation,'' Lief said.
``The jury, without leaving the jury box, found her defendant not
guilty. So she got a good result and she took (the prosecutor) to
the woodshed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lief got the idea for the book in 1993, while he was in his
first year at the Pepperdine University School of Law. Assigned to
write a closing argument for a class, he scoured the library for
examples of great closing statements. Finding none, he mulled the
idea over and then approached one of his law professors, H.
Mitchell Caldwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went up to his office and I sort of kicked back and put my
feet up on his desk and asked him what he was doing this summer,''
Lief recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell liked the idea and agreed that Lief would not be
relegated to a mere assistant on the project.
</P>
<P>
   As their guide, they sought out trials that were historically or
socially significant. In some cases, trial transcripts had
disappeared from archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we wrote it, our intention was not to write it for
lawyers,'' Lief said. ``Our intention was to write it for the
layperson, someone who is interested in history, true crime and
public speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   After they finished the book, Lief and Caldwell tried without
success for two years to entice a publisher or even an agent.
Caldwell then suggested bringing on board Ben Bycel, a
well-connected friend and dean of the University of West Los
Angeles School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, the book was making the rounds at Scribner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In no time at all, we went from (Caldwell) and I struggling to
get an agent to suddenly being in the big leagues,'' Lief said.
</P>
<P>
   The book has won favorable reviews around the country and
climbed to the No. 2 spot on the Barnsandnoble.com list of best
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The book's success hasn't made Lief wealthy enough to quit his
job with the Ventura County District Attorney's Office, where he
reviews misdemeanor cases for filing of charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think I'm a pretty good trial attorney,'' said Lief,
who is now working on a murder mystery set in a courthouse. ``While
I don't think any of my closing arguments are going to end up in a
book like this, practice makes perfect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 1224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
