<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      02-20 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS-BULLS: ALAS, A GAME THAT LACKS SOUL  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 &HT;     c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Forgive Patrick Ewing if he looks lost Sunday. He's
like the tall, awkward kid who missed graduating with his own class
by a year. Or the poor soul who shows up at the party after the
chips, salsa and guests are gone.
</P>
<P>
   When the 36-year-old center surveys the landscape at Madison
Square Garden, he will wonder whatever happened to that fierce
rivalry between his brooding Knicks and Michael Jordan's
incomparable Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael's not there, Scottie's not there and Rodman's not
there,'' Ewing said of Chicago's championship triumvirate. ``And
for us, John isn't and Oak isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Eastern Conference showdown, huh?
</P>
<P>
   No Jordan, no Scottie Pippen, no Dennis Rodman, no John Starks
and no Charles Oakley. Other than the bit-part player Herb Williams
and Chicago's Ron Harper and Toni Kukoc _ both late arrivals in the
saga _ Ewing is the last man standing amid the ashes of Chicago's
dynastic saga in which they continually turned the Knicks into
silver medalists.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry essentially died the day Jordan announced his
retirement last month, a development that created a domino effect
in Chicago and depression in New York. Ewing, who always said he
wanted to go through Jordan to win an elusive championship ring,
now has to settle for dethroning the Bulls reserve guard Rusty
LaRue.
</P>
<P>
   As proof the game is not near the spectacle it once was, NBC
will televise the matchup only regionally, the first time it has
done so with a weekend Knicks-Bulls game since the early 1990's.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks beat the Bulls in Chicago last week, hanging on
despite a late run from Chicago. They really have nothing in common
other than that game. Rebuilding instead of reloading for a change,
Chicago is off to a 1-8 start with a cast featuring Brent Barry and
Bill Wennington.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks improved to 5-3 with a victory over Philadelphia on
Friday night, although a slow, inconsistent start and a heel injury
to Latrell Sprewell raises serious questions as to whether they'll
be in sync once the regular season moves into its second month.
</P>
<P>
   But one constant has stood out, just as he did in perhaps the
league's most intriguing rivalry over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has led the Knicks in rebounding in six of their first
eight games. He's averaging 16.3 points per game, 9.3 rebounds per
game, 2 assists and 2.3 blocks per game.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the ball with his teammates, he has taken five fewer
shots than Allan Houston this season. New York's 78-67 victory over
the 76ers on Thursday night marked Ewing's fourth game in five
nights. Though he seemed bolted to the floor at times, he managed
to block two shots and hit one of the game's most important shots _
a wild, spinning, left-handed layup that ignited a 10-0 run in the
fourth quarter and put away the game for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   In only his 12th game back since fracturing his shooting wrist
in December 1997, Ewing played 37 minutes, his average. He may
still go through ineffective stretches, but his durability after 13
seasons is impressive. And his role in the rivalry, as that
stone-faced antagonist trying to wrest the championship from
Jordan, has not been lost on Ewing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came in, people didn't think I could do a lot of
things,'' Ewing said. ``But I'm still here. I'm still surviving. He
added, ``We may have won some battles, but they always won the war.
Except for one year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks overcame the Bulls without Jordan in 1994 en route to
their first finals appearance in more than 20 years. But mostly,
Bulls-Knicks has been extremely one-sided. Jordan's Bulls were 5-0
against the Knicks in playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   There is not much redemption in dunking on Tim Floyd's new team
rather than Phil Jackson's old one. The halcyon days of the rivalry
are indeed gone. It is merely another game Sunday, a game between
two franchises that used to mean so much more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
