<HEADLINE>
REFILING TO FIX CODING
</HEADLINE>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  (nk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Feb. 21:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions or reruns: (888) 346-9867. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The late supervisor is Henry Warnken (E-mail:
hewarn(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Technical problems: &LR;  Peter Trigg.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Rambouillet, France) _ Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright negotiated intensely Saturday, hours past
deadline, to try and achieve peace in Kosovo, spelling out to the
leaders of Serbia that they must accept deployment of up to 30,000
NATO troops, including a small contingent of American soldiers. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ As the deadline passed Saturday
without a peace deal in Kosovo, Defense Department and NATO
officials said they were ready to launch immediate air strikes on
Serbia, even though dozens of American warplanes assigned to the
mission will not be in place in Europe until after the weekend. By
Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RESIDENTS (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Residents in the
capital of Kosovo listened intently to the news Saturday as peace
talks passed with no word of an agreement. By Carlotta Gall. With
art.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (Wagah, India-Pakista Border Crossing) _ In an
extraordinary show of warmth between two bitterly hostile nations,
India's Prime Minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, rode a bus Saturday
through the fertile plains of the Punjab, across the usually closed
border gate here and cordially embraced his Pakistani counterpart,
Nawaz Sharif. By Barry Bearak. With art.
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-RITTER-BOOK (Washington) _ Reversing itself for a
second time, the Pentagon has demanded that Scott Ritter, a former
U.N. weapons inspector, provide it with an advance copy of a book
in which he is expected to accuse the Clinton administration of
hindering the search for evidence of Iraqi chemical and biological
weapons. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-FILMMAKER (Moscow) _ Oscar-winning film director Nikita
Mikhalkov premiers his new film at the Kremlin, a palace he says
he'd like to occupy as President after the elections in 2000. By
Michael S. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE-ECON (Lviv, Ukraine) _ Ukraine's political leaders say
they see the future in Europe, capitalism and democracy. But
Ukraine's basket-case economy remains lashed to its Russian past _
and the longer it stays there, the tighter the bind becomes. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LABOR (Jerusalem) _ Why the Labor Party seems to keep
committing political suicide. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-KURDS (Istanbul, Turkey) _ What will happen to the
Kurdish nationalist movement now that its most visible leader has
been captured and evidently emasculated? By Stephen Kinzer. With
art.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-IMMIGRATION (Hong Kong) _ Last month, a Hong Kong court
ruled that children born in China of Hong Kong parents have the
right to live in the territory. The decision opens the door to tens
of thousands, if not hundreds of thousands, of mainlanders. But
officials in Beijing have said the ruling violates China's
constitution and must be ``rectified.'' By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-WELFARE (Milwaukee) _ As Wisconsin drives its welfare
rolls to record lows, many of the state's most troubled mothers
have lost their benefits, often en route to drug clinics, jail
cells, shelters, or the streets. And grandmothers are being left to
care for the children abandoned along the way. It is just one
chapter of the complex treatise on social change being written here
by welfare's end. And like most aspects of Wisconsin's daring
experiment, it is drawing national _ and even international _
attention from a world eager for glimpses of the post-welfare
future. By Jason DeParle. With art.
</P>
<P>
   LIBRARIES-GATES (Undated) _ The plan of the Gates Learning
Foundation to donate money for public-access computers in libraries
in all 50 states by 2003 raises a nagging question: At what cost
does a public institution accept the largess of a benefactor whose
corporate interests are so closely linked to the social good he is
providing? By Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-RESTORATION (Undated) _ An ambitious $8 billion plan
to restore the Florida Everglades to ecological health over the
next several decades is coming under fire from experts who say
that, as now conceived, the proposal will actually do little in the
way of restoration. By William K. Stevens. With art.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-BADNEWS (Gadsen, Ala.) _ This small Alabama city reels from
the recently announced closing of a Goodyear tire plant, the city's
largest employer, and the anticipated closing of a steel mill, the
second-largest. The bad news shows that there are still are pockets
of gloom within the economic boom. By David Firestone. With art.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TRASH (New York) _ Strong opposition from states slated to
receive New York City's garbage is forcing city officials to
rethink their plans for where New York's trash will be dumped as
they prepare to close the giant Fresh Kills landfill on Staten
Island. By Douglas Martin and Drew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-FRAUD (Washington) _ The federal government will try to
enlist millions of Medicare beneficiaries in its war against
Medicare fraud next week, urging them to report billing errors,
overcharges and other evidence of wrongdoing by their doctors and
hospitals. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-DEMOCRATS (Washington) _ The Democratic Party's hopes of
retaking the Senate next year may have dimmed a bit with the
unexpected retirements announced this week by two Democrats who
almost certainly could have kept their seats: Frank Lautenberg of
New Jersey and Richard H. Bryan of Nevada. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-NEWYORK (Washington) _ Political strategists,
including some in Gore camp, are expressing quiet concerns about a
potential Senate run by Hillary Clinton, noting that they would
lose her as a national campaigner if she ran in New York. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (New York) _ Bob Herbert on Mayor Giuliani's
recent message to police cadets: deal with people politely and
conduct themselves with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Maureen Dowd on questions the New York
City press corps would like to ask Hillary Rodham Clinton if she
decides to run for the Senate.
</P>
