<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PACERS-HARRINGTON     02-20 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-HARRINGTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRINGTON LEARNS PATIENCE ON THE PACERS BENCH AND SO DOES HIS
FAMILY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ind.)   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Indiana Pacers play, the scene is always the same in
Roselle, N.J. Nearly a dozen people gather in the Lawton family
living room and wait for Al Harrington to appear on the television
screen.
</P>
<P>
   While the gatherings are fun for the basketball-loving family,
these evenings typically end in disappointment for the Lawtons,
because Harrington, the latest high school prodigy to jump directly
to the National Basketball Association, has not played in the last
six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been rough because you anticipate him being out there on
the court and then he doesn't get a chance to play,'' said Aaron
Lawton, Harrington's father. ``The only game he really got a chance
to play in was the exhibition against Chicago, and we were off our
feet then. Then, he kind of went through a little drought where
they haven't played him as much as we would've liked. But we spoke
to him and we understand that it's all a part of Larry Bird's
formula to bring him along slowly. We can accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   To say that Harrington's introduction to the NBA has been
discomfiting would be an understatement. Since electing to enter
the 1998 draft out of St. Patrick's High School in Elizabeth, N.J.,
the 6-foot-9-inch forward has endured a surprisingly low selection
(25th), a dubious seven-month lockout and the indignity of playing
only four minutes in the first eight games.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the top high school players in the country last year,
Harrington expected to step in and contribute 20 to 30 minutes a
game for the Eastern Conference favorites, who will play the Nets
Sunday at 6 p.m. in Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he played only three minutes in the season opener,
grabbing two rebounds and missing two free throws, and one minute
the next game, notching a rebound and missing his only shot of the
season. He has yet to score his first NBA point.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he denied having any regrets about his decision to forgo
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't gotten to that point yet,'' Harrington said Friday
in a telephone call from Indianapolis. ``But I'm a competitor so
I'm a little frustrated by not getting time. It's tough. It's real
tough. It kills me sitting and watching because I always want to
play. I definitely thought I was going to play more than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana Coach Larry Bird, the Hall of Fame player and reigning
coach of the year, could not be reached for comment, but he has
told Indiana reporters not to view Harrington's lack of playing
time negatively. The Pacers simply are overcrowded at small
forward, Bird has said, noting that the veterans Chris Mullin,
Jalen Rose, Sam Perkins and Austin Croshere are getting the minutes
that would be Harrington's.
</P>
<P>
   The coach reportedly is happy with Harrington, who at times has
been tremendous in practice, and views him as a key player for the
future. But presently, the Pacers are playing the exact lineup that
took them to within one game of the NBA finals last season, with
the addition of Perkins, a 37-year-old free agent.
</P>
<P>
   That is the message that the Indiana assistant coach Rick
Carlisle shared with Harrington's mother, Mona Lawton, in a
telephone call last week that was sparked by her anxiety over her
son's lack of playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how mothers are,'' said Harrington, who has lived
with his Pacers teammate Antonio Davis since September. ``They
always think it's somebody else's fault. But she finally realized
that I just have to be patient and wait my turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said he enjoys playing for Bird and has no resentment
towards his coach for not playing him more. ``Our relationship is
cool,'' he said. ``I'm learning a lot from him. A lot of times we
joke about how he used to dominate, how he used to kill people on
the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lawtons will attend their first Pacers game in person next
weekend in their first trip to Indianapolis. Aaron and Mona are the
only family members going. Harrington's siblings, Harvey, Tiffany
and A.J., plus the relatives from Long Island who travel to Roselle
for the Pacers games, will stay behind and watch on the DirectTV
program that Harrington bought for his family right before the
season started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al wanted to give that to us for a little present,'' Aaron
Lawton said. ``So we could keep up with his games.''
</P>
<P>
   Like their son, they will have to be patient. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
