<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-LABOR-820&AMP;ADD-     02-20 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LABOR-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS SEE POLITICAL MELTDOWN, LIVE ON PRIME TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Broadcast live on Israeli television, the finale of
the Labor Party primary last week was supposed to be a rousing
affair. As it began, balloons bobbed, the theme from ``Rocky''
played and Laborites congratulated one another for assembling what
they believed to be a diverse, experienced and winning ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But then Adissu Massala, the only member of Parliament
representing Israel's Ethiopian immigrants, climbed on stage and
commandeered the podium. Filled with rage, Massala faced the
cameras and accused Ehud Barak, the Labor Party leader and its
candidate for prime minister, of racism. Barak, a former general,
stood beside him, his face frozen in an embarrassed half-smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never forgive the Labor Party,'' Massala said, after
learning that he had lost the ``new immigrant'' slot on the party
ticket to a Russian. It was only after he finished his bitter
harangue that Massala was ushered off the stage so that Barak could
deliver an anticlimactic celebratory speech.
</P>
<P>
   The moment ruined the festivities and humiliated the party.
Having overcome disarray in its ranks, Labor was finally ready to
propel itself into the campaign for the May elections. Instead, it
presented to the Israeli public on Tuesday night a spontaneous
meltdown within the minority ranks of a party desperate to break
free of its image as a bastion of the elite.
</P>
<P>
   Labor has had a difficult time grabbing the spotlight in this
race. The conservative Likud Party holds a publicity edge because
its candidate, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, is the incumbent.
And the new Center Party, because it is a novelty, is stealing the
show.
</P>
<P>
   But when Labor finally had its moment, it bombed, and the
reviews were devastating. Nachum Barnea, of the newspaper Yediot
Ahronoth, called it ``a performance of collective suicide _ live on
prime time.'' Chemi Shalev, of Maariv, described the party as ``an
errant whale that insisted on beaching itself in order to die, in
front of the entire nation, on prime-time television.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really ruined our day,'' acknowledged Alon Pinkas, Barak's
foreign-policy adviser. ``People _ our own supporters _ were
saying, `Why do they have these idiotic suicidal tendencies?' If it
happened to Likud, your average Likudnik would be much more
receptive to the idea that Massala was just a disgruntled man who
lost his job and went berserk.''
</P>
<P>
   But it did not happen to Likud and so Likud was quick to
capitalize on the fiasco. Netanyahu introduced new posters and a
new mode of attack: ``Barak is too weak to unite the people,'' his
new slogan said. ``He cannot even unite his own party.''
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, the damage had been kept somewhat in check.
Although Barak slipped a bit in the polls, one showed him ahead of
Netanyahu, if only by 3 percentage points. Still, Israeli
journalists could not keep themselves from speculating about a
highly unlikely outcome: that the Labor Party might consider
dropping Barak and inviting the more popular Yitzhak Mordechai, the
Center Party candidate, to represent them.
</P>
<P>
   Labor strategists find such speculation galling. Barak, 57, a
Stanford University-trained engineer who speaks in elaborate,
metaphor-ridden language, does not possess his opponents' charisma.
James Carville, one of his U.S. consultants, talks about wanting to
knock 100 points off his IQ before each campaign appearance.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Labor strategists see it, charisma is overrated.
Netanyahu, they say, is a great candidate, but a poor prime
minister. Anyway, they say, what tarnished Barak's golden week was
bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Massala, 37, a social worker from the development town of Bat
Yam, had proved a disappointment to the Labor Party as a
legislator, and had failed to woo many of his fellow Ethiopians
away from the Likud Party. In cold, hard terms, he was not as
valuable to the party as Sofa Landver, the Russian woman who ended
up in his slot because she garnered more votes.
</P>
<P>
   There are 60,000 Ethiopians in Israel and 1 million immigrants
from the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, Israeli radio announced that Massala was likely
to win the new immigrant slot. But in the interest of building
toward a dramatic prime-time show, the Labor Party stopped
releasing the returns. And it was not until the show began that
Massala really understood that he had lost. He and his supporters
were furious and began pushing toward the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, sensing a possible disaster, waved Massala to the podium
and allowed him to speak. And as he spoke, an Israeli-Arab woman
candidate, who also lost, joined him on stage, echoing his anger.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lose-lose situation for Barak with no way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strategically, Ehud knew the minute he allowed him to take the
microphone that he was in for a media disaster,'' Pinkas said.
``But he also knew that to not let him speak would probably cause
even greater damage.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If the episode had not occurred, Labor would have celebrated,
among other things, what it considers a high voter turnout of 60
percent, or about 100,000 party members. This is important to party
leaders because it signals that they will be able to bring out
their forces in a tight race.
</P>
<P>
   But the party also selected a ticket that it considered balanced
and experienced, with hawks and doves, two Sephardic immigrants and
one woman among the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Shlomo Ben Ami, a Moroccan-born intellectual, drew the most
votes. From the lowest-ranking member of the Labor delegation, he
rocketed into the No. 3 spot, after Barak and Shimon Peres, the
former prime minister whose second slot was reserved.
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Beilin, another academic and a peace negotiator who has
maintained strong working relationships with the Palestinians, took
the fourth slot. Matan Vilnai, a former general who turned down
Netanyahu's offer of the post of defense minister to join Labor,
took fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Intent on portraying all his opponents as leftists, Netanyahu
was quick to pick up and reproduce, in advertisements, Beilin's
words as he embraced the ticket: ``My heart beats on the left. The
results of the primaries shows that the heart of Labor beats on the
left as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But a lead editorial in Haaretz urged those Labor leaders who
cringed to stand tall and proud. ``The Labor Party has no reason to
apologize for being leftist,'' it said. ``There is no basis for
Netanyahu's nightmarish propaganda, which seeks to depict those who
want to bring him down as somehow endangering the national
interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
