<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2666 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SELF-IMMOLATION-REVIE     02-20 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELF-IMMOLATION-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE DESPERATE, THE ULTIMATE PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A grisly shadow from the earliest days of the Vietnam War crept
across the media landscape last week during the outbreak of rioting
among Kurds infuriated by Turkey's capture of the top Kurdish rebel
leader. Protesters in Germany, England and Denmark set themselves
on fire. In Paris, London and Marseilles, Kurdish protesters
occupied embassies and threatened to immolate themselves before
finally surrendering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, I'm thinking 1963, those pictures of Buddhist monks
burning themselves to death in Vietnam on the front pages,'' said
Professor Anthony Joes, director of the International Relations
Department at St. Joseph's University in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Those haunting images appeared in June 1963 and continued for
months: Surrounded by prayerful supporters, monks engulfed
themselves in flames to protest the South Vietnamese regime of Ngo
Dinh Diem, the U.S.-backed leader whose powerful sister-in-law,
Madame Ngo Dinh Nhu, ridiculed the self-immolations as ``a
barbecue'' and taunted, ``Let them burn!''
</P>
<P>
   That November, Diem was killed in a coup supported by the United
States. Though other horrifying pictures would soon dominate the
news, the burning monks remain among the indelible images of the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few forms of political statement more impressive
than deliberately setting yourself on fire,'' said William Harman,
a professor of religious studies at DePauw University in
Greencastle, Ind., who has written extensively on historical
religious attitudes toward martyrdom and public suicide. He sees
such acts as a technique for manipulating a community into
commitment to causes that transcend material concerns like
self-preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of those 1963 Vietnam images, self-immolation is
commonly associated with Buddhism. But Harman said the practice
springs from no single cultural tradition and shares ancient
philosophical origins with religious sacrifices and martyrdom,
including the crucifixion of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Joes noted that the Kurdish militants were mostly Muslims, whose
religion forbids suicide for personal reasons but condones ``heroic
martyrdom'' _ including acts like terrorist suicide bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Harman said self-immolation is increasing in parts of India and
Burma. In Vietnam, at least five Buddhists have burned themselves
to death in the past two years protesting religious persecution. In
Bangalore, India, the site of the Miss World pageant in 1996,
police rounded up scores of feminists who were planning to stage a
mass self-immolation before TV cameras broadcasting the event
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   And in India last April, the Dalai Lama issued a statement that
followers interpreted as suggesting support for hunger strikes and
self-immolation after he visited a hospitalized Tibetan exile who
had set himself on fire to protest the Chinese occupation of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Joes said last week's rioting, including the self-immolations,
underscored both the desperation and the determination of militants
in the Kurdish Diaspora, who were apparently organized enough to
coordinate well-timed street protests all over the world. In
Vietnam in 1963, Western reporters and photographers were always
given advance notice when Buddhist protesters set themselves on
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Immolation as protest is ``a kind of theater _ a religious act
tied into a political act,'' Joes said. ``In 1963, Americans looked
at those pictures and said, `Man, what would it take for me to set
myself on fire? I'd have to be flat-out crazy.' But we sensed those
Buddhist monks weren't crazy. It really had an enormous public
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-immolation is ``obviously a very painful way to die,''
Harman said, ``although some say that you actually suffocate first,
because the fire consumes the oxygen. When someone does it,
essentially they are saying, `I gave my life.' The act itself makes
it very clear what the lines are between the committed and the
uncommitted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 1239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1049 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SELF-IMMOLATION-REVIE     02-20 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELF-IMMOLATION-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE DESPERATE, THE ULTIMATE PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A grisly shadow from the earliest days of the Vietnam War crept
across the media landscape last week during the outbreak of rioting
among Kurds infuriated by Turkey's capture of the top Kurdish rebel
leader. Protesters in Germany, England and Denmark set themselves
on fire. In Paris, London and Marseilles, Kurdish protesters
occupied embassies and threatened to immolate themselves before
finally surrendering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, I'm thinking 1963, those pictures of Buddhist monks
burning themselves to death in Vietnam on the front pages,'' said
