<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-POLITICS-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: unemployment insurance? 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Few people would die with the words `free markets' on their
lips,'' notes Daniel Yergin, who has chronicled the rise of the
markets in the 1980s and '90s and the consequent reduction of state
power. And so all of a sudden, from Davos to Shanghai, the talk is
about re-imposing control on the markets to protect the citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't so easy to do, not in a world grown dependent on
foreign capital to build the office buildings and the factories.
</P>
