<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-TURKEY-KURDS-0221     02-20 1594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TURKEY-KURDS-0221 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A REBEL LEADER JAILED AT HOME, AND A MOVEMENT INTRODUCED TO THE
WORLD
 &HT;    EDs: Note optional trim at 650 words.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey _ The emotions of 25 million people without a
state seized the world's television screens last week. Viewers saw
anger and frustration, clinched fists and in a few instances bodies
ablaze in suicidal protest.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy being a Kurd.
</P>
<P>
   For much of this century, this ethnic minority has sought to
promote its national identity in a tumultuous part of the world. On
a cluttered agenda of global oil, Israeli-Arab animosity, Saddam
Hussein and Iran's Islamic fundamentalists, there's been little
room for Kurdish rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurds want self-determination, but no one else seems ready
to take up their cause. They are Muslim farmers, merchants and
nomads -- scattered across Turkey, Iraq, Iran and Syria. In each of
these countries, regimes have effectively contained and weakened
the Kurdish minority. What's more, the Kurdish movement remains
beset by its own internal feuds and tribal distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   With ``no friend but the mountains,'' as their self-pitying
legend goes, the Kurds have long been cloaked in relative
obscurity. But now that veil is gone.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest Feb. 16 of separatist leader Abdullah ``Apo'' Ocalan
by Turkey -- with the help of the CIA -- provoked riots by the
Kurdish diaspora across Europe and brought the quest for self-rule
into the world's living rooms, with TV pictures of Kurds taking
over embassies, wrestling with police and committing
self-immolation.
</P>
<P>
   The capture of the charismatic Ocalan, leader of the militant
Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), places the aspirations of Turkey's
12 million Kurds and the Turkish government at a crucial turning
point in the decades-long struggle over Kurdish rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``And clearly it is not only Turkey's problem, but the
world's,'' said Sedat Yurtdas, 38, a moderate Kurdish politician
and lawyer whose activities have been banned by the Turkish
government.
</P>
<P>
   The Entebbe-style capture of Ocalan in Kenya by Turkish
commandos was widely celebrated in Turkey, comparable to if Israel
had nabbed Yasser Arafat amid the Palestinian terrorist movement in
the 1970s. Ocalan's rebel forces are credited with a 15-year
insurrection that has cost the lives of some 30,000 Turks, both
soldiers and civilians.
</P>
<P>
   He is routinely referred to in Turkey's pro-government press as
``the babykiller.'' Some families who lost sons serving in the
Turkish army held parties to toast his capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victory!'' screamed the headline this week in a leading
Turkish newspaper, Hurriyet. Pro-government TV relished
broadcasting a videotape of a humiliated and blindfolded Ocalan
being transported to his high-security island prison on Imrali, in
the Sea of Marmara, near Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question nagging Turkey is: What next? Will the
arrest of Ocalan debilitate the Kurdish movement, or galvanize it
as never before?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's is great rejoicing at what we've accomplished in
apprehending this criminal. But I don't think anyone in Ankara is
under the illusion that it is going to make our problems go away,''
said a foreign ministry official who asked to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that eliminating the opposition is not possible in the
short term. The guerrilla movement is still active, there are
millions of Kurds living in Europe. They have a structure and a
cause that is not simply going to fade away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: The story may end here.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   A sobering problem for Turkey is the delicate matter of how to
handle Ocalan's upcoming trial and anticipated conviction, after
which he could be sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan and the PKK's brutal tactics have been loathed by many
moderate Kurds. But Turkey risks turning Ocalan into a martyr for
all Kurds if the trial is viewed as a sham and Ocalan is put to
death.
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate aftermath of Ocalan's arrest, Kurds living
abroad and linked by e-mail and a Europe-based satellite TV
station, took the streets and occupied embassy buildings in more
than 20 European cities. It was a surprising and sudden show of
coordination and logistics.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other man has done as much to publicize the plight of
the Kurds. A vindictive Saddam Hussein sought to annihilate Iraqi
Kurds in the north of his country in the aftermath of the 1991 Gulf
War. The United States and other Western forces had to intervene
with threats and a no-fly zone to curb an all-out military assault
by what was left of Iraq's battered army.
</P>
<P>
   With Saddam contained and supply lines of refugee aid
established, the West offered little hope that more would be done
to address the ambition of Kurdish independence. With American and
United Nations help, the Kurds in northern Iraq are largely running
their own affairs, without realizing their ultimate goal of
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most militant of Kurds began to set their sights lower;
In Turkey, Ocalan relinquished the goal of an independent
statehood, calling instead for limited autonomy within Turkey's
borders.
</P>
<P>
   With the bulk of Kurds living in Turkey, the United States has
been hesitant to enter the fray and risk upsetting Turkey, a NATO
ally strategically situated next to Iran and Iraq that hosts the
U.S. military most notably at the large Air Force base at Incerlik.
</P>
<P>
   Washington regards the PKK as a terrorist organization. On
Friday, the State Department acknowledged that the U.S.
intelligence services helped Turkey track down and capture Ocalan,
who had looking for a hiding place since mid-October when he was
forced from his haven in Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey used the arrest as an opportunity to launch a fresh
offensive against the Kurds in the southeast, where troops backed
by artillery and air power routinely drive the guerrillas into the
snow-covered highlands across the border with Iraq. Since the early
1990's, Turkish forces have effectively place the PKK on the run
and in the process pulverized more than 3,000 towns and villages to
eliminate their hiding places.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a pronouncement by Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit that
``the terrorist organization's back has been broken and the
terrorist chief has been captured,'' no one expects the Kurdish
problem to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   If Turkey's relentless military and security offensive is the
stick, Ecevit offered a carrot this week in proclaiming a campaign
to increase investment and improve roads in mainly Kurdish
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish President Suleyman Demirel appealed for a special
session of parliament to pass an amnesty law to urge Ocalan's
followers to end their 15-year struggle for self-rule.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, the Kurds will be looking for more.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among their demands are basic human and democratic
rights. Most moderate Kurdish voices have been jailed or their
activities curbed by the government and courts who consider almost
any Kurdish political expression as tantamount to sedition.
</P>
<P>
   Local and general elections are scheduled for April 18. But
Turkey's chief prosecutor has begun legal proceedings to bar the
pro-Kurdish People's Democracy Party (HADEP). If outlawed, it would
be the fourth political party sympathetic to the Kurds to be banned
in Turkey during this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Such crackdowns go over well among mainstream Turkish voters,
who tend to view the Kurdish issue not a quest by disenfranchised
people, but as a threat to national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   A few public figures in Turkey do openly question government
policy, at the risk of prosecution for violating security laws, by
suggesting that the Kurdish problem could have been preempted years
ago had Turkey relaxed its opposition to limited regional self-rule
for the Kurds and allowed Kurdish moderates a greater voice in
national affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to name this problem -- it is the Kurdish problem. If
you don't recognize that it is there you won't be able to solve
it,'' said Akin Birdal, a leading Turkish human rights activist in
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arrest has placed the eyes of the world on Turkey. It is
an important test, not only for the future of the Kurds but for
Turkey's reputation in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey can take comfort in the fact that during his months on
the run, no European country would offer Ocalan refuge.
</P>
<P>
   But now that it has him in custody, the government here appears
to be ignoring demands by international human rights groups for
greater tolerance towards the Kurds and a fair trial for Ocalan.
Turkey is preparing a closed trial before a military tribunal for
the rebel leader and has rejected attempts of Ocalan's European
lawyers to enter the country to confer with him.
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Greece have asked the European Union to insure a fair
trial for Ocalan, one that would avoid the death penalty he faces
under Turkish law. They would make such procedures a condition for
eventual Turkish membership in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Turkey, the threat of new violence was faxed Friday to
the Associated Press. Ocalan's PKK warned that Turkey would ``face
the consequences'' if Ocalan were harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that a dark period is waiting for us in the future,''
said Yurtdas, the Kurdish politician. ``If Turkey has a genuine
intention to solve this problem peacefully, it is high time to do
it now. There would be no reason for Kurds to rebel if we were
allowed to be part of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
