<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-KIDNAPPING-465     02-20 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-KIDNAPPING-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN KIDNAPPING IS PUZZLE WITH HINT OF POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The kidnappers who stunned Mexico last week by
abducting the father of the country's most popular sports figure
have left the authorities puzzling over whether the crime was
motivated by politics or simply done for ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a country where kidnapping has become disturbingly
common, the abduction of the father of the soccer star Jorge Campos
Navarrete has drawn national media attention, not only for the
celebrity involved but also for the brazen manner in which it was
carried out.
</P>
<P>
   A gang of at least half a dozen men seized their victim in broad
daylight on Wednesday and did not even bother to cover their faces.
</P>
<P>
   In another curious detail, Gov. Angel Aguirre Rivero of Guerrero
state, where the crime took place, said on Friday that the
kidnappers had still not established communication with the Campos
family. That appeared to contradict newspaper reports that the
kidnappers had demanded a $1 million ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Campos Navarrete, who in major-league soccer has played for the
Los Angeles Galaxy and now has a contract to play for the Chicago
Fire, also plays in Mexico's professional leagues and for the
national team. He is the idol of millions here and appears
frequently on Mexican television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   At least six men wearing workers' clothes lay in wait for the
soccer star's father, Alvaro Campos Gonzalez, 65, shortly before 2
p.m. Wednesday at a soccer field in a southern suburb of the
Pacific city of Acapulco, according to news accounts. When Campos
arrived, the men pulled out AK-47 rifles, seized, beat and tied up
two of his aides, and drove him away in a pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because the abduction came during a tense post-election
standoff between President Ernesto Zedillo's Institutional
Revolutionary Party, and the leftist Party of the Democratic
Revolution, some experts see political motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an important current of analysts who believe this
kidnapping has political dimensions,'' said Lucio Mendoza, a former
coordinator at Mexico's national intelligence agency who has
founded an institute that studies organized crime here.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnapping occurred 10 days after gubernatorial elections in
Guerrero in which Rene Juarez Cisneros, the governing party
candidate, claimed victory by a narrow margin. The Party of the
Democratic Revolution, accusing the governing party of vote-buying,
ballot-stuffing and vote-count irregularities, has refused to
recognize the victory and promised to harass the party with
continuing protests.
</P>
<P>
   During the gubernatorial campaign, Campos Navarrete appeared in
television commercials on the governing party candidate's behalf,
and his father is friendly with several prominent governing party
politicians, including the Acapulco mayor, Mexican newspapers said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The political context in Guerrero is also complicated by the
presence there of at least two guerrilla organizations tied to
previous kidnappings. Before the vote on Feb. 7, one group
threatened unspecified retaliation if the election appeared
fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers appear not to have carried out the abduction in
stolen vehicles. That, coupled with their failure to cover their
faces, suggested that they may have been inexperienced small-time
local criminals, Mendoza said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Campos Gonzalez's sisters told Mexican reporters that she
doubted that politics was a motive. ``These people just want money,
and we hope to reach a deal,'' she told the Mexico City newspaper
La Jornada.
</P>
</TEXT>
