<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Feb. 21, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONALISM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Kurds, Bosnians, Scots, former
Soviet republics, central African tribes, Marshall Islanders and
others: there is something startling, ironic and troubling in
discovering that nationalism is militantly bucking the trend toward
globalism and transnationalism and emerging with a new vengeance
from a half-century of enforced quiescence. Or is it? Many of the
new nationalistic movements are fighting not each other but simply
trying to better position themselves in the new global marketplace.
By Serge Schmemann. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-BRUTALITY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Can the `zero tolerance'
anti-crime policies that have come into vogue over the last decade
be implemented without the trampling of innocent people's rights?
Embedded in the public angst over police brutality, there is a dark
underbelly to the superficially unassailable goal of stamping out
crime: Americans have come not only to tolerate a degree of
brutality from their police officers, but also, in ways subtle and
unsubtle, to encourage it. By Frank Bruni. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVES-MORALS-REVIEW (Nashua, N.H.) _ Angered and puzzled
by President Clinton's acquittal, some conservatives have come to
an extraordinary realization, which may carry grim implications for
the their movement: They blame not themselves for mishandling the
whole episode, but a public whose moral standards have collapsed.
But blaming the prevailing public will can be risky, particularly
in an age when politicians find that public to be increasingly
aloof. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATORS-LAWYERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ State legislatures have
always had their farmers, teachers, engineers and entrepreneurs,
but from the early days of the Republic, no group has been as
over-represented as lawyers. But for the last three decades, even
as the profession has grown in numbers, its grip on state capitols
has steadily slipped, a trend that continued in the turnover
brought by the 1998 elections. By Richard Perez-Pena. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-JOBS-REVIEW (Bad River Reservation, Wis.) _ Many Indians
are returning to their ancestral homes, not just for funerals and
weddings but for jobs. Legalized tribal gambling has spawned a
windfall of new employment in casinos, hotels and restaurants. And
the profits are often invested locally, enlivening formerly
moribund tribal economies. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   YANKS-CLEMENS-REVIEW (New York) _ Roger Clemens, the best
starting pitcher in baseball over the last 15 seasons and one of
the 8 or 10 best of all time, gets a chance, possibly his last, for
the World Series ring that will validate his career. The Yanks get
the best pitcher of his era, in his prime or close to it. By Allen
Barra.
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL-POLICE-REVIEW (Washington) _ A look at the growing trend
in Congress to federalize crimes that are traditionally handled by
state and local authorities. Federal law enforcement agents are
being asked to track down car-jackers, wife beaters, drunk drivers
and low-level drug dealers. Some legal experts warn of the
emergence of a national police force. By Steven A. Holmes. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   TABLOIDS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The National Enquirer and the
Star have seen their circulations plummet in the last five years as
the median age of their readers has risen from just over 35 to
around 40. A look at some recent headlines and quotations.
</P>
<P>
   TOY-FAIR-REVIEW (New York) _ A look at the 96th American
International Toy Fair, where 1,700 exhibitors gathered to peddle
their wares to 20,000 buyers. Most of the toys and games haven't
hit stores yet. Some are still prototypes and failed in
demonstrations; others succeeded in demonstrations and will still
fail in stores. A look at some of the toys exhibited. By Jenny Lyn
Bader.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-WAR-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Pentagon does not like to say
it, but almost-daily skirmishes between U.S. pilots and Iraqi
forces have quickly turned into a low-level war of attrition that
appears to have no end in sight. Not since the Persian Gulf War in
1991 _ and, before that, Vietnam _ have U.S. forces engaged in such
routine combat in such a sustained way over such a prolonged
period. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ A look at the political
consequences of the recent economic crisis in East Asia and Brazil;
they are as varied as the countries themselves. Even as the world
economy seems to be stabilizing after 20 months of chaos, the
political tensions engendered by those events are only worsening.
From Brasilia to Beijing to Tokyo, leaders who once talked,
Clinton-like, about the benefits of plunging into a globally
integrated economy are now talking about how to get out of the
pool. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   SELF-IMMOLATION-REVIEW (Undated) _ A grisly shadow from the
earliest days of the Vietnam War crept across the media landscape
last week as Kurdish protesters in Europe set themselves on fire or
threatened to. The events evoked memories of 1963, when Buddhist
monks immolated themselves to protest the Saigon regime. A look at
the historical and psychological aspects of self-immolation. By Joe
Sharkey.
</P>
