<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-NEWYORK-NY     02-20 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-NEWYORK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GORE, BANE OR GAIN OF A CLINTON CANDIDACY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over the past week, Democrats have reveled in the
possibility that Hillary Rodham Clinton might run for one of New
York's seats in the Senate, casting her hypothetical candidacy next
year as a precious gift from the political gods. For the state's
beleaguered Democratic Party, it might be exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   But for someone else with a rather large stake in the elections
of 2000, Mrs. Clinton's candidacy might not be so divine.
Democratic political analysts and several advisers of Vice
President Al Gore, the front-runner for the Democratic nomination
for president, say Gore may have more to lose than gain if Mrs.
Clinton runs in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably creates a little bit of a distraction for two of
Al Gore's most important supporters, namely the president and the
first lady,'' said Geoff D. Garin, a Democratic pollster. ``Both
Clintons could and would play an enormously supportive role for
Gore in a whole host of ways, and if Mrs. Clinton is a candidate
for the Senate, there's going to be something at least as pressing
on their to-do list.''
</P>
<P>
   Her candidacy also could draw money and celebrities from Gore's
side to Mrs. Clinton's. ``Will it overlap with some fund-raising?''
asked one of Gore's campaign advisers, who spoke on the condition
of anonymity. ``Yes. Will it be a high-profile campaign that
attracts talent we would like to attract? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Smith, who has been hired to manage Gore's presidential
campaign, said the diminished presence of the Clintons on the
campaign trail for Gore would not be critical, in part because the
excitement about the Democratic Party that the Clintons would be
creating in New York would fan out to other places.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she chooses to run,'' Smith said, ``we would look forward
to running with her.''
</P>
<P>
   But other people working on Gore's campaign said that for the
vice president, there would be an undeniable downside. They said
that while Gore had not expressed any reservations about Mrs.
Clinton's candidacy, some of his advisers briefly had discussed the
implications, because they had been operating on the presumption
that and Mrs. Clinton would campaign extensively for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a potential weapon we don't have,'' said one of Gore's
advisers, noting that Mrs. Clinton's speeches and appearances at
fund-raising events last year provided enormous help to Democratic
Senate candidates like Barbara Boxer of California.
</P>
<P>
   Another adviser, however, said that the Democratic turnout that
Mrs. Clinton might inspire in New York would sew up victory in the
state for Gore, allowing him to devote energy and money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it means we only have to buy a third as much television
time in New York,'' said the adviser, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, ``that's millions of dollars saved. There are upsides
and downsides, and we'll just have to adapt to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the frenzy of speculation that intensified with the
first lady's announcement on Tuesday that she was giving her
candidacy careful thought, some people who know her say there is
little chance she will decide to run. Several of her close friends
said this week that Mrs. Clinton was probably months away from
making a decision and was not leaning either way.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hasn't said yes or no in her mind yet,'' said Diane Blair,
a longtime friend from Arkansas. ``She very strongly feels she
needs some time and space _ real thinking time. Hillary does not
jump into things.''
</P>
<P>
   One close friend said that in addition to Mrs. Clinton's
concerns about money and the family's privacy, the first lady knew
that the pedestal she occupies as one of the country's most
respected, popular women might crumble instantly in the rough and
tumble of a campaign. Mrs. Clinton also remembers how it felt, just
a few years ago, not to have such a perch, her friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends also said that Mrs. Clinton realizes that energy spent
on herself is energy denied others like Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are questions of opportunities lost and roads not
taken,'' said Mandy Grunwald, a Democratic media consultant who
worked not only for Clinton but also for Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan of New York, whose retirement is opening up the seat for
which Mrs. Clinton would run.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's true of the campaign road 2000,'' Ms. Grunwald
said. ``If she was campaigning for herself, she obviously would not
have the time to campaign as fully for Vice President Gore or House
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there are some reasons why Mrs. Clinton's candidacy
might actually be desirable for Gore. By all appearances, she has a
good shot at winning and helping to lift other congressional
candidates in New York to victory, and more Democrats in Congress
would make it easier for a Democratic president to institute his
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert G. Torricelli of New Jersey, chairman of the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, also said that Mrs.
Clinton's candidacy in New York could help Gore by making sure that
Democrats defined the terms of the political debate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather she shook less hands in other states'' and instead
``changed the national debate on substantive issues,'' said
Torricelli, who has been fiercely lobbying Mrs. Clinton to run.
</P>
<P>
   But other political veterans took a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have an asset like Hillary Clinton showing up at
fund-raisers in California, as well as Florida and other key states
_ that's a hell of a draw,'' said Leon E. Panetta, a former
Democratic congressman from California who served as Clinton's
chief of staff in his first term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you can have others, but not with the same impact,''
Panetta said. ``In a tight race nationally, I think it could make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Gorlin, a Democratic strategist in Washington, D.C.,
pointed out another potential problem for Gore. In terms of issues,
Ms. Gorlin said, Mrs. Clinton's candidacy could essentially box
Gore in, because she would be the one defining the president's
legacy in the course of her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore no longer has the option of picking and choosing among
the things in the Clinton record that he wants to run on or
defend,'' Ms. Gorlin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
