<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2683 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-69     02-20 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-695(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN LEADER VISITS PAKISTAN IN SHOW OF FRIENDSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAGHA, Pakistan _ In an extraordinary show of warmth between two
bitterly hostile nations, India's prime minister, Atal Behari
Vajpayee, rode a bus Saturday through the fertile plains of Punjab,
crossed the usually closed border gate here and cordially embraced
his Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries, led by these same two leaders, startled the
world last May when they conducted tit-for-tat tests of nuclear
bombs. The bellicose euphoria of their people _ stoking the fires
of half a century of enmity _ led much of the world to fret that
the Indian subcontinent was now the globe's most perilous nuclear
flash point.
</P>
<P>
   But relations between them, while still tense and unpredictable,
have taken a turn for the better. In recent months, the two prime
ministers have spoken both in person and on the telephone,
developing the rapport that led Sharif to invite Vajpayee to pay a
call. It is the first visit to Pakistan by an Indian prime minister
since 1989 and only the third ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bring the good will and hopes of my fellow Indians, who seek
abiding peace and harmony with Pakistan,'' Vajpayee, 72, said as
his bus finished its journey along a route that holds vivid, if not
always happy, memories for the people of both countries. ``I am
conscious that this is a defining moment in South Asian history,
and I hope we will be able to rise to the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharif had been waiting for his guest for 15 minutes and at one
point walked a few feet across the border into India, where a brass
band was playing and dancers whirled in the shady lane.
</P>
<P>
   Colorful bunting was strung on both sides of the crossing
station. The roadways were a burst of color with newly planted
flowers and freshly painted stripes. Red carpets had been unfurled.
Indian and Pakistani flags flew side by side.
</P>
<P>
   As the bus crossed into Pakistan, Sharif, a 49-year-old
millionaire industrialist, stood at the door and waited for the
older prime minister to manage the steps down. The two men greeted
each other with a double handshake. It did not seem enough to those
cheering. Vajpayee initiated a hug.
</P>
<P>
   Then the bus was slowly emptied of the diplomats, businessmen,
athletes and film stars who had joined the journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling, the greatest in the world,'' shouted Dev
Anand, a veteran actor who has family roots in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   After juice was served, a color guard saluted Vajpayee, and the
prime ministers inspected the Pakistani troops who stood at
attention with bayonets drawn. Finally, the two leaders left
together aboard a helicopter for the historic city of Lahore and a
day and a half of serious discussions and highly choreographed
pomp, including a banquet at Lahore Fort, a Mughal-era treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Topics for discussion will include both nuclear weaponry and the
disputed territory of Kashmir. Results of the talks are to be
announced at a joint news conference on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not just two neighbors any more _ we are nuclear
neighbors,'' said Pakistan's information minister, Mushahid
Hussein. ``Success means we are not shooting at each other. We are
not shouting at each other. Success means we are talking to each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   The nominal occasion for Vajpayee's trip was the inaugural run
of regularly scheduled bus service between New Delhi and Lahore.
The 250 miles would normally require a 14-hour journey, but
Vajpayee avoided most of the wearying travel by getting on the bus
in the northern Indian city of Amritsar and staying aboard only for
the final 23 miles to the border.
</P>
<P>
   As he entered the bright gold 31-seat vehicle, he said: ``I have
mixed feelings. I am happy that I am going to Lahore on Prime
Minister Sharif's invitation, but I feel sorry that we have lost so
many years.''
</P>
<P>
   To many Indians, these will be surprising words, coming as they
do from the leader of the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party,
the political arm of groups widely seen as anti-Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message to the people of Pakistan will be short and
simple,'' Vajpayee said. ``Put aside the bitterness of the past and
let us together make a new beginning.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The elaborate welcome the Indian prime minister received holds
special emotional meaning, not merely for its promise of peace but
because of the indelible grief suffered by families of both nations
along this same route in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Some 12 million people were uprooted during Partition, the name
history has given to the sundering of the subcontinent with the
stroke of a pen. Hastily drawn maps separated predominantly Muslim
Pakistan from predominantly Hindu India when both nations were
granted independence.
</P>
<P>
   Hindus, Muslims and Sikhs had all staked their claims to the
rich farmland and ancient cities of Punjab, and those who lost out
fled in enormous migrations, crossing paths with the masses of
people coming to supplant them.
</P>
<P>
   Atrocities were carried out on all sides in a prolonged mania of
rage and vengeance. Children in both nations are told and retold
stories of skewered infants, massacres of entire trainloads of
passengers, drainage ditches teeming with bloody corpses. One
million people rapidly perished, and the two countries still feed
off that hate.
</P>
<P>
   The border here has remained a gash that separates the former
countrymen. In a half-century, India and Pakistan have fought three
wars with each other, and military skirmishes and artillery fire
continue relentlessly like a low-grade fever.
</P>
<P>
   For some Indians and Pakistanis, news of the bus trip has
brought a surge of nostalgia for their ancestral homes, though for
others emotion rises in waves of anger.
</P>
<P>
   Across Pakistan, thousands of Islamic fundamentalists on
Saturday protested Vajpayee's visit. Some carried signs: ``Vajpayee
Go Home'' and ``No friendship between Hindus and Muslims.'' Many
stores were closed. Some roads were blocked and vehicles were
attacked. One policeman was shot in an exchange of gunfire in an
area not far from Sharif's private residence in Lahore.
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders have hard-liners to mollify. A week ago, in the
midst of the felicitous buildup to the bus ride, Sharif declared a
Day of Solidarity with Kashmiri ``freedom fighters'' _ people the
Indians consider terrorists. During protests, Sharif's supporters
dragged Vajpayee's effigy through the streets before setting it
ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   The prime ministers have domestic troubles as well. Vajpayee
heads a multiparty coalition government with small allies who
require full-time cajoling. Sharif's country is economically
hobbled and frightfully lawless. His use of military courts to try
criminal cases speedily was ruled unconstitutional by the Supreme
Court the week before last.
</P>
<P>
   Bus diplomacy will likely be a boon to their popularity.
According to polls, the common people in both countries
overwhelmingly want improved relations.
</P>
<P>
   There was a demonstration of this in recent weeks as Pakistan's
cricket team toured India for the first time in 12 years. The
matches were played without disruption. Indeed, when the Pakistanis
won the first match, played in Madras, Indian fans gave the
visitors a thunderous ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the current talks will produce substantial progress as
well as smiling photos depends on the willingness of each side to
move from entrenched positions, especially those regarding Kashmir,
an Indian state with a Muslim majority.
</P>
<P>
   For the last five months, high-level civil servants from the two
nations have been holding periodic _ and largely fruitless _
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, men with more power will step in. The meetings in Lahore
may be merely a historic start. Sharif has accepted Vajpayee's
invitation to ride the bus the other way. Details for further bus
diplomacy are expected to be worked out soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
