<HEADLINE>
IN KOSOVO, FEAR OF AIRSTRIKES AND REPRISALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-TALKS, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Isa Hoxha looked out through the cracked
glass of his shop window and gestured toward his Serbian neighbor
who, he said, had hurled a stone through his bakery the week before
last.
</P>
<P>
   Hoxha, an ethnic Albanian in the overwhelmingly Serbian village
of Kosovo Polje, on the outskirts of Kosovo's capital, Pristina,
said he had had no problems until that stone was thrown. As the
deadline neared for agreement on Kosovo's fate, however, the
tension with his Serbian neighbors rose palpably, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is listening to the news, Serbs and Albanians,
waiting to see what will happen,'' Hoxha said. His family is still
living behind the bakery, but he said he was ready to evacuate them
at a moment's notice if the peace talks in France broke up without
agreement and NATO bombed Serbian targets.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every member of Kosovo's ethnic Albanian population _ 90
percent of the estimated 2 million people in this Connecticut-sized
province _ expects the Serbs to retaliate against them if the
alliance strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo's Serbs, barely one in 10 of the province's population,
were also nervous. A Serbian shopkeeper across the road from
Hoxha's bakery refused to talk to a Western journalist on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Some 150 Serbs, throwing stones and shouting anti-NATO slogans,
forced nine of the unarmed foreign monitors here to flee the
northern village of Lapastica, said Beatrice Lacoste of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's 1,300 foreign monitors may evacuate on Sunday
if peace talks fail.
</P>
<P>
   An hour's drive southwest of Pristina, in the ethnic Albanian
village of Dragobilje, men were hanging around on a muddy street,
shivering in the damp cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope for the best, but we just do not know if there is
danger ahead for us or not,'' said Rame Paqarizi, a farmer and
father of four.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer the villagers fled into nearby woods when Serbian
security forces attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two miles away is the town of Malisevo, still deserted
and scorched from last year's fighting, occupied by a single
Serbian police unit.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers said the real danger was that if the peace talks
failed, fighting could resume. The armed ethnic Albanian fighters
of the Kosovo Liberation Army, who guarded the entrance to the
village, were no match for Serbian tanks and artillery and would
not be able to protect them, said Paqarizi's nephew, Imer.
</P>
</TEXT>
