<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-DEMOCRATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 RETIREMENTS CLOUD DEMOCRATS' HOPES IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Nev., Ky., Calif., Wis., Pa., Wash., Mo., Minn., R.I.,
Del.)   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Democratic Party's hopes of retaking the Senate
next year may have dimmed a bit with the unexpected retirements
announced last week by two Democrats who almost certainly could
have kept their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey and Richard Bryan of Nevada
surprised the political world by saying they would not seek
re-election next year. Lautenberg said he was tired of raising
money; Bryan, who has been in politics for more than three decades,
wants to try something else.
</P>
<P>
   They joined Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the New York Democrat, as
the only senators so far to announce their exits, creating three
open seats in states that Democrats had counted on in their uphill
fight to recapture the Senate. Republicans control the chamber,
with 55 seats compared with 45 for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have been riding a wave of optimism since the November
elections, when they exceeded expectations by winning five House
seats and holding their own in the Senate. They have also been
buoyed by polls showing that the public soured on the Republicans
during their drive to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were also hoping to make headway in the Senate because
they had fewer seats to defend. Of the 33 senators up for
re-election in 2000, 19 are Republicans and 14 are Democrats. Of
the 19 Republicans, 13 are from states that Clinton won in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who heads the National
Republican Senatorial Committee, said in an interview that the
Democrats have little reason to celebrate now.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Democratic euphoria over impeachment has vanished in a
week,'' McConnell said. ``All this big talk about getting the
Senate has been made dramatically more difficult. Now they're going
to have to fight like hell to hold onto three seats they already
hold.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that trying to save those seats would divert money and
energy from other states where Democrats were hoping to pick off
Republicans who might be vulnerable because they voted to convict
Clinton while polls showed their constituents supported keeping him
in office.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a strong fund-raiser like Hillary Rodham Clinton enters
the race in New York, McConnell said, the Democrats would still
have to send money her way because her presence would prompt big
contributions from Republicans who oppose her.
</P>
<P>
   Prime targets for the Democrats are Republican Sens. Rod Grams
in Minnesota, Rick Santorum in Pennsylvania, Spencer Abraham in
Michigan, John Ashcroft in Missouri and Slade Gorton in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Rothenberg, author of a nonpartisan political newsletter
that analyzes races across the country, said the three Democratic
departures marked at least a temporary setback for the party. ``It
makes a five- or six-seat Democratic gain that much harder,'' he
said. ``Democrats didn't have to worry about what was going on
behind their own lines, but now they do.''
</P>
<P>
   He agreed that the Democrats would have to divert money to New
York and New Jersey, two very expensive states, forcing the party
into difficult choices during a presidential election, which
traditionally drains donations away from lower-ballot races.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans historically enjoy a financial edge, and 2000 is
shaping up no differently. Already, the 19 Republicans facing
re-election have raised $6.5 million, according to reports from the
Federal Election Commission, while the 11 Democrats for whom
records were available have raised just $1.8 million. Fund-raising
reports for the three other Democrats were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tucker, a spokesman for the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee, played down the potential damage from the three
Democratic retirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into '98 knowing we would play defense, and in 2000 we
still have to play defense,'' he said. ``But we've also got
opportunities where we're able to play offense. That gives us some
reason to be encouraged that we are within reach.''
</P>
<P>
   One unknown is whether this month's Democratic retirements will
be balanced out by Republican retirements and whether any more
Democrats will leave.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation centered on Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., who has said
only that he will announce his plans at the appropriate time. Other
question marks are hanging over Republican Sens. John Chafee of
Rhode Island, who will be 78 in 2000, and William Roth of Delaware,
who will be 79.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to all these people, which is not to say they've
given me total assurance,'' McConnell said, but he added, ``I don't
believe we'll have any retirements at all.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, there was speculation about Sens.
Herbert Kohl of Wisconsin and Charles Robb of Virginia, although
aides to both said they were preparing for re-election. Another
possible loss for Democrats could be Sen. Dianne Feinstein of
California if Vice President Al Gore wins the Democratic
presidential nomination and chooses her as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   On average, Rothenberg said, three or four senators from each
party retire every two years. The numbers have ranged recently from
a low of three senators, all Republicans, who left in 1990 to a
high of 14 (six Republicans and eight Democrats) who left in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He said he could not predict any other retirements because there
appeared to be no common theme among the three departing Democrats.
``All three just want to get on with their lives,'' he said. ``The
Senate is a peculiar kind of occupation that takes 100 percent of
your time. There just happen to be some normal people up this year
who decided they wanted to get a life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
