<SLUG> BC-NY-TRASH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY RETHINKS PLAN TO EXPORT TRASH TO OTHER STATES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Ind., N.J., Ohio, Pa., Va.)   (rk) 
 By   DOUGLAS MARTIN and ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Strong opposition from states slated to receive New
York City's garbage is forcing city officials to rethink their
plans for where New York's trash will be dumped as they prepare to
close the giant Fresh Kills landfill on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   With the tentative sites in three states in doubt, the city will
soon ask companies for more proposals on ways _ and places _ to
deal with trash. And for the first time, the city is scouting rural
areas in upstate New York for landfills, a strategy that could
reduce the risk of political attack. Earlier planning had focused
exclusively on out-of-state landfills.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty New York City is having negotiating the politics
of exporting its 13,000 tons of daily residential trash raises
questions about how easily _ or even whether _ it will be able to
meet the state-ordered deadline for closing Fresh Kills by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   When the city agreed to close Fresh Kills, it planned to
establish waste transfer stations throughout the city where garbage
would be taken before being shipped to out-of-state landfills by
private companies. This was seen as a viable option since the city
was already exporting all 13,000 tons a day of commercial trash.
</P>
<P>
   But recently and in rapid succession, the city's plans have been
pounded by officials in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia is about to pass several laws severely limiting garbage
shipment and dumping. Pennsylvania is pushing for a freeze on the
size of its landfills and has doubled its inspections of trash
trucks. State, county and local officials in New Jersey roundly
reject the idea of huge new transfer stations, which the city has
proposed there.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at City Hall and the Sanitation Department insist that
the setbacks and the scrambling for new strategies will not delay
plans for closing Fresh Kills, but others have their doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city's proposals have run into obstacles all over the
place,'' said Jim Tripp, general counsel for the Environmental
Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the mounting uneasiness on Staten Island, Borough
President Guy V. Molinari has questioned whether city Sanitation
Department officials are committed to closing the landfill, and
suggested that some are sabotaging Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's plan.
For one thing, he said, the states through which New York plans to
ship its waste should have been fully consulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some individuals within the Sanitation Department don't want
to see the landfill closed,'' he said, an assertion the department
vigorously rejects.
</P>
<P>
   Under the city's plan, announced in December, three new transfer
stations would handle the city's residential waste: two in Newark
and Carteret, N.J., to be built by private companies, and one at
the Port of Red Hook in Brooklyn. From the transfer stations the
garbage would be taken by truck, rail or barge to landfills in
Virginia, Pennsylvania and other states.
</P>
<P>
   In states that only recently were aggressively enlarging
landfills or building new ones, politicians now grouse that they
resent their states being regarded as dumps.
</P>
<P>
   That resentment intensified recently after after Giuliani said
other states should welcome city trash in return for the New York
cultural attractions their citizens might enjoy. The campaign had
begun last fall when Pennsylvania, Virginia and several other
states began developing common strategies to curtail the influx of
out-of-state trash.
</P>
<P>
   This led to intensified inspections of the hundreds of garbage
trucks traveling on interstate highways, and the placement of
limits on the amount of trash permitted at new landfills or
expanded ones.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery 11 days ago of illegal medical waste from Brooklyn
dumped at a Virginia landfill further aggravated feelings about New
York waste. Virginia, like other states, requires that medical
waste be disposed of at special facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia and other states are cooperating to develop a proposal
for a federal law giving states more control over the waste
crossing their borders. A series of Supreme Court decisions over
the last decade has made it clear that only an act of Congress can
give the states the power to regulate the interstate garbage
business.
</P>
<P>
   The push for federal legislation is ``not an anti-New York
effort,'' said Donald S. Welsh, deputy secretary for state-federal
relations of the Pennsylvania Department of Environmental
Protection. ``We do not want to build a fence at the border and
choke it off completely,'' he said. ``We just want to put a set of
reasonable restrictions on it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The mounting opposition from other states surprised city
officials because New York has exported its commercial waste to
other states, including Pennsylvania, Virginia, Ohio and Indiana,
for more than a decade. The residential garbage going to Fresh
Kills is being gradually rerouted through this established
commercial system.
</P>
<P>
   City officials would not comment on their search for new
options, saying it must be kept secret under municipal procurement
rules. But they suggested that they might consider proposals
previously rejected, as well as completely new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Local and county officials in New Jersey have opposed building
transfer stations in Carteret and Newark, and Gov. Christie Whitman
has said she would not permit garbage barges to travel past the
state's beaches.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey authorities have so far taken no official action.
But in Virginia, state legislators last week agreed on the outlines
of a law that would ban garbage barges on Virginia's rivers.
</P>
<P>
   New York City had planned to send as much as 4,000 tons of
residential garbage a day by barge from Red Hook to a new barge
pier on the James River in Charles City County, Va. Waste
Management Inc., which handles most of the city's exported waste
and is one of the largest contractors in the field, built the $15
million pier to funnel garbage to one of its landfills.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the city had planned to truck most of its
garbage out of state. For the long term, the city is committed to
using rail and barge transportation, and it is the threat to this
approach that most concerns city officials.
</P>
<P>
   The result could be that what was intended to be the interim
plan becomes permanent, meaning tens of thousands more trucks on
city streets for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the trucks would be piling up at all hours of the day and
night,'' warned Eric Goldstein, a senior attorney for the Natural
Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   States receiving the garbage see their own endless parade of
garbage trucks in similar fashion, particularly in Pennsylvania and
Virginia, No. 1 and No. 2. respectively, in landfill capacity in
the country. Both have a surplus of dump space and have for years
imported millions of tons of commercial garbage and construction
debris from New York City and New York state.
</P>
<P>
   There were few complaints, even when the city started sending
residential garbage from the Bronx in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But 1997 was also the first year that Virginia began compiling
an annual tally of garbage imports. When the numbers were totaled,
local newspapers made much of the fact that the state was the
nation's second-biggest trash importer.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Giuliani's comments about the obligations of Virginia
and other states to accommodate the trash of the nation's leading
city, which inflamed passions and prompted renewed calls from
Virginia politicians for federal legislation allowing states to ban
imports of garbage.
</P>
<P>
   The grand finale was the medical waste discovered mingled with
Brooklyn garbage on Feb. 10 at a Virginia landfill in Charles City
County, the third day of a blitz of inspections across eight states
and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in the Virginia Capitol, Gov. James S.
Gilmore III, wearing rubber gloves, displayed the used syringes,
bandages and other material, vowing to seek $500,000 in fines
against Waste Management and push for stronger laws to control
medical waste.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
