<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2703 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-2TAK     02-20 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-2TAKES(1,150)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT PRESSES FOR NATO'S FORCES TO POLICE KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-RESIDENTS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMBOUILLET, France _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
negotiated intensely on Saturday, hours past deadline, to try and
achieve peace in Kosovo, spelling out to the leaders of Serbia that
they must accept deployment of up to 30,000 NATO troops, including
a small contingent of American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and four European foreign ministers arrived Saturday
morning at the 14th-century castle where ethnic Albanian and
Serbian delegates have been sequestered for two weeks, and tried to
squeeze an accord out of them.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after a NATO-appointed deadline of noon (6 a.m. Eastern
time), the biggest sticking point remained the demand that NATO
troops enforce a settlement in Kosovo, a province of southern
Serbia that has been roiled by conflict for the last year. About
2,000 people are thought to have been killed, and as many as
200,000 driven from their homes by fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and NATO have said airstrikes against
Serbian military targets would commence if the president of
Yugoslavia, Slobodan Milosevic, did not back down and accept
foreign troops.
</P>
<P>
   But although more than 400 NATO strike and support planes
remained at the ready, there was little talk at the castle on
Saturday of airstrikes, and greater concentration on working out
details of making NATO soldiers acceptable to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   More than two hours after the deadline, Albright's spokesman,
James Rubin, said the secretary had just completed a half-hour
face-to-face session with Milan Milutinovic, the president of
Serbia and Milosevic's close ally. The man with the biggest
decision-making power, Milosevic, remained in Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
But it appeared clear that he had authorized Milutinovic to
negotiate seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has insisted so far that NATO troops in Kosovo would
represent an infringement of the sovereignty of Serbia and
Yugoslavia, the federation of which Serbia is a part, along with
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, which was stripped of its autonomy 10 years ago by
Milosevic, is a province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   By the noon deadline, Albright had hoped to have the ethnic
Albanian delegation sign the political text of the peace agreement,
which calls for autonomy for Kosovo over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no announcement of this, and the ethnic Albanians
have said they were upset about the addition of an upper house to a
proposed legislature. ``If everything was great, we'd tell you; if
it was terrible, we'd tell you that,'' Rubin said to reporters
after the deadline passed.
</P>
<P>
   No decision had been made, he said, on whether to extend the
talks formally, or whether to let the deadline informally slide.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 ambassadors of NATO were scheduled to meet in Brussels,
Belgium, to review the status of the talks. The NATO
secretary-general, Javier Solana, was empowered by the 16 member
nations two weeks ago to order airstrikes if the Serbs failed to go
along with an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Solana said he would consult NATO members before ordering
any bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent attempt to water down the NATO deployment,
Milutinovic raised the prospect on Friday night of using armed
civilians working under the auspices of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe as a substitute for alliance
troops keeping the Kosovo peace, Western diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO was extremely unlikely to accept such a proposal, it
was the first sign that the Serbs might eventually accept armed
foreigners on their territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs are also not pleased that they would be required under
any settlement to make dramatic reductions in their security forces
in Kosovo _ for the police, who have been blamed for massacres of
ethnic Albanian civilians, and for the Yugoslav army, which patrols
the borders with Albania and Macedonia. Ethnic Albanian guerrillas
have received weapons mostly across the porous, mountainous
frontier with Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanian guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army are
required under the proposed pact to disarm over a period of six
months.
</P>
<P>
   The high-stakes drive to reach an accord in Kosovo began after
the massacre of 45 ethnic Albanian civilians by the Serbian
security police last month in the village of Racak.
</P>
<P>
   The killings, apparently the worst of the massacres that have
marked the yearlong conflict, dramatized what many had known: that
the hatred between the two ethnic groups in Kosovo was
irretrievably deep. Unlike other parts of former Yugoslavia, where
different ethnic groups spoke the same language and intermarried,
there is little intermingling between the ethnic Albanians and the
Serbs in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the two ethnic groups deteriorated further
when Milosevic revoked the autonomy of Kosovo in 1989, swept
Albanians from all important posts and introduced a repressive
Serbian police and military regime in the province.
</P>
<P>
   The Racak massacre also illustrated that both sides in the
conflict were rearming for renewed hostilities in the spring. In
the last month, international monitors in Kosovo have reported
seeing fighters of the ethnic Albanians' Kosovo Liberation Army
carrying new, highly sophisticated sniper rifles as well as other
new weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian police and Yugoslav army increased the numbers of
their units in violation of a cease-fire agreement worked out in
October by the Clinton administration's special envoy, Richard
Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   With the danger of an unchecked conflict in Kosovo spoiling the
celebrations in Washington in April for the 50th anniversary of
NATO, the administration moved quickly in late January to forge a
combination of diplomacy and military force that would convince
both sides to sign a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Albright urged the Contact Group _ which includes the United
States, France, Germany, Britain, Italy and Russia _ to run the
diplomatic negotiations that have taken place at Rambouillet.
During her visit to Moscow in late January, the Russians made clear
they were ready to work toward a solution in Kosovo and signaled
that they were ready to distance themselves from their traditional
allies, the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO, the administration fought hard to get the 16 alliance
members to give Solana the authority to order airstrikes against
Serbia if peace talks failed. It also moved, but with less
appetite, to have Americans included in a NATO-led ground force
that would enforce any political settlement emerging from the
Rambouillet talks.
</P>
<P>
   The point of a political agreement is to grant the province
self-government status within Yugoslavia, giving the ethnic
Albanians who make up 90 percent of the population the control over
their daily lives that has been denied by the Serbian authorities.
The question of Kosovo's future independence _ the rallying cry of
the insurgents _ would be deferred for three years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For the administration, the toughest part has been making the
case for a second deployment of U.S. troops to the Balkans in less
than four years.
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary of Defense Walter Slocombe told a congressional
hearing that regional stability was at stake in the southern
Balkans, where a continued war in Kosovo could spill over into
neighboring Albania and Macedonia, and possibly envelop two NATO
partners, Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The peace in Bosnia, where U.S. troops remain stationed, was
also on the line, Slocombe said, as well as the performance of
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the U.S. troop commitment on Feb. 13, President
Clinton stressed that this time _ in contrast to Bosnia _ the
Europeans would be providing the bulk of the NATO force. The U.S.
offer of 4,000 troops was only 15 percent of the deployment, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 Marines from the 24th Marine Expeditionary Unit
based at Camp Lejeune, N.C., were poised this weekend on ships in
the Mediterranean to be among the first troops to land in Kosovo in
the event of a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to allow Europe to do most of the work in Kosovo,
the administration is trying to ensure that it does not lose its
leverage. It is a new and at times seemingly uncomfortable
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington doesn't want to pay the bills but doesn't like
being the junior partner,'' said a NATO official of the military
plans for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union, whose countries are most concerned about
waves of impoverished ethnic Albanian refugees flooding into
Western Europe if the fighting continues, has pledged hundreds of
millions of dollars in civil reconstruction money for Kosovo over
the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The diminished role of U.S. troops will mean that a British
general will be the commander on the ground in Kosovo for the first
months of the peacekeeping operation. Thus, U.S. soldiers will have
to get accustomed to a non-American commander on the ground under
the authority of an American, Gen. Wesley Clark, who is the supreme
commander of NATO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
