<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Feb. 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moderately heavy snows will fall in the Rockies on Sunday as a
tandem of Pacific disturbances advance inland. Bursts of snow, a
few accompanied by thunder and lightning, will strafe the mountains
of northern Utah and northern Nevada as a potent jet-stream
disturbance approaches from the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   In some of the valleys, rain showers will change to snow showers
as a pocket of cold air arrives overhead. Snow will spread to the
mountains of western Colorado and southwest Wyoming later Sunday.
In the wake of the disturbance, snow showers and flurries will
linger in the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Snow will accumulate from the Cascades of Washington and Oregon
to the Bitterroots of Montana and Idaho and the Tetons of northwest
Wyoming as an upper-level low-pressure system pivots slowly east
over the region. Snow may accumulate in the valleys, with storm
totals of 4 inches possible in spots by later Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the upper-level low, gusty showers, a few with
thunder and small hail, will speckle western Oregon, western
Washington and the coast and interior valleys of northern
California early in the day. Intervals of sunshine with puffy
cumulus will develop in some areas of Oregon and northern
California on Sunday afternoon as a ridge of high pressure
approaches from the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered snow showers will develop along southwest shores of
the Great Lakes, where chilly winds from the northeast have been
moistened in transit over open waters. Flurries and snow showers
will dust some of the mountains in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Rare Cacophony
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for snow to mix with rain, but it is rare for
heavy rain and heavy snow to occur simultaneously. At Charlotte,
N.C., on Friday, while lightning flashed and thunder echoed
overhead, heavy rain and heavy snow were observed at the same time.
With temperatures a few thousand feet aloft hovering near 32
degrees, air rising within thunderstorms cooled, allowing
snowflakes to avoid melting on descent toward the ground. But the
variable cooling from changeable updrafts also permitted some
snowflakes to melt, setting the stage for a cacophony of heavy rain
and snow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
