<HEADLINE>
NO TIME TO ORGANIZE THE SURF, UNION LEADERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., Nev.)  (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ The labor leaders gathered here for the
AFL-CIO's winter meeting last week seemed haunted by one image:
those embarrassing pictures from years past of big-bellied union
potentates, cigars in mouths, sunning themselves by the hotel pool.
</P>
<P>
   Labor's strategic thinkers were so alarmed by this image that
three years ago they announced they would halt the decades-old
practice of meeting each winter in exclusive Bal Harbour, just up
the road from here. John Sweeney, who was elected president of the
AFL-CIO two and a half years ago, knew it looked bad to use
members' dues money to pay for golf and luxury suites at a seaside
resort.
</P>
<P>
   So the decision was made to hold these meetings elsewhere, with
an emphasis on places where labor's chieftains could give impetus
to organizing drives. Accordingly, the 1997 winter meeting was held
in Los Angeles, and last year it was in Las Vegas (labor leaders
defended that choice because Las Vegas was a showplace of
successful union organizing).
</P>
<P>
   But this year the AFL-CIO, pulled perhaps by sun and surf,
returned to Florida, and not just to any hotel, but to the famed
Fontainebleau.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, nary a labor leader could be found poolside.
One reason was from 7 a.m. to 9 p.m. every day many union
presidents had meetings: about trade, politics, organizing
strategies. And unlike in past years, the leaders held community
forums about Social Security and safeguarding the right of workers
to form unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a minute to get outside during the day, although
one night at 11 I was finally able to take a stroll outside,'' said
John Wilhelm, president of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant
Employees Union.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders squirmed and squealed when a Republican Party
official attacked them for using members' dues to live it up in
sunny Miami. (``I suppose Republicans don't have meetings in places
like this,'' one labor leader said.) But a few union presidents
questioned the wisdom of gathering at a luxury resort that they
were too busy to enjoy. ``A lot of us haven't seen the sun or sea
in two days,'' said Sandra Feldman, president of the American
Federation of Teachers. ``Maybe we should have just met in
Washington. That would have saved us the trouble of flying down
here. And we wouldn't be hearing any of these attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy Days With Hoffa
</P>
<P>
   Labor conventions are even more scripted than political
conventions. Big-name Democrats always drop in to pay homage. Union
leaders always denounce free trade.
</P>
<P>
   But this year one big thing was not scripted: how James P.
Hoffa, the teamsters' president-elect, the man with the famous
father, would get on with other union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   There was anxiety about a split because Sweeney and several
other leaders had backed Hoffa's 1996 opponent, Ron Carey. There
were even rumors that Hoffa would pull the mighty International
Brotherhood of Teamsters out of the AFL-CIO. But Wednesday, when
Hoffa stopped in for a few minutes at a news conference alongside
Sweeney, it was as if they were best buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted he's with us,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hoffa gave a brief speech that could have been written by
Sweeney's staff. ``I'm absolutely committed to working with the
AFL-CIO to advance the cause of working families,'' he said. ``It's
no secret we've had our differences in the past. We cannot afford
disunity now. I'm interested in one thing _ it's rebuilding the
labor movement.''
</P>
<P>
   He ruled out leaving the federation, he attacked the North
American Free Trade Agreement, and he promised to do more
organizing and to back labor-friendly candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Several leaders said Hoffa and Sweeney needed each other. A
fight would weaken both, distracting Hoffa from rebuilding the
teamsters and Sweeney from reviving the AFL-CIO. ``He's been
received warmly and with relief,'' said Wilhelm of the hotel union.
``He's made explicitly clear that he wants to be an active,
participating member of the House of Labor. His father always told
him of the importance of being in the House of Labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Tall Men and a Tall Tale
</P>
<P>
   At the last two winter meetings, there was an out-and-out beauty
contest. One contestant was Vice President Al Gore; the other Dick
Gephardt, the House Democratic leader. When both were vying for the
2000 Democratic presidential nomination, Gore made sure he
delivered a major goodie. Two years ago, he warmed labor hearts by
announcing a plan to blacklist federal contractors that repeatedly
violated labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, with Gephardt having bowed out of the
presidential race, Gore provided only a minor goodie _ some draft
regulations on ergonomics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad for labor that Gephardt's not running because
that would have forced Gore to be a lot more generous,'' one
official said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a contest this year, but it was of the
David-vs.-Goliath variety. Goliath was played by Gore, the
front-runner for the Democratic nomination, and David was Bill
Bradley, the former New Jersey senator and former New York Knick
now running for president. (This David was at least 6 inches taller
than this Goliath.)
</P>
<P>
   When asked how he felt about playing David, Bradley borrowed a
page from basketball: ``I've been the overdog in my life. I've been
the underdog. I don't mind being the underdog. If you're the
overdog, you play cautious. If you're the underdog, you can be
bolder.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders said they came away impressed with Gore and
Bradley, but several acted like eager little boys toward a tall,
gangly, graying man who accompanied Bradley. It was Phil Jackson,
the former coach of the champion Chicago Bulls and a teammate of
Bradley's on the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   With many curious about Jackson's presence, Bradley volunteered
that he had plans for his friend if he was elected: ``He'll be my
secretary of DEEE-fense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
