<HEADER>
A2743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-585&AMP;A     02-20 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READINESS IS ASSURED, BUT KEY JETS STILL AWAITED 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: La.) (See related KOSOVO-TALKS, KOSOVO-RESIDENTS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE) 
(lb) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite the decision on Saturday to extend the
deadline for peace talks on Kosovo, Defense Department and NATO
officials said they were pushing ahead with plans for airstrikes on
Serbia, with dozens of U.S. warplanes assigned to the mission
expected to arrive in Europe over the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO force is awaiting the arrival of a variety of U.S.
aircraft, most notably the six B-52 bombers that have been ordered
to fly to Europe from their base in Barksdale, La. The heavy
bombers, which can be armed with Tomahawk air-launched cruise
missiles, are expected to leave for an air base in Britain this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could go right now _ this minute _ with cruise missiles and
the planes we already have in Europe, and we might,'' said a
Defense Department official, speaking on the condition of
anonymity. He and other military officials said the B-52s were
considered an especially important addition to the NATO force,
certainly as tools of psychological warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hulking silhouette of a B-52 is a powerful image, and it
can make an adversary rethink his options pretty quickly,'' he
said. ``We'd like Milosevic to see them on their way,'' he added,
referring to the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The new deadline for the peace talks in France has been set for
Tuesday. If the talks end in failure, Clinton administration
officials said, the airstrikes could begin quickly after the
deadline passes, although they said the attacks would almost
certainly be delayed until all of the more than 1,000 foreign
civilian monitors in Kosovo were evacuated to protect them from
retaliation by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation of those monitors, who were assigned there last
year to police a cease-fire that has since collapsed, is expected
to begin this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Western embassies began evacuating diplomats from Yugoslavia on
Thursday and Friday. The United States was evacuating nearly 130
diplomats and dependents from Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon put a total of 51 U.S. warplanes on alert last week
to fly to Europe to join in a possible NATO strike against Serbian
targets, including 12 F-117A stealth fighters, 25 KC-135 refueling
planes and 10 EA6B Prowler radar-jammers. They would join more than
260 other U.S. warplanes that are already in place in Europe as
part of the NATO force.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have said that a first wave of
strikes would probably be made with cruise missiles fired from U.S.
warships that are now in the Mediterranean and Adriatic. Five
warships and two submarines assigned to the 6th Fleet in the area
are capable of firing the missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Under one proposal that U.S. officials said had been weighed by
the Pentagon, several dozen cruise missiles would be launched
against Serbian targets in the first volley of attacks, most of
them aimed at anti-aircraft batteries, radar stations and other
command posts across Yugoslavia that could pose a threat to
warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia is the dominant republic in Yugoslavia, which consists of
Serbia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the missile attacks would be followed by
successive waves of attacks by NATO warplanes against Serbian
airfields, military warehouses, tank depots and other targets.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its NATO allies have left the final
decision on airstrikes to NATO's secretary-general, Javier Solana.
He has said that ``NATO will have all the political support'' that
it needs for airstrikes against Belgrade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``If a political solution is not reached, then we say very
clearly that NATO knows very well what it has to do,'' Solana said
on Thursday during a trip to Macedonia, which borders Kosovo, to
review NATO preparations for action.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said there was still debate within NATO over how
quickly to begin strikes once the deadline had passed. Western
diplomats said France was adamant that the attacks not occur
automatically, and added that Solana would probably be required to
consult several NATO leaders before making a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will clearly consult in an informal way,'' said Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, quickly adding, however, that Solana
had the final say on an attack. ``I think it's very important to
know that he has that authority already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
