<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2749 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILOSOPHY     02-20 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILOSOPHY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves power up for fall in spring
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Braves general manager John Schuerholz
doesn't want to call it a change of philosophy, this turn of events
that has pitcher Denny Neagle playing for the Cincinnati Reds and
two new bats in the Braves lineup belonging to Brian Jordan and
Bret Boone.
</P>
<P>
   So let's find another way to put it, to describe what happens
when the National League's team of the '90s decides to do some
restructuring with one year left to elbow its way into the Yankees'
and Blue Jays' claims as baseball's team of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   What to call a steady run of Fab Fours _ starting rotations that
border on the obnoxious in their completeness, talent and
propensity to turn back hitters at the plate _ becomes, for now, a
Fab Three of Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz?
</P>
<P>
   How to categorize trading away Neagle two seasons removed from a
20-win season and leave the fourth and fifth spots in the rotation
to Kevin Millwood, in his second full year, and 21-year-old rookie
Bruce Chen?
</P>
<P>
   First of all, call it early postseason planning.
</P>
<P>
   The idea came into Schuerholz's focus after the Braves blew away
the National League East by winning a franchise-record 106 games
last year but then stumbled in the pitching-packed NLCS duel with
San Diego as Neagle watched idle from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might not go out and win 110, 115 games in the regular
season,'' third baseman Chipper Jones said, ``but we should
certainly make it to the playoffs, and, offensively, we'll have the
horses to score some runs against some top pitchers in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always fun to have a loaded starting rotation, but one of
those guys has to sit in the postseason,'' Jones said. ``Why not
have another big bat in place of that, somebody who can come in
from the very beginning of spring training and gel with the team,
generate more offense for this staff?
</P>
<P>
   ``In streaks, we've been a very hot team, where we've scored a
lot of runs and won a lot of games,'' he said. ``But if we hit a
stretch where we face tough pitching, we've also struggled. One
more hot bat could get us through those struggles.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it a relief.
</P>
<P>
   No way the Braves would have figured on losing Andres Galarraga
for the season to lymphoma, but those offseason moves are starting
to look even better. Without Jordan and Boone, the Braves would be
in dire straits offensively. With Jordan and Boone, the Braves are
merely fidgety, to see how to fill a pretty large gap.
</P>
<P>
   Call it an easy choice.
</P>
<P>
   On this end, Millwood had just finished winning 17 games in his
first full season of pitching in the major leagues, and Chen showed
his combination of talent and poise during his September callup.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end, Cincinnati offered 32-year-old Mike Remlinger,
a veteran who has pitched plenty as both a starter and a reliever
and can fill in if Millwood or Chen falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't toss or turn,'' Schuerholz said. ``You'd really be
standing out on the precipice if you traded a guy like Denny Neagle
and you didn't have guys coming along you feel comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, call it popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited, because the team got better,'' Greg Maddux said.
``It's not about leading the league in ERA or home runs. It's about
winning games. I think we have a chance to win more games this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   And because it's his project, give Schuerholz the last word.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy has not changed,'' he said. ``I still think the
way you win championships and build championship teams is with
starting pitching as the cornerstone of the foundation. Not just
starting pitching, but dominant, excellent starting pitching. . . .
I'd suggest that there are a lot of other teams in baseball who
would love to have this (rotation).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
