<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-QUESTIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loss of Big Cat a rally cry
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the next five weeks the Braves will prepare for the start of
the 1999 season. Here are 10 questions they have to answer in the
meantime:
</P>
<P>
   1. How will the Braves deal with the loss of Andres Galarraga?
</P>
<P>
   Stripping the lineup of 44 home runs, 121 RBIs and statistically
the best clutch hitter in the National League makes the 1999
outlook much less clear. Each of the Braves hitters must increase
his productivity. The Braves can ill-afford any off-years. But
players already are saying they want to win this season for
Galarraga. Giving a supposedly stoic team a personal reason to win
could make them even more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   2. Who is going to bat cleanup?
</P>
<P>
   Probably Brian Jordan. But don't look for Galarraga-like
production. When he's healthy, Jordan is a solid power hitter, but
he doesn't reach Galarraga's standard _ more than 40 home runs each
of the last three seasons, more than 30 the last five. Jordan can
help on the basepaths. Hitting ahead of Mark McGwire last year,
Jordan kept the steal attempts to a minimum, but he's adept when
the opportunity is right. He also has excellent skills in right.
</P>
<P>
   3. Can Klesko answer the call?
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are expecting him to, and the signing of Brian Hunter
as a backup supports that. The only way Klesko can take full
advantage is if he stays healthy, quits swinging for the fences,
and returns to being the more disciplined, opposite-field hitter he
was when he broke into the big leagues. He says he'll be
comfortable playing first base.
</P>
<P>
   4. How will Bruce Chen do as the fifth starter?
</P>
<P>
   If he's even slightly concerned he won't measure up, Chen sure
doesn't show it. His cool and confident demeanor suggests that he
will do just fine. With only eight starts above the AA level _ four
in Richmond, four in Atlanta _ his experience is severely limited.
Bobby Cox likes Chen's maturity and the way he and Kevin Millwood
use Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz as resources.
</P>
<P>
   5. Will Mark Wohlers make it back?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't look like it. The season is only five weeks away, and
Wohlers is still having trouble finding the catcher, much less the
strike zone. His breaking ball is OK, but everybody knows that
Wohlers' fastball made him one of the dominant closers. What is
working in his favor is Wohlers' attitude. He hasn't backed down
from the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   6. What happens to those final couple of spots in the bullpen
otherwise?
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cather is making a strong comeback bid from his
rib-extraction surgery. If he can come close to throwing the kinds
of pitches that made him so effective in 1997, he's a shoo-in to
return. Kerry Ligtenberg, John Rocker and Rudy Seanez are all but
locked in. Mike Remlinger gives Cox a second lefty in the pen, so
it's doubtful that he'll keep rookie Odalis Perez in Atlanta. But
with Russ Springer still out recovering from back surgery, Perez
can't be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   7. Will Chipper Jones be able to put his offseason troubles
behind him?
</P>
<P>
   The way he figures it, yes. Jones has settled his marital
problems and is moving ahead. He is entering his baseball prime _
he'll turn 27 in April _ and is ready to build on a 1998 season
that brought him his first All-Star Game start. He worked in the
offseason to gain strength and stamina and added an extra 20
pounds. Jones knows that adoration from the fans comes with great
production, no matter how much he hurt his All-American image.
Jones will get his fourth consecutive 20-homer, 100-RBI season.
</P>
<P>
   8. Can Bret Boone repeat the kind of season he had last year?
</P>
<P>
   Boone had career highs in hits, doubles and runs to go along
with 24 home runs and 95 RBIs. But Boone spent the 1998 offseason
shortening his swing and saw immediate results. He was finally
awarded a Gold Glove for his outstanding play at second. His
defense is a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   9. Has Otis Nixon still got it?
</P>
<P>
   The Braves franchise record-holder for stolen bases _ 72 in 1991
_ apparently still does, even at age 40. Nixon was a regular for
the Minnesota Twins last year and stole 37 bases in 110 games _
while fighting through a sore hamstring late in the season. Having
him and Walt Weiss in the lineup gives Cox a nice 1-2 punch at the
top of the order.
</P>
<P>
   10. What difference will Don Baylor make?
</P>
<P>
   That question probably will be answered best come playoff time.
Baylor's known for reviving careers, as he did with Galarraga and
Vinny Castilla in Colorado, and Klesko is his primary focus now.
The Braves are happy to have a coach of his experience and know-how
and will need him now more than ever with the loss of Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
