<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High-profile managers in NL West spotlighted
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although no National League team from the West Coast
has won a World Series in 10 years, there will be no division in
the majors this season with a higher manager profile than the NL
West. The arrivals of Davey Johnson in Los Angeles and Jim Leyland
in Colorado assure the fact.
</P>
<P>
   From the bottom up, each team in the division is dwarfed by the
men in the dugout. Buck Showalter won 65 games in Arizona's first
season, fourth most among the 14 expansion clubs dating back to
1961. With the addition of Randy Johnson and Todd Stottlemyre, the
Diamondbacks become an instant contender, the notion bolstered by
Showalter's cachet.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Bruce Bochy has been a professional manager only
seven years but has finished first four times, including twice in
four Padres seasons. His club made the Series last October with
less offense than his 76-win team of 1997. In San Francisco where
Dusty Baker has twice won NL manager of the year, his Giants have
been alive for the playoffs on the last day of the season three
times in six years. He forced last years' one-game playoff with the
Cubs after a 5-7 slump in early September.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps then it is no wonder the Rockies are paying the largest
manager salary in history (three seasons at $2 million per) to get
Leyland. He has taken two franchises into the postseason four times
in the last 10 years and though only his infamous 1997 Florida
Marlins went all the way, he immediately inflated Colorado's stock
(even if the roster hardly shifted from Don Baylor's last season).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start kidding yourself and over-evaluating your
importance, you got a problem,'' Leyland said. ``Players see it.
Other people see it. And you normally don't last long.''
</P>
<P>
   That style is opposite that of Johnson, whose history for
clashing with the front office flags his .575 winning percentage,
the highest among all active managers. Johnson was the Dodgers'
third choice behind Leyland and Felipe Alou for the job, but he may
be best suited to run this team, a bloodless roster that simply
abandoned Bill Russell last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 7:30, there isn't anybody better,'' said Philadelphia
hitting coach Hal McRae, who worked on Johnson's Cincinnati staff
1995 staff. ``He wins regardless of where he manages. He's kind of
like (NFL New York Jets coach Bill) Parcells in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   HIRSUTE PURSUIT
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' decision to drop a 30-year ban on facial hair was
welcomed by different players for different reasons. Perhaps the
most legitimate reason belonged to outfielder Dmitri Young, who
said, ``Some people are real ugly without facial hair and I'm one
of them. We can hide behind beards and mustaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Danny Graves is apparently not one of them. ``It would
take me 10 years to grow (a beard),'' he said, ``and all you'd see
are some wild hairs. Maybe when I reach puberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves, for the record, is 25.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever changes Lou Piniella has in mind for how he handles the
Seattle Mariners this year, the team figures to be a step ahead of
him. The M's have already scheduled a players-only meeting on the
first day the whole team reports to foster team unity. Said pitcher
Jamie Moyer, ``We need more discipline.'' . . . Orel Hershiser, 40,
continues to play teams against each other for his services, with
Florida, Philadelphia and Cleveland still showing interest. The
going rate starts at $2 million for one year but the Phillies have
grown suspicious about Hershiser's intentions. Three days after
receiving a Philadelphia offer, agent Robert Fraley called to say
he hadn't been able to reach his client, who had been
``traveling.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Opening Day at Pro Player Stadium: Marlin Alex Fernandez is
expected to face New York's Al Leiter, a former teammate.
Fernandez's last live pitch came in the third inning of Game 2 of
the 1997 NLCS, after Atlanta drilled him for five runs. Doctors
discovered his torn rotator cuff the next day. . . . Pittsburgh's
interest in Arizona outfielder Bernard Gilkey has become a money
deal. Although the Pirates had offered outfielder Al Martin and
second baseman Tony Womack for Gilkey and a pitching prospect, the
Pirates dropped the pitcher component in exchange for an extra $6
million to defray Gilkey's contract ($11.5 million over two years,
plus a $9 million annuity).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
