<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2753 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BOBFELLER21-COX     02-20 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BOBFELLER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Revisiting a 1937 field of dreams
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOMASTON, Ga. _ It was more than six decades ago, but Hall of
Famer Bob Feller hasn't forgotten his visit as a teenage pitching
phenom to this central Georgia city of about 9,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mill town, I remember that,'' said Feller, 80. ``It was my
first spring training, and we had a heck of a crowd. Of course, we
did everywhere that year.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, Feller at 18 was the talk of baseball, and spring
training was very different. Teams barnstormed north for weeks,
hitting towns that would never get an up-close look at
major-leaguers in action today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indians traveled by train with the Giants and stopped
about everywhere,'' recalled Feller, who won 266 major-league games
and pitched three no-hitters. ``We played in a dust storm in
Oklahoma and all through the South. Everybody wanted to see me
pitch against Carl Hubbell.''
</P>
<P>
   Feller, who had struck out 15 in his first start for Cleveland
and a record-tying 17 later in the 1936 season, didn't pitch
against Hubbell in Thomaston. With sellouts at both Georgia sites
assured, Hubbell pitched in Rome the day before. But that didn't
dampen the excitement in Thomaston on April 13, 1937. Feller _ the
fastest-throwing pitcher since Walter Johnson _ and the defending
National League champion New York Giants were in town.
</P>
<P>
   More than 4,000 crowded into Silvertown Ballpark to see the
Indians beat the Giants 8-6 in the city's first and last
major-league exhibition game. Feller struck out 12 in eight
innings, but was finally scored on by the Giants after 11 hitless
innings against him.
</P>
<P>
   Next weekend, Feller will return to Thomaston for the reopening
of Silvertown Ballpark. Built by B.F. Goodrich in 1936 to house its
Martha Mills textile-league team, the refurbished stadium will now
be home to Upson-Lee High baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to fix up everything just like it orginally was,''
Upson-Lee coach Bobby Smith said. ``There won't be a nicer high
school stadium anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Feller will participate in 11 a.m. rededication ceremonies
Saturday before Upson-Lee plays Pike County at 1 p.m. The game is
free, but a fee will be charged for Feller autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to going down there,'' Feller said from
his home in Ohio. ``I remember the town, but I don't remember a
darn thing about the game. I pitched in too many of them.''
</P>
<P>
   But only one in Thomaston. Fans met the teams at the train
station, then went to Silvertown, a mill village of small, neat
homes just north of downtown. Julian Bethel, like nearly everyone
else in Thomaston, was determined to see the game.
</P>
<P>
   Now 83, Bethel worked the soda counter at a pharmacy then.
``Some fellows from Macon came in and asked me to sell them my
ticket,'' Bethel recalled. ``They said they would give me anything
I wanted for it. I needed the money, but there was no way I was
going to miss seeing Feller pitch. The town about closed down for
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph McGill, writing in The Atlanta Constitution, called young
Feller the ``most publicized player since Babe Ruth.'' And after
seeing Feller's blazing fastball and sharp-breaking curve, McGill
was impressed. ``He is a great pitcher now,'' McGill wrote,
``needing only the polish of experience to become an even greater
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Frank Radcliffe, Thomaston's most famous baseball son, was
only 9 in 1937 and wasn't at the game. But he has fond memories of
Silvertown Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   It was there in 1948 that he struck out 28 batters _ one reached
base on the third strike _ in a nine-inning one-hitter for R.E. Lee
High, which merged into Upson-Lee in 1992. The Phillies gave
Radcliffe a near-record $40,000 bonus contract. An arm injury cut
short his career, but he played long enough in the minors to be a
teammate of Cliff Melton, who pitched vs. Feller in Thomaston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord a-mercy, Silvertown was a pretty park, especially with
that hedge around the outfield fence,'' Radcliffe recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But the ballpark lost its prime tenant in the 1950s when the
textile league folded, and it fell into disrepair in the early
1990s. Last year, a campaign to save Silvertown Ballpark began,
raising approximately $200,000. The grandstand has been restored,
dugouts built and a new scoreboard installed in left field. The
playing surface is as green as Turner Field. Lights are next.
</P>
<P>
   ``The park looks great,'' said Jim Fowler, chairman of the
rededication committee. ``Now, we just hope it doesn't rain next
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
