<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not so Great times
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Wayne Gretzky is thinking about staying around one
more season to see if the New York Rangers turn it around, he might
as well retire. The team has one of the league's highest payrolls
with a plethora of elderly veterans _ Gretzky, Ulf Samuelsson, John
MacLean, Kevin Stevens, Brian Leetch _ and coach John Muckler is
starting to feel pressure to give extended playing time to some of
the team's younger players. Further, a number of the vets,
particularly Samuelsson and MacLean, will be sought before the
March 23 trading deadline. Notwithstanding Gretzky's five-assist
night this week in a win over Nashville, the Weary One has about
had it. ``It's not one guy, it's not two guys, it's the whole
team,'' he said. ``And it's always the same way. We take three or
four penalties in the first period, fall behind by a goal, and then
spend the rest of the night fighting for our lives. It's not good
enough.'' Postscript: the Rangers lost six of seven at home.
</P>
<P>
   JAGR-MEISTER
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that Mario Lemieux's league-mandated March 15
deadline to form an ownership group that would purchase the
bankrupt Pittsburgh Penguins is eight days before the trading
deadline. The significance? Jaromir Jagr is to earn $8.9 million
next season, and rumors that the club might deal him to a
big-market team haven't cooled, despite the Pens' recent 10-game
winning streak. Odds are that if Lemieux takes over, Jagr will
stay. Otherwise, current co-owner Roger Marino might wish to ease
the team's debt. Jagr is not shying away from the talk: ``If the
owners or general manager think they have to trade me, that's their
decision. I love to play in Pittsburgh. If they can't afford me,
then I would love to play in L.A. or New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ETC. ...
</P>
<P>
   If Art Williams doesn't sell Tampa Bay, he might turn operations
over to his son, Art III, who runs a sporting-goods store in
Covington. ... Jagr had 26 points, including 10 goals, during the
Pens' streak. ... How's this for a test? Pittsburgh's next four
games are against Philadelphia, Phoenix, Colorado and Dallas, four
of the top five teams currently. ... Scrappy Buffalo forward
Matthew Barnaby, who at first discounted trade rumors, now is
embracing them. He has asked the Sabres to deal him. ... Chicago
defenseman Chris Chelios dislikes the whispers that have him being
dealt to Philadelphia. Chelios captained the 1998 U.S. Olympic
hockey team that was ripped by Flyers' GM Bob Clarke. Quoth
Chelios: ``Just tell Bob Clarke to shut up and leave me alone.''
... Lightning GM/coach Jacques Demers on suggestions by Williams
that his job is in jeopardy: ``It's Art's team, and he can do what
he wants with it, but I'm not changing my plan. I'm not going to
leave a legacy here that says I screwed things up. I'm sticking
with my game plan.'' ... Philadelphia has one of the league's best
records but is only 5-6-3 in the second of back-to-back games. ...
Boston's oldest player, Ray Bourque (38) also leads the team in
minutes played (30-plus per game). ... So you want to coach the
Montreal Canadiens? Two headlines last week in Montreal newspapers
read, ``The season is over'' and ``Get out the golf clubs.'' So
much for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
