<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eclipse of the Stars?
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With Detroit still sleep-walking and Phoenix having
leveled off, today's game between Colorado and Dallas (Fox, 3 p.m.)
should give some indication of the balance of power in the West.
Even though the Stars own the best record in the league, some
league scouts still view them Despite owning the best record in the
league, the Stars still are viewed by some league scouts as a
mentally fragile team that succumbs to pressure in close games and
could do the same in the playoffs. That's quite an indictment for a
team that has lost only 20 percent of its games, but the Avalanche
will be a severe test. Colorado has overcome an 0-4 start and
adversity that included goalie Patrick Roy busting some TV sets and
video equipment in a tirade; general manager Pierre Lacroix trading
his son Eric; and Keith Jones, among the players who felt Eric
Lacroix was a distraction, being traded to Philadelphia. But Roy
was signed to a contract extension and is now the hottest goalie in
the league, 11-2-1 in a stretch of 14 starts; the Avalanche had
lost only three of its last 18 games going into Friday's game at
Nashville; and forwards Peter Forsberg and Joe Sakic are thriving
as linemates. Even Jones, who was thrilled to be out of Denver, is
impressed. ``They're playing super hockey,'' he said. ``Now that I
can look back on it, there were many reasons for the (poor) start,
and it was just of matter of them getting back on track. if there
were some questions about the organization's commitment, they have
spent a lot of money and absolutely corrected that.''
</P>
<P>
   SAME OL' STORY
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the great views in British Columbia, it remains a
mystery why Marc Crawford took the Vancouver coaching job when
several other jobs figured to become available after the season,
even aside from the one in Atlanta. The hiring of Crawford hardly
changed the Canucks' fortunes. Mark Messier and Ed Jovanovski,
acquired from Florida in the Pavel Bure deal, are injured, and the
Canucks were so lethargic in an 8-1 loss to St. Louis that Crawford
said some of his players should be in a ``beer league.'' Gee.
Vancouver must be a little slice of paradise. Fired coach Mike
Keenan was 15-24-6 (.400). Crawford was 3-7-1 (.318) after
Thursday's 4-0 loss to last-place Chicago. GM Brian Burke continues
to take most of the heat. ``Whether we make the playoffs or not,''
Burke said, ``we're in a rebuilding process. I see a night and day
difference since Marc got here.''
</P>
<P>
   ETC. ...
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Phoenix to make any high-profile deals before the
playoffs. Coyotes owner Richard Burke said the team's projected
financial losses of $10 million this year will handcuff general
manager Bobby Smith to a degree. The Coyotes have the NHL's
sixth-lowest payroll but their revenues are hampered by
approximately 4,500 seats with obstructed views at America West
Arena that often go unsold. Burke now is backing off threats to
move the team, but he continues to push for a new arena or
renovations to the existing one. ... Los Angeles, desperate for a
player who can score goals and sell tickets, had a deal with
Calgary for Theo Fleury fall through when Fleury rejected a
five-year, $30 million extension. He will become unrestricted after
the season and thinks that the salary bar was raised by Bure's new
six-year contract, with salaries escalating from $8 million to $11
million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
