<SLUG> BC-JONBENET-RAMSEY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JonBenet book puts slaying back in spotlight
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The appearance of a provocative new book on JonBenet
Ramsey has once again catapulted the unsolved slaying into
headlines, news shows, and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect Murder, Perfect Town,'' by Lawrence Schiller, has been
the subject of extensive news reports, including a segment on the
show ``Dateline NBC.'' Newsweek magazine did a cover piece
featuring a lengthy excerpt. And the face of JonBenet's mother,
Patsy Ramsey of Atlanta, is once more on tabloid covers.
</P>
<P>
   Schiller, the author of ``American Tragedy,'' an account of the
O.J. Simpson trial, spent more than two years writing the book,
which does not try to solve the case but rather illuminate the
troubled investigation, including the deep divisions between the
police and district attorney's office, and the story's growth into
a media phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The 615-page book on the Christmas night, 1996, murder in the
family's former home of Boulder, Colo., offers more than a
half-dozen accounts that support the theory that JonBenet was
killed by an intruder, including that blood in her underpants
contained DNA traces from two unknown people.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the book asserts that tests show a pubic hair found
on the blanket in which JonBenet's body was wrapped doesn't belong
to anybody in the family or circle of friends.
</P>
<P>
   But Schiller also reveals circumstantial evidence that he says
makes the girl's parents logical suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much much of the crime took place too slowly. There was no
fear of discovery. You would think an intruder would quickly get
the hell out of there,'' he said in an interview. ``But there was
40 minutes of work done afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he learned that Patsy Ramsey has a ``hard and
tough'' side to her. When Boulder police Detective Tom Haney told
Patsy Ramsey during a June 1998 interview that she had lied to him,
she replied, ``Pal, you don't want to go there. Don't start that,''
Schiller wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schiller acknowledged, ``No one fact breaks the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Boulder police and the district attorney's office had no comment
on the book. Attorneys for the Ramseys did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Patsy Ramsey's sister, Pam Paugh, said she would not read the
book. She declined Schiller's request to be interviewed. ``I do not
want to help someone make money off my niece's murder,'' said
Paugh, who lives in Dunwoody, a suburban town north of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Police have said the Ramseys remain under suspicion in
JonBenet's death, though the Ramseys have repeatedly maintained
their innocence. A Boulder County grand jury has been reviewing
evidence in the case since September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect Murder'' has topped Amazon.com's Hot 100 best-seller
list. In the Ramseys' hometown of Atlanta, the book has been
selling moderately well, said Barbara Babbit Kaufman, president of
Chapter 11 Discount Book Stores. She said each of the 13 stores has
sold about eight copies.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Schiller said he believes ``one of the parents''
will be indicted, though he would not say which one. Still, he
said, enough information exists for a good defense attorney to win
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
