<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-WHITMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS URGE N.J. GOVERNOR TO RUN FOR U.S. SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ky., Nev.)  (bl)  
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ To help beat back efforts by Democrats to gain
control of the U.S. Senate in 2000, state and national Republican
leaders are heavily lobbying Gov. Christie Whitman to run for the
seat being vacated by Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Since Wednesday, when Lautenberg announced his decision to
retire at the end of his third term, Whitman has been besieged with
messages and phone calls from party leaders and Republican senators
urging her to run.
</P>
<P>
   Before last week, Whitman would quickly dismiss questions about
whether she was planning a run for the Senate. After Lautenberg's
announcement, she said she would give a race ``serious
consideration,'' but added that she had much to think about before
deciding to run in 2000, a year before her second and final term
ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to decide what's the best way to serve the people of
this state, and family becomes very important in this as well,''
she said in an interview. ``Don't forget, there's a real world
outside of politics, too. And while my husband has some doubts
about whether I could stand it if I weren't still involved in
politics and government, I think I could, and that's another
option.''
</P>
<P>
   State and national Republican leaders say they are trying to
sway Whitman because she stands a good chance of becoming the
state's first Republican senator since Clifford Case in 1972. Until
a few days ago, they said, the New Jersey seat was assumed to be
solidly in the Democratic column.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Jersey was not on the radar screen before Frank's decision
to retire,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., head of the
Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee. ``It might have gotten on
the radar screen. But this is a total change in the situation. I
think that everyone would agree that Governor Whitman would be our
strongest candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell and other Republican leaders say the battle lines over
control of the Senate have been redrawn with Lautenberg's decision
and the announcement the following day by Sen. Richard Bryan,
D-Nev., that he would not seek re-election next year.
</P>
<P>
   There are now three Democrats, including Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., who are retiring and leaving open seats next
year. Hillary Rodham Clinton and New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani are among the people considering a race to succeed
Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened as a result of these retirements is that
Democrats are going to have to work to just stay even,'' McConnell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans now hold a 55-45 edge in the Senate. But they must
defend 19 seats next year, including many held by first-term
Republicans, compared with 14 for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats, noting that New York and New Jersey voters
have leaned Democratic in presidential election years, contend that
they will hold all three seats. ``We also think that the
Republicans will have some retirements, in which we can put forth
competitive candidates to move those seats into Democratic
columns,'' said Michael Tucker, a spokesman for the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Rep. Robert Menendez, a Democrat from Union City
in Hudson County, is expected to announce, possibly as early as
Monday, that he will seek the Democratic nomination. He already has
more than $1.2 million in his campaign account for a race that
analysts estimate will cost $10 million to $12 million. There is a
long list of other possible contenders for the Democratic
nomination, including former Gov. Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a long list of potential Republican candidates,
but state party chairman Chuck Haytaian said that a decision by
Whitman to enter the race would probably clear the Republican field
so she would escape a bruising primary.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Duffy, a political analyst with The Cook Political
Report, which tracks state and federal elections around the
country, said she moved New Jersey into her tossup column from
leaning toward Democrat after Lautenberg's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Whitman runs, I would probably push it to Republican
favor,'' Ms. Duffy said. ``Democrats are going to be hard pressed
to come up with her equal. I am not saying it will not be a
competitive race. But her equal in terms of her ability to raise
money and her statewide name recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania is among several Republican
senators, mostly moderates, who have called Whitman in recent days
to urge her to consider running. Beyond helping their party
maintain control of the Senate, Specter said, Whitman could broaden
its national appeal with her brand of moderate politics. ``And we
don't have sufficient representation for the Republican Party at
the center of the political spectrum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, New Jersey's junior senator who is head
of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, said Whitman's
entrance into the race ``would make it very competitive.'' But he
added that he believed New Jersey Democrats were in good shape with
voters, and he noted that Mrs. Whitman won her 1997 re-election
campaign by only 1 percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic chairman Thomas Giblin said that he and other
Democrats are concerned about what impact Whitman might have on the
gubernatorial contest in 2001. If Whitman went to the Senate, state
Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, a Republican, would become
governor. DiFrancesco is already planning to run for governor, and
being the incumbent would give him an enormous edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win this race,'' Giblin said of the Senate seat.
``It presents a big problem to the Democratic Party if we don't.
All of these elections are intertwined.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said that she expected to decide within a month whether
to create an exploratory committee. ``That's only fair,'' she said.
``There are a lot of people who are interested in this, and the
important thing, to me, is for the Republicans to win that Senate
seat. So I don't want to hurt someone else's chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
