</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA'S GOVERNOR MAKES AN END RUN  
 CALIFORNIA'S GOP FALLS ON HARD TIMES  
 THIS TIME AROUND, KENNEDY IS PREPARING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Calif., Mass., Mich.) (rk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alabama is one of a small number of states in which the governor
and the lieutenant governor run separately for election and can
hail from different parties. For much of this century, the
divisiveness that could result from such an election arrangement
never materialized because Democrats decisively dominated politics
in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, Republicans have been on the rise in the
state, as elsewhere in the South _ and so, too, has divisiveness
between Alabama governors and lieutenant governors.
</P>
<P>
   Until he was elected governor last fall, Don Siegelman, a
Democrat, was Alabama's lieutenant governor, playing No. 2 to a
Republican governor, Fob James. They tangled early and often, with
Siegelman repeatedly thwarting James' political aims and desires.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman was able to do that because Alabama was one of a small
number of states in which the lieutenant governor had significant
governing power, including the power to appoint legislative
committees, pick their chairmen and control the flow of many bills.
Siegelman helped kill many measures dear to the state's powerful
business leaders, most notably a proposal to tighten restrictions
on damage suits.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as governor, Siegelman, who ousted James last fall, is
himself contending with a lieutenant governor from the other party,
Steve Windom. And things are contentious, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Windom is the first Republican to be elected lieutenant governor
of Alabama this century. He was voted in with the strong financial
backing of business groups _ he spent more than $5 million in all _
and the first thing he promised in his victory speech was to use
his power to block a legislative vote on Siegelman's favorite
cause, creation of a state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   But Siegelman struck first, persuading the Democrat-controlled
state Senate a few weeks back to strip away the traditional power
of lieutenant governors to appoint committees and direct
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Windom, reduced to little more than a ceremonial figure, says he
may counter by taking the governor to court. ``We didn't elect him
dictator,'' he groused the other day.
</P>
<P>
   California's GOP Falls on Hard Times
</P>
<P>
   When California Republicans gather next weekend in Sacramento
for their annual convention, some may wonder if they are at a wake.
Consider:
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat is newly installed in the governor's office _ the
first in 16 years. Both houses of the state Legislature are under
Democratic control, more firmly now than in years past. The state's
two U.S. senators are Democrats, one re-elected last year and the
other headed for what looks like certain re-election next year.
</P>
<P>
   Further, a solid majority of the state's House delegation is
Democratic, with a third or more of the Republican members worried
that repercussions from the Clinton impeachment trial may cost them
the seats that they won only narrowly in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes even more bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, The Contra Costa Times took a close look at voter
registration trends over the last three months in 10 counties
around the state. Its finding:
</P>
<P>
   Through most of the 1990s, California, like most states, saw a
slowdown in Democratic and Republican registration and an increase
in independents. But the pace of Democratic registration appears to
be picking up again, or at least no longer slipping, whereas
Republican registration continues to lag and even slip.
</P>
<P>
   The paper found the shifts in numbers to be small, usually less
than a percentage point. ``But coming in just three months, they
are significant,'' it concluded, noting that the Clinton
impeachment trial took place during the period covered.
</P>
<P>
   In the East Bay area, east of San Francisco, the newspaper's
home territory, it found Democrats gaining strength and Republicans
losing. In Orange County, a Republican stronghold south of Los
Angeles, Democrats held their ground but Republicans lost strength
as independents gained. And in San Diego, Democrats and
independents both had a slight gain in strength, whereas
Republicans slipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going well for us,'' Bob Mulholland, a leading
Democratic strategist, told the paper.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican strategist, Dora Kingsley, did not disagree.
``We're not getting our message across,''she lamented.
</P>
<P>
   This Time Around, Kennedy Is Preparing
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., got a bit of a scare five years
ago when he ran for re-election. Overconfident after more than
three decades in office and focused more on his powerful position
on Capitol Hill than on the condition of his political fences back
home, he was slow, almost indifferent, about getting out of the
blocks, and his Republican opponent, Mitt Romney, got an early jump
on him.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Romney, a wealthy businessman whose father, George, was
governor of Michigan and a presidential candidate in the 1960s,
actually was out front in the polls at one point.
</P>
<P>
   But then Kennedy began to pour in effort and money ($11.5
million eventually) and in the end won going away.
</P>
<P>
   Looking toward 2000, when he will be up for re-election again,
the senator seems to be keeping the lessons of 1994 firmly in mind.
For the last six months or so, he has been working the phones hard
in search of campaign money and has been showing up all over
Massachusetts at gatherings large and small, meeting and greeting.
His intent, aides say, is to demonstrate early strength and scare
off any potential challengers.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the oldest campaign tactics in the book, one that
often works. But Geoffrey Rehnert hasn't been scared off. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnert, a wealthy Republican fund-raiser and a member of Bain
Capital, the same venture capital firm that Mitt Romney once
belonged to, told The Boston Globe the other day that the odds were
``50-50 and trending upwards'' that he would challenge the senator.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
