<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big dreams plentiful for Big Dog
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They don't talk about Glenn ``Big Dog'' Robinson when
the discussion is the NBA game excelling without Michael Jordan,
and, really, there's something inherently wrong with that. All the
1994 No. 1 pick out of Purdue has done since being selected by the
Milwaukee Bucks is average 21.4 points while being a solid citizen
off the court. He's got game.
</P>
<P>
   But he gets _ pardon the pun _ dogged when it comes to
recognition. When he was a rookie, Robinson averaged 21.9 points,
was the only first-year player to win the NBA Rookie of the Month
award twice, and yet Grant Hill of Detroit and Dallas' Jason Kidd
were named co-rookies of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, when critics complained because Robinson was selected to
Dream Team II, the 6-foot-7, 230-pound forward took himself off the
squad. Although he continued to put up impressive numbers playing
alongside Vin Baker, it was Baker who made the all-star team and
who got league-wide recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Jordan is gone and the list of wannabes extends from Kobe
Bryant to Tim Duncan to Hill to Penny Hardaway to a dozen or so
others. But no Big Dog Robinson, although he's been more consistent
than most of them.
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson's playoff record gets in the way. He doesn't have
one. And even he understands that it matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I've always said, I feel like I'm one of the best small
forwards in the Eastern Conference and the NBA,'' Robinson said.
``Individually, I have great numbers. The only thing that separates
Glenn Robinson from Scottie Pippen and some of the other great
small forwards is they have W's. They have been to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucks entered the season with a 128-200 record during
Robinson's time, with no postseason berths. But with new coach and
proven winner George Karl, Milwaukee _ and the Big Dog _ have
higher aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really look at it as a new start,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Karl, accomplished at meshing personalities, likes what he sees
in Robinson so far. But the lasting effects of losing remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenn has been great,'' Karl said, ``but I still see, not just
from Glenn, but everybody, some of those frustration scars of a
couple of years of losing.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, Robinson sometimes reverts to the player who forced the
issue offensively on a talent-starved team. With point guard
Terrell Brandon, rising star Ray Allen and a group of complementary
players, Karl's quest is to get Robinson to be multi-faceted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can be an all-star in this game by being a
one-dimensional player,'' Karl said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has shown a willingness to change his game and produce
victories, to be a better defender, passer and rebounder. ``I think
Glenn is driven to be a great player,'' Karl said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his greatness is on offense. Robinson forced overtime in
the season-opener in Charlotte with a jumper at the buzzer and hit
another jumper with 0.1 seconds left to win a game at Philadelphia
last week. But he averaged 17.3 points going into the weekend, an
indication of his willingness to share the load for the good of the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about what other people think, because deep down
inside I know what I can do,'' Robinson said. ``I'm going to prove
everybody wrong because I will be a part of a great team. I will be
on a championship team one day, and all the negative thoughts in
people's minds about Glenn Robinson will be totally erased.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
