<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ward's transition a success
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The best quarterback in the NBA has developed into a
reliable professional point guard for the New York Knicks. It's
been five years now _ five years _ since Heisman Trophy winner
Charlie Ward entered the league under a cloud of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   He went from playing just 10 games as a rookie to a starter on a
team with championship aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes Charlie so good for us,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy
said, ``is that he doesn't need the ball to make plays. He creates
things with his keen sense of knowing where to be on the court. And
when he does have the ball, he's always looking to make a play for
someone else. He's totally unselfish.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his reputation in some circles for alleged cheap shots,
the part of Ward's persona that could be most valuable to the
Knicks is his character.
</P>
<P>
   Ward has taken the responsibility of offering the notorious
Sprewell subtle guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latrell, like anyone else, needs to know the right path,''
Ward said. ``I'm there for him, like all my teammates. It's part of
being a teammate and a man.''
</P>
<P>
   STACKED WITH PROBLEMS
</P>
<P>
   If you noticed poor shooting statistics from Detroit's Jerry
Stackhouse recently, cut him some slack. He's been distracted, even
if he won't admit it, by the death of his sister, Lois. She died of
diabetes last week.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second sister he has lost in the last six years to
diabetes. And his mother and father also have it. Stackhouse has
not been diagnosed with diabetes, but he's aware that it could
develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I need to keep getting it checked,'' he said. ``I went
when I was in Philadelphia, but it wasn't a problem. But that's a
question I had, too, with the history of it in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Stackhouse went 0-for-7 against Orlando on Thursday, 1-for-11
against the Knicks earlier. Stackhouse at one point was just
7-for-27 from the field. But he said his misfiring was not a result
of his grieving.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it was from, of all people, all-star Grant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant has been on a tear, and that's been great for him,''
Stackhouse said. ``But I don't think it's been so great for our
team. I think we've become stagnant in watching him. If you're
coming down the court, and you haven't touched the ball the last
two or three times down, it's hard to go down and chase a guy and
do all the little things you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the bottom line for Stackhouse is: ``I want the ball more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill has refused to fire back at his cohort _ so far.
</P>
<P>
   THEY SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   _ ``No, I don't have any concern. They could, and maybe they
should, (fire me). I don't know.'' Charlotte coach Dave Cowens said
after publicly noting that he's the lowest-paid coach in the NBA at
$675,000 and that if he didn't get a raise after the season, he
would quit
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I must have killed somebody in a past life.'' Cleveland
center Zydrunas Ilgauskas after learning his season was over with a
broken foot
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I could have worn a thong.'' Miami swingman Dan Majerle, who
was omitted from this year's Sports Illustrated swimsuit issue
after an appearance last year.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To Sacramento's Chris Webber. The exciting forward made it
public that he did not want to play for the Kings, and yet he's
playing the best ball of his career. He had seven double-doubles in
the first seven games and led Sacramento's upset overtime win
Wednesday over previously unbeaten Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To Seattle's Vin Baker. For all the chatter about Shaquille
O'Neal's poor foul-shooting, Baker has been horrifying at the line.
He missed his first 18 free throws before making one. It has become
a mind thing for the SuperSonics' all-star forward. Still, pros
must do much better than that.
</P>
<P>
   GAMES OF INTEREST
</P>
<P>
   _ Today: Chicago at New York, 1 p.m. (NBC); Houston at Orlando
(NBC), 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monday: Chicago at Atlanta, 7:30 p.m. (Fox Sports South); L.A.
Lakers at Denver (TBS), 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tuesday: Seattle at Houston, 8 p.m. (TNT)
</P>
<P>
   _ Wednesday: Atlanta at Dallas, 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thursday: Sacramento at Washington, 7 p.m.; Minnesota at New
York, 7:30 p.m.; Atlanta at Houston, 8:30 p.m
</P>
<P>
   _ Friday: New York at Boston, 8 p.m. (TNT); Miami at Detroit, 8
p.m.; San Antonio at Seattle, 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   The draft class of 1996 has had the most explosive scorers so
far this season, with three top draft picks registering
career-highs:
</P>
<P>
   _ 46 by Philadelphia's Allen Iverson against San Antonio;
</P>
<P>
   _ 40 by Minnesota's Stephon Marbury against Houston;
</P>
<P>
   _ 39 by Vancouver's Shareef Abdur-Rahim against Boston.
</P>
