<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turnaround in Ottawa
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the uninitiated, would-be hockey fans in the
South, here's a rough guide to Ottawa: Take I-85 to Richmond,
forget the left to Charlottesville, proceed north to Pennsylvania,
forget the right to Atlantic City, continue north, cross the
Canadian border into the province of Ontario and if you hit Hull _
the city, not the player _ you went too far.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that if the Canadian capital and its hockey
team haven't come up in conversation, fear not, for you're not
alone. Amid all the talk about the Dallas Stars' domination of
Detroit and everybody else, winning streaks by Colorado and
Pittsburgh and the assault on goalies by Philadelphia's John
LeClair and Eric Lindros, the Ottawa Senators were the third NHL
team to reach 30 wins. They surprisingly lead the Northeast
Division, ahead of Toronto, Buffalo, Boston and Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is talking about us, and that's fine,'' said defenseman
Lance Pitlick, one of several non-household names on the Senators'
roster. ``As Atlanta will find out, it takes a while to establish
yourself in the NHL. Even last year when we beat New Jersey in the
playoffs, all we heard was what New Jersey didn't do, not what we
did. Maybe soon, people will realize we're one of the elite
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Elite? Ottawa? Since entering the league as an expansion
franchise in 1992, the Senators had been a study in buffoonery:
</P>
<P>
   _ They finished last four seasons in a row.
</P>
<P>
   _ Twice in negotiations, they so infuriated No. 1 draft picks _
Radek Bonk and Alexei Yashin _ that the players signed with a
minor-league team in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   _ The team was fined $100,000 in 1993 when then-owner Bruce
Firestone suggested that tanking games would be a good idea to
secure the No. 1 draft pick. (Thus, the NHL lottery was born.)
</P>
<P>
   _ The arena locker rooms were robbed one year. All the video
equipment was stolen _ but the thief left the game tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were a long shot to even get into the league,''
said Ottawa president Roy Mlakar, an executive with Los Angeles at
the time of expansion. ``Unfortunately, when Ottawa got the
franchise, there were a lot of organizational problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Gauthier changed that. Hired as the team's third general
manager in 1995, Gauthier, who had been an assistant GM in Anaheim,
began a series of roster moves that shaped the club into a
conservative but smart team that made the playoffs two consecutive
seasons, including last year's upset of the Devils in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   But Gauthier resigned after the season, citing exhaustion and
personal reasons. It was known that his family was not enamored of
Ottawa. But Gauthier found himself deflecting rumors that he merely
was angling for the Anaheim job when he said he was moving back to
California. A firestorm in Canada then turned into a raging inferno
two weeks later when, indeed, the Disney-owned Ducks hired
Gauthier. Added to that, the Senators declined to pursue tampering
charges and/or seek compensation. Gauthier has proclaimed
innocence, and Mlakar backed him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be suspicious if Pierre and I didn't have an
excellent relationship and if I didn't have a 25-year relationship
with (Disney executive) Tony Tavares,'' Mlakar said. ``I'm 100
percent convinced when he left here he did not intend to go to
another job in hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier remains a villain to most in Ottawa, but the team is
thriving under coach Jacques Martin and new GM Rick Dudley. The
Senators play a style that Mlakar admits is ``boring to everybody
outside of Ottawa.'' They take few chances on offense and play
strong team defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a change from the early years,'' said Pitlick, who
is in his fifth season. ``Back then, this organization was in such
disarray. Guys just completely goofed up. We were playing in a
makeshift arena (while the Corel Centre was being built). It felt
like you were still in the minors. But we've gone from the whipping
boys of the league to one of the top teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Although that still remains somewhat of a secret.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
