</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rink owner: `No hard feelings'
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Bardis, owner of The Cooler in Alpharetta, said
he has ``no hard feelings'' that the Thrashers are about to close a
deal for a practice facility with the Ice Forum in Duluth. The
Thrashers had negotiated with The Cooler first, but talks fell
apart after Turner Sports executives declined to foot the bill for
a 15,000-square-foot facility, which will cost approximately $1.7
million. The Ice Forum will build the facility and another sheet of
ice at a cost of $3.2 million, then lease the space to the
Thrashers. ``The fact that the Thrashers are coming to town is good
for all of us in this (ice-rink) business,'' Bardis said. ``They're
drawing fans to the sport. I have no hard feelings about the fact
they chose to go to Duluth. They had to do what's in their best
interest financially. We would've welcomed them at The Cooler, but
their economic objectives and our economic objectives were not
aligned in the short term.'' For what it's worth, Bardis is buying
season tickets. ... General manager Don Waddell is on a 14-day
scouting trip that included a stop in Calgary for last week's ``Top
Prospects'' game, which included 40 potential draft picks from the
Canadian junior leagues. One player was Quebec defenseman Martin
Grenier, who has 357 penalty minutes in 54 games. He was the only
all-star in the game with more than 300 PIM. ... In a skills
competition among the prospects, Grenier registered the hardest
slaps hot, at 96.3 mph. Forward Jamie Lundmark of Moose Jaw
finished among the top five in four events and set a record in the
60-foot dash at 2.541 seconds. He also won the 150-foot dash
(5.587) and ranked third in shot and puck-control events. Sudbury
forward Taylor Pratt won the fastest skater competition, circling a
rink at 14.139.
</P>
<P>
   THIS OLD HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   With the Toronto Maple Leafs moving out of Maple Leaf Gardens,
the Civic Arena in Pittsburgh becomes the NHL's oldest active
arena. Following are the venues built before 1980.
</P>
<P>
   City _ Arena (capacity) _ Opened _ Tenant's status
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh _ Civic Arena (16,958) _ 1961 _ Pursuing new arena
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles _ Great Western Forum (16,005) _ 1967 _ New arena
next year
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. Rangers _ Madison Square Garden (18,200) _ 1968 _ No plans
to move
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. Islanders _ Nassau Coliseum (16,297) _ 1972 _ Pursuing new
arena
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton _ Skyreach Centre (17,099) _ 1974 _ No plans to move
</P>
<P>
   Detroit _ Joe Louis Arena (19,983) _ 1979 _ No plans to move
</P>
<P>
   WIN-PLACE
</P>
<P>
   If John LeClair and Eric Lindros finish 1-2 in the league in
goals, they will be the sixth set of teammates to finish in the top
two spots since expansion in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Players (goals) _ Team _ Season
</P>
<P>
   John LeClair (37), Eric Lindros (32) _ Philadelphia _ 1998-99
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hull (44), Stan Mikita (40) _ Chicago _ 1967-68
</P>
<P>
   Phil Esposito (76), Johnny Bucyk (51) _ Boston _ 1970-71
</P>
<P>
   Steve Shutt (60), Guy Lafleur (56) _ Montreal _ 1976-77
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky (73), Jari Kurri (71) _ Edmonton _ 1984-85
</P>
<P>
   Mario Lemieux (69), Jaromir Jagr (62) _ Pittsburgh _ 1995-96
</P>
<P>
   through Feb. 17
</P>
<P>
   INJURY OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis coach Joel Quenneville was cut under his right eye
after officials allowed a disputed goal by Edmonton. The cut? ``I
banged a stick on the boards and hit myself. The stick spun around
and hit me in the face. Bad play all the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE/UNQUOTE
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I asked said, with such a young, inexperienced team,
I should hire the most experienced coach I could find. I hired
Barry instead. Why not? Expansion teams are about chances and as we
look for upside potential in players, we looked for it in coaches
as well. You have to go by gut-feel.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Nashville GM David Poile on coach Barry Trotz
</P>
