<HEADER>
A2767 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUNTING-TURKEYS21-COX     02-20 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNTING-TURKEYS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turkey season approaches
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An army of more than 100,000 will be moving through
the forests of Georgia from March 20 through May 15, a special kind
of army.
</P>
<P>
   This army skulks in the misty predawn hours clucking and
gobbling like turkeys, hoping to bag the crafty Eastern wild
turkey.
</P>
<P>
   There will be men, women, even children like the eight-year-old
Landt twins, Nick and Rory of Macon.
</P>
<P>
   Their dad, Jim Landt, 38, will take the Tinsley Elementary
third-graders with him. They won't have guns; they'll just be
learning the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest, though, they'll experience the adrenaline rush
when they hear a gobble in answer to their dad's owl call just
before sunrise. . . .
</P>
<P>
   They'll gasp with exertion and excitement as they move in
careful haste toward the sound. . . .
</P>
<P>
   And they'll get giddy and grow goosebumps when an old gobbler
comes strutting into view. . . .
</P>
<P>
   If they've done their homework in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Wildlife Federation's Turkeyrama last weekend
offered the chance to talk to a pair of the state's better turkey
hunters about what to do in the preseason to increase the chance of
a successful hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Roscoe Reams, 74, of Morrow hunted turkeys in Georgia before the
big restoration and is the recognized expert. He is in great demand
as a seminar speaker and as a guide.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Chase, 46, of McDonough accomplished turkey hunting's
``World Slam'' _ all seven species _ in only one year. She shares
her experiences in her Slammin' Jan's Turkey Chase booth at various
shows and in seminars.
</P>
<P>
   The two know and respect each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first time I ever saw Jan,'' Roscoe said. ``I
was teaching a seminar, and she jumped up, holding up this Quaker
Boy `Easy Yelper,' saying, `I got my first turkey using this call.'
She's come a long way since then.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase replied, ``As a matter of fact, I am still using the same
Quaker Boy call he mentioned. I have probably taken over 90 percent
of my birds using that call. That sure was a great bit of advice he
gave me years and years ago. I admire and respect that man
tremendously _ always have.''
</P>
<P>
   The advice both give works on private land as well as Wildlife
Management Areas. Both are independent and do a thorough scouting
job, no matter what ``experts'' tell them about an area.
</P>
<P>
   Their general technique is similar because Chase has learned so
much from Reams.
</P>
<P>
   While thousands of men try to imitate a hen's clucks, purrs and
other sexy sounds to entice a gobbler, Chase has a different
approach.
</P>
<P>
   After declaring Rule No. 1 _ Don't use a turkey call in
preseason scouting _ Chase says, ``Birds on public land are called
to death and are used to aggressive calling. Use gentle calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Reams explains why hunters should leave their turkey calls at
home: ``Turkeys remember calls. When you are scouting, the worst
thing you can do is carry your turkey call with you. You'll use it,
and that's the worst thing you can do.'' The gobbler will remember
that call and won't respond to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can use owl, crow, hawk or other locator calls (to make
them gobble), but not a turkey call,'' Reams said.
</P>
<P>
   Both warn about scouting too soon. Within their habitat, turkeys
migrate with the availability of food.
</P>
<P>
   During scouting, Reams said, walk the shady sides of fields and
other openings looking for droppings, shed feathers and tracks. In
areas with a healthy acorn crop, work waterways _ creeks and
streams _ scouting logging roads parallel to creeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water and turkeys go together,'' Reams declared.
</P>
<P>
   Chase looks for burns, either prescribed or accidental, because
``the ones you find in February will be a mecca for turkeys by the
time the season opens.''
</P>
<P>
   While scouting, she looks for food sources, droppings, tracks _
``I'm big on tracks'' _ at edges of fields, pastures and
clear-cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Reams said, ``Don't worry about finding gobbler tracks. If you
find hen tracks, that's fine. Gobblers have to go where hens are in
the spring.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that, because of warm weather, gobblers already are
strutting, ``but they don't control things. The temperature doesn't
control the urge _ the amount of light available each day does and
the days aren't long enough yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase: ``Find out where everyone else wants to be and go
elsewhere. Find out where guys in hunt clubs say you shouldn't go.
That's where I'll be. They're there: They're just smart birds.''
</P>
<P>
   And more: ``Find a place you don't find all the vehicles.'' On
WMAs, hunters tend to stay close to roads. A little extra walking
pays big dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
