<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2768 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARSHLAND21-COX     02-20 1850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARSHLAND21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cajun lawyer takes on oil companies
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUMA, La. _ Michael St. Martin cranked up the roaring engine on
his airboat, put on ear protection and dark sunglasses, and checked
the time on his Rolex watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go for a ride,'' he said as he shot the airboat through
a skinny alley in the tall marsh grasses. The closeness gave way to
a vast open marsh covered with a carpet of viny vegetation, and St.
Martin sped up and skittered across the surface so fast it seemed
the boat would take flight.
</P>
<P>
   Deep in Cajun country between New Orleans and the Gulf of
Mexico, this waterworld of marsh and swamp is St. Martin's
``2,400-acre hobby.'' He has roamed it since he was a child, built
his estate next to it in the 1980s, and finally bought it in 1992.
It looks pristine and almost prehistoric: Alligator eyes poke out
of the water every few minutes, ducks fly overhead by the
thousands, coots fly in black masses and rest like carpets on the
surface of the water, and huge swamp rats, called nutria, dart
between the hanging moss and the gnarled trunks of cypress trees.
Swamp maples are in bloom and look like pink torches against the
deep greens, grays and browns of winter.
</P>
<P>
   This is the land St. Martin went to court to protect in a
lawsuit that could set new precedent in environmental claims.
</P>
<P>
   The 100-foot-wide canals cutting through the marsh like city
streets were dredged decades ago by oil companies with mineral
rights to the oil and gas below the surface of the watery land. St.
Martin does not receive money from the leases because he owns only
the surface of the swamp.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to breaks in the canal levees. A current of water
flows freely back and forth from the canals into other parts of the
marsh every time there's a boat or barge on the nearby Intracoastal
Waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Those breaks, he said, are an environmental disaster which,
unchecked, will turn the entire marsh into a lake, unable to
support any of the wildlife now flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the oil industry at its finest,'' St. Martin said, and
shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   In January, as a result of a 1997 lawsuit filed by St. Martin,
U.S. District Judge Marcel Livaudais Jr. ordered two major oil
companies to repair the breaks in the canals, and awarded St.
Martin $240,000 in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Although there have been lawsuits against oil companies for
property damage, this case is unusual. It holds the companies
responsible for something that has been accepted as the way things
are done for as long as anyone can remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever takes them to task and says, `You can't just
leave,''' said St. Martin, a 56-year-old attorney and Houma native.
``As far as I'm concerned, this is now the war cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobil Exploration and Producing U.S. Inc., which had the mineral
rights under St. Martin's property until 1995, and Phillips
Petroleum Co., which has them now, deny the damage was caused by
their canals. They say the marsh is becoming submerged because of a
variety of natural and human causes for which they can't be held
responsible. And they dispute St. Martin's claim on the grounds
that the erosion existed when he bought the property in 1992. They
are appealing.
</P>
<P>
   But many landowners could follow St. Martin's lead, and oil
companies across Louisiana might wind up spending millions of
dollars repairing open spots in canals. Already, St. Martin has
plans to sue several other oil companies for damage to his land,
and he is helping the Terrebonne Parish School Board to sue any
companies that have damaged its land, which is adjacent to his.
</P>
<P>
   Every school board in Louisiana owns land, given to them in 1820
as a means of funding school systems. Much of it is wetlands, which
means they are cut through with oil and gas canals. School boards
alone, could account for dozens of suits.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin would like to see courts force the oil industry not
only to repair the breaks in the canals, but also to erase the
canals they no longer use by filling them with silt and replanting
marsh grasses. In his case, the court ruled that would be so
expensive _ millions of dollars _ that it would not be reasonable,
considering St. Martin paid $245 an acre for the land. But that
might not be the case in other suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were those oil companies, I'd be very nervous,'' said
Charlie Storrs, regional coordinator for the National Wetlands
Inventory in Atlanta, a project of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service. ``There are so many canals that have never been filled,
and the price of oil has dropped so low, they may not have the
resources to fix the problem.'' For decades, oil companies have
leased the mineral rights below the surface of Louisiana's marshes
and swamps. The cheapest way to get in and drill is to dredge a
canal, and as a result, there are now 10,000 miles of oil and gas
canals criss-crossing Louisiana's wetlands. Lease agreements state
that the oil companies must maintain them, and they hold the
companies liable for any damages they cause to the property.
</P>
<P>
   But, St. Martin said, ``in most cases, like 99 percent, the
companies just depleted the reserves and left. A lot of them didn't
so much as remove a well head or a piling.'' During the trial, a
Mobil employee testified that the company has no program in place
for maintaining canals, and certainly no budget exists for filling
in the ones they have stopped using.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that the wetlands, which make up almost a third
of the state, are eroding at a stunning rate. Louisiana lost
518,000 acres of wetlands from 1970 to 1980, according to the
National Wetlands Inventory. One expert for the defense testified
during the St. Martin trial that in 30 to 50 years, several
parishes in southeast Louisiana _ places tens of thousands of
Louisianans call home _ could disappear under water.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is what is responsible for the land loss. Testifying
for St. Martin, Robert Chabreck of Louisiana State University said
that 100 percent of the damage to the marsh could be blamed on the
canals. However, experts for the defense, also from LSU, testified
that a variety of factors ranging from hurricanes to nutrias caused
the erosion, and the canals were only a minor player.
</P>
<P>
   The federal and state governments blame breaks in the
Mississippi River levees for much of the damage to Louisiana's
wetlands. Storrs said the canals are just one of many factors
contributing to the erosion, along with breaks in the levees,
natural subsidence and saltwater intrusion into freshwater marshes.
But he said his department has not done a study on how canals
specifically have contributed to wetland loss.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Houck, director of the Environmental Law Clinic at Tulane
University, said blaming the river levees is ``the government
line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are reluctant to tighten regulations on the oil and gas
industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most studies by independent scientists attribute anywhere from
50 percent to 95 percent of the wetland damage to the canals, Houck
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The canal cuts through a living system and interrupts all the
functions,'' he said. ``It would be just like a cut in your belly.
One or two acres of canals can put 100 to 200 acres of marsh into a
death spiral.''
</P>
<P>
   In the St. Martin case, the judge concluded that 60 percent of
the damage in St. Martin's marsh was due to the canals.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's case, Houck said, shows that private initiative can
step in when the government is doing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important case, because it may start requiring oil
companies to pay the bill,'' he said. ``They have been walking away
from this stuff for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The canals at the heart of St. Martin's suit were dredged in the
1950s and '60s by Superior Oil, the predecessor to Mobil. The
company had leased the mineral rights from then-owner Southdown
Sugars to look for gas and oil. The previous owners never objected
to the canals.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Martin bought that property in 1992 and the canals and the
alleged damage were already there,'' said John Scofield, an
attorney for Mobil. Moreover, Scofield said, he was surprised by
the money awarded to St. Martin. The court decided to award him
$10,000 an acre for a 24-acre area that has been damaged since he
bought the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Supreme Court case holds you can't claim damages in an
amount in excess of the property value,'' he said. ``He bought the
property for $245 an acre. That's a pretty good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But this case isn't about money, St. Martin said. St. Martin,
who likes to call himself ``just a Cajun lawyer,'' is also a
prosperous '90s guy. He likes to listen to New Age Irish singer
Enya while he drives around in his Lincoln Navigator, an alligator
briefcase parked on the back seat. Another Navigator, two Mercedes
and several shiny powerboats are parked beside his large home on
the edge of his swamp. He owns about 10,000 acres of Louisiana
marsh, swamp and farmland. And he has a successful law practice
suing oil companies _ not for environmental damages, until now, but
in workers compensation cases.
</P>
<P>
   The swamp and philanthropy are in St. Martin's blood. He lives
next door to a home for battered and abused children that his
father established 25 years ago. The kids come over almost every
day to swim in his pool or relax in his hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, he bought 7,000 acres of marsh and swamp behind his
home, kept 2,400 acres and immediately set aside the rest for the
Nature Conservancy to create a wildlife refuge. Because the
conservancy couldn't afford to buy the land, St. Martin helped them
raise money, getting Dow Chemical to make a large donation and
donating $140,000 to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to put the $240,000 he won from the lawsuit right back
into the swamp, he said, using it to restore what he can or buy
additional property.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants the oil companies to repair what they damaged
because it's the right thing to do, but also because he says he
doesn't have the expertise or the equipment to repair it himself.
</P>
<P>
   And though it might sound like St. Martin is an environment nut
with a grudge against the oil and gas industry, that is not the
case. St. Martin has a permit to catch and kill 70 alligators every
fall, and he likes hunting so much his finger ``gets itchy'' when
he sees all the ducks in his marsh.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps most surprising, he owns an oil company. He even
drills in his own marsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in oil fields,'' St. Martin said. His grandfather
was a rig builder, and his father owned several oil service
companies. St. Martin earned money while he was in law school by
driving a tanker truck, and he is a member of the Teamsters union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil and gas and the environment can get along together,'' he
said as he sidled the airboat up to a production rig. ``I spent
$750,000 extra . . . It costs a little more money to do business in
an environmentally safe way. The consumer should just learn to pay
a penny a gallon more to do what's right.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
