<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RTP-CISCO21-COX     02-20 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RTP-CISCO21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Telecommunications competition sparks a middle-age rejuvenation
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. _ A child of California's Silicon
Valley, Cisco Systems decided to grow up in the Research Triangle
Park. But it suddenly finds its computer networking playground
crowded by two other big kids, Lucent Technologies and Northern
Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   The telecom competition has spurred unprecedented growth in the
Research Triangle Park. Combined, Cisco, Lucent and Nortel are
constructing six buildings in the region and have other projects on
the drawing board to accommodate several thousand additional
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, North Carolina leaders set aside 6,900 acres
between Raleigh, Durham and Chapel Hill in hopes of luring
companies and government agencies engaged in research and
development. It was a far-fetched notion, to sprout technology like
corn from a desolate patch of pine trees and overgrown fields.
</P>
<P>
   But promoters touted its proximity to budding research efforts
at Duke University in Durham, the University of North Carolina at
Chapel Hill and North Carolina State University in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Research Triangle Park finds itself in the midst of a
middle-age rejuvenation that promoters believe will strengthen its
international recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in telecommunications technology is so explosive,
said Cisco Senior Vice President Selby Wellman, that companies want
to hire experienced people rather than to hire college graduates
and train them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about the labor pool, you talk about your
competitors,'' said Wellman, who oversees a Research Triangle Park
work force that's grown from 56 in 1994 to 960 today. It's forecast
to reach 4,000 by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco, based in San Jose, Calif.; Lucent, based in Murray Hill,
N.J.; and Nortel, based in Brampton, Ontario, are pouring hundreds
of millions of dollars into the Research Triangle region. The
investments have put the Raleigh-Durham-Chapel Hill area at the
leading edge of a telecommunications revolution fueled by data
networking and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The investments by Cisco, Lucent, Nortel _ global giants with
annual revenue topping $50 billion _ are also likely to lure other
companies to the Research Triangle seeking to tap into the
cutting-edge developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``As companies battle together in a local area, they increase
the productivity of the industry in the area,'' said high-tech
economist Patrick Howie of Dynamic Resource Solutions in St.
Davids, Pa. ``You have information spillovers and structural
economic gains that build upon themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Research Triangle region is one of the South's hottest
technology hubs, but it's growth hasn't been smooth. The recent
past illustrates the volatility of technology.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, two semiconductor plants owned by Mitsubishi
and Motorola have closed. In a corporate streamlining, Nortel
eliminated 875 jobs in the Research Triangle Park last fall, even
as it is constructing three buildings to accommodate growth in
areas of hot technology.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest is ``convergence'' technology, and Cisco,
Lucent and Nortel are gearing up in the Research Triangle for a
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Big changes are forecast over the next decade for the world's
telephone networks. In simple terms, telephone lines once carried
only people's voices. Now they're transmitting increasing amounts
of computer data as the Internet's popularity soars.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom companies are in the early stages of integrating voice,
data and video on a single, high-speed network. Cisco, Lucent and
Nortel have decided to develop this technology in the Research
Triangle.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are huge, estimated globally as a $450 billion a year
market in voice and data networking sales. Many companies, big and
small, are joining the competition. It promises to reach a frenzied
pace in the Research Triangle Park, some officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It drives entrepreneurship within those major corporations,''
said William Glynn, director of Southeast Interactive Technology
Funds, a Durham-based venture capital firm. ``It drives innovation.
When there is innovation within companies, it creates spinoffs.
That only adds to the critical mass that we are experiencing in the
Research Triangle Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The location was key. North Carolina leaders wanted to stop the
brain drain from the universities in an era when the state's
economy was tied largely to tobacco, textiles and furniture. The
latest surge of growth, officials said, reinforces the achievement
of that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, if you went to Duke, UNC-Chapel Hill or N.C. State
and had a graduate degree related to anything but agriculturally
related stuff, you had to leave North Carolina,'' said Jim
Roberson, president of the Research Triangle Foundation, the park's
developer. ``We are now an importer of Ph.D.s, not an exporter.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is organizing a 40th anniversary celebration and
symposium March 3 to tout the park's role in shaping North
Carolina's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The park's first anchor tenant _ and today its largest employer
_ is IBM. More than 2,000 of Big Blue's 14,000 employees in the
region work for its Networking Hardware Division.
</P>
<P>
   In competition with Cisco, Lucent and Nortel, the IBM division
designs and manufactures computers, switches, routers and other
equipment that allows companies to link their computer networks to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's network management software subsidiary, called Tivoli, is
expanding as well. It is building two 100,000-square-foot buildings
in the Research Triangle Park as part of the region's
networking-related construction boom.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent is in the midst of a major project and is exploring
another. It is building a 123,000-square-foot software research and
development facility in Cary, between the Research Triangle Park
and Raleigh. An estimated 200 Lucent employees will relocate to the
center when it opens at the end of the year, but the company has
enough acreage to expand more.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent is also negotiating to establish a research center at
N.C. State University's Centennial Campus. With plans for up to 500
employees, the center would tap into N.C. State's expertise in
computer networking research. The company also hopes to improve its
odds of recruiting the university's engineering graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel, with 7,500 local employees after last year's layoffs, is
adding three 100,000-square-foot buildings to its Research Triangle
Park campus. A park tenant since 1980, the company said its
three-year, $181 million project will relieve crowding in its
research and development facility and will make Nortel more
attractive to prospective employees.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, Cisco envisions half of its revenue coming from
convergence technology. With that research focused in the Research
Triangle Park, Senior Vice President Wellman said the company plans
rapid growth for its Kit Creek campus.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's corporate officials decided in 1994 to expand beyond the
Silicon Valley because of the region's tight labor supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Research Triangle Park was our choice, hands down,'' said
Wellman, citing the availability of engineers and the proximity of
Duke, UNC-Chapel Hill and N.C. State. Another consideration was the
region's quality of life, which Wellman said has suffered in the
past year because of worsening traffic that the growth of companies
such as his have created.
</P>
<P>
   Wellman has warned that traffic could slow Cisco's expansion,
but so far it hasn't. The company has four buildings, two more
under construction, and three more on the drawing board on its
170-acre campus. If that's not enough, the company has agreements
for adjoining property.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
