<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2776 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RTP-COGENT21-COX     02-20 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RTP-COGENT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Incubator launches tide of high-tech whizzes
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ When the breeze blows across West Main Street,
the syrupy sweet smell of tobacco being turned into Chesterfield
and L&AMP;M cigarettes swirls into Max Wallace's office at Liggett
Tobacco Co.
</P>
<P>
   But the business of Wallace's fledgling company, Cogent
Neuroscience Inc., is anything but cigarettes. The biotechnology
start-up is renting space in Liggett's research and development
laboratory, a squat brick building across West Main from Liggett's
cigarette factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a natural launching pad for companies like ours,''
said Wallace, Cogent's 47-year-old founder and chief executive
officer, as he walked down a green-and-beige-tiled hallway leading
to small laboratories built in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Cogent raised $5.5 million in venture capital to
begin the long, expensive and uncertain process of discovering a
new treatment for strokes. Its eight scientists outnumber Liggett's
researchers, whose work includes testing the quality of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new era in this old tobacco town where some of the
best-known institutions _ from Duke University to the Durham Bulls
minor-league baseball team _ rose from the fortunes of the golden
leaf. The tobacco industry is fading, and a tide of high-tech
whizzes is rising from the ashes.
</P>
<P>
   They're on the verge of delivering, at last, on Tobacco Road's
promise to become a national hub of high-tech entrepreneurship in
biotechnology, software and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is real. I do not believe it is chamber of commerce hype,''
said Charles Moseley, general partner of Noro-Moseley Partners. The
Atlanta-based venture capital firm has invested $8 million in four
Research Triangle start-ups since September 1997 and it is scouting
more deals. ``It is one of the leading spots in the Southeast.''
</P>
<P>
   Located on 6,900 acres between Raleigh, Durham and Chapel Hill,
the Research Triangle Park is the nation's largest and one of the
oldest technology centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The universities understood that it was in their best interest
that this thing called the Research Triangle Park would become an
asset in the community,'' said Tom Wooten, who retired last fall as
president of Research Triangle Institute, a nonprofit independent
research organization and the park's first tenant. ``It was
enlightened self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the park earned its reputation by recruiting
major research companies and goverment agencies as tenants. Other
than in Washington, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has
its largest concentration of research facilities in the Research
Triangle. IBM employs 14,000 people in the region, the biggest
concentration of Big Blue employees in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Research Triangle Park plans to keep hunting ``big buffalo''
tenants responsible for thousands of jobs. Yet officials also
envision cultivating enough start-ups to attract venture
capitalists now pouring money into California's Silicon Valley and
the New England region centered on Massachusetts Route 128 in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see emerging technology as a real opportunity for
entrepreneurs to get started,'' said Jim Roberson, president of the
Research Triangle Foundation, the park's developer. Since
accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers started tracking venture
capital four years ago, the Research Triangle region has emerged,
along with metro Atlanta, as a Southern technology hot spot.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley easily tops the nation in venture capital, raking
in $4.6 billion from 787 deals in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists invested $247.3 million in 59 deals in the
Research Triangle last year. There was a total of 73 venture
capital deals in North Carolina last year, worth $300.4 million,
Pricewaterhouse said. Investments in the Research Triangle have
risen steadily since 1995's tally of 19 deals valued at $67.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in terms of raising money to launch high-tech entrepreneurs,
the Research Triangle region hasn't shaken loose from North
Carolina's tobacco and textile legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between Boston and Silicon Valley vs. here is
there is not that classic roll-the-dice culture that comes out of
central North Carolina,'' said Barrett Joyner, vice president of
North American sales and marketing for SAS Institute Inc., a major
software producer in Cary, just south of the Research Triangle
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, wealthy North Carolinians have favored investments
they could put their hands on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money that has been made was in textiles, tobacco, real
estate development,'' said Wallace, a former Duke University lawyer
who helped start three other biotech companies before Cogent
Neuroscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I go to them and say that I am going to discover the
genes that may provide new drugs for stroke patients and that I
need $50 million to get there, with no foreseeable returns?''
Wallace said. ``There has to be a culture change.''
</P>
<P>
   A Newsweek cover story last November on ''the hot new tech
cities'' excluded the Research Triangle. So did a Business Week
cover story in 1987 when it concluded that ''local start-ups ...
are rare'' in Raleigh, Durham and Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Some bristle at the unflattering comparisons, and some, like
Research Triangle Foundation's Roberson, say they're dead wrong. He
cites numerous surveys by publications including Money, Fortune and
Entrepreneur that rank the Research Triangle among the nation's
best places to live and do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to get over the hump with more money coming
from outside the area, including from Atlanta,'' said David Blivin,
managing director of Durham-based Southeast Interactive Technology
Funds, a major investor of venture capital in the Research
Triangle.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the region's growing reputation, Southeast
Interactive has teamed up with Silicon Valley magazine Upside to
sponsor the fourth annual Southeast Technology Conference May 10-11
at Duke's Fuqua School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   People who work with entrepreneurs in the Research Triangle say
the region is poised for explosive growth in the next year or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very much on the launch pad, if we haven't taken off,''
said Suzanne Cantando, training director at the Council for
Entrepreneurial Development in the Research Triangle Park.
</P>
<P>
   Officials tick off signs that conditions are ripening for
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1995 merger between pharmaceutical giants Burroughs
Welcome and Glaxo, some employees who left the companies stayed in
the Research Triangle and started more than a half dozen new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
