<HEADER>
A2777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RTP-GEORGE21-COX     02-20 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RTP-GEORGE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. park success based on teamwork
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. _ Poor George is a goner, a
virtual-reality victim at the Research Triangle Institute.
</P>
<P>
   George, a computerized talking head, responded too slowly in
conversations with people. So he was replaced by fast-talking Rocky
and Roxanne, the rising stars at the institute, the Research
Triangle Park's oldest tenant.
</P>
<P>
   The pair of hip, high-tech 30-somethings illustrates some of the
latest fast-moving but practical research under way at the
institute. Its recent efforts in virtual reality also demonstrate
how the nonprofit research organization has dutifully clung to its
original mission of collaborating with the three universities that
started it in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, North Carolina
State University in Raleigh and Duke University in Durham own the
institute.
</P>
<P>
   The institute operates independent of the universities and it
solicits research funds, expected to reach $200 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collaboration has been crucial,'' said Alvin M. Cruze, the
institute's interim president, who joined the staff in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Created in an era when independent research was rare in a region
dominated by textiles and farming, the institute has prospered
beyond the expectations of its founders.
</P>
<P>
   With a staff of 1,525 worldwide, including 1,325 on its 180-acre
campus in Research Triangle Park, the institute conducts research
under contract to government agencies, companies and foundations,
such as the National Institutes of Health, the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency, NASA and pharmaceutical giant Glaxo Wellcome.
</P>
<P>
   In its largest project, worth $205 million over eight years, the
institute is conducting a national survey on drug abuse for the
U.S. Department of Health and Human Services. Sales of one of the
institute's anticancer discoveries, Taxol, approached $1 billion
last year for Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.
</P>
<P>
   The institute opened an office in Atlanta last fall to be near
one of its clients, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The institute earned $4.2 million in revenue last year from the
CDC. It is involved in nine CDC projects, including national
surveys of smoking behavior and studying school health programs.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's research spans many fields, including economics,
chemicals,electronics and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of placing a research laboratory in the university
environment was fairly rare at that time,'' said George Simpson,
77, chancellor of the University of Georgia system from 1965 to
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson was a UNC-Chapel Hill sociology professor who in 1956
became executive director of the committee created to establish the
institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's call it a long shot,'' Simpson described the institute's
initial odds for success.
</P>
<P>
   State leaders, including Gov. Luther Hodges, were troubled by
North Carolina's dependence on low wages in textiles, farming and
furniture. They envisioned tapping the universities' budding
research efforts to create an institute that, in turn, would anchor
a major research park to attract high-paying employers.
</P>
<P>
   When it decided five years ago to venture into virtual reality,
which creates a three-dimensional, interactive experience, the
institute sought one of the field's early developers, UNC-Chapel
Hill computer scientist Fred Brooks. He helped the institute select
computers and software to demonstrate virtual reality to potential
customers. The institute chose to invest its efforts in training, a
largely untapped market.
</P>
<P>
   It developed a virtual medical trainer prototype for the U.S.
Army that recreated on a computer monitor emergency scenes such as
an automobile crash and sniper fire. The institute is negotiating
with a publisher interested in selling the program on CD-ROM to
emergency medical agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to present a true-to-life representation of a
trauma, so the student can practice assessment and treatment,
especially in the first 10 minutes of coming onto the scene,'' said
Paul Kizakevich, a senior research engineer at the institute.
Another project was to develop virtual humans to provide training
for businesses. Last spring, researchers developed George, a
sometimes surly bank customer who wanted to cash a $25 check.
</P>
<P>
   His head bobbed and his lips moved as he told the teller, ``My
account number here is 1,2,3.''
</P>
<P>
   As he received two fives, a ten and five ones, his forehead
knitted and he scowled. ``I am not satisfied with your branch,'' he
said. George had a fatal flaw.
</P>
<P>
   He always paused for a couple of seconds, creating a jerky
conversation. That would diminish the effectiveness of training
customer service representatives, such as airline reservationists,
who handle a rapid succession of calls.
</P>
<P>
   George was retired and along came Rocky and Roxanne.
</P>
<P>
   The pair was a big hit recently at a national convention in Las
Vegas, where passersby were surprised to find themselves engaged in
conversation with virtual humans.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky and Roxanne were to demonstrate how they could assist real
people in manning booths at trade shows. Not only could that save
money, but it also could create excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is cool,'' said Dean Hering, the institute's manager of
commercial projects for virtual reality. ``People get hyped up
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
