</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RTP-TRAFFIC21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bumper-to-bumper traffic congestion clouds town's future
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORRISVILLE, N.C. _ For Grover and Peggy Lewter, a retired
couple who live on the outskirts of this fast-growing Research
Triangle town, one rule of the road exceeds all others. Don't
drive, if you can avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   Grover, 66, owns a red Chevy pickup, his 63-year-old wife a
beige Chevy Impala. They keep horses, chickens and two dogs,
Trouble and Amy, on six acres developers have been drooling over
for years.
</P>
<P>
   They've learned that, during rush hour, only fools _ and
thousands of Research Triangle Park commuters _ travel the
bumper-to-bumper stretch of Davis Drive that fronts the Lewters'
tidy brick home of 34 years.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the two-lane highway was partially paved, and traffic
was so scarce that Lewter went to the mailbox in his underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw about two cars a day come up and down the road, and
one of them was the mailman,'' Peggy Lewter said.
</P>
<P>
   The mail comes later now, slowed by the congestion of the
estimated 25,000 vehicles that pass every weekday. The couple
rarely ventures out between 7:30 and 10 a.m. or between 4:30 and 7
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is Wednesday night. Then it takes up to 30 minutes
to drive the mile and a half to supper and the prayer meeting at
Good Hope Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Short of divine intervention, it's hard to fathom how traffic is
going to get much better.
</P>
<P>
   With mind-boggling growth forecast for the region, the
congestion is expected to worsen until highway improvements
projected to cost $435 million are completed.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly frustrating in this region that boasts one of
America's highest concentrations of PhD.s has been the inability of
civic and political leaders to get much of a handle on traffic
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is bad but not as bad as Atlanta,'' said Scott Lane, a
long-range planner in Raleigh. ``But we are trying hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Lured by the Research Triangle's booming economy, people are
flocking to jobs centered on the research park. And 25,000 new jobs
are forecast for the region this year.
</P>
<P>
   But congestion threatens to stymie growth. One of the Research
Triangle Park's fastest-growing companies, computer networking
giant Cisco Systems, has raised public concerns about its ability
to meet expansion goals if traffic doesn't improve.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the Research Triangle could only dream of the
prosperity that has sprouted from the concentration of global
technology companies. In an ever-widening circle, small towns such
as Morrisville find themselves grappling with kudzu-like growth.
</P>
<P>
   Population estimates in Morrisville rocket from 2,808 in 1998:
5,439 this year, 14,250 in 2005 and 18,705 in 2010. The number of
dwelling units is forecast to jump by 466 percent, from 1,783 in
1995 to 10,095 in 2025.
</P>
<P>
   A 270 percent increase is expected in the number of people
working in Morrisville, from 10,334 in 1995 to 38,225 in 2025,
according to a forecast last year by the Capital Area Metropolitan
Planning Organization and the Durham-Chapel Hill-Carrboro
Metropolitan Planning Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Morrisville having 3,000 people, and you say this
is a small town,'' Town Manager David Hodgkins said. ``Then you
look at all of the people passing through and working here during
the day.'' Its proximity to the Research Triangle Park and
Raleigh-Durham International Airport has transformed Morrisville
into an industrial and commercial hub. As a result, the town's tax
base amounts to $228,000 a person.
</P>
<P>
   The town's prosperity is deceiving, Hodgkins said, because its
soaring population of residents and office workers is pressuring
municipal services. In a state whose nicknames include ``The Good
Roads State,'' North Carolina Transportation Secretary Norris
Tolson has recommended radical remedies to ease traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding one more highway or one more lane will not be enough,''
he said. ``We cannot just pave our way out of this congestion.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Transportation Department plans to widen I-40 and
other major roads, but it and other regional planning agencies are
recommending other steps, such as expanding bus routes and
encouraging greater car and van pooling.
</P>
<P>
   In a $250 million project slated for completion in 2004, the
Triangle Transit Authority plans to build a regional rail system
connecting Raleigh, Cary, Apex and Durham with the Research
Triangle Park.
</P>
<P>
   Tolson has suggested companies in the research park encourage
employees to telecommute and consider charging them for parking.
None of these is a sure-fire solution, partly because of the
sprawling design of Research Triangle Park. Nobody lives in the
6,900-acre park, so the roughly 50,000 people employees must
commute.
</P>
<P>
   Employers are scattered across the park, and office buildings
are set back from the roads. That complicates transporting rail
passengers to their offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very difficult area to ever take root to mass
transit,'' said Jim Goodnight, president of SAS Institute, a
software manufacturer in Cary. ''We have a lot of people talking
about it, but nobody is ever going to ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
