<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOY-UNDIES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The real shock for parents? That boys' skivvies are clean!
 &HT;    By Matt Reed
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Parents: Take a look at Calvin Klein's
controversial _ and hastily yanked _ ad for children's underwear.
</P>
<P>
   You're horrified, aren't you? And for good reason:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, you kids! Stop jumping on that sofa!''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, you probably don't think twice about 3- and
4-year-old boys playing in their underpants. (Do you?)
</P>
<P>
   Because once you finally get them to wear undies, little boys
live in them. The grubbier the better, as far as they're concerned.
Perfect attire for watching Arthur, dashing to the Playskool Turtle
sandbox or cramming a Pop-Tart into the VCR.
</P>
<P>
   It's the thought of Junior hopping around in a pair of pricey
designer briefs that's a little troubling.
</P>
<P>
   But folks in New York had other concerns when Calvin Klein
unfurled its billboard in Times Square. Someone might get ... you
know ... the wrong idea, they said. Could this be ... kiddie porn?
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudy Giuliani _ who apparently never saw Underoos modeled
in a Sears catalog _ told the New York Post the ads ``did not look
like the kind of thing you'd want to do with young children.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper called them ``provocative ads, featuring semi-nude
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Provocative? Semi-nude?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with kids knows that a 3-year-old wearing tightie-whities
and some Spaghetti-O stains is half-dressed.
</P>
<P>
   And hats off to the parents of the two boys pictured: The truly
remarkable thing is that they got them into underpants at all.
</P>
<P>
   See, persuading a tot to wear ``big boy'' underpants for the
first time is a huge accomplishment for everyone involved. It means
the the little guy has to give up his beloved diapers. (Girls are a
little different: They can't wait to get into something fancy.)
</P>
<P>
   So you make a big celebration out of it, take little Danny or
Brandon to Target and let him pick them out himself. There's a
whole exciting lineup to choose from: Arthur, Barney, firetrucks,
Winnie-the-Pooh, Spider-Man, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   And you pray he takes the bait.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the first couple of packs end up bleached out or in
the trash after a predictable series of, shall we say, misfires.
</P>
<P>
   So, what mom or dad is going to pay big bucks for Calvins? Heck,
what 3-year-old is going to pick those dour, minimalistic CKs to
begin with over, say, the Rugrats?
</P>
<P>
   And wait one minute: Is one of those preschoolers in the ad
wearing boxers?
</P>
<P>
   That's not nudity. That's a boy who knows how to dress.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Reed's 3-year-old prefers Oshkoshes with tigers and
giraffes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
