</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSEPAINTING21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's time to paint the house: Here's what you need to know to do
it right!
 &HT;    By Africa Fine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I painted my dorm room in a couple
hours, you figure, surely I can paint my house next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And if your standards are no higher than they were when you were
thumb-tacking that Farrah Fawcett poster over the lumpy spot on the
wall, you probably can.
</P>
<P>
   But most of us would prefer a more sophisticated job on the home
we've gone into deep debt to buy. A good paint job should last 10
years or longer, but a bad one may need to be redone in a year or
less.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say you can't do it yourself, just that there's
a lot to consider before you tackle it.
</P>
<P>
   Here, some guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   DO IT YOURSELF OR HIRE A PRO? The best do-it-yourself candidate:
</P>
<P>
   - has tackled home improvements before
</P>
<P>
   - has some painting experience
</P>
<P>
   - is willing to do his or her homework
</P>
<P>
   - is not afraid to ask for help
</P>
<P>
   - is patient and persistent
</P>
<P>
   If you do it yourself ...
</P>
<P>
   - Allow two to three times longer to complete the project than
the average pro estimate.
</P>
<P>
   - Have a plan. Talk to experts at a paint store and check the
Internet for home improvement sites.
</P>
<P>
   - Gather all supplies and equipment before you begin.
</P>
<P>
   - Be prepared to make some mistakes, and have a plan B just in
case.
</P>
<P>
   PROS
</P>
<P>
   - You have control
</P>
<P>
   - Cheaper (unless you make costly mistakes)
</P>
<P>
   - No risk of contractor fraud
</P>
<P>
   CONS
</P>
<P>
   - Can result in costly mistakes
</P>
<P>
   - May not look as good as pro job
</P>
<P>
   - Can be time-consuming
</P>
<P>
   If you hire a professional ...
</P>
<P>
   - Ask friends, neighbors, co-workers for recommendations of
painters they have used.
</P>
<P>
   - Talk to at least three contractors, and get estimates from
each before choosing one.
</P>
<P>
   - Deal only with licensed contractors; ask to see the license
plus at least one other form of identification.
</P>
<P>
   - Call the state licensing bureau to verify the license and
check for complaints.
</P>
<P>
   - Ask for references _ and contact them.
</P>
<P>
   - Get a written contract and agree on a payment method upfront.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't pay cash.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't pay the full cost upfront. Legitimate contractors will
not require more than half upfront; many will agree to a
pay-as-you-go arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   PROS
</P>
<P>
   - Professional-looking job
</P>
<P>
   - Experts know how to deal with any problems that arise
</P>
<P>
   - Saves time
</P>
<P>
   CONS
</P>
<P>
   - Unskilled contractor could do a poor job
</P>
<P>
   - More expensive (from $300 for one room to $3,000 or more for
the exterior of a 3-bedroom home)
</P>
<P>
   - You have less control
</P>
<P>
   BEFORE YOU BEGIN
</P>
<P>
   - Examine the area to be painted to determine the type and
texture of the surface, any imperfections that need repair and the
amount of trim.
</P>
<P>
   - Calculate the square footage to be painted.
</P>
<P>
   - Organize the supplies you already have and make a list of
things you need to buy. (See supply checklist.)
</P>
<P>
   - If you're painting outside, check weather reports to make sure
rain isn't forecast for 48 hours. Also avoid hot, humid conditions.
Moist conditions make paint sticky and increase drying time.
</P>
<P>
   - Make sure you have the time and commitment to finish the job.
Many factors affect how long a project takes, but if painting your
3-bedroom house would take a professional two to three days, it
will take most do-it-yourselfers about a week. Add time for high
ceilings, odd-shaped rooms and surfaces that need repair before
painting.
</P>
<P>
   PICKING THE PAINT
</P>
<P>
   - FORMULA _ Paint comes in two basic formulas: latex-based and
enamel. Latex is the most popular and the easiest to use. It's
water-soluble, takes about an hour to dry and cleans up with soap
and water. Enamel paint contains oils, so it resists staining
better than latex and can withstand heavy scrubbing in kitchens and
bathrooms. But it takes longer to dry and you'll need solvents for
cleaning up.
</P>
<P>
   - FINISH _ Exterior paints are available in several finishes:
flat (low-sheen, hides imperfections), semi-gloss (good for
high-traffic areas such as doors and shutters, repels dirt), satin
(all-purpose, durable) and gloss (high-sheen, good to accentuate
trim).
</P>
<P>
   - BRAND _ Prices range from about $6 for a pint of Glidden to
$30 for a gallon of Ralph Lauren paint, but a good-quality paint
will probably cost about $16 per gallon. Look for a resin content
of at least 20-25 percent _ the higher the resin content, the more
durable the paint. Otherwise, your choice should be based on your
familiarity with the brand, your price range and the colors
available.
</P>
<P>
   - COLOR _ Consider your furnishings and decor when choosing a
paint color for the inside of the house. If you're not absolutely
sure about a color, do a patch-test on a small area and live with
it for a few days to see how it looks in different light. Outside,
consider the style of your home and the colors of other homes in
the neighborhood. A lime green door might seem like a fun idea, but
consider how it would blend into the neighborhood and what
prospective buyers might think if you decided to sell.
</P>
<P>
   - AMOUNT _ At the beginning of the project, buy enough paint for
the entire job. It's better to have more than you need than to run
back for extra only to find that the new batch is a slightly
different hue. Plus, paint is cheaper if you buy it in four- or
five-gallon containers. Most paints cover about 400 square feet per
gallon for one coat; assume you'll need at least two thin coats.
For more help determining how much paint you need, check out
Benjamin Moore's Web site at www.bejaminmoore.com and use their
interactive calculator.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPLY CHECKLIST
</P>
<P>
   Expect the cost of supplies to paint the outside of an average
3-bedroom home to be $300-$500. Allow $100-$300 for interior
projects, depending on the number of rooms being painted.
</P>
<P>
   BRUSHES
</P>
<P>
   - To paint smaller areas, crevices and corners.
</P>
<P>
   - Use a 1/2-inch angled brush for corners and a 4-inch brush for
broad strokes. Nylon bristles offer the most versatility because
natural fiber brushes cannot be used with water-based paint.
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $4-$5 per brush.
</P>
<P>
   BUCKET
</P>
<P>
   - For storing brushes, rags and other small tools
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $1-$3.
</P>
<P>
   DROP CLOTHS
</P>
<P>
   - Protect furniture and floors, grass and plants
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $4-$5 each.
</P>
<P>
   CAULK/CAULK GUN
</P>
<P>
   - Repair cracks and imperfections on the surface
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $2-$5 for gun; caulk ranges from $2 for basic
interior type to $5 for outdoor masonry quality.
</P>
<P>
   EXTENSION POLE
</P>
<P>
   - Connect to roller to reach high spots
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $3-$4.
</P>
<P>
   MINERAL SPIRITS
</P>
<P>
   - Clean up enamel-based paints
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $3-$5 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   PAINTER'S TAPE
</P>
<P>
   - Protect interior window sills and electrical outlets (this
tape is wider and thicker than regular masking tape)
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $4-$5.
</P>
<P>
   SANDPAPER
</P>
<P>
   - Smooth out rough spots
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $2-$3 for a package of medium-weight paper.
</P>
<P>
   PUTTY KNIFE
</P>
<P>
   - Smooth over caulked areas (get several sizes)
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $2-$5 each.
</P>
<P>
   RAGS
</P>
<P>
   - Clean up
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: nothing; tear up some old T-shirts
</P>
<P>
   ROLLER/ROLLER TRAYS
</P>
<P>
   - Paints larger areas quickly
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $12-$15 for a kit including trays, two ormore
rollers and handles. Individually, handles cost about $5, rollers
are$3-$5 and trays runs $2-$3.
</P>
<P>
   LADDER
</P>
<P>
   - Reach high places
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $25-$35 for a standard 6-foot metal or wood
ladder; more for extension ladders.
</P>
<P>
   STEEL WOOL
</P>
<P>
   - Scrape away old paint or dirt on home exterior
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $2-$5 for a package of 10 or more.
</P>
<P>
   SPRAY APPLICATOR (outdoors only)
</P>
<P>
   - Used by pros to apply paint fast, can be rented by
do-it-yourselfers
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $60-$300 to buy (depending on spray
capacity); rent one for about $50 per day.
</P>
<P>
   GLOVES/GOGGLES
</P>
<P>
   - Protect hands and eyes from splatters and fumes
</P>
<P>
   - Expect to spend: $5 for gloves; $3-$5 for goggles.
</P>
<P>
   APPLYING THE PAINT
</P>
<P>
   - No matter what the label says, two or more thin coats are
usually better than one thick coat, which may drip, dry very slowly
and/or remain sticky. It's best to allow 24 hours drying time
between coats.
</P>
<P>
   - Inside, paint ceiling first, then walls.
</P>
<P>
   - Use rollers for the ceiling and large wall areas; they cover
more area and tend to drip less.
</P>
<P>
   - Use brushes for smaller wall areas, around door jams and in
corners.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't overload brushes or rollers with paint. Roll the roller
back andforth in the paint pan once or twice, then shake excess
back into tray. Try to load brushes without dripping, then tap
against the side of the can to remove excess paint.
</P>
<P>
   - Choose ONE directipon to paint _ horizontally or vertically _
and stick with it. Overlap strokes slightly.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't start painting a wall or the ceiling if you won't have
time to finish that area. You want each surface to dry evenly for a
uniform appearance.
</P>
<P>
   MOST COMMON MISTAKES MADE BY DO-IT-YOURSELF PAINTERS
</P>
<P>
   1. Neglecting to consider the weather. Best time to paint: When
the temperature is between 60 and 90 degrees. Avoid painting when
rain is expected within 48 hours or when it's very humid.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mistaking paint for primer, and vice-versa. It comes in the
same kind of can and is stacked in the same hardware-store aisle,
but it's not the same. Primers seal the surface or walls, and paint
protects that seal. Any surface that is porous, stained or bare
needs to be primed before painting, or the paint will seep into the
surface and leave it vulnerable to the elements.
</P>
<P>
   3. Failing to prepare the surface before painting.
</P>
<P>
   Inside:
</P>
<P>
   - Move as much of the furniture out of the room as possible
</P>
<P>
   - Cover the floor and remaining furniture with drop cloths
</P>
<P>
   - Cover light fixtures and electrical cover plates with plastic
bags or tape
</P>
<P>
   - If you're painting behind outlet covers, turn off the
electricity to the room.
</P>
<P>
   Outside:
</P>
<P>
   - Scrape all loose paint and sand those surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   - Wash the surface thoroughly with a cleanser designed for this
purpose. If there is mildew, add bleach according to the label
directions.
</P>
<P>
   - Rinse to remove soap residue
</P>
<P>
   - Repair any surface problems before beginning
</P>
<P>
   - Use a primer if you're painting over a darker color or making
repairs to the surface before painting.
</P>
<P>
   4. Using dirty equipment
</P>
<P>
   Make sure your brushes and rollers are clean and in good
condition to ensure the best, most consistent results. Latex-based
paints clean up easily with soap and water, while enamel paints
require mineral sprits. Be careful when using flammable solvents _
wear gloves and goggles _ and clean up immediately after you finish
the job.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCES
</P>
<P>
   - Randy Arnold and Erin Andrews, Sears Weatherbeater Paint Pros.
</P>
<P>
   - Home Depot
</P>
<P>
   - Loews
</P>
<P>
   - Benjamin Moore Paints
</P>
<P>
   - ``Season by Season Guide to Home Maintenance'' by John Ward
($24.95, Consumer Reports Books)
</P>
<P>
   - www.nari.org (web site of the National Association of the
Remodeling Industry).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
