<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVPOST-SONNY-CHER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `And the Beat Goes On'
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``And The Beat Goes On: The Sonny And
Cher Story'' : 9-11 p.m. Monday (ABC)
</P>
<P>
   They were the ultimate odd couple. He was short, she was tall.
She could sing, he couldn't. He was goofy-looking, she was an
exotic beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny and Cher definitely left their indelible stamp on pop
music. Their stormy relationship and Sonny's tragic death in a
skiing accident are the stuff of TV movies.
</P>
<P>
   In ``And The Beat Goes On,'' a touching, but mostly one-sided
story (it's based on Sonny's book), the phenomenon that was Sonny
and Cher is colorfully recreated. The film stars Jay Underwood
(``Afterglow'') as the controlling Sonny and Renee Faia (``The
American President'') as the moody Cher. I recently caught up with
Faia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you afraid Cher will kick your butt if she doesn't like
your performance?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, I wouldn't expect that from her. She's an actress and she
knows what that's about. I'm sure she'll have her criticisms. But I
think she'll be pleased that the love story came through.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Watching you as Cher really freaked me out because you looked
just like her. Were you freaked out, too?
</P>
<P>
   A: A little bit, mostly in the beginning. It was a wild
experience. When we started putting on the wigs, it was really
coming together and it got a little freaky.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was that your real nose in the movie?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, they didn't have to do anything to my nose. Now, Jay
got, like 19 fake noses.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After wearing many of those garish '70s get-ups, didn't you
just want to burn them all?
</P>
<P>
   A: I thought they were great. I really loved the leather,
whipped stitch pants. I thought they were cool. I just dig that
whole style.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The leather, whipped, WHAT?
</P>
<P>
   A: Whipped stitch. It's an industry term, baby.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Before getting this role, did people tell you that you looked
like Cher?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not really. My hair is lighter and shorter. The cast didn't
even recognize me out of costume.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You worked on `A Few Good Men' as a costume designer and
secretly studied Jack Nicholson. What did you learn?
</P>
<P>
   A: I would go down to the set when they were doing the courtroom
scenes and I saw how professional he was and how he would give 110
percent on and off camera. He's such a professional and he has fun
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Jack ever hit on you?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, the most he would say was, `Hi, gals.'
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the last few months, have you a desire to wear see-through
Bob Mackie outfits, date young guys and curse out David Letterman?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Laughing) No, I've done all that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you get tired of listening to Sonny and Cher sing?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, I really enjoyed their music. I wasn't that familiar with
it, other than `I've Got You Babe.' I even kept one of the CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who's got YOU, babe?
</P>
<P>
   A: Who's got me? My boyfriend, for a year-and-a-half.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 1512EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
