<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOGEL21-COX     02-20 1491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOGEL21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why is a play about pedophilia so popular?
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Domestic violence. Gay parenting.
Prostitution. Pedophilia.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Vogel makes us laugh at the most unlikely things.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, when her brother died of AIDS, she wrote ``The
Baltimore Waltz,'' a surreal farce and cathartic comic take on her
loss. And three years ago, she wrote a response to ``Lolita,''
turning it into a seductively humorous tale of a teen-age girl
called Li'l Bit and the sexual advances of her Uncle Peck.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``How I Learned To Drive,'' the play motors down the dark
roads of child abuse and incest with an unexpectedly light tone.
Rather than a story of villain and victim, it tells a more complex
tale of Li'l Bit's ability to take control of her life and move
beyond the potential scars of molestation.
</P>
<P>
   The play not only won the 1998 Pulitzer Prize for Drama, but
will be the most produced stage script in America this season, with
26 regional productions scheduled, including the Florida premiere
at Boca Raton's Caldwell Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Why has ``How I Learned to Drive'' become so popular?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Vogel responds automatically, with the
weariness of a writer who has fielded the question too often. ``You
know what? I have to tell you, this is my survival strategy. In
order to survive all the years of rejection, I had to be in a state
of denial. So now I'm denying the success, because I don't
understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   After so many rejection slips for her quirky scripts _ some of
which, Vogel concedes, deserved to be rejected _ this roly-poly,
47-year-old playwright is getting the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feel that the way we, if not entrap an audience but
get them involved and engaged, is through the response of
laughter,'' says Vogel, by telephone from her Providence, R.I.,
home. ``Once you've laughed at something, you're inside the play
world, you've accepted the rules of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``So of course, I'm making people laugh at Li'l Bit. I'm making
them laugh at the family and at Peck,'' she says, referring to the
richly comic dinner table scenes which show Li'l Bit as
misunderstood and mocked by her blue-collar Maryland clan. ``And
the second that they start laughing, I got them.''
</P>
<P>
   To theatergoers resistant to seeing a play about pedophilia,
Caldwell's Artistic and Managing Director Michael Hall downplays
the label. ``It's really a play about people who are attracted to
each other for very real reasons,'' he says. ``The two of them are
really fascinated by each other, and I want to forget for a long
time that they are related. It's a love story.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact that it is receiving so much attention remains a
puzzlement to Vogel. She begs off the question, but others have
their theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just takes you by surprise,'' says Kim Cozort, who plays
Li'l Bit at the Caldwell. ``She will make you laugh and then, all
of a sudden, she'll (produce) a line or a scene that hits you in
the gut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a writer who dearly loves the theater, and audiences
respond to that, no matter the subject,'' adds director Susan
Booth, whose production of ``How I Learned to Drive'' is at
Chicago's Northlight Theatre and will next transfer to Atlanta's
Alliance Theatre. ``I think she could take on any topic. She's just
not going to take it on in the way that Lifetime television for
women is going to take it on.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Vogel carried the notion of responding to Lolita from
a woman's viewpoint, looking for a striking, personal route into
the story. The breakthrough came when she had a visual image: ``I
saw a woman adjusting a rear view mirror and having a dead man
materialize in the back seat of her car. I knew somehow that that
was the metaphor for my Lolita and that that was my Humbert
(Lolita's older lover) in the back seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a detective, she worked backward from the image to deduce
what her play should be. ``I went, `OK, you've got a woman
adjusting a rear view mirror, it has something to do with driving.'
And I mulled that and thought driving is a wonderful metaphor,
because we learn to drive at the age of sexual ambiguity and
maturity. Sexual adolescence and driving correspond.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogel wrote the relationship between Li'l Bit and Peck as a
series of driving lessons, with metaphorical quotes from a driving
manual. ``I saw how to do that, how I can be seemingly talking
about cars, but actually cars are the female body, which is a
connection that's made by this culture in all of the
advertisements,'' she notes.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it was finished, Lolita had been drained from the
play. Unlike such previous Vogel plays as ``Desdemona,'' her
perspective shift on ``Othello,'' or ``Meg,'' her version of ``A
Man For All Seasons'' as told by Sir Thomas More's daughter, ``How
I Learned to Drive'' cruises along on its own power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think where I am now is I've gone from adaptation and
translation into response,'' says Vogel. ``I'm now thinking, `How
do I create a parallel universe that's not the same thing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, ``How I Learned to Drive'' connects with
theatergoers, and Vogel's career is in overdrive. ``I think the
times are in tune with me or I'm in tune with the times,'' she
offers, calling it a ``union between playwright and audience and
zeitgeist. This happens to be my point in time, and I don't know
for how long that will be.''
</P>
<P>
   So she's keeping busy. Her newest play, ``The Mineola Twins,''
opened off-Broadway on Thursday. Published together with ``How I
Learned to Drive'' in a volume dubbed ``The Mammary Plays,'' ``The
Mineola Twins'' is the more overtly comic flip side of the Pulitzer
Prize winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dealing with the same period of time, the '50s through
the '80s,'' explains Vogel. ``It's meant to be the satyr play to
the tragedy. It's dealing with the female body, but in the same way
that Greek playwrights were asked to burlesque their Medeas on the
same night,'' so that audience would go home smiling instead of
depressed. The play spoofs the evolution of suburban life as seen
through identical twins _ one good, one evil _ both played by
Swoosie Kurtz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's me saying, `OK, folks, now for something completely
different.'''
</P>
<P>
   In any mode, colleagues feel she will be a major force in the
theater for a long time to come. ``Paula has always been a
wonderful writer and will always be a wonderful writer,'' says
Molly Smith, who helped develop ``Drive'' at Perseverance Theatre
in Alaska and will present it again this spring at Washington's
Arena Stage, where she is the new artistic director. ``She always
writes about hot-button areas of society. She's constantly going to
places that other writers would be afraid to go to.''
</P>
<P>
   After she won the Pulitzer and had a champagne-fueled party in
Boston with friends and her longtime partner, biology professor and
author Anne Fausto-Sterling, Vogel gave herself a more lasting
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quit my day job,'' she says, referring to her resignation as
the director of Brown University's graduate program in playwriting.
``I am now going to be something called professor-at-large, which
always reminds me not to eat dessert. I'm putting the writing first
as sort of my celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   You would too, if you were booked solid with stage and film
writing projects through 2002. First she has to polish her
screenplay of her geriatric hookers play, ``The Oldest
Profession'', scheduled to begin shooting in September with Olympia
Dukakis. For Arena Stage, where Vogel has been named
playwright-in-residence, she has to rewrite her pornography
industry play (``Hot 'n' Throbbing'') and start a history-based
musical called ``A Civil War Christmas'' to premiere at holiday
time in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   She's writing an original script for Showtime cable and is
supposed to deliver her screenplay of ``How I Learned To Drive'' to
director Fred Schepisi (``Roxanne,'' ``Six Degrees of Separation'')
by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, but it feels a little bit like O'Hare Airport,
with plays circling,'' Vogel laughs.
</P>
<P>
   So far, she has been treated well by film executives, and
doesn't expect to go Hollywood. ``I know who I am and I'm not going
to be somebody who wants to make millions of dollars and buy a big
house in L.A.,'' Vogel insists. ``I'm a New Englander, I've got my
house in Providence. My life is very good, I don't want to change
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she has an academic curiosity about film, and wants to
rethink ``How I Learned To Drive'' for the big screen. ``It's going
to be incredibly seductive, and it's not going to be anything like
the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may go, `Oh, my God, I loved the play, how could
you do this?' And other people who have never seen the play will
ask, `How could that have ever been a play?'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
