<HEADER>
A2783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALL-OPPONENTS-550&AMP;AD     02-20 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALL-OPPONENTS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MALL'S OPPONENTS DON'T GIVE UP EASILY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBRA WEST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST NYACK, N.Y. _ When the Palisades Center mall opened here in
March, the developers might have thought their long battle with
opponents in the community was finally over. They would have been
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   An average of 300,000 shoppers pass through the glistening mall
doors each week. They pick up lumber at Home Depot and pressed
linen suits at Ann Taylor, kitchen elegance at Williams Sonoma and
bargains at Target.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of Rockland County residents who opposed this
mall-cum-city since it was first proposed in 1985 are not to be
found among the crowds. They still are shocked that the mall, all
four stories and three million square feet of it, was not only
built but has apparently triumphed, while they are still scarred
and paying legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who have devoted a quarter of their lives to
fighting this mall,'' said Linda Rauer, a former shopkeeper and
inveterate environmentalist who became involved in opposing the
mall in the early 1990s when she found out that it was being built
on top of two landfills about 20 miles northwest of Manhattan.
``They are not going to just give up, walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   The opponents, some of whom still hope to close the mall down,
are now focused on insuring that a proposed expansion of the
Palisades Center is voted upon in a public referendum, as promised.
The expansion, which would permit the use of 1.15 million square
feet of unoccupied space at the center, would make it the second
largest mall in America.
</P>
<P>
   So when Rosie O'Donnell, who lives in Nyack, went on her morning
talk show last month and joked about rumors that the mall in her
town was sinking and would soon close, it only made the acrimony
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rauer and the loyal members of the Rockland Civic
Association, a grass-roots organization that was formed to stop the
mall, were incensed. Their last hope for closing the mall _ the
possibility that cracks in the concrete floor and a distinct shimmy
in the structure meant it was unsafe _ was being turned into a
joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a public safety issue,'' Ms. Rauer said. ``We
want a structural engineer to come in and measure whether the mall
is settling. We want a seismic engineer to find out why that
building shakes. The mall is built on two former, unregulated
landfills,'' she said, adding that she fears that despite a system
designed to collect them, contaminants could percolate through the
soil and end up in the drinking supply.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas J. Valenti, a developer of the Palisades Center, concedes
that the underground parking lot at the mall has settled, that
cracks run helter-skelter across the bare concrete floors and that
the building's shake is disconcerting. None of it, however means
the mall is dangerous, Valenti said. He noted that the mall has
been inspected by engineers and backed by bonds that put the
Pyramid Companies, the nation's largest mall developer behind the
$390 million project.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are never satisfied with anything you do,''
Valenti said. ``You clean up landfills and that's not good enough.
You solve the traffic problems, stop the roads from flooding and
that's not good enough. No matter what solution you provide, it's
never going to be good enough for them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Palisades Center was built by the Pyramid Companies of
Syracuse, and their reputation for aggressiveness preceded them
when they came to Rockland County.
</P>
<P>
   The company was investigated by the New York Commission on
government Integrity for spending $776,967 to influence the 1985
election of the Poughkeepsie Town Council to elect members who
favored the construction of the Poughkeepsie Galleria.
</P>
<P>
   Karl S. Coplan, co-director of the Pace Environmental Law Clinic
in White Plains, brought five suits against Pyramid. Copland, who
lives in West Nyack and in good weather kayaks across the Hudson
River and then bicycles to work, became involved in 1996 when
Pyramid announced its plan to expand from 1.85 million square feet
to more than 3 million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   The developer prevailed in all five of Coplan's suits.
</P>
<P>
   The final blow to the opponents came when Pyramid, without
approval from the Clarkstown Planning Board or Town Board went
ahead with plans to build 3 million square feet rather than the
1.85 million that officials had approved. The only approval Pyramid
obtained for the larger structure was from the town building
inspector, Aldoph Milich.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the additional space remains empty, on floors above Lord
&AMP; Taylor and Filene's. A Supreme Court judge ruled, after the
building already was under construction, that the extra space could
be completed but not occupied. It is that empty space that the mall
opponents hope to stop from being filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see how they operate, you can understand why no one
in town believes a word they say,'' said Coplan.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Lasker, the founder of the Rockland Civic Association,
decided that the only way to fight the expansion of the mall, and
what she sees as the overdevelopment of Rockland County, was to run
for the Clarkstown Town Board. She ran in 1997 and lost in a close
election.
</P>
<P>
   She is gearing up for another race this November.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I loved, what I came here for, the parkland, the open
space, is nearly gone to overdevelopment,'' said Ms. Lasker, 48,
who teaches disabled children and has lived in West Nyack for 17
years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lasker, like Ms. Rauer and other devoted members of the
Rockland Civic Association, don't patronize the mall. Coplan,
however, has had to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your son is invited to a skating party at the ice rink,
you can't very well tell him that it's the Death Star and you just
can't go,'' Coplan said. ``I went, but I didn't enjoy it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
