<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-JAPANESE-GARDEN-AR     02-20 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JAPANESE-GARDEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING THE RIGHT TOUCH FOR `A LITTLE PIECE OF JAPAN' IN BROOKLYN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Japanese Hill-and-Pond Garden _ with its antique
lanterns, cherry and pine trees, shrubs and flowers and waterfalls
_ has been the esthetic heart of Brooklyn since its opening as the
centerpiece of the Brooklyn Botanic Garden in 1915. It is
breathtakingly colorful in the spring and sublimely austere in the
snow, and attracts Brooklynites and tourists from near and far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little piece of Japan transplanted to Brooklyn,'' said
Eugene Himmelstein, who lives in the nearby Flatbush neighborhood
and visits the garden frequently.
</P>
<P>
   But gardens, which face the incessant effects of rainfall,
drought and the inevitable death of plants, are disturbingly
impermanent. The Japanese Garden has been falling apart, and the
Botanic Garden has begun an intensive program to save it.
</P>
<P>
   Because the garden is so beloved, however, its admirers fret
about any change. People worry that trees will be needlessly cut
down; that animals living in the pool _ including a giant snapping
turtle named Godzilla _ will be harmed, and that the intentions of
the garden's designer, Takeo Shiota, will be obliterated because no
Japanese-trained horticulturalists are involved in the restoration.
For the garden's first quarter-century, almost all the gardeners
were Japanese. No plans for the Japanese Garden have been found,
and it is not even clear if Shiota drew any.
</P>
<P>
   ``The garden needs to have the hand of someone trained in Japan
to certify the authenticity of the change,'' said Victoria Ehrlich,
a member of the garden's auxiliary who works in the garden one day
a week as a volunteer. ``Being about right or 99 percent right
isn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ehrlich, whose adherence to Zen Buddhism influences her own
esthetic sensibility, pointed out that as in calligraphy, painting,
flower arrangement and other branches of Japanese art, formal
gardens follow specific formulas.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Zuk, the garden's president, insists that the current
work will be largely invisible after it is finished, and that
Japanese experts will be called in if something unexpected comes
up.
</P>
<P>
   The design is being done by Vollmer Associates, landscape
architects, because of the firm's experience remodeling the Turtle
Pond in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zuk is concerned enough about fears that the garden's
character will be marred that she had a long meeting with Ms.
Ehrlich to answer her questions. She also met with Jane Gill, a
Brooklyn Heights resident who had written a letter wondering
whether Ms. Zuk was destroying the garden in order to save it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gill's worries were allayed. ``As happens with root canal,
I'll try to make it through the digging and construction phase,''
she wrote in a second letter. ``And I look forward to more springs
of Weeping Cherry blooms reflected in the pond.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zuk's case is simple: repairs are urgently needed, or the
Japanese Garden will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have now is a big mud puddle rather than a pond,'' she
said, explaining that erosion has turned what was originally a
five-foot-deep lake into two feet of water resting over three feet
of muck. Fully four feet of shoreline has been lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last five years, it's been an almost geometric
progression,'' she said. ``This is like the Mississippi Delta.''
</P>
<P>
   But erosion is not the only problem. The sad truth, Ms. Zuk
said, is that the four-acre garden has not been properly tended in
years.
</P>
<P>
   Some tree roots are exposed because of erosion. Young trees have
not replaced those that died. The lovely Japanese irises are gone.
The tree peonies are dangerously diminished. The azaleas are fading
from old age.
</P>
<P>
   The solution is to close the garden for six months beginning in
July. The pond will be drained, and the muck will be trucked away.
Eroded hillsides will be rebuilt, shorelines will be girdled to
hold them in place, the storm drain system will be upgraded. A new
fence will replace one that is falling down, and trees will be
planted to fill what Ms. Zuk calls ``gaps in the garden's teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost will be $3 million, with $2.5 million coming from
appropriations won by Brooklyn members of the City Council and the
remainder from the 1996 state environmental bond act.
</P>
<P>
   Repairing the Japanese Garden is one of a series of smaller jobs
at the Botanic Garden in the wake of opening a $25 million
conservatory, a new children's garden and a new administrative
building over the last decade. Other projects include redoing
paths, replanting the fragrance and herb gardens and fixing the
leaking Rose Arc Pool. ``Over the next decade we'll be looking at
all the garden features,'' Ms. Zuk said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Japanese Garden, perhaps the most popular place in
Brooklyn for wedding photographs, comes first.
</P>
<P>
   Walking around it, Ms. Zuk said to imagine four feet of the
shoreline filled in. There will again be double-blossom cherries on
both sides of the path. She pointed to the young Korean pines,
nestled among older Austrian pines, as an example of how the garden
should have been managed over the years. There are too many old
trees, she said, though she promised they will be propped up as
long as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Features will return that have been gone for generations,
including two statues of storks standing elegantly in the lake that
old photographs show. Lotus plants, a standard in Japanese gardens,
will again bloom, but this time they will be confined by underwater
wires to prevent them from taking over the pond as they once did.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of the koi _ the orange, white and black carp
species _ will return. So will many box turtles. But Ms. Zuk would
not promise that Godzilla would be back, although he would
definitely find an appropriate home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love him,'' she said. ``He's a nice old guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
