<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-ITALIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVETTI MAKES $60 BILLION BID FOR MAJOR RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story has been added to the front page.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ In a hostile move not unlike David's bold assault on
Goliath, Olivetti SpA, the midsized Italian computer and telephone
company, announced Saturday that it was opening an effort to
acquire the former Italian state telephone company, Telecom Italia
SpA, for 52.24 billion euros, about $60.56 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal moves ahead, it would be one of the largest
corporate acquisitions ever, intended to restore direction and
purpose to the former Italian state telephone monopoly, which has
been largely rudderless since it was privatized by the government
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government, which holds a ``golden share'' of 3.4
percent in Telecom Italia, could block the move at any time, and it
was unclear whether Olivetti had disclosed its plans to government
leaders before making its offer.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia, which is now owned by banks, pension funds and
the Agnelli family, is said to be mustering troops to defend
itself, considering a rival takeover bid by its own mobile
telephone subsidiary, Telecom Italia Mobile SpA, known as TIM, to
counter what it evidently viewed as a hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia, measured by market capitalization, is more than
five times the size of Olivetti, the 90-year-old former typewriter
company that nearly went bankrupt in the mid-1990s before
reinventing itself as an operator of phone systems.
</P>
<P>
   The bid appeared for the moment to set the stage for a dramatic
struggle for control of Telecom Italia, an unusual development in
the chummy world of corporate Italy, where deals are usually struck
quietly and announced only when they have been signed and sealed.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Olivetti said the bid would be mounted by its
computer subsidiary, Tecnost SpA, and would involve 5.26 billion
shares of common stock with a nominal value of 1,000 lire (0.51
euro, or 59 cents) each, representing all of Telecom Italia's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti officials published the bid in a filing to the Italian
stock-market regulatory body Consob.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia ranks as the world's sixth-largest phone company,
but it has undergone three changes in management in the last 18
months. Franco Bernabe, its present chairman, is a hard-nosed
executive who successfully ran the giant Italian oil group, ENI
SpA, before he was given the top job at Telecom Italia last year
and charged with putting it back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe, as was expected, did not take the attack lying down,
and managers at Telecom Italia said he had scheduled meetings
Saturday for the boards of Telecom Italia and TIM to consider a
rival takeover bid to counter Olivetti's move.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning appeared to be that TIM, which has been raking in
earnings thanks to Italy's vibrant mobile-phone market and which is
60.14 percent controlled by Telecom Italia, would use its resources
to raise the capital needed to defend the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Olivetti announced that its board would meet on
Sunday to review a ``strategic investment'' regarding Telecom
Italia. But the company apparently decided to jump the gun after
details of the planned offer became public.
</P>
<P>
   According to the terms of the bid that Olivetti announced
Saturday, Olivetti is expected to raise some $10 billion by selling
its telephone subsidiaries, Infostrada and Omnitel Pronto Italia,
to Mannesmann AG of Germany, its partner in those ventures. It said
it would obtain guarantees from Italian and foreign banks for the
remainder of the cash needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
