<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COLUMN-HIGHWAY-HAZARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. COLUMN: A RISKY MIX _ SMALL ROADS AND BIG RIGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST AMWELL, N.J. _ The interstate now begins at the end of
Barbara Gill's driveway, on what the maps still call County Road
179.
</P>
<P>
   At least it feels that way to Mrs. Gill. County Road 179 is no
more than two lanes wide, but it has become a lot scarier now that
caravans of semitrailer trucks are constantly growling through this
and other back roads and main streets of central New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   If one of those trucks is coming up behind Mrs. Gill when she is
getting ready to turn left into her driveway, she just keeps going,
down to the corner where the gas station used to be. Then she turns
around and goes back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no telling how good his brakes are, or if he even sees
us,'' Mrs. Gill said. ``We don't even try to turn.''
</P>
<P>
   For reasons ranging from highway construction to toll rates to
the online shopping phenomenon, New Jersey's familiar north-south
highway pattern is spreading east to west. People in little towns
like this have found that roads laid out for horses, and later for
drivers who drove slowly enough to wave, are now clogged with
tractor-trailers that come from far away and are headed for no
place near here.
</P>
<P>
   For someone accustomed to the whispering silence of county
roads, the sudden appearance of a semi with Texas plates bulking
over a hill can be as disorienting as encountering a locomotive on
a sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the business of the left turn has become such a
topic around here, where roads are too narrow to let an impatient
teamster muscle past on the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little trips, like going down 31 to the Pennington Market,
that used to be a piece of cake are just no fun at all anymore,''
said Andy Reid, a township committeeman for East Amwell, next door
to here. ``You're sitting there waiting to turn left with your
blinker on and your eyes on your rearview mirror and your heart in
your throat, and you're scared to death.''
</P>
<P>
   An elderly couple died last year when their car was rear-ended
by one truck and driven head-on into another as they waited to turn
left at the Amwell Diner on Highway 31. Two others have died on
that road in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   So when The Hunterdon County Democrat ran a letter not long ago
about the perils of left turns in the age of semis, its headline
was ``Pray for Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Reed, the mayor of Princeton Township, another
truck-clogged place, said he believed that the surge in semis was
due mostly to the completion of Interstate 287 through northern New
Jersey, which connected the highway with the Gov. Thomas E. Dewey
Thruway. Now trucks from the Philadelphia region can take a rural
road, like U.S. 206 through Princeton, to pick up I-287 in
Somerville and avoid tolls on the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   But adversity has made trucking experts of many these days, and
what Reed and others have discovered is that the very commercial
geography of New Jersey and its neighbors has shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was because of 287,'' the mayor said. But traffic
counts show that 25 percent of the trucks passing through this
region are from Easton, Bethlehem and Allentown in eastern
Pennsylvania, ``where government programs have helped turn all
those closed-down steel mills into distribution centers,'' Reed
said.
</P>
<P>
   And the enemy is also us, said Reid, the East Amwell
committeeman. ``Just-in-time stocking has really boosted trucking
exponentially,'' he said, ``and so has home shopping through
catalogs and online purchases, where the goods come directly to our
houses. So some of this is a problem of our own life styles.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Turnpike Authority has cut truck tolls at certain
hours to lure back some traffic, and Princeton, the Amwells and
other towns have lowered some speed limits. The state police have
stepped up truck checks on back roads and the use of portable
roadside weigh stations to keep big rigs legal, and perhaps to
nudge a few drivers back onto no-hassle interstates.
</P>
<P>
   But this is scant comfort to Marian Williamson, Mrs. Gill's
neighbor here. She, too, often has to drive out of her way to avoid
turning left into her driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here a long time,'' she said, ``and this is not
progress, I can tell you that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
