<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT &LR;      02-20 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORTGAGE REFINANCING STRATEGIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Homeowners thinking of refinancing their loans to
take advantage of the prevailing low interest rates, as well as
borrowers who simply want the lowest monthly payment possible,
should be aware of two potential strategies in the always complex
world of mortgages _ swapping ``jumbo'' loans for less costly
``conforming'' loans or, for shorter terms, making use of
adjustable-rate loans calculated by using a 40-year amortization
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say that the mortgage refinance market has pretty much
died,'' said Neil Bader, chief executive officer of Skyscraper
Mortgage, a Manhattan mortgage broker. ``But for many homeowners,
it can still make sense to refinance.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that a recent increase in the maximum loan amount
acceptable to Fannie Mae _ the nation's largest source of
residential mortgage funds _ may make refinancing attractive for
homeowners who, until now, have not had any real incentive to cash
in an old loan for a new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good time for homeowners to sit down and crunch the
numbers on their mortgage,'' Bader said, explaining that while it
might not have made sense for some homeowners to refinance as
little as two months ago, it might make sense to do so now. The
main reason, he said, is because of the increase in Fannie Mae's
limit on ``conforming loans'' _ loans that meet the company's
underwriting criteria.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Bader said, the maximum loan that Fannie Mae would
accept on a single-family home was $227,150. On Jan. 1, however,
the loan limit for such dwellings was increased to $240,000. Limits
on two-, three- and four-family dwellings increased
proportionately, Bader said, going from $290,650 to $307,100,
$351,300 to $371,200 and $436,600 to $461,350, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``These increases present a substantial savings opportunity for
homeowners who want to swap their jumbo mortgages for conforming
loans,'' Bader said. He explained that jumbo loans _ those that
exceed the Fannie Mae limit _ typically carry interest rates that
are .50 to .75 of a percentage point higher than conforming loans.
As a result, he said, any increase in the conforming-loan limit
means more homeowners are likely to benefit from refinancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in a position to cash in on the new limits are those
whose original loans have been paid down to within striking
distance of $240,000,'' Bader said. Thus, he added, it might even
make sense for such a homeowner to use any cash available to pay
down the existing mortgage enough to be able to refinance at
conforming-loan levels.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the difference between the cost of a jumbo loan
and a conforming loan Bader provided the following example:
</P>
<P>
   A $241,000 jumbo mortgage at 7.25 percent interest, he said,
would result in a monthly payment of $1,644. A $240,000 conforming
loan taken at the same point in time, however, would generally
carry an interest rate of 6.75 percent. That would result in a
monthly payment of $1,556 _ $88 less a month for just a $1,000
difference in the loan amount.
</P>
<P>
   Bader said that lower monthly payments alone don't always
justify refinancing. He noted that borrowers must also take into
consideration closing costs of the new loan and determine whether
the loan will be held long enough to recover those costs.
</P>
<P>
   Bader pointed out, however, that the interest rates used in the
above example reflect only the difference between jumbo and
conforming loans at the same point; those who are paying interest
rates on jumbo loans taken out several years ago _ rates that are
probably higher than prevailing rates for such loans today _ would
save even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This increase in the conforming loan limit hits right in the
breadbasket for borrowers in the New York area,'' Bader said,
explaining that the average loan made by his company last year was
around $252,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential benefit for some borrowers, Bader said, is the
increasing willingness of lenders to offer adjustable-rate loans
with payment schedules based on a 40-year amortization.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Gumbinger, vice president of HSH Associates, a mortgage
publishing company in Butler, N.J., said that such mortgages could
be useful for borrowers who want to pay the smallest monthly
payment possible for a relatively short number of years.
</P>
<P>
   Adjustable-rate mortgages, Gumbinger explained, carry initial
interest rates that are somewhat lower than fixed-rate loans. The
initial, lower rate, however, is subject to change after a fixed
period of time, usually from 1 to 10 years. And while monthly
payments are usually calculated on a 30-year payment schedule, such
loans generate the greatest savings when they are held for a short
period of time _ usually as long as the low initial rate lasts.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching the amortization period of the loan from 30 to 40
years lowers the monthly payment even further.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gumbinger said, the monthly payment on a $200,000
loan at 7 percent interest using a 30-year amortization schedule
would be $1,330. The same loan paid on a 40-year schedule, he said,
would cost $1,242 a month _ a savings of about $80 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The longer such a loan is kept, however, Gumbinger said, the
more it ends up costing in the long run. After just five years, for
example, the borrower in the above example would have paid $69,099
in interest and would owe a balance of $188,263 using a 30-year
payment schedule. Five years' worth of payments on a 40-year
payment plan, on the other hand, would result in the payment of
more money in interest _ $69,116 _ with a higher outstanding
balance of $194,545.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 40-year amortization loan is certainly an option if you want
to keep your out-of-pocket expenses down,'' Gumbinger said. ``But
keep in mind that it's only good for the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   But keeping a mortgage for the short term isn't necessarily good
for lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Oded Ben-Ami, senior loan officer for Sterling National Mortgage
in Great Neck, explained that investors who make mortgage money
available to lenders have traditionally earned a good portion of
their income by servicing loans they purchase from the lenders.
Because of the expectation that the service agreements would last
for seven years, investors have usually been willing to offer
no-point financing programs to their lenders, who then make them
available to borrowers. Points are fees, expressed as a percentage
of the amount borrowed; 1 point on a $200,000 loan would be $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the wave of refinancings in recent years has made servicing
loans a losing proposition because the loans are often exchanged
for a new loan before the servicing arrangement turns a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investors are now acting defensively,'' Ben-Ami said.
``They're realizing that they better collect some money up front or
these loans may not pay anything back at all.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, it is now becoming increasingly common for
investors to discourage lenders from offering ``zero-point''
mortgage programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely differences from lender to lender,''
Ben-Ami said. ``So it is now more important than ever to shop
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
