<HEADER>
A2793 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIANA-HOTEL-REAL-2T     02-20 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIANA-HOTEL-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIC INDIANA RESORT HOTEL IS FOR SALE AT $31 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT SHAROFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST BADEN SPRINGS, Ind. _ For sale: Architecturally stunning
turn of the century resort hotel on 710 acres in rustic downstate
Indiana. Guests included Diamond Jim Brady and Al Capone. No golf
course or swimming pool but abundant mineral springs. Partially
renovated. Price: $31 million or best offer.
</P>
<P>
   Any takers?
</P>
<P>
   William Cook, by most reckonings the richest man in Indiana, has
spent $31 million over the last two years renovating the historic
West Baden Springs Hotel in this fading resort town of 675 people
about an hour west of Louisville, Ky., and two hours south of
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Cook is the founder of Cook Group, a medical instrument
manufacturer in Bloomington, Ind. His personal fortune has been
estimated recently by Forbes magazine at more than $1 billion. Now
he and his partner in the project, the Historic Landmarks
Foundation of Indiana, are trying to sell the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that it won't be easy. ``It's a fantastic place
but it's in the middle of nowhere,'' he said. ``When I got involved
with it, I wasn't thinking dollars and cents. I wanted to save a
part of history.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, he has done so. But at the same time, he is
learning one of the great realities of the historic renovation
business _ that finding new uses for architecturally significant
historic buildings can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   No one says the hotel is not worth saving. When the West Baden
Springs Hotel opened in 1902, it was billed as the Carlsbad of
America and the eighth wonder of the world. Until the construction
of the Houston Astrodome in the mid-1960s, it had the world's
largest enclosed atrium and dome. The hotel's name (pronounced West
BAYden) alludes to Wiesbaden, the town in Germany that is
celebrated for its mineral springs, as is the former Carlsbad, now
known as Karlovy Vary, in what is now the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The building was designed by Harrison Albright, a West Virginia
architect who designed a number of hotels and public buildings. It
is generally acknowledged, however, that the idea for the atrium
came from the hotel's owner, Lee Sinclair, a banker turned hotelier
with a flair for hype and promotion.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier hotel on the site, also owned by Sinclair, burned in
1901. In planning its replacement, Sinclair was determined to trump
his neighbor down the road, the better known French Lick Springs
Hotel in French Lick.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, the towns of West Baden Springs and French Lick
were two of the most famous resort communities in the country.
Founded before the Civil War, they became famous because of the
innumerable mineral springs in the area, which were presumed to
have great medicinal value. An early advertisement for the West
Baden Springs Hotel claimed that drinking the sulphurous water that
gushed from several springs on the property would cure more than 50
health problems, including alcoholism, pimples and malaria.
</P>
<P>
   Later, with the onset of Prohibition, the emphasis switched from
curing alcoholism to encouraging illegal drinking. In the '20s the
area developed a raffish reputation as a haven for illegal drinking
and gambling. A character in the original 1927 production of the
musical ``Show Boat'' talked about winning ``a thousand at roulette
alone'' at French Lick. The line was later cut after the owner of
the French Lick Hotel protested.
</P>
<P>
   To say that the hotel dominates the town of West Baden Springs
is an understatement. Nothing else comes close. Visitors approach
the hotel by passing through a double arched entry gate off Route
56 in the middle of town and driving a quarter mile or so under an
overarching canopy of trees. In the distance are acres of
landscaped grounds and a number of architecturally distinctive
secondary buildings that once housed everything from stables to
bowling alleys.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the hotel comes into view _ an enormous, round
six-story building constructed of yellow brick with a scalloped
roof line and a wide veranda around the base. There are four
Moorish towers, two at each of two main entrances. And topping it
all off is a gigantic red tiled dome studded with skylights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building is unique _ there's eight acres under one roof
here,'' said George Ridgway, president of G.S. Ridgway and
Associates of Vincennes, Ind., the architecture firm overseeing the
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, said Ridgway, ``the guest rooms are almost secondary to
the building. They just happen to be around the atrium.'' The
atrium _ surrounded by two rings of rooms separated by a corridor _
is a stunner: 100 feet tall and 200 feet in diameter and ringed
with 24 enormous Ionic columns.
</P>
<P>
   The floor is marble terrazzo in an elaborate pattern. Many guest
rooms that surround the atrium have wrought-iron balconies that
provide dizzying views of the interior. The final effect is closer
to a Baroque church in Rome than a hotel in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The West Baden Springs Hotel went out of business in the
Depression and afterwards became first West Baden College, a Jesuit
seminary, and then an independent college, the Northwood Institute.
It has been vacant since 1983 and for a long time was tangled in a
complicated bankruptcy case.
</P>
<P>
   By 1991, the building had deteriorated to the point where a
section of the outside wall had collapsed and the building was
included on the National Trust for Historic Preservation's annual
list of the most endangered national landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The next year the Indiana Historic Landmarks Foundation spent
just over $200,000 to stabilize the building, and four years later
bought it outright for $250,000. ``We knew if we didn't do it, it
would just cave in,'' said Tina Connor, director of marketing for
the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Cook, who had been involved in a number of
historic renovation projects in Bloomington and other parts of the
state, offered to help. His agreement with the foundation is an
unusual one. ``There's nothing on paper,'' said Ms. Connor. The
foundation continues to own the building through a subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   But this did not stop Cook from embarking on an extensive
renovation effort that involved reinforcing the building and
restoring the public areas, beginning with the atrium. The project
was completed last fall and unveiled at a lavish benefit dinner
that attracted over a thousand people, including Indiana's Gov.
Frank O'Bannon and two former governors.
</P>
<P>
   According to Cook, the building is about half renovated. Still
to be done are the guest rooms and the ballroom. The hotel at one
time had more than 700 rooms with just one elevator (it now has
two), but many of the rooms were small and without bathrooms. Cook
said that after renovation there would be perhaps 260 rooms. He
noted, however, that work is being done on just one model suite on
one of the upper floors, pending determination of the building's
use.
</P>
<P>
   What that use might be is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, 14 different rail lines converged on the area and
travelers could choose from more than 20 hotels. Today the trains
are long gone and the only hotel still functioning as such is the
venerable French Lick Springs Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the things the area had going for it in the first part
of the century no longer apply,'' said Mark Siegel, assistant vice
president of finance at Duke Realty Investments, a real estate
investment trust in Indianapolis, who has looked at the property.
</P>
<P>
   There is also considerable uncertainty about how to market the
building. So far, no brokerage firm has been engaged. Marketing
efforts are being coordinated jointly by the Landmarks Foundation
and executives at Cook's company.
</P>
<P>
   Cook has fixed a possible price of $31 million on the property,
based on what he needs to recoup at least part of his investment,
but no one really knows what it is worth. ``We got into it thinking
that it possibly could be used as a back office for a corporation
or as a hotel or _ naively, I guess _ as a casino,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling does not appear to be an option at this point and many
real estate professionals think the outlook for the other two
possibilities is mixed at best.
</P>
<P>
   Cook is more optimistic but also sees what he is up against. ``I
got carried away by my passion for it,'' he said, explaining why he
got caught up in a cause in which he might have to take a loss.
``But selling it is another question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
