<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOFT-PIONEERS-REAL     02-20 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOFT-PIONEERS-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOFTY PRICES SEND LOFT PIONEERS IN SEARCH OF NEW FRONTIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jacques Roch sometimes has the sense that he is back
in the Paris of the late 1950s, once again living in a neighborhood
with slant-roofed garrets and bustling street life. But this is no
deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   Roch, ponytailed at 60, lives in a loft in Williamsburg,
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fourth-floor walkup _ ``The freight elevator, it is long
kaput,'' he says in a French-tinted lilt _ with pulleys still
bolted to the loft's century-old corrugated tin ceilings. Leaning
against the walls of the long-defunct factory stand 12-foot-high
paintings by Roch in what he describes as his ``comic-style, dark
humor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a man like me,'' he says of living in Williamsburg, ``it
has to do with Paris in the old days, a kind of nostalgic feeling
from when I was one of all the young artists in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Roch is one of hundreds, perhaps thousands, of artists,
craftspeople, art-scene followers and those simply searching for
the open space of loft living who have migrated across the East
River to old industrial neighborhoods like Williamsburg and
Greenpoint in Brooklyn, Long Island City and Astoria in Queens, and
the South Bronx _ squeezed out of lower Manhattan by a burgeoning
luxury loft market in which the average price is closing in on
$700,000.
</P>
<P>
   It is a frustrating development for the struggling artists who,
unlike the wealthy ones who can afford grand spaces, consider
themselves the loft pioneers. They are the ones, they point out,
who, with a wink from commercial landlords, slipped into desolate
downtown Manhattan factories and warehouses two and three decades
ago, built live-in studios by dint of their own hammering, sawing,
painting, plumbing and rewiring, and, over time, spurred the
creation of vibrant, attractive neighborhoods _ too attractive for
the good of those pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more and more uptown money is muscling into Soho, Noho,
Tribeca, Chelsea and Nolita (North of Little Italy). ``Downtown is
catching up to uptown prices, and we are no longer the cheaper
alternative,'' said Helene Luchnick, a senior vice president at the
Douglas Elliman brokerage who specializes in high-end lofts.
``We're getting more Upper East Side people purchasing downtown
because they like the space of the lofts, the downtown casualness,
the trendy restaurants, the name stores like Louis Vuitton and
Prada.''
</P>
<P>
   And even in less-fashionable areas, like the Lower East Side,
space can get costly when sets of up-and-coming professionals share
_ two pals from grade-school days, a college buddy of one and the
kid brother of the other pooling their resources to rent raw lofts
for $2,000 to $3,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three years, said Jonathan Miller, the president of
Miller Samuel, a leading Manhattan real-estate appraisal company,
there has been ``a significant upper progression'' in the average
purchase price of lofts below 34th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Basing his calculations on the sale of 774 co-op and condominium
lofts in the three-year period, Miller said that the average price
for a downtown loft was $404,645 in 1996 and $484,290 in 1997 _ an
18 percent increase. Then, ``as supply tightened in 1998,'' he
said, ``we saw a 28 percent increase, up to $693,754.'' The highest
price paid for a loft below 34th Street last year, Miller said, was
$4.5 million for a 6,000-square-foot expanse (1.25 NBA basketball
courts) on Wooster Street with an additional 3,000 square feet of
roof terrace.
</P>
<P>
   Avra Jane likes the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jane, who said she ``was a Wall Streeter'' for 14 years, is
now living in her third downtown loft _ 2,500 square feet in a
former fan factory, the Acorn Machinery Building on Lafayette
Street in Soho.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got the classic brick walls, the big windows, the steel
beams and pillars,'' she said. ``When I got here, it was raw, dark
and empty.''
</P>
<P>
   After paying $540,000 for the space in July 1997, Ms. Jane ``put
in another couple hundred thousand dollars,'' she said. ``I put
down wide-plank, white maple floors, mahogany frames on the
windows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On whatever walls I have,'' she said, ``I used an Italian
artist technique _ sandblast and plaster, then tint beeswax with
yellow, green or pink pigment, then rub it on. You want to run your
hands across them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jane has bought and renovated three lofts, ``sold them and
moved to the next,'' she said. And now she's becoming a full-time
loft developer _ along with one friend who is an architect and
another, a Wall Street trader who, she said, ``used to live uptown
on the park, Fifth Avenue, but sold that to move downtown, like
most people, to get more space and light'' _ and profit.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling partnership is currently converting a building on
Laight Street in Tribeca into 31 units that are due to go on the
market in the spring of 2000 for $1 million and up, or between $400
and $450 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   That would seem in keeping with the current trajectory of
per-square-foot prices. In 1996, said Miller of Miller Samuel, the
average price per square foot of downtown loft space was $258. Two
years later, it was $390 _ a 51 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   But those are just averages. As Ms. Luchnick pointed out: ``Last
year, I sold a property in Soho for a record of $900 a square foot.
And so far this year I have two properties heading into contract,
one at over $900 a square foot, another at over $1,000.''
</P>
<P>
   In a less-dear district downtown, Anthony Borelli and Tom
Pfister, both 28, Brad Trent, 27, and Pfister's 26-year-old
brother, Mike, are renting.
</P>
<P>
   Borelli, an urban planner, and Tom Pfister, an architect, have
been buddies since grammar school in Cambridge, Mass. A year and a
half ago they began looking for a two-bedroom to share. ``We looked
uptown near Columbia,'' Borelli said, ``all over downtown. What we
found was small and too expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   About that time, Trent, also an architect, was moving out of his
childhood home in Midwood, Brooklyn. And soon after, Mike Pfister,
currently a bartender but with ears open for a sound technician's
job, came to the big city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brad found a loft listed by Benjamin James,'' Borelli said,
referring to a downtown brokerage, ``2,200 square feet near the
Seaport'' _ the second floor of a warehouse, built in 1831, on
Front Street. It is not quite chic.
</P>
<P>
   There were ``semipermanent walls'' left up by a previous tenant,
Borelli said. ``Nothing matches; the stove clearly doesn't match
the countertops.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a fireplace that doesn't work, and a pool table left by
the previous tenant. And a safe, Borelli said, ``so heavy that it's
probably been there since the building was built; we had to cut the
rug around it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone's interested in cracking the safe, we'd oblige,''
Borelli said. ``Could be one of those disastrous `Geraldo
Rivera-Opens-Al Capone's-Safe' things.'' For now, there's a candle
on the safe.
</P>
<P>
   The young men pay $2,500 a month _ split proportionally
according to the size of their bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Between the influx of young out-of-towners, uptown transplants
and mounting competition for commercial space among law firms,
financial companies and the computer-driven ``new media'' industry,
there is little affordable room left for those loft pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original artist colony from downtown,'' said Sharon Zukin,
a professor of sociology at Brooklyn College, ``is now living in
lofts across the river and working for the `new media' operations
in their old lofts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all rather ironic,'' she said, ``that as non-artists
become active in cultural consumption, from looking at art in
museums and galleries to wanting to live `like artists,' the
consumer demand prices artists out of their lofts.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Zukin, who is author of ``Loft Living'' (Rutgers University
Press, 1989), a study of the phenomenon, wonders: ``Does somebody
who pays $2,000 to $3,000 a month live in luxury? That's the going
rent now. I'm amazed. I don't know who can pay this. This is the
real social problem of rising rents.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Schurr is a loft pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   A painter and photographer, Schurr lived in a loft in Tribeca in
the late 1970s, paying $450 a month in rent; then in another loft
in Long Island City, where he paid $800. And then, eight years ago,
he moved into a 7,000-square-foot space in an old fiber mill in
Greenpoint, Brooklyn, for which he now pays $2,100 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The artists who are still downtown are either very lucky to
have a longterm lease or are very well established _ that's my word
for rich,'' said Schurr, who is 43 and describes his art as a
paradoxical blend of ``abstract and representational.''
</P>
<P>
   Through his high windows, Schurr looks out at smokestacks, the
Pulaski Bridge, the Midtown Tunnel approach and the less than
pristine Newtown Creek. A ``romantic industrial landscape,'' he
calls it.
</P>
<P>
   The bay doors, loading docks and freight elevator in Schurr's
building _ for decades portals for bales of raw fiber, then
finished fabric _ now make it possible for at least 60 painters,
sculptors, lighting designers and cabinet makers to create and
transport their often ample works. One man there carved a menagerie
of phantasmagorical carousel creatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have projects I've worked on for years,'' Schurr said, ``so
storage and wall space are very important.''
</P>
<P>
   For such space, Suzy Kline, owner of Kline Realty on the
Greenpoint-Williamsburg border, would broker rental deals at $10 to
$20 a square foot a month _ would if she could.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary, I can't help them,'' she said of her loft clients.
</P>
<P>
   Checking her records, Ms. Kline said that in December and
January she had 114 loft customers, but her company managed to
place only five. ``I'm suffering what every real-estate broker is
suffering,'' she said, ``the shortage of housing stock in New
York.'' In January, Ms. Kline did manage to rent a
1,100-square-foot ground floor space in a Greenpoint loft building
for $1,550 a month, or $17 a square foot. ``That's pretty
typical,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're either Soho refugees or Soho wannabes,'' Ms. Kline
said of her clientele. ``We do get artists, sculptors, but also
computer whizzes, Wall Street brokers. Instead of a loft, we put
them in a storefront.''
</P>
<P>
   Such spaces, lofts as well as storefronts, are usually zoned for
commercial occupancy _ not residential. ``For the record, no one
lives here,'' Schurr said. And sprinkled throughout Greenpoint and
Williamsburg, large-letter signs have been bolted to buildings,
saying, ``A.I.R.'' (Artist in Residence) _ something akin to those
Tot-Finder decals affixed to home windows, directing fire fighters
to children in peril.
</P>
<P>
   The A.I.R. signs in Brooklyn are, in fact, unofficial, as
opposed to those found on some buildings in Soho and Noho where,
under a 1972 zoning change, residents must be artists certified by
the city's Department of Cultural Affairs _ who have been
classified as performing ``light manufacturing,'' and allowed to
set up living-work spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Dolgin, vice president of Kalmon Dolgin, a brokerage in
Greenpoint, has nothing but appreciation for the influx of Soho
refugees and wannabes. ``God bless them,'' Dolgin said, ``because
since the downturn in manufacturing in this area they have taken up
the surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Without them,'' he said, ``there would have been so much space
on the market that it would have sent many more owners into tax
arrears and possible foreclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dolgin said his company receives 30 to 40 inquiries for lofts a
week and places two or three. ``Now,'' he said, ``you're getting
Manhattan investors, looking to come into the area to buy property
for potential conversion. We get at least a dozen a week, but
everything has been gobbled up.''
</P>
<P>
   With a broker's inherent optimism, Dolgin envisions a shift in
his market. ``There are no condos or co-ops yet,'' he said, ``but
as rents increase and the city becomes more favorable to zoning
changes, condos and co-ops could develop in the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who rue the day. Scrawled on walls throughout
Williamsburg, and on storefronts where brokers have posted leaflets
with those tear-off phone number strips, is the message: ``Yuppies
Go Home!''
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers do tend to change the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   As Dolgin pointed out: ``They bring their boutiques,
restaurants, craftsy-type stores.'' There are now a dozen art
galleries in the neighborhood, and an underground movie house in a
mayonnaise factory, where a truck bay has been transformed into a
candle-lit reflecting pool.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hindy, president of the Brooklyn Brewery on North 11th
Street, producer of 27,000 barrels a year of Brooklyn Lager since
'89 _ 1989, that is _ has witnessed the change. ``I didn't know it
then,'' he said, ``but back when we were looking to build our
brewery, our competition was not industry, it was artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Hindy's brewery shares the old Hecla Ironworks complex with what
is now a residential building. ``It has a cast-iron facade,'' Hindy
said, ``and the lofts are dazzling. The roof has an outdoor garden
you wouldn't believe _ 6,000 to 8,000 square feet with fountains
and decks and lush shrubbery. There's a bed there; sometimes they
sleep up there in the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside a storefront on Bedford Avenue _ the artist
colony's Main Street _ Kimberly Reed says some degree of tension
exists between the newcomers and long-established Hispanic,
Hasidic, Italian and Polish residents living in small apartment
buildings, row houses and aluminum-sided, chain-link-fenced private
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrant communities are very stable,'' she said. ``They've
been here for generations, own their own homes and rent to one
another. So they aren't about to gentrify overnight or leave any
time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is some friction, she said, with the industrial
sector. In a hoped-to-be published book called ``Changing Spaces,''
Dr. Reed, a sociology professor at Queens College, has documented
how artists ``reconfigure their spaces and neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Reed lives in a converted industrial garage in Greenpoint,
cater-corner to a food distributorship where cargo bays are fed by
freight pallets hoisted on forklifts, and across from an old
packaging plant where a row of spindly trees has been planted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a sign that the building has been colonized by artists
or loft-livers,'' Dr. Reed said. ``They landscape so that there
will be shade in the summer.'' And also, she said, ``because in an
industrial area, 18-wheel trucks often pull up on the sidewalk; so
the trees restrict the sidewalk from being used to deliver goods.''
</P>
<P>
   There are far more significant tradeoffs that come with living
in an industrial area. As Eric Goldstein, senior lawyer for the
Natural Resources Defense Council, said: ``Greenpoint-Williamsburg
has received more than its fair share of environmental burdens.''
It has, Goldstein said, at least two dozen garbage transfer
stations that receive ``thousands of tons of waste a day from a
stream of diesel-spewing trucks.'' There are ``the 17 million
gallons from an underground Mobil oil spill back in the '70s'' that
are still being cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the huge Newtown Creek Sewage Plant sometimes send odors
wafting into the community,'' Goldstein said. ``Let's just say that
Williamsburg-Greenpoint is no environmental paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Dr. Reed points out, many artists have set those
concerns aside. ``Many art processes involve toxic materials _
kilns, forges, resins for mold-making,'' she said. ``They need a
live-work space where they aren't too concerned about the mess.''
</P>
<P>
   So, who is stenciling those ``Yuppie Go Home!'' signs around the
neighborhood? Hindy, for one, believes ``it's being done by artists
because they view what's happening here like what happened in
Soho.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, as Roch, the French expatriate, points out: ``Some
artists get a longterm lease, renovate, subdivide and sublet. So,
some artists are also entrepreneurs, and they are making money off
the backs of other artists.''
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
