<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGE GIRL AND BUILDING OWNER KILLED AT DRUG HOUSE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 14-year-old girl was one of two people killed by
gunfire on Friday night at a dilapidated brownstone in Brooklyn
known as a haven for crack cocaine users, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors had been complaining for months about drug users,
including teen-agers, frequenting the house in Bedford-Stuyvesant.
Everyone inside fled after the shootings, the police said, and they
have no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The other victim, and the apparent target of the gunman, was
Harry Carter, the owner of the brownstone. Carter, 49, was found
lying inside the front door of his apartment with a fatal gunshot
wound to the head, according to police. The girl, Marion Pittman,
had managed to run a few feet before being shot in the back, they
said, adding that she died shortly after arriving at Kings County
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers recovered a .40-caliber Smith &AMP; Wesson handgun
outside Carter's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager was from the Bronx, the police said, and it
remained unclear Saturday afternoon what had brought her to
Carter's apartment in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said Carter's mother had been a longtime neighbor, and
her son's trouble started after her death 18 months ago. In
despair, he turned to crack cocaine, according to his friend Joseph
Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised by this, but I'm saddened,'' Clarke said
Saturday, shaking his head in the quiet shadow of the two-story
brick building.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of that culture of drugs,'' he added. ``His
mother's death sent him over the edge, but it was his decision to
continue to do this. I wanted him to change his ways, but this is
the end result.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarke and other residents said they had made several calls to
police to complain about the activity in Carter's home and that the
police were a frequent presence on the street outside, although the
house remained open. Neighbors said school-age children could be
seen coming up his stairs most hours of the day, while the night
brought a caravan of other users to his door. At other times Carter
would try to get neighbors to move in and pay some rent. When he
saw Clarke walk by on Friday afternoon, he quickly asked for
repayment of a $5 loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to get me to move in, but I didn't want to be
involved,'' Clarke said. ``There were people coming in and out all
the time, young people who should have been in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I told him, `You can throw your life away, but not our
children's lives,' and I tried to convince him to go straight,'' he
said. ``This was the last time I saw him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
