<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HAWKINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. JAN HAWKINS, AN EXPERT   ON USING COMPUTERS IN SCHOOLS , DIES
AT 47 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Va. Ohio, Calif., Mich. )   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Jan Hawkins, a pioneer in the use of computers
and other technology in education, died Feb. 9 at New York
Presbyterian Hospital. She was 47 and lived in Cambridge, Mass.,
and in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was breast cancer, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the education faculty at Harvard University in
September, Hawkins established her reputation through her work as
director of the Center for Children and Technology, an agency
founded in 1981 by the Bank Street College of Education in New
York. Hawkins joined the group that year, long before computers had
become an integral part of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``She worked to find the mutual fit needed so technology could
work in an educational setting,'' said Dr. Howard Gardner, a
colleague of Dr. Hawkins' at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins was often called upon for help and advice by school
districts, museums and other educational institutions looking for
ways to integrate computers into their programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the one person that everyone went to,'' Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   In her first studies during the early 1980s, she showed that
children, especially girls, used computers in sociable and
collaborative ways, not in isolation as critics had feared, said
Dr. Margaret Honey, a longtime colleague of Hawkins' at the center.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Center for Children and Technology became a
division of the Education Development Center, based in Newton,
Mass. Dr. Hawkins became a vice president of that association,
which, like the Center for Children and Technology, is a nonprofit
research and development group financed by grants and contracts
with foundations and government institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Hawkins was born in New Canaan, Conn., and received her
bachelor's degree in psychology and English from Tufts University
in 1973. She received a master's degree in psychology and a
doctorate in developmental psychology from the Graduate Center of
the City University of New York in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   She belonged to numerous boards and advisory groups in her
field. She was an editor of professional journals and at Cambridge
University Press, dealing with its ``Learning by Doing'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hawkins is survived by her parents, John and Francette
Hawkins of Mountain View, Calif.; two sisters, Kim Hawkins of
Cleveland and Cynthia Rahilly of Manhattan; a brother, John Hawkins
of Virginia Beach, Va., and her fiance, Rand Spiro of East Lansing,
Mich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 1624EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-GIULIANI-6     02-20 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-GIULIANI-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK POLITICAL THEATER, UNDERSTUDIES WAIT IN THE WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Fla.)  (See also MRSCLINTON-NEWYORK and SENATE-DEMOCRATS) 
(jw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ For several weeks now, Hillary Rodham Clinton
and New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani have been starring in a shadow
play titled ``Senate 2000,'' garnering top billing in a race they
have yet to join officially.
</P>
<P>
   But while Giuliani and Mrs. Clinton coyly deflect questions
about their intentions, their would-be understudies _ Rep. Nita
Lowey and Rep. Rick Lazio _ are quietly campaigning in the wings,
positioning themselves to step into the bright lights should the
headliners fall from grace or off the political stage.
</P>
<P>
   And for that reason, both Ms. Lowey, a Democrat from
Westchester, and Lazio, a Republican from Suffolk County, were
crisscrossing upstate New York this month, meeting potential
contributors, road-testing their messages, gauging the support of
local kingmakers and trying to broaden their paper-thin name
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   With an ice-clogged Niagara River as a backdrop outside, Ms.
Lowey told a lunch crowd of Democrats at a Buffalo restaurant on
Friday that she could win a statewide campaign because her
district, which snakes from suburban Westchester into the Bronx and
Queens, is as diverse as the Empire State itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot of hard work to win my first race,'' she told
the group. ``Sounds a little like the Senate race. No one thought I
had a prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Being second fiddle in the race to replace Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, who plans to retire at the end of next year, carries its
own special burdens.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lowey and Lazio must constantly parry the skepticism of
local politicians and reporters who view them as dark horses. Each
will have trouble winning endorsements or expanding fund-raising
lists while Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani cast their long shadows over
the race.
</P>
<P>
   And both must endure a seemingly endless stream of news reports
that focus on the mayor, a Republican, and the first lady, a
Democrat, while mentioning Ms. Lowey and Lazio in buried paragraphs
that inevitably begin, ``The other potential candidates are . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ms. Lowey and Lazio, as well as many political analysts,
contend that being the unnoticed understudies has potential
benefits at this early stage. The mere possibility of Giuliani's
and Mrs. Clinton's entering the race has discouraged others from
joining the fray, increasing the likelihood that Lazio and Ms.
Lowey will emerge as the presumptive front-runners if the
headliners choose not to run.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the intense media focus on Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani
has allowed Ms. Lowey and Lazio to work on their own campaigns in
relative peace, suffering fewer distractions from intrusive camera
crews and badgering reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stressless,'' Lazio said in Syracuse on Wednesday. ``I
think it makes it comfortable for me to move around, to ask
questions, for people to be honest with me.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be an added benefit for Ms. Lowey, her supporters say.
She has praised Mrs. Clinton as the party's strongest candidate and
said she would drop out if the first lady decided to get in. By
displaying such loyalty, Ms. Lowey could grab the support of Mrs.
Clinton's fans should the first lady skip the race. And polls
indicate that those fans are legion in New York State.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lowey, who has spoken with the first lady several times in
recent weeks, said Mrs. Clinton has promised to back Ms. Lowey if
she does not run herself. Mrs. Clinton has said she is ``carefully
considering'' the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be second to Hillary Clinton is an honor,'' Ms. Lowey said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, on the other hand, has said he is prepared to challenge
Giuliani in a primary.
</P>
<P>
   Though he would be considered the underdog, Lazio has support
among the conservatives who usually dominate Republican primaries.
Though each is widely considered a moderate, Lazio runs with the
backing of the Conservative Party in his district and voted for
impeachment _ which is likely to endear him to primary voters _
while Giuliani loudly opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he had heard Republicans in northern New York express
concerns about having two senators from New York City. (Sen.
Charles Schumer, a Democrat, is from Brooklyn). Like many
Democrats, he also raised questions about whether Giuliani's
iron-fisted governing style would work in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people like about him as a mayor may not be what they
want in a senator,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Lazio and Ms. Lowey say they have not decided
whether to enter the race. Ms. Lowey says she expects the Democrats
to retake the House in 2000, which would give her a senior position
on the powerful Appropriations Committee. Lazio holds a leadership
position now, assistant majority leader. And both say they are not
thrilled about having to raise $15 million or more for the Senate
race.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews, the two representatives said they were
leaning strongly toward running. And both sounded very much like
candidates on their recent upstate tours. (Both declined to talk
about what it would be like to run against each other).
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, a boyish-looking 40, seemed in full-scale campaign mode
last week, when Congress was in recess, as he drove his wife,
Patricia, and their two daughters, Molly Ann, 6 and Kelsey, 5, from
Buffalo across the state to Long Island. Between speeches, a
hearing on housing issues and meetings with local Republicans,
Lazio sandwiched in family visits to Niagara Falls and other
upstate attractions.
</P>
<P>
   At each of his stops, Lazio delivered a message that illustrated
his efforts to balance between the party's dominant conservative
wing and its Northeastern moderates. He emphasized what he
considered traditional Republican values _ hard work, personal
responsibility and strong families _ but also endorsed an array of
traditionally Democratic policies, like health insurance for the
poor, federal spending on public education and the arts, and strong
environmental regulations. He also supports abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Americans don't clearly know what the Republican
Party stands for,'' he said in an interview in the lobby of the
Hotel Syracuse. ``I'm saying government is not the enemy. We can
talk about the end of big government, but we should also talk of
the beginning of the era of good government. Which means some of
these programs that we are getting value from, we should be
supporting.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, in his fourth term, is a lawyer and former county
prosecutor who, at 34, defeated Rep. Thomas Downey in 1992. Lazio's
youthful enthusiasm impressed John Long, the Republican chairman of
Niagara County. ``People up here would support a down-home person
like Rick,'' he said. Asked about Giuliani, Long replied, ``I think
he's perceived as being a little liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   But echoing a concern raised by other Republicans, Long
suggested that Lazio might not be strong enough to defeat Mrs.
Clinton. And several Republican officials said they wanted to avoid
a primary at all costs, which many think will involve encouraging
Lazio to drop out.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lazio, Ms. Lowey has tried to position herself as a
centrist within her party, advocating gay rights, abortion rights
and strong environmental policies on the liberal side, while siding
with Republicans on some welfare and trade policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people look at my record, they say, `She's a moderate
Democrat,' '' said Ms. Lowey, a former assistant secretary of state
under Gov. Mario Cuomo. Ms. Lowey is now in her sixth term. ``I
consider myself an independent progressive.''
</P>
<P>
   But in her speech in Buffalo, Ms. Lowey, 61, did not sound
particularly independent, outlining essentially the House
Democratic agenda: expanding federal aid for school construction
and after-school programs, making tuition tax-deductible and
increasing consumer protections in managed care policies.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the year, Ms. Lowey has traveled upstate
five times, as well as to California to meet with potential donors
and to Miami to address the national convention of the AFL-CIO,
where she was introduced as ``one of the two great women'' thinking
of running for the Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Many state Democratic leaders say Ms. Lowey is widely perceived
as the party's next best candidate after Mrs. Clinton. Steve
Pigeon, the Erie County Democratic chairman and a supporter of Ms.
Lowey, said many Democrats thought she could exploit the
Republicans' gender gap problems and negate their traditional
strength in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   He also contended that Ms. Lowey, a grandmother with a toothy
smile and easygoing manner, would provide a pleasant contrast to
the combative Giuliani. ``He's mean, he's scorched earth,'' Pigeon
said. ``In the Senate, you want somebody who will build bridges,
not burn them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Democrats privately fret that a Lowey-Giuliani race
could be a repeat of Gov. George Pataki's decisive victory over
City Council President Peter Vallone last year. But such concerns
were not evident among the party loyalists who gathered in Buffalo
to meet Ms. Lowey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giuliani has name recognition, no question,'' said Camille
Brandon, vice chairwoman of the Erie County Democratic Committee.
``So did Sen. D'Amato. And it didn't help him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
