<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-EDMONTON-270&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY RETURNS TO SCENE OF PAST GLORY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twenty years ago, before he joined the NHL, Wayne
Gretzky of the Rangers played with the Edmonton Oilers in the last
season of the World Hockey Association.
</P>
<P>
   His 43 goals with Edmonton that season, plus three with
Indianapolis early in that 1978-79 schedule, were the first 46 of a
total that has reached 1,071 in a 21-year professional career.
</P>
<P>
   The best of those years were with Edmonton, where he played on
teams that won the Stanley Cup four times from 1984 to 1988.
Gretzky's goal total includes the WHA and the NHL regular-season
games and playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   His figure equals that of Gordie Howe, who also played in both
leagues, from 1946 to 1980. Gretzky has eight goals this season,
none in his last six games and only one in his last 16.
</P>
<P>
   But a coincidence of scheduling could create a significant
moment in an appropriate place. Gretzky and the Rangers play at
Edmonton Sunday night in the first game of a two-game road trip to
Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Oilers' arena stands a statue of Gretzky, frozen in
time, holding the cup over his head. And he has done important
things there as a visitor. On Oct. 15, 1989, Gretzky set the NHL's
regular-season career point record of 1,850, breaking a Howe
record, while playing for the Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   A record-setting goal against the Oilers Sunday night would be a
highlight of what could be the final Edmonton appearance of his
career. Although Gretzky may return for another season next fall,
the unbalanced schedule for interconference games gives no
guarantee that the Rangers will visit all Western cities like
Edmonton.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  As for the Rangers, they would be satisfied with merely
another victory. By beating Pittsburgh, 6-1, on Friday night in
Madison Square Garden, they moved, at least temporarily, into 11th
place in the Eastern Conference, four points behind the Florida
Panthers, who hold the eighth and final playoff spot. Also
contending for that berth are Montreal, Washington and Boston. The
Panthers, Canadiens and Capitals played Saturday night. The Bruins
play Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting the Oilers, the Rangers move south in Alberta to
play at Calgary Monday night, ending a stretch of seven games in 11
nights. Both Western foes, the Oilers and the Flames, have records
comparable to the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Two or more points on the trip could leave the Rangers within
range of post-season play when they return home to begin their
final 24 games on Friday night against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in there,'' said John MacLean, who sparkled Friday
with three assists. ``It's a strange game, and that's how you have
to look at it. You never know. The opportunity is still there and
we will try to make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have won only five of their last 15 games, but they
have maintained a professional approach even in their worst skids.
</P>
<P>
   Ulf Samuelsson, who scored one of Friday's goals, said that
``there are an incredible amount of points'' still to be gained in
the standings and that ``it's too early to start panicking'' about
the possibility of missing the playoffs for the second consecutive
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to focus in and have a good trip,'' Samuelsson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Stevens scored twice for the Rangers against the Penguins,
who lost for the second straight time after a 10-game winning
streak. The other Ranger goals were scored by Richard Brennan, Petr
Nedved and Adam Graves.
</P>
<P>
   Playing well in goal was rookie Dan Cloutier, who lost his
shutout at 14 minutes 26 seconds of the third period, when Kevin
Hatcher scored for Pittsburgh. Cloutier played in all four games
last week, two of them starts and both starts victories.
</P>
<P>
   There is a possibility that he will start at least one of the
games in Alberta. Mike Richter, the first-string goalie, has been
pulled from his last two starts after giving up three early goals
each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing the puck pretty well, and I got lucky on a few,''
Cloutier said. ``I'm just thrilled to get a chance to play and gain
some experience. I have to take this opportunity to play well
because Mike is going to bounce back and play well for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As for playoff possibilities, Cloutier said: ``We're very
confident. We have a real close team here. There's a lot of games
left and a lot of things that could happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
