<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHN-GEORGETOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S ELUDES UPSET BY GEORGETOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The small St. John's contingent was saying bye-bye
to the departing Georgetown fans with a few seconds left in
Saturday's 74-66 Red Storm victory, a bit of bravado on behalf of a
team that had to scramble in the last minute to hold on to a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown has shown promise in the last few weeks and St.
John's got a preview of what could be one of the better Big East
teams next season.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied with 1 minute 44 seconds to go, before St.
John's hit four consecutive free throws. Lavor Postell, who had a
magnificent day with 18 points and 15 rebounds, grabbed a crucial
rebound of a missed jumper by Trey Kilpatrick, was fouled and sank
the two free throws that had eased St. John's back to safety with a
four-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   When Bootsy Thornton, who scored only two points in the second
half, stripped Georgetown's Kevin Braswell of the ball, and Erick
Barkley finished with a layup, St. John's was back up by six, a
lead large enough to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   In the teams' first meeting in January, Georgetown dominated the
inside game as Tyrone Grant was limited to 11 minutes because of
his wrist injury. This time, St. John's had Grant back but the
Hoyas, glimpses of its bruising past resurfacing, still manhandled
the Red Storm in the paint early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Grant had a superb flurry early in the second half when St.
John's desperately needed it. Georgetown had moved ahead by 35-34
when Anthony Perry fouled Barkley and Barkley responded with an
elbow to Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was hit with a technical foul for unsportsmanlike
conduct at 17:38 and Braswell hit the two free throws to give
Georgetown its first lead since 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Grant then took over, scoring six points in 40 seconds and
adding a steal. St. John's was back in front, 40-35, as the Hoyas
went scoreless for more than three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgetown kept banging St. John's. When Jameel Watkins went
for a rebound, he was called for a foul with 11:15 left to play and
St. John's leading by seven. Georgetown coach Craig Esherick argued
the call and was charged with a technical.
</P>
<P>
   But Albert Richardson missed the front end of the one-and-one,
and Barkley made just one of the two free throws and St. John's
squandered a chance to get four points at the line.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's was struggling and it only got worse. Barkley picked
up his fourth foul with 7:04 left and Georgetown was down by one
with five minutes left when Ruben Boumtje-Boumtje hit a baby jumper
to make the score 56-55.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 1646EST &QL; 
