<HEADER>
A2816 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-MIAMI-275&AMP;A     02-20 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-MIAMI-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI, DOWN 14 POINTS, UPSETS UCONN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Moments after the game ended, Miami's players
were hugging each other in celebration at midcourt. Connecticut's
players were walking to their locker room dejectedly, forced to
digest their second loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming a 14-point first-half deficit, and holding off a late
rally by Connecticut, Miami kept its poise and escaped with a
thrilling 73-71 victory this afternoon at Gampel Pavilion. The
victory improved the Hurricanes' record to 19-5, and continued one
of the best basketball seasons in Miami's history. The Huskies are
23-2, but they lost a chance to clinch at least a share of the Big
East regular season title.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was decided on Connecticut's final possession.
Trailing by two points, the Huskies called time out with 17.4
seconds to play, but they failed to convert a game-tying basket.
</P>
<P>
   With five seconds to play, Richard Hamilton passed to Khalid
El-Amin, who was forced into an off-balance 17-foot jumper over the
tough defense of John Salmons. El-Amin's shot was an air ball, and
the horn sounded as the two teams scrambled for possession of the
rebound, giving the Hurricanes their first win ever at Connecticut
in seven attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Both Miami and St. John's are now 13-3 in the Big East, one game
behind Connecticut (14-2), with two games remaining. The Huskies
who entered the game ranked No. 2 in the Associated Press poll,
will be forced to regroup before Monday's game at Providence. With
Miami leading 73-71, Jennings missed a 14-foot jumper in the lane
with 31 seconds to play, giving Connecticut a chance to tie. The
Huskies brought the ball to the front court and called timeout with
17.4 seconds left, setting up the final sequence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A stunning 8-0 run by Connecticut tied the game at 71-71 with
two minutes left. With Miami leading, 71-63, Hamilton made a
3-pointer from the right corner to make the score 71-66. Then after
a steal by Ricky Moore, Hamilton made one of two free throws to
pull the Huskies to within 71-67 with 3:35 left.
</P>
<P>
   Then after Tim James missed badly on a 14-foot baseline jumper,
Kevin Freeman scored on a driving bank shot, shaving Miami's lead
to 71-69, and the crowd was in a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the basket looked smaller to the Hurricanes, and after
James missed another jumper, the Huskies made the type of poised
play that quality teams make. Jake Voskuhl made a beautiful
back-door cut away from the ball, and Moore fed Voskuhl for an
uncontested dunk, tying the score, and forcing a Miami timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Hemsley of Miami missed a jumper from the top of the key
when play resumed, but James rebounded and was fouled by El-Amin.
James made both foul shots with 1:40 left to put Miami ahead,
73-71. Connecticut went to Hamilton, its leading scorer, but he
missed a jumper from the top of the key. James rebounded for the
Hurricanes, who called timeout with 53.7 seconds left to set up the
final sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Mounting an impressive comeback on the road against a quality
team, Miami opened the second half with a 15-2 run to take a 50-45
lead with 16:47 left to play. The Hurricanes were getting solid
play from three starters _ James, Hemsley and Mario Bland, making
it difficult for Connecticut's man-to-man defense to key on any one
player. Miami was not intimidated by Connecticut's impressive
record or by the hostile atmosphere, and it became clear that this
game would not be won easily by either team.
</P>
<P>
   As the game's momentum changed, the Huskies became more
frustrated. Jim Calhoun, Connecticut's coach, received a technical
foul during Miami's 15-2 run, and Calhoun angrily removed his
jacket in disgust. The play was intense and physical, and if
Calhoun was looking for a tough game to prepare his team for the
coming postseason, this was it.
</P>
<P>
   After Connecticut led by as many as 14 points, Miami regained
its composure and pulled to within 41-35 at halftime. But for the
first eight minutes, it looked as if Connecticut might win in a
rout.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Huskies' final home game of the season, which was
particularly emotional for their seniors, who were playing their
final game on campus. After pre-game ceremonies to honor the senior
class and their families, the Huskies roared to a quick 18-8 lead.
While Connecticut looked quick and intense, Miami looked shaky and
sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   Once Miami finally settled down, the Hurricanes looked more like
the solid team that barely lost, 70-68, in overtime when these two
teams met last month in Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
