<HEADER>
A2823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CLEMENS-DAY-750&AMP;A     02-20 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-DAY-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS SWITCHES ALLEGIANCE AND GETS DOWN TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Originally skedded as BBA-YANKEES) 
(lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ After Roger Clemens was traded to the New York
Yankees two days ago, his sister wrote a poem for him about the
Yankees. He would not reveal the lines specifically, but they were
about tradition and pinstripes, about Clemens, about winning, and
it rang true to him.
</P>
<P>
   He became part of that tradition and wore pinstripes in his
first workout with the Yankees Saturday, when he attracted as many
reporters, photographers and camera operators as any rock star.
Shortly after Yankees General Manager Brian Cashman met him at the
airport, Clemens chatted briefly with Manager Joe Torre and then
pulled on a Yankees cap and held up his No. 12 jersey at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a second chance to be part of the Yankees, I'm very
thrilled,'' said Clemens, who had turned down an opportunity to
sign with the Yankees as a free agent after the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens _ sporting a slight goatee that will come off to meet
the dress code of the Yankees' principal owner, George Steinbrenner
_ smiled a lot and stated repeatedly how excited he was to have a
chance to win a championship, how that is what drives him now.
Clemens has warred with the Yankees for years, but he wants all
that to be forgotten, in this new challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to continue to punish my body and do everything I
can to continue to be a power pitcher,'' he said. ``I definitely
met my match with Steinbrenner when it comes to winning. He's not
satisfied with last year.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Clemens hit Derek Jeter and Scott Brosius with pitches,
in two beanball incidents, but Clemens brushed that history off.
``The same guys you want to knock down are the same guys you want
on your side sometimes,'' Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   When pitching with Boston and Toronto, Clemens would run after
games outside the ball parks, but he smiled when asked if he would
continue that tradition in the Bronx. ``I don't know if I'll be
going too far outside there,'' he said. ``I'll have to ask Joe, and
maybe he'll have some insight on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre met with Clemens for about 10 minutes and, Torre said
later, he was taken by the mass of the man, his oak-tree legs and
Sherman tank chest, the shoulders and arms that could pass for
bucket loaders. Clemens began his spring training regimen two days
after the other Yankees, but one look and there was no doubt: He is
in extraordinary physical condition. This is one reason Yankees
officials prefer him to David Wells, whom they traded to Toronto
with reliever Graeme Lloyd and infielder Homer Bush for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens dressed in his uniform and played catch briefly with Mel
Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, before heading to the
bullpen for his first throwing session with his new team. Catcher
Joe Girardi met Clemens near the gate to welcome him, and Clemens
swung an arm out and gripped Girardi's hand.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen here is at the end of the stands down the
right-field line, and as Clemens strolled to the second of five
bullpen mounds, fans were lined up three and four deep in the
stands. It could have been a theater, the bullpen a stage. Clemens
set forth on the rubber. The first of his 59 warm-up pitches popped
loudly in Girardi's glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, Roger,'' somebody yelled.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this informal 13-minute workout, everything about how
Clemens threw was precise, and this is always the case. He would
hold both hands in front of his face as he stared in at Girardi's
mitt, over the webbing of his own glove. He would begin his motion,
plant his back leg _ the right leg, for the right-handed pitcher _
and drive off that leg, his left foot moving in a straight line at
Girardi, his hand cocking the ball and then whipping forward,
catapulting the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is careful with his mechanics, and if anything seemed
out of place on a particular pitch, he would quickly mimic the
motion of what should have happened: he should have extended his
arm more, he should have followed through, or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   He would wipe his face and touch the back and bill of his cap
before each delivery. Torre and Stottlemyre stood nearby and
watched, mostly in silence. But then, what was there to say? This
is Roger Clemens, the Rocket. Yankee pitchers have won four Cy
Young Awards over the years; Clemens has won five himself.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens finished the workout, stepped forward and shook hands
with Girardi again, and some in the crowd clapped and called his
name. ``Good luck, Roger!'' another yelled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His hair glistening wet and his cap darkened at the brim from
the sweat, Clemens moved down the stands along the right-field
line, a uniformed Hillsborough County sheriff at his side. Fans
scurried and jumped over seats and pushed forward, extending
baseballs and pictures and pens, yelling for him to sign. Jammed
together, several crashed through a gate and tumbled forward to the
dirt at Clemens' feet. The pitcher stepped back, glanced down to
see if they were all right, and then continued signing.
</P>
<P>
   The scene could be the same in Yankee Stadium in two months,
when Clemens is there in pinstripes, an enemy no longer. Wells
pitched a perfect game and got the keys to the city; if Clemens
meets expectations, if he wins 20 to 25 games, challenges for the
Cy Young Award and leads the Yankees to another championship, he
may get the deed.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those close to Clemens, 36, have told him that this is a
perfect way to end his career, with an organization steeped in
tradition and with annual expectations for championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants that ring,'' his agent, Randy Hendricks, said. ``He
lusts after that ring. It's a big missing part of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's his destiny. He has earned the right to be part
of a legendary team.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officials familiar with Clemens believe that, if all goes
according to plan, he can work out a contract extension within the
next two months that will allow him to end his career with the
Yankees. When asked if he believes Clemens will finish his career
in pinstripes, Hendricks said, ``It's more likely than not.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clemens: ``I've got a team of All-Stars behind me. When I
take the mound, it'll be exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry, attempting a comeback from colon cancer, took
batting practice Saturday for the first time since his surgery and
reported that all went well. ``I'm kind of surprised I'm swinging
the bat as well as I did at this early stage,'' said Strawberry,
among four outfielders who will compete for playing time in left
field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
