<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PITCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON, DOTEL FACE TOUGH ROAD TRYING TO BREAK INTO METS' PITCHING
STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Va.)  (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ The crowd came out Saturday to see Mike
Piazza, who is finally and firmly entrenched as the Mets' catcher.
But beyond the spotlight on the first official workout for pitchers
and catchers, two bright pitching prospects began trying to get
some attention.
</P>
<P>
   It is a difficult task for Paul Wilson and Octavio Dotel,
though. The staff that Piazza will be catching this season is all
but set.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter, Rick Reed, Bobby Jones, Masato Yoshii and Hideo Nomo
are the starters. John Franco, Armando Benitez, Dennis Cook, Turk
Wendell, Greg McMichael and Allen Watson are the relievers, with
Watson _ whose contract is guaranteed _ figuring as a spot starter.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine said one of those 11 pitchers could
conceivably lose his job, but that does not give much hope to
Wilson and Dotel.
</P>
<P>
   A third perennial prospect, Jason Isringhausen, will begin the
year at Class AAA Norfolk after missing all of last season while
recovering from elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Unless something extraordinary happens these next six weeks,
that is where Wilson and Dotel will be, too. Still, it might be up
to someone like Wilson or Dotel to inject a little life into the
pitching staff as the season wears on.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who will be 26 by the time the season starts, can be
excused if he is becoming a little impatient.
</P>
<P>
   The former No. 1 overall pick in the 1994 draft, who put in a
full season at the major league level in 1996, reported to camp the
strongest he has ever been. And yet, after throwing only 57 innings
split between Class A and Class AAA last season, Wilson _ who
missed most of 1997 after undergoing shoulder surgery _ knows he
will probably not begin the year with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at the point now where `just let me help,''' said Wilson,
who went 4-1 in seven starts for Norfolk with a 4.42 earned run
average last season. ``I know I can help. But I'm pretty much
resigned to my fate. There are six guys here with guaranteed
contracts, six guys here who are established. So where do I go?
What do I do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to go out and show them how far I've come and let
them make a decision. But just get me in the door. That's all I
want, my way back in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel is trying to get through that door for the first time.
After going 12-8 with a 2.84 earned run average at Class AA
Binghamton and Class AAA Norfolk, Dotel was brought up to the major
leagues in September, but he did not pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old is beginning his seventh season in the
organization and many feel that Dotel _ who was 5-0 with a 1.29 ERA
in the Dominican winter leagues this year _ has the potential to
become a star.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson compared Dotel to Pedro Martinez. Dotel is a tad bigger
than Martinez, but does resemble him. With a 90-plus-mile-an-hour
fastball, Dotel also throws nearly as hard as Martinez, but he
knows he needs to work on his changeup.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel also is likely to start the season at Norfolk, where he
tossed 99 innings last season. But, he said, ``If they give me the
opportunity, I'd like to show them here that I can throw.''
</P>
</TEXT>
