<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2826 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-BUSINESS-HNS &LR;      02-20 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-BUSINESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA INVASION BOOSTS JASPER BUSINESSES, 
BUT MANY RESIDENTS EAGER FOR HORDE TO GO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Okla.) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ There hasn't been anything like this to hit the
Belle-Jim Hotel since Mamie Patten built the place in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   Every noon the old wooden establishment's dining rooms are
flooded with hungry spectators from the courthouse across the
square. Others line up at the front desk to pick up orders of daily
specials like chicken pot pie or enchilada casserole to carry out
to the courthouse press room or to the satellite TV trucks that
line one side of the square.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the hungry television cameras roam the square,
looking for someone important to photograph. At the same time the
locals look out on the scene and wonder just what has become of
their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The circus has come to town,'' mused local real estate agent
John Matthews, who stepped from his office on the square with his
old dog, Domino, to survey the hubbub. He smiled as he looked at
all the photographers and reporters milling around, looking for
their piece of the action in the trial of John William ``Bill''
King, 24, a white supremacist on trial in the dragging death of a
black man.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews has seen the media ``circus'' before. It was here last
June when the dismembered body of James Byrd Jr., 49, was found a
few miles east of town. It was here again later when Ku Klux Klan
members came to rally on the courthouse steps and were met by
members of black militant groups.
</P>
<P>
   And he'll see it again, though probably on a smaller scale, when
two co-defendants are tried separately in Byrd's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just be glad when it's over and you can all go home,''
Matthews said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a common sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   David Stiles, who operates the Belle-Jim as a bed and breakfast
with his wife, Pat, said the trial has definitely affected his
regular business. ``A lot of our regular customers have stayed
away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, his crew has had to struggle with almost half again as
many noon lunch orders as usual to help feed the big crowds that
pour out of the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   This time of year is generally fairly quiet for the little bed
and breakfast in downtown Jasper, he said, but this time news
reporters have taken all eight bedrooms. Last week he had to open a
ninth bedroom to make room for a fisherman with a long-standing
reservation. The Swann Hotel, a block from the courthouse, is
filled as well.
</P>
<P>
   Full hotels aren't rare in Jasper. ``When we moved here nine
years ago, it was almost impossible to ever get a motel room,''
said Diane Domenech, director of the Chamber of Commerce. It's just
that they're usually full of visiting workers, businessmen and bass
fishermen, not reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Locals would rather Jasper be known for its fishing than as the
place where a terrible racial murder occurred, said James Shumake,
who runs a fishing tackle shop. He said most folks agree with a
former police chief who said, ``We'd like for you all to go home
now. And when y'all come back, come back to go fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishing is a $9 million-a-year business in Jasper, the
cornerstone of its tourism income. Only forest-related industries
have more impact on the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, members of the media have been made welcome in the
friendly town of 8,000 in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Most have found their way to local eateries like Texas
Charlie's, where Charlie and Nancy Nicholson are now accustomed to
being interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Twirling one end of a longhorn-style moustache, Charlie
Nicholson, 63, said Jasper residents tend to welcome strangers _
although he would never be considered a native, because he wasn't
born in the county and has operated a business there only since
1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will accept anybody,'' he said. ``They like for you to be
a bit of a rogue, to be able to tell a story, but they don't want
you to beat your wife or dog, they want you to pay your bills and
have some semblance of a church life.''
</P>
<P>
   As for being in the news, Jasper folks don't care for that. ``We
can read about it,'' Nicholson said. ``We do read the papers. We'd
just like to stay out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Nicholson said Byrd's slaying has caused many in Jasper to
rethink their racial attitudes. She had just joined the City
Council when the crime occurred. She said civic leaders _ black and
white _ quickly started meeting to see what needed to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Diggles, a black man who heads a multicounty council of
governments, said it was difficult for whites to understand how
deeply Byrd's death affected black residents. ``Something like this
brings back all that pain from the days of slavery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Mayor R.C. Horn, who is also black, has formed a
special task force to look into all facets of the town's racial
climate.
</P>
<P>
   That task force, Nancy Nicholson predicted, will help make
Jasper a much better place to live. ``You come back in 10 years,''
she said. ``We will see walls come tumbling down.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Nicholsons have gotten used to having news
reporters eating in their restaurant, nighttime business has fallen
off. ``It just seems like people aren't going out at night as much
as they used to,'' Charlie Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   Local motel operators said tourism seemed to drop off last
summer, especially after the Klan and black militant groups came to
town.
</P>
<P>
   But this week every room in town is filled _ and not just with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the big bass fishing tournaments hit town last week
just as testimony was starting in the trial. There will be a
different tournament almost every weekend through the spring,
summer and into next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd heard about it when it happened,'' said professional bass
fisherman Tom Biffle of Wagoner, Okla. He said fishermen on the
tournament circuit said to each other, ``Jasper? Can you believe
something like that happened in Jasper?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't believe it,'' he added, checking his boat
after parking it in front of his motel room within sight of where
police think the suspects picked up Byrd the night he was killed.
</P>
<P>
   He said he never considered not returning to Jasper for the Bass
Angler Sportsmen's Society's tournament. The top prize is $40,000
and points earned there can qualify fishermen for even
higher-paying contests.
</P>
<P>
   John Rogers, another tournament fisherman who came from New
Hampshire, said the trial doesn't concern him. His interests are
simpler: ``It's all about fishing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Rogers and 300 other fishermen zipped across the
114,500-acre Sam Rayburn Reservoir at speeds higher than would be
legal on the highways, each searching for wherever the
money-winning fat bass were hanging out.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back on the square, Beaumont musician Ricky Jason was
making a few bucks selling T-shirts with a portrait of James Byrd
Jr. on them, as well as CDs by his group, Colorblind, and caps that
said, ``Trial of the Century, Jasper, Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason said his group had the portrait of Byrd painted shortly
before the CD, ``Love, Peace and Harmony,'' was released. He said
10 percent of the sales of the disc will go to Byrd's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is real good,'' he said. ``We're going to be here
right through this trial, the next trial and the one after that.''
</P>
<P>
   While the world's view of Jasper was primarily formed by what
was going on in the 110-year-old courthouse, many of the pictures
the world was viewing went through the same place: the
film-developing machine at the one-hour photo lab in Jasper's
Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Many news photographers brought their film there to be processed
before scanning the images into computers for transmission around
the world. Autopsy photos and police pictures of the crime scene,
King's many tattoos and other case-related film also were processed
at the lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not proud of what we had to do, but we're proud they
(the photos) turned out well,'' said lab manager Charles Griffing.
</P>
<P>
   It's an attitude echoed all around Jasper by townspeople who are
dismayed by the murder that occurred there, but remain proud of
their town.
</P>
<P>
   They're ready for justice to be done at the courthouse and for
life to get back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
