A2836 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES21-CO     02-20 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers pleased with performance
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Mark Wohlers walked away from the mound
happy on Saturday morning, which was a welcome feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Just two days after facing live batters for the first time since
mid-August and looking as raw as ever, Wohlers came away from
Saturday's batting practice throwing session looking much more like
a man who might make this comeback.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't hit anybody. He didn't throw anything out of the
batting cage. He was hitting his target with his fastball, and the
pitches in the dirt came less often. Out of 30-plus pitches, seven
or eight were in the dirt as compared to double-digits on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day was kind of bad,'' Wohlers said. ``I was really
nervous out there. Yesterday got a little bit better. I'm not
saying I was consistent with my fastball, but I was more consistent
(today) than the previous day, which was good.''
</P>
<P>
   One big difference Wohlers found was when he bounced balls down
and away against right-handed hitters - he had hit Mike Mahoney
twice on Thursday, including once with a fastball - he could make
some mechanical adjustments to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first two days I was throwing 10 or 15 in a row whereas
today I'd throw one or two then make the adjustment,'' Wohlers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wohlers wasn't ready to go out and celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to have the approach that it was a good day but
you know what, I'm supposed to have good days,'' Wohlers said.
``I'm realistic (enough) to know there might be days when it looks
like I've never picked up a baseball before in my life, and I'm
prepared for that. I'm not going to drive myself crazy...
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the thing that's going to help me is having the
attitude that I don't give a damn, whereas deep down I care dearly.
That's my problem. I care too much. I'm self-critical. I care too
much about pleasing my teammates, fans watching in the stands,
people watching on TV. I don't allow myself room for error.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers joked that he was considering launching his first pitch
over the batting cage to start each workout in spring training to
entertain the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm able to laugh at it now,'' Wohlers said. ``I don't let it
get deep like it did last year. I'm trying to keep it on the
surface and say `Oh well, whatever happens happens.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moves on hold
</P>
<P>
   With the announcement of Brian Hunter's signing on Friday,
general manager John Schuerholz said Saturday for now he's not
looking to bring anybody else in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're satisfied with what we've got right now,'' Schuerholz
said. ``As we scout other teams and see what other teams have
available, that may change. But right now we're not going to go out
and sign anybody else or bring anybody else in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter first contacted the Braves through former dugout coach
Jim Beauchamp six weeks ago before the Braves had any openings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always like Brian's bat and his defense at first base,''
manager Bobby Cox said. ``He'll be a great late-inning guy if Ryan
Klesko is playing first base. We could platoon him.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez on the mend
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez spent another night in Osceola Regional Medical
Center Saturday night recovering from surgery to stop testicular
bleeding after he took a foul tip in the groin during batting
practice on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors predicted it would take Perez seven to 10 days to
recover, but the Braves don't expect Perez to be ready to get back
in there and catch for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can catch in even three weeks, it will be OK,'' Cox
said. ``The thing is he won't be able to do any running, lifting,
swinging, not much of anything right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marino golf tournament
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux and John Smoltz were given Cox's blessing to throw
early Saturday and leave and miss Sunday's workout so they could
play in Dan Marino's charity golf tournament Saturday and Sunday.
The event _ the First Plus Financial Celebrity Golf Invitational _
raises $300,000 each year for the Dan Marino Foundation which
donates money to a treatment facility for children with
neurological disorders. Marino's son Michael is mildly autistic.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other participants are Chris Chandler, John Elway,
Mario Lemieux, Troy Aikman, Emmitt Smith, and Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
