<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elie puts Spurs to San Antonio
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mario Elie made a living with Houston by beating the Spurs in
big games. Now that Elie is in San Antonio, he's dumping on
teammates who are notorious for their lack of emotion and fire.
</P>
<P>
   After the Spurs blew an 11-point fourth quarter lead to Phoenix,
Elie reminisced. ``We had guys (in Houston) who were warriors,'' he
said. ``(Coach) Rudy (Tomjanovich) didn't have to tell those guys
what to do. I'm tired of the attitude here, that we're the Spurs
and all we have to do is walk out and play. It's the guys'
demeanors, and I can't change that. They tell me it's been that way
here for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie didn't have to name anyone. The Spurs' front line of David
Robinson, Tim Duncan and Sean Elliott is notorious for being
laid-back.
</P>
<P>
   The Rodman watch
</P>
<P>
   He might be putting the best face on it, but Lakers exec Jerry
West is going crazy over the Dennis Rodman saga in L.A. At a recent
home game, he complained of not feeling well and went home early.
He talks about the situation to anyone who asks, telling friends
that he'll re-sign.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that wouldn't happen, even if owner Jerry Buss wanted
to bring in Darryl Dawkins. After all, West signed a new contract
for $3.5 million a year and he isn't going to leave that on the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant are feuding, and
Elden Campbell and Eddie Jones keep hearing that they're going to
Charlotte, while coach Del Harris swings in the wind on the final
year of his contract. Players talk behind his back like he's
history.
</P>
<P>
   A new streak
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Vin Baker said he wasn't going to make a big deal
about it when he finally made a free throw. But when he ended the
streak of misses at 18 Wednesday and got a standing ovation from
17,000, Baker was clearly relieved. ``I have to be honest: It was a
tremendous relief. I got the monkey off my back. I think I was
tremendously tense. But I have a long ways to go. It's a joke to be
one for 19 or whatever I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Try 1-for-20. He missed the next one.
</P>
<P>
   Ref's best friend?
</P>
<P>
   Terry Cummings has no use for Karl Malone. After the Utah
forward tuned up the Warriors with 35 points and 12 rebounds,
Cummings complained, ``The referees gave him every break. It ain't
like they let you play him. They let me play him. But when the
other guys (Jason Caffey and Adonal Foyle) were playing him, they
can't do anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Karl does is cry,'' Cummings said. ``I've never seen a
team go to the championship twice and cry and whine so much. And
they've been there and come home with nothing. That's why. You
can't cry in the championship. They don't do nothing there when you
cry.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, the Kings were complaining when referee Sean
Corbin called a foul against Chris Webber on Malone's 3-point try.
Malone made all three shots, tying a game Utah won in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Same ol' Nuggets
</P>
<P>
   Denver blew a 19-point lead to Phoenix and coach Mike D'Antoni
was so angry he kicked the bucket _ the Gatorade bucket _ and broke
a couple of toes. The Nuggets went to Portland and lost their
seventh in a row at the Rose Garden arena. The 15-point beating
dropped their average margin of defeat in that span to 27.6 points.
</P>
<P>
   Layups
</P>
<P>
   Malik Rose's landmark 22 points, nine rebounds in his hometown
of Philadelphia had no impact on his role with the Spurs. Two days
later, he did not leave the bench in Chicago. ... Mike Bibby still
won't forgive dad Henry for leaving his mother. When Vancouver
played in Los Angeles, the son did not leave tickets for his dad,
whose Southern Cal basketball team had the night off. ... Kevin
Garnett of Minnesota, on playing his last game in the L.A. Sports
Arena: ``I've had some memorable moments in here. But at the same
time, it would be nice to have some hot water in the showers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
