<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-CLEMENS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A BRIEF DRY SPELL, IT'S GOOD TO BE A YANKEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ When he isn't offering his persistent platitudes
toward the departed David Wells, George Steinbrenner is walking
with more of a swagger and talking with more bravado. The Yankees
shocked Wells and most of the baseball world by acquiring Roger
Clemens late Wednesday night, and Steinbrenner, despite his
feelings about Wells, is gleeful that the already attractive
Yankees are staying in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   It is good being affiliated with the Yankees these days. Very
good.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone used to hate the Yankees. But it is difficult to hate a
team led by a popular manager and populated by gracious players.
Everyone used to want to beat the Yankees. Now it seems that
everyone wants to be a Yankee. Who can blame them?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a pretty good job of people wanting to become
Yankees,'' Steinbrenner said. ``It hasn't always been this way, but
it has changed. I think guys aspire to be Yankees. I don't think
guys want to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Jeff Nelson agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once guys get to New York, this is a great place to play,''
Nelson said. ``It's not like it used to be or what some people
think. I love playing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who arrived at Legends Field Saturday, spurned the
Yankees once, but he did not let his second chance vanish. Two
years ago, Clemens ignored Steinbrenner's personal sales pitch and
signed a four-year contract with the Toronto Blue Jays. This time,
Clemens jumped into Yankeeland even though they declined to extend
his contract beyond the remaining two years and $16.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty fortunate,'' Clemens said earlier in the week of
his second chance to join the team.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had never expressed an undying love for the Yankees, but
after the trade was completed, he reminisced about how he discussed
the Yankees as a boy and claimed he wore the Yankee jacket and cap
that Steinbrenner had given him when he was wooed two years ago. If
it sounded as if the only five-time Cy Young Award winner in
baseball history was thrilled to be a Yankee, Clemens was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the tradition, I love it,'' Clemens said. ``I love
pitching at Yankee Stadium. The monuments and all the stuff that
goes with it, I love it. I'm excited about getting the opportunity
to go there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heady atmosphere these days, even Steinbrenner
conceded that it has not always been easy to persuade players to be
Yankees. Clemens did not want to join the team in his first
opportunity. Before the 1993 season, Greg Maddux opted for Atlanta
even though the Braves offered $5 million less than the Yankees,
and Barry Bonds signed with San Francisco even though the Yankees
were offering a similar contract to the one the Giants gave him.
Even David Cone declined an opportunity to sign with the Yankees
that season, calling them too disorganized. Instead he signed with
his hometown Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want any players who don't want to be in New York,''
Steinbrenner said at the time. The statement rang hollow since the
players had already said no, but now it the issue is moot.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill and Cone stayed with the Yankees for less than what
they likely could have received on the open market, and Bernie
Williams never really wanted to leave the team, although in the end
the $87.5 million contract he received made that a nonissue for
him.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Yankees appealing?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think guys want to be Yankees because we win,'' Nelson said.
``We've won it all in two of the last three years. The team doesn't
change and, if it does, it's to get someone like Clemens. If guys
have a chance to come here, they should.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There are more reasons than that, though. Torre is a player's
manager who has few rules, many friends and a superb success rate
in New York. Steinbrenner is no longer as vocal in his criticism of
players and has grown to be appreciated because he continues to
open his checkbook to keep the Yankees in contention for the World
Series. The owner also brings in former Yankees like Whitey Ford,
Rich Gossage, Ron Guidry, Mickey Rivers and Craig Nettles at his
own expense as instructors in the spring and keeps such former
players as Mel Stottlemyre, Willie Randolph and Chris Chambliss
employed as coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens conceded that Steinbrenner's will to be the best was
seductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met my match in a guy who wants to win,'' Clemens said.
``This guys settles for nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner is also thoughtful in how he treats his players.
The Yankees have a full-time masseur, two batting practice pitchers
and two trainers who travel with the team. They received an
upgraded weight room at the Stadium shortly after one player
mentioned that some equipment was below par, and the players even
have protein shakes waiting for them after each spring workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's because we do things first class,'' Steinbrenner
said. ``Joe has a way with his players, and I give him full credit
for that. I'm proud that people want to play on the Yankees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
