<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oakley is still firing at Knicks
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Oakley won't let his hostility for Knicks' management
go. He now maintains that a meeting with bosses Ernie Grunfeld and
Dave Checketts greased his exit to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just conversations and stuff we didn't agree on,''
Oakley said. ``I always would try to tell them the truth, but
that's not what they want to hear. With them, it's like playing
poker. You never want anyone to see all your cards. They're like a
guy standing around the table, and you figure maybe you would be
smart to hold down some of your cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might not have liked some of my comments to the press,''
Oakley said. ``We know it's all about making money; all of us are
about making money. But they try to make it into something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley added that the pressure to justify continually raising
the price of seats at Madison Square Garden has forced the team to
make bad decisions. ``Every year they have to make it look like
they're doing something _ trade somebody, make a move,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last four or five years, they made a move every year.
It made it hard to play together. With Pat Riley, we were together
for a while. The good teams around the league, like Indiana, have
kept their key pieces together. The Knicks trade away their main
pieces and then hope the new guys can catch on. It ain't easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Good-time Charlie
</P>
<P>
   When Toronto's Kevin Willis elbowed Knicks guard Charlie Ward,
he said he remembered how Ward took P.J. Brown's knee out two years
ago to ignite a Game 5 playoff brawl. ``It was the same type of
situation as Miami,'' Willis said. ``You just don't want to be in
that situation where a guy hits you like that and damages my knees
or puts me out for a game or, even more seriously, my career. ...
He was pushing down toward my knee or going at my knee.''
</P>
<P>
   Not-so-sweet Charlotte
</P>
<P>
   Dave Cowens could be replaced as Charlotte's coach the next few
days after complaining about money. Club president Bob Bass did not
offer a vote of confidence: ``The only thing I'll say about that is
that he's the coach at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowens confirmed a conversation with Bass: ``Yeah, he was upset.
He wanted to know why I said what I said. I just told him I
answered some questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowens, who led Charlotte to 54- and 51-victory season seasons,
is reportedly the lowest-paid coach in the NBA. His contract pays
$675,000 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Fakin' it?
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Brandon, accused of feigning injury and angling to get
out of Milwaukee, said, ``I was disappointed. No one really ever
asked me how I felt. I've always played hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of it came from the disappointment of me not
being on the court. But I tried to turn it around to the positive
and see that people maybe appreciated me being here and were
frustrated I couldn't play. And when I thought about it like that,
I felt pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   No special feet
</P>
<P>
   So, how smart was Wayne Embry in Cleveland to sign up Zydrunas
Ilgauskas for six years and $70.9 million? When the 7-foot-3
Lithuanian broke his left foot, it became the third season in four
he has missed with injuries to his feet.
</P>
<P>
   The injury also raised the question of what the Cavaliers will
do with Vitaly Potapenko. Unwilling to tie up more big money in the
middle, they were shopping him in tandem with Bobby Sura until the
Ilgauskas injury. Ilgauskas averaged 13.9 points and 8.8 rebounds
last season as a starter, Potapenko 7.1 and 3.9 off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
