 Develop the saving habit: Pay yourself first  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you ever feel as though your working life is a treadmill to
oblivion because the proceeds from your paycheck seem to belong to
everyone but you?
</P>
<P>
   Those trapped in the nightmare of living from paycheck to
paycheck know the frustration of sharing their income with everyone
except themselves. Sometimes there's a smidgen left to finance some
fun, sometimes not. If not, well, there's always the credit card,
but putting it on the cuff speeds up the treadmill by expanding the
claim on future paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a younger worker trapped in this situation, your
future is bleak unless you do something about it. Before you know
it, you wake up an older worker facing retirement with nothing to
sustain your post-working life except Social Security benefits and,
if you're lucky, a modest pension.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the question for those whose working life is an exercise
in futility is how to escape the trap. The solution, fortunately,
is as easily said as done: Pay yourself first.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Pay yourself first. With the MoneyWise Personal
Finance Fair scheduled to focus on such matters Friday and
Saturday, this is a good time to revisit this best money-management
strategy ever devised.
</P>
<P>
   The pay-yourself-first concept in this sense doesn't mean
setting aside mad money to blow on a good time. Rather, this
pay-yourself-first plan is designed to ensure that you get as much
long-term reward from your work as those to whom you write checks
each month. They're using your money to make money, so why
shouldn't you do the same?
</P>
<P>
   The whole point of embracing the pay-yourself-first concept is
building an asset base that gets your moneymaking some money. A job
with a regular paycheck is the foundation stone of financial
security, but progress toward financial independence can be
accelerated significantly by putting your money to work as well.
</P>
<P>
   If your resources are relatively meager, your starting point
might be as basic as putting a set amount from each paycheck into a
savings account until you accumulate enough to get into a mutual
fund or purchase a certificate of deposit with a higher interest
rate.
</P>
<P>
   The higher your income, of course, the more latitude you have.
You might think about getting into a mutual fund immediately and
initiating a systematic plan to make a substantial deposit once or
twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky enough to work for a company offering a 401(k)
plan, you're already far ahead of the game. Not only does the
company help ensure discipline by withholding your savings at the
source, but many employers sweeten your pot with a profit-sharing
contribution that partly matches yours.
</P>
<P>
   Don't despair, though, if no company saving-and-investment plan
is available. Look into the options available for establishing
individual retirement accounts, tax-advantaged and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Paying yourself first is about developing the saving habit.
</P>
<P>
   Many people don't save because they don't think they can afford
to put anything aside. In truth, they can't afford not to put
something aside for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not in the saving habit, your challenge is to convince
yourself that you have as much right to your money as anyone else.
Try it. You'll like it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
