<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-PRIVACY _ WASHINGTON _ ``You're kidding!'' my wife
exclaimed. I had just told her that someone had gained access to
our private bank records, lifted our account number and recorded
our balance. She listened in stunned silence. There was more. They
had also tracked our recent long-distance calls, identifying those
we had telephoned by name, address and occupation. And they had
compiled dossiers on us, complete with Social Security numbers,
property holdings and financial dealings. ``That's incredible,''
she said. ``How can they do that?'' Easily, it turns out, in the
computer age. (Alexander, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/ONLINE-SLEUTH _ WASHINGTON _ Many private detectives use
``pretexts'' to fool banks into releasing a customer's confidential
financial data. Al Schweitzer, an investigator who once pleaded
guilty to illegally obtaining Social Security numbers, told the
House Banking Committee last year how he used ``gags'' to get
information. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-LAWS _ WASHINGTON _ At first glance, a pending House bill
seems to be on the side of the angels: it would make it a federal
crime for anyone to fraudulently obtain information about your
account from a bank. But Dana LeJune, a Houston attorney, says that
in order to find where debtors are hiding their money, it is
sometimes necessary to trick banks into revealing if a deadbeat has
an account. (Jaspin, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: All MOVED Monday.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CUT _ WASHINGTON _ Prospects appear good for a federal tax
cut this year, but it may not be the 10 percent across-the-board
income tax cut favored by some congressional leaders. Instead,
Democrats and many Republicans appear to favor tax cuts targeted to
specific groups they find deserving, such as married couples or
families needing home health care. The sentiment is fueled by polls
showing few Americans favor the broader cuts. (Mollison, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-THEN&AMP;NOW _ WASHINGTON _ George W. Bush is a man who has
played opposite roles on the national scene. As the son of a
president under fire, he became the ardent and sometimes angry
defender of his father and the adviser deputized for the tough
jobs. Now as the popular Texas governor, he is seen as the cheerful
optimist. Who's the real George W.? (Malone/Herman, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-2000 _ Dick Gephardt wants to be speaker of the House come
Jan. 2001, and Democrats need a gain of just six seats in the next
election to make it happen. Two Georgia seats, held by Republicans
Saxby Chambliss and Charlie Norwood, are crucial to the Democrats'
quest. Gephardt, Patrick Kennedy, John Lewis and others will be in
Atlanta Monday to raise money for those and other campaigns. Of
course, Democrats were whistling the same tune two years ago, but
could not recruit top-flight challengers. They say 2000 will be
different. (Sherman, Cox News Service). Will move by 7 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   JONBENET-RAMSEY _ JonBenet Ramsey is back in the news as a newly
published books gives the most detailed theory yet of her death.
Next month, the grand jury might taking some definitive action.
(Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 20. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MARSHLAND _ HOUMA, La. _ Deep in Cajun country between New
Orleans and the Gulf of Mexico, a waterworld of marsh and swamp is
Michael St. Martin's ''2,400-acre hobby.'' He has roamed it since
he was a child, built his estate next to it in the 1980s, and
finally bought it in 1992. It looks pristine and almost
prehistoric: Alligator eyes poke out of the water every few
minutes, ducks fly overhead by the thousands, coots fly in black
masses and rest like carpets on the surface of the water, and huge
swamp rats called nutria dart between the hanging moss and the
gnarled trunks of cypress trees. Swamp maples are in bloom and look
like pink torches against the deep greens, grays and browns of
winter. And when St. Martin's found damage to that land, he sued
two oil companies that had leased drilling rights. The precedent
could lead to hundreds of other lawsuits and cost oil companies
millions to repair past damage. (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-KURDS _ ANKARA, Turkey _ Kurds climbing on roofs, taking
hostages, tussling with the police, setting themselves ablaze and
occupying embassies in a dozen countries across Europe this week
threw an unusually bright spotlight on this nation of people
without a state. Who are these people that have come blazing into
American living rooms the last few days? How can such a diaspora of
people be organized enough to mount simultaneous demonstrations in
different cities, yet factionalized enough not to agree on how to
go about building their own nation-state? What is the nature of
their relationship with the United States? Developing. (Holmes, Cox
News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ With its rough
democracy and market economy, Russia is often compared to the Wild
West. If so, reformer Galina Starovoitova was widely viewed as one
of the white hats. The St. Petersburg legislator was gunned down
last November in what appeared to be a political assassination.
Then, she was viewed by her allies as a respectable martyr whose
death would surely inspire some essential changes to Russia's
faulty experiment with democracy. But three months later, her death
is almost an after-thought. There are no dead martyrs in today's
Russia, just as there are no living heroes. That's unfortunate in a
country with a broken economy, and the election of a new parliament
and president scheduled to take place in the next 18 months.
(Holmes, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-ROYAL _ PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ Only a few monarchs left
in the world really matter. And not one has mattered for longer
than King Norodom Sihanouk, Cambodia's master of dramatic intrigue
for the last 58 years. In the 1940s, Sihanouk acted the playboy
king with scores of mistresses, the self-described ``randy
rabbit.'' In the fifties, he became the father of Cambodian
independence from France and the slippery Cold War neutralist. In
the sixties, he occupied himself as the absolute ruler who doubled
as a film maker. In the seventies, he became the figurehead of the
genocidal Khmer Rouge guerrillas and then the Khmer Rouge's gilded
prisoner. Twenty years ago, when Sihanouk was an exiled prince with
slim prospects of reclaiming his country, he was told by Henry
Kissinger that he was as good an actor as Lawrence Olivier. Now
Sihanouk is back on the throne, playing the most improbable role of
his checkered career. (Kunstel-Albright, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   w/CAMBODIA-BOX _ PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ These are among the
twists and turns in King Norodom Sihanouk's life.
(Albright-Kunstel, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   US-MEXICO _ WASHINGTON _ An analysis of the U.S.-Mexico
relationship following the high-level meeting in Merida, Mexico.
(Deans, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ An ABA task force report tries to wave Congress
off from the accelerating trend to boost every new fad crime into
the federal code. Sometimes even the self-evident needs a ramrod to
get through to the politically obtuse. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ ``Let me see if I can understand this,'' I
remarked to a colleague who had spent time with Kurds in northern
Iraq and Turkey in the days immediately after Desert Storm. ``We
are in daily combat with Iraqi defenses over no-fly zones that we
established for reasons that included protecting Kurds from Saddam
Hussein's attacks and now the Kurds are attacking the embassies of
our NATO allies and others because a Kurdish leader, who many
identify as a terrorist the like of Osama bin Laden, has been
jailed in Turkey, which Saddam Hussein now says may be targeted by
Iraqi missiles because our planes take off from Turkey and bomb
Iraqi defenses in the zones in which we are protecting Kurds.''
(Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVED
THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ Americans pride themselves on
leading the world in the digital quest to conquer cyberspace. But
Britain, which introduced the first mass postal service some 160
years ago, has leaped ahead by letting anyone with access to a
computer and a phone line surf the Internet at no cost. (Andy Glass
is a columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.)
MOVES THURSDAY.
