<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2848 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-1STL     02-20 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT PRESSES FOR NATO'S FORCES TO POLICE KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS for complete writethru to note extension of deadline to
Tuesday and to summarize Saturday developments.) (See related KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-RESIDENTS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMBOUILLET, France _ The Clinton administration and its
partners in negotiating peace for Kosovo said Saturday night that
Serbia continued to refuse NATO ground troops to police any accord,
but that enough progress had been made to justify extending talks
until Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The extension comes after President Clinton said on Friday that
it would be ``a mistake'' to let the talks run on beyond the
original deadline of noon (6 a.m. Eastern time) Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who arrived here Saturday
morning, said that after a day of stalled negotiations she spoke to
Clinton and they agreed that the ``United States and the
international community should stay the course.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-day extension of the talks, while not as long as some
European countries had requested, forestalled the air strikes which
NATO had threatened against Serbia if no accord emerged.
</P>
<P>
   The major stumbling block Saturday was the refusal of the
Serbian delegation, headed by the Serbian president Milan
Milutinovic, to consider accepting a NATO-led force as peacekeepers
in Kosovo, the southern province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic is a close ally of the Yugoslav President, Slobodan
Milosevic, the sole decision maker for the Serbs, who has remained
at home in Belgrade but continues to exert absolute control over
the delegation here.
</P>
<P>
   Albright criticized the Serbian delegation for taking ``every
opportunity for evasion and delay.'' In contrast, she said, the
ethnic Albanians, who are seeking an independent Kosovo but
apparently will agree to the autonomy on offer here, had negotiated
with ``discipline and unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the good faith behavior by the ethnic Albanians, it was
a setback for the Clinton administration that they declined at the
last moment to sign the political portion of the overall peace
settlement. With the agreement of the ethnic Albanians on the
political make up of Kosovo during the three year interim
agreement, the Clinton administration had hoped to pile extra
pressure on the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has said it will deploy up to 30,000 soldiers, including a
small contingent of U.S. troops, to monitor an accord intended to
end the year-long conflict in Kosovo. As leader of Yugoslavia,
which consists of Serbia and Montenegro, Milosevic has consistently
refused to contemplate such a foreign presence on his soil.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and four European foreign ministers arrived Saturday
morning at the 14th-century castle where ethnic Albanian and
Serbian delegates have been sequestered for two weeks, and tried to
squeeze an accord out of them.
</P>
<P>
   Although more than 400 NATO strike and support planes remained
at the ready, there was little talk at the castle on Saturday of
airstrikes, and greater concentration on working out details of
making NATO soldiers acceptable to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who stripped Kosovo of its autonomy 10 years ago, has
insisted so far that NATO troops in Kosovo would represent an
infringement of the sovereignty of Serbia and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement proposed here would grant Kosovo autonomy for
three years, but leave unresolved any question of eventual
independence, which the ethnic Albanians seek.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO secretary-general, Javier Solana, was empowered by the
alliance's 16 member nations two weeks ago to order air strikes if
the Serbs failed to go along with an agreement to end the fighting
in Kosovo, which has claimed 2,000 lives in the last 12 months,
according to estimates. As many as 200,000 people have been driven
from their homes in the province, where an estimated 90 percent of
the 2 million population is ethnic Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   NATO ambassadors in Brussels scrapped a meeting planned for
Saturday as the talks here dragged on. Solana had said he would
consult with NATO members before ordering any bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent attempt to water down the NATO deployment,
Milutinovic raised the prospect on Friday night of using armed
civilians working under the auspices of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe as a substitute for alliance
troops keeping the Kosovo peace, Western diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO was extremely unlikely to accept such a proposal, it
was the first sign that the Serbs might eventually accept armed
foreigners on their territory. Foreign Secretary Robin Cook of
Britain said no changes were made in the composition of the force,
and rebuffed any suggestion that it might fall under the authority
of anybody except NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs are also not pleased that they would be required under
any settlement to make dramatic reductions in their security forces
in Kosovo _ for the police, who have been blamed for massacres of
ethnic Albanian civilians, and for the Yugoslav army, which patrols
the borders with Albania and Macedonia. Ethnic Albanian guerrillas
have received weapons mostly across the porous, mountainous
frontier with Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanian guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army are
required under the proposed pact to disarm over a period of six
months.
</P>
<P>
   A major sticking point for the ethnic Albanians Saturday evening
was the failure of the political agreement to stipulate that a
referendum would be called after the three-year interim period. The
delegation believes that such a referendum would result in a vote
for independence from Serbia, a status that the international
community opposes.
</P>
<P>
   The high-stakes drive to reach an accord in Kosovo began after
the massacre of 45 ethnic Albanian civilians by the Serbian
security police last month in the village of Racak.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The killings dramatized what many had known: that the hatred
between the two ethnic groups in Kosovo was irretrievably deep.
Unlike other parts of former Yugoslavia, where different ethnic
groups spoke the same language and intermarried, there is little
intermingling between the ethnic Albanians and the Serbs in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the two ethnic groups deteriorated further
when Milosevic revoked the autonomy of Kosovo in 1989, swept
Albanians from all important posts and introduced a repressive
Serbian police and military regime in the province.
</P>
<P>
   The Racak massacre also illustrated that both sides in the
conflict were rearming for renewed hostilities in the spring. In
the last month, international monitors in Kosovo have reported
seeing fighters of the ethnic Albanians' Kosovo Liberation Army
carrying new, highly sophisticated sniper rifles as well as other
new weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian police and Yugoslav army increased the numbers of
their units in violation of a cease-fire agreement worked out in
October by the Clinton administration's special envoy, Richard
Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   With the danger of an unchecked conflict in Kosovo spoiling the
celebrations in Washington in April for the 50th anniversary of
NATO, the administration moved quickly in late January to forge a
combination of diplomacy and military force that would convince
both sides to sign a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Albright urged the Contact Group _ which includes the United
States, France, Germany, Britain, Italy and Russia _ to run the
diplomatic negotiations that have taken place at Rambouillet.
During her visit to Moscow in late January, the Russians made clear
they were ready to work toward a solution in Kosovo and signaled
that they were ready to distance themselves from their traditional
allies, the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO, the administration fought hard to get the 16 alliance
members to give Solana the authority to order airstrikes against
Serbia if peace talks failed. It also moved, but with less
appetite, to have Americans included in a NATO-led ground force
that would enforce any political settlement emerging from the
Rambouillet talks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the administration, the toughest part has been making the
case for a second deployment of U.S. troops to the Balkans in less
than four years. Clinton, announcing his readiness to deploy some
4,000 men in Kosovo if there is a peace accord, said last week that
this was in the national interest.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that continued war in Kosovo could spill over into
neighboring Albania and Macedonia, and possibly envelop two NATO
partners, Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The peace in Bosnia, where U.S. troops remain stationed, and the
credibility of NATO were also at stake, Clinton noted.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the U.S. troop commitment on Feb. 13, President
Clinton stressed that this time _ in contrast to Bosnia _ the
Europeans would be providing the bulk of the NATO force. The U.S.
offer of 4,000 troops was only 15 percent of the deployment, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 Marines from the 24th Marine Expeditionary Unit
based at Camp Lejeune, N.C., were poised this weekend on ships in
the Mediterranean to be among the first troops to land in Kosovo in
the event of a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to allow Europe to do most of the work in Kosovo,
the administration is trying to ensure that it does not lose its
leverage. It is a new and at times seemingly uncomfortable
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington doesn't want to pay the bills but doesn't like
being the junior partner,'' said a NATO official of the military
plans for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union, whose countries are most concerned about
waves of impoverished ethnic Albanian refugees flooding into
Western Europe if the fighting continues, has pledged hundreds of
millions of dollars in civil reconstruction money for Kosovo over
the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The diminished role of U.S. troops will mean that a British
general will be the commander on the ground in Kosovo for the first
months of the peacekeeping operation. Thus, U.S. soldiers will have
to get accustomed to a non-American commander on the ground under
the authority of an American, Gen. Wesley Clark, who is the supreme
commander of NATO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
