</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-2000-21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats size up political chances in Georgia
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Six seats in the House of Representatives separate
the Democrats from their fondest hopes for the 2000 election,
expressed on simple blue-and-white posters here at their
congressional campaign headquarters: ``Speaker Gephardt.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.) is expected in Atlanta Monday for
three fund-raisers as the Democrats focus on races in Georgia that
could help them win control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Patrick Kennedy (D-R.I.), chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, and Georgia's three Democratic
representatives, Sanford Bishop, John Lewis and Cynthia McKinney,
also are scheduled to attend the closed-door luncheon and two
private receptions later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Although Democrats, aided by organized labor, are expected to
pour more money and effort into promising districts in the
Northeast, upper Midwest, California and the Pacific Northwest,
they like their chances of adding a couple of seats in the South,
where Republicans have come to dominate congressional elections
after decades of Democratic rule.
</P>
<P>
   Using public reaction against the Republican-led impeachment as
a fund-raising tool, the Democratic leaders will make clear why
they believe 2000 is the year to end Republican control of the
House and why they think Georgia Republicans Bob Barr, Saxby
Chambliss and Charlie Norwood are vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us good candidates and we'll win at least one of those
seats,'' said Mark Gersh, a consultant to the Democratic campaign
committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Gersh's refrain is familiar in Georgia. Democrats have
almost nowhere to go but up in terms of House seats in Georgia.
Before the 1992 election, they controlled nine out of 10.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-1995, they held just three of 11 (Georgia having gained a
seat after the 1990 census), and have been unable to win any back
in the past two elections.
</P>
<P>
   They vowed to field strong challengers to Norwood and Chambliss
in 1998, but did not, even though both men represent districts
President Clinton carried twice and where other statewide
Democratic candidates run well.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Chambliss and Norwood narrowly prevailed after
court-ordered redistricting left them with significantly new
constituencies. Chambliss represents Macon and a swath of counties
running south to the Florida line. Norwood's base is Augusta, Ga.,
but his district stretches west to the outer Atlanta suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say next year will be different. One reason is the
strong showing of Democratic Gov. Roy Barnes of Georgia in the 1998
election. ``He showed us the way a centrist Democrat, with appeal
to the black community, can be successful,'' Gersh said.
</P>
<P>
   Black voters, overwhelmingly Democratic, made up nearly 30
percent of the electorate in 1998, and their support helped
Democrats to a surprisingly strong showing in a year in which
Republicans were counting on making strong gains.
</P>
<P>
   But Chambliss and Norwood received 62 percent and 60 percent of
the vote, respectively, in their districts, far more comfortable
victories than they recorded two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Those results persuade Republican pollster Whit Ayres, who has
done work for both men, that the congressmen will retain their
seats if they run again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just wishful thinking on the part of the Democrats,''
Ayres said. ``I don't see any particular problem for them, any
particular dislike.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Rothenberg, a Washington political analyst who writes the
Rothenberg Political Report, said, ``I've heard over and over again
how these are targeted seats. The `out' party says this is going to
be the year we win these seats. After three cycles, I'm
skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg and Emory University political science professor
Merle Black said the Democrats could make a stronger showing in
Barr's 7th District, west and northwest of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, it ought to be a Republican district,'' Black said.
``But the way Barr has chosen to represent it is to emphasize
ideology at the expense of everything else. That is not the way to
expand your base of constituent support.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr is one of several House prosecutors in President Clinton's
impeachment trial whom Democrats would love to replace in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats point to Barr's relatively lackluster showing in 1998
against a little-known, poorly financed Democrat. While he won 55
percent of the vote, he carried Cobb County, located north of
Atlanta, by just 900 votes of 36,000 cast and Floyd County, with
its Rome population base, by 1,000 votes out of 21,000 cast.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's margins in the two largest population centers of his
district should entice a strong Democrat who can raise $800,000 to
$1 million into the race, Gersh said.
</P>
<P>
   An additional uncertainty in 2000 is the impact of the
presidential campaign on the congressional races. ``The image of
the parties will be defined by their presidential nominees,'' Ayres
said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has been hotly contested in the past two elections,
going for Clinton narrowly in 1992 and against him, also narrowly,
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, if he is the nominee, would enter with
the advantage of coming from neighboring Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   But Black said it might be difficult for Democrats to repeat
their 1998 performance in 2000 if the Republican presidential
nominee is Texas Gov. George W. Bush or another GOP candidate who
can bridge the gaps between the party's various factions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone with broad appeal would make it tough on Gore in
Georgia,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
