<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-GATECH-MARYLAND21     02-20 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GATECH-MARYLAND21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Terrapins playing in the zone
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to be Dick Vitale to know that No. 5 Maryland has
the talent to be a Final Four team. From Steve Francis, the
spectacular JUCO transfer, to sophomore Terence Morris, who might
be the most underrated player in college basketball, to Laron
Profit, the steady and dependable warrior, this could be the most
talented team in the country not named Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland (22-4, 10-3 ACC) has been ranked in the Top 10 for 15
consecutive weeks. The Terps have four victories over teams in the
Top 10: Stanford, UCLA and North Carolina twice. Their only losses
are twice to No. 1 Duke, at No. 6 Kentucky and at Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The only question being raised about the Terrapins as the NCAA
Tournament looms is whether they have the hearts and minds to be
champions. Today's game at Georgia Tech could go a long way toward
providing the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago Maryland looked like a team in trouble. The
Terps were caught napping against Wake Forest _ a team they had
beaten by 23 points on Dec. 3 _ and lost 85-72. Three days later,
they were crushed at Duke 95-77 in a game that
</P>
<P>
   wasn't that close.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the last half hour of the Feb. 9 practice, senior center
</P>
<P>
   Obinna Ekezie suffered a ruptured Achilles' tendon and was lost
for the year. With five games left in the regular season, the Terps
suddenly were without a pivotman who had started 105
</P>
<P>
   games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't change anything. That's the last thing you want to
do,'' coach Gary Williams said. ``The question then became, would
the others step up and compensate for Obinna?
</P>
<P>
   ``If so, I thought we had a chance to be okay.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams got his answer the next night at N.C. State. Maryland
held the Wolfpack to 12-of-47 shooting (25.5 percent), the worst in
school history, in a 63-50 victory. Told he had to pick up the
rebounding slack with Ekezie gone, Morris pulled down 16.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last Saturday against No. 14 North Carolina, Maryland
unleashed all of its talented fury. The smaller Terps blocked 14
shots and forced 25 turnovers, the most the Tar Heels had committed
in two years. Maryland won 81-64 and for the first time in nine
years, the Terps won both regular-season games against UNC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people wonder how we were going to respond,
and we wanted to send a message without Obinna,'' Profit said
afterwards. ``We wanted to be aggressive from the opening tip.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is pleased about, but wary of, these most recent
events. He has seen other teams have a temporary surge after losing
a key player. Invariably, those teams can't sustain the effort and
the hole in the lineup begins to show.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Sunday's game at Georgia Tech is so important.
Maryland has had an entire week to rest but also to lose the
adrenalin high from its reaction to Ekezie's injury. Georgia Tech's
front line of Alvin Jones (6-11) and Jason Collier (7-0) could
present problems now that Williams is starting freshman Lonny
Baxter (6-8, 260) at center.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets play reasonably well at home, as evidenced by
their 10-point lead over Duke before losing to the Blue Devils on
Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game is a major-league test to see if Maryland really
has the right stuff to overcome the loss of Ezekie and make a
serious run in the NCAA Tournment, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're a team that has the luxury of playing
average,'' said Williams, in his 10th year in College Park. ``When
we play our game, we can play with anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have to do this the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
