<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NY-IMMIGRANT-RALLY-     02-20 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-IMMIGRANT-RALLY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCHRAN ASSEMBLING LEGAL TEAM FOR DIALLO CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REFILING to correct slug (filed as NY-COCHRAN) and to add photo
note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawyer Johnnie Cochran joined the Rev. Al Sharpton
Saturday morning at a rally in Harlem, vowing to seek justice in
court for the family of Amadou Diallo, the West African street
peddler slain by four New York police officers, and for the broader
black population.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran said he was assembling a legal team similar to the one
that won acquittal for O.J. Simpson, and that it would include a
``community lawyer.'' He offered no specifics about his plan for a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the police accountable?'' Cochran asked the crowd of about
400 gathered in the auditorium of Sharpton's National Action
Network for the two-hour rally, which was also broadcast on radio
station WWRL-1600 AM.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are these four going to be held responsible and accountable?
The police are not above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   With people in the crowd wearing buttons with faces of people
shot by the police, several Latino politicians recalled Anthony
Baez, killed by officers in 1994 after a confrontation that began
over a game of street football, and Luis Baez, a mentally disturbed
man, unrelated to Anthony Baez, who died in 1979 in a hail of 24
bullets fired by five officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is safe,'' said U.S. Rep. Jose E. Serrano, D-N.Y., of
the Bronx. ``I used to worry only, as a congressman, about the
local mugger. I am worried more now about the local police than I
am about the local mugger.''
</P>
<P>
   Serrano noted that he was now the ranking Democrat on the
appropriations subcommittee that handled funding for the Justice
Department, and said he would try to hold up funds if he was
unsatisfied with the federal role in investigating the Diallo case.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran spoke of his recent visit to the Wheeler Avenue
apartment building in the Soundview section of the Bronx where
Diallo, 22, lived and was shot at 41 times in the vestibule on Feb.
4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is such a small area, it is a death chamber,'' Cochran
said. ``He couldn't go anywhere. You would not shoot an animal in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, who returned Thursday from Diallo's funeral in Guinea,
called the shooting ``an international disgrace'' and led the crowd
in chants of ``No justice, no peace,'' and ``Amadou, Amadou,
Amadou.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This young man, Amadou, represents to us, in our judgment, the
test case in whether or not judicial procedures in this country are
for everyone,'' Sharpton said. ``There's more on trial here than
four police. The U.S. itself is on trial before the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The four officers, Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon
and Richard Murphy, have turned in their guns and are on
administrative duty. A grand jury in the Bronx has been convened to
consider the case.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said daily vigils at the Bronx courthouse where the
grand jury meets will continue, with a larger rally there scheduled
for Wednesday. Demonstrators are also planning to rally Sunday
afternoon at White Plains Road and East Tremont in the Bronx, and
Monday in front of City Hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
