Rabbi Marvin Hier, the founder of the Simon Wiesental Center, with
items from the Avery Brundage archives, says Olympic leaders ``sold
their souls,'' for the 1936 Games. Rabbis of the center maintain
that the well-documented anti-Semitism of that era's Olympic
leadership is a simple barometer of an overall hypocrisy in the
Olympic movement. (Michael Tweed/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CONAKRY, Guinea -- Feb. 20, 1999 -- GUINEA-NEWYORK, 2-20
-- A traffic officer in Conakry, Guinea, minds a crossing near
Niger Market. The police presence in this West African country is
constant and sometimes brutal, but rarely deadly, which is a reason
the news of Amadou Diallo, the unarmed Guinean immigrant shot to
death by four New York City police officers in the Bronx on Feb. 4,
resonates so deeply. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Feb. 20, 1999 -- NY-JAPANESE-GARDEN, 2-20 --
The Japanese Hill-and-Pond Garden -- with its antique lanterns,
cherry and pine trees, shrubs and flowers and waterfalls -- has
been the esthetic heart of Brooklyn since its opening as the
centerpiece of the Brooklyn Botanic Garden in 1915. The Japanese
garden which is falling apart, is currently undergoing an
intensive, $3 million program to save it. (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PORT ELIZABETH, N.J. -- Feb. 20, 1999 --
NY-HEROIN-SWALLOWERS-3, 2-20 -- A Customs agent at Port Elizabeth,
N.J., using a density meter to examine a cargo container. Heroin
smugglers have had to become more crafty as the Customs Service
employs more sophisticated technology. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Feb. 20, 1999 -- NY-HEROIN-SWALLOWERS-2, 2-20
-- A drug-smuggling suspect shows how heroin is prepared for
couriers -- usually young women who are dirt poor -- who swallow
it, packed into pellets made from the fingers of surgical gloves.
Known on the streets and by federal agents as swallowers, the women
have become an important link in the heroin trafficking chain that
extends from Colombia to New York. (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Feb. 20, 1999 -- NY-HEROIN-SWALLOWERS-1, 2-20
-- Customs agents at Kennedy International Airport use a body
scanner, instead of a pat-down, to detect drugs concealed inside of
clothing. Federal agents have expanded their operations at the
airports in their ever-evolving cat-and-mouse game with traffickers
-- one that now largely pivots on catching the couriers who smuggle
heroin in their luggage, under their clothing and, increasingly,
inside their stomachs. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MILWAUKEE -- Feb. 20, 1999 -- WISCONSIN-WELFARE-2, 2-20
-- Nakia, 3, left, and Na'Quee Smith, 2, peer through the front
door of their grandmother's house. Jessielean Smith, their
43-year-old grandmother, is looking after the two children under
Wisconsin's tough welfare program, after their mother, Carmelina
Smith, was caught stealing more than $11,000 from a bookstore she
worked in. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MILWAUKEE -- Feb. 20, 1999 -- WISCONSIN-WELFARE-1, 2-20
-- Jessielean Smith, a 43-year-old grandmother who is looking after
her daughter's two children under Wisconsin's tough welfare
program, takes a rare smoking break in her car. Carmelina Smith,
the children's mother is serving time for stealing more than
$11,000 from a bookstore she worked in. With little help and a
fixed income, Ms. Smith has seen her spirits sag, her finances
falter, and her blood pressure medication double. ``It's been a
disaster!'' she says. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
