A2863 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES21-COX     02-20 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turmoil in Lions' front office only part of problem
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ His nickname is ``Boss'' and, indeed, former
Georgia Tech coach Bobby Ross remains very much the man in charge
of the Detroit Lions. To keep his job, though, Ross had to
short-circuit a quiet insurrection in December that, if successful,
would have resulted in his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The story, which can now be told in more detail: Hoping to
reshape the front office, Lions vice chairman Bill Ford Jr. sought
to hire Fox television analyst Matt Millen for a high-profile
management position. When Ross caught wind of that proposed move,
he went to chairman and owner William Clay Ford and told him he
would quit if Millen was brought in to run the football operation.
</P>
<P>
   Millen, who considered the possibility for about two weeks,
actually had conversations with San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci,
whose future with the 49ers was uncertain at that time, about
succeeding Ross. The coup disintegrated, however, when the elder
Ford sided with Ross and Millen opted to stay in the television
booth. Ross, who is here for the NFL combine workouts, won't
discuss the events but it is no secret that he and general manager
Chuck Schmidt remain bitter about them.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the power struggle behind them, the Lions have myriad
problems, not the least of which is that tailback Barry Sanders
continues to think about retirement.
</P>
<P>
   On bended knee
</P>
<P>
   After two months on the banquet circuit, Heisman trophy winner
Ricky Williams came here at 244 pounds, 20 pounds over his 1998
playing weight, and begging to be selected by Cleveland with the
first pick in the draft. ``When I meet with (Browns officials),
I'll be on my knees,'' the Texas tailback said. ``I'll pray and
I'll beg.'' The puffy Williams didn't even stick around, however,
for the physical exam and blew off all the on-field workouts. He
will not have an on-campus workout for scouts but allowed he'll
consider a private session for the Browns. Team officials remain
split over what to do with the first pick. President Carmen Policy
is sold on quarterback Tim Couch and director of operations Dwight
Clark is leaning to Williams. The tiebreaker will be coach Chris
Palmer and, given his background with the passing game, Couch is
the likely selection.
</P>
<P>
   On wounded knee
</P>
<P>
   The most compelling evidence that former Georgia star Robert
Edwards will never play again came last Tuesday morning. At a
meeting of the league's finance and expansion committees in an
Atlanta hotel, New England owner Robert Kraft asked his colleagues
to award him compensation _ an extra draft pick at the end of the
first round _ for the loss of Edwards. He also sought salary-cap
relief on Edwards' contract. The request will be considered at the
annual league meetings next month, but Kraft has little hope of
success. Oakland got no such relief last year after second-round
choice Leon Bender died following a seizure.
</P>
<P>
   Combine stuff
</P>
<P>
   Florida offensive tackle Zach Piller helped himself Friday when
he did 40 repetitions in the 225-pound bench press, best for any of
the linemen. ... Offensive tackle looks to be one of the few strong
areas of the draft with John Tait (Brigham Young), Kris Farris
(UCLA), Matt Stinchcomb (Georgia), Lonnie Shelton (Eastern
Michigan), Solomon Page (West Virginia), Chris Terry (Georgia),
Aaron Gibson (Wisconsin) and Floyd Wedderburn (Penn State) all
first-round possibilities. ... Stock of Miami tailback Edgerrin
James is on the rise, and he rates second only to Williams at his
position. Like the Heisman winner, James sports dreadlocks and was
upset Friday when someone mistook him for Williams. ... In an
effort to improve draft chances, Missouri quarterback Corby Jones
also will work out at running back. ... Scouts are anxious to see
the workout of Fort Valley State defensive lineman/linebacker Peppi
Zellner, a physical specimen who is raw as a player. ... Syracuse
star Rob Konrad clearly is the top prospect at fullback, and the
dropoff after him is a big one.
</P>
<P>
   Oversized cap
</P>
<P>
   Last week provided a graphic reminder of how big an advantage
the Cleveland Browns, with about $30 million of salary cap room,
have over the rest of the league. Cleveland signed four top-shelf
unrestricted free agents _ center Dave Wohlabaugh, offensive tackle
Orlando Brown, cornerback Corey Fuller and punter Chris Gardocki _
in a span of three days. The Browns doled out $18.2 million in
signing bonuses and the quartet will earn total compensation of
$21.73 million in 1999. The signings, however, put a dent of just
$6.63 million in the Browns' cap total. The upshot: Until owner Al
Lerner stops the flow of upfront money, the Browns can outbid any
team for a player they really want.
</P>
<P>
   Northern exposure
</P>
<P>
   Colts president Bill Polian, former general manager in Carolina,
continues to acquire players from the Panthers' inaugural draft
class. Indianapolis now has three players _ defensive end Shawn
King, corner Tyrone Poole and strong safety Chad Cota _ selected by
Carolina in '95. Only center Frank Garcia remains with the Panthers
from that draft, in which Carolina chose 11 players.
</P>
<P>
   The last word(s)
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame tailback Walter Payton on the 10,000 pieces of mail
he received in the six days after he announced he needed a liver
transplant: ''If I had been a jerk, people might have felt sorry
for me, but there wouldn't have been this outpouring.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
