A2864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-FOUNTAIN-NYT &LR;      02-20 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-FOUNTAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICAR IS FASTEST OF A SLOW BUNCH IN FOUNTAIN OF YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ A herd of 3-year-old colts ran the slowest
Fountain of Youth Stakes in 36 years Saturday, raising more
questions than they answered about their pathways to the Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   And they finished the Fountain in the same tight way they
started it: Vicar first by a neck over Cat Thief, and Certain
three-quarters of a length back in third.
</P>
<P>
   All three colts are booked for a return match in the Florida
Derby on the same Gulfstream Park track on March 13, the final
flourish in Florida for horses bound for Kentucky. But while all
three probably gained some experience from the Fountain of Youth,
none of them ran a rocket race, and the issue remained wide open:
Who is the ranking 3-year-old horse in the East?
</P>
<P>
   ``We at least found out that this horse wants to be a race
horse,'' said Carl Nafzger, who trains Vicar for James Tafel, a
retired book publisher from Illinois. He also trained Unbridled to
victory in the 1990 Kentucky Derby. ``But there were six or seven
horses in the race who will be on the Derby trail, and they'll all
get better.''
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas, the trainer of Cat Thief, lost his other
Kentucky Derby hopeful this week when Cape Canaveral injured his
right front shin. But Lukas, nurturing Cat Thief as his ace in the
hole, said: ``He ran an excellent race, just what I wanted to see
from him. He hung tough in the stretch, and I think he'll continue
to improve. The Florida Derby is definitely next.''
</P>
<P>
   And Leo Azpurua, the trainer of Certain, echoed the sentiments
when he said: ``I couldn't be happier with his performance and
effort. If everything goes right, he'll be back in the Florida
Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner ran the mile in 1:38 4/5 and the mile and sixteenth
in 1:45 3/5 on a dry, fast track that did not produce fast times.
In fact, he did not come within 5 seconds of the track record. But
the top three came within one length of each other, leaving the
impression that their story was yet to be told.
</P>
<P>
   Vicar, who ran fifth in the Holy Bull Stakes at Gulfstream Park
last month after running into a pack of trouble on a wet track, has
won three of his five starts and gained ground in the Triple Crown
standings. In his only other loss, he ran second last November in
the Kentucky Jockey Club Cup to Exploit, the nominal leader of
California's Derby candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief, a seasoned runner from the Lukas stable, ran third in
the Hutcheson Stakes three weeks ago and has run in the money in
eight of his nine races. Certain came to the end of a four-race
winning streak Saturday, but has run in the money in all six of his
starts. And behind them came a flock of contenders: Grits'n Hard
Toast, Successful Appeal, Legal Street, The Groom is Red, Casanova
Star, Aly's Alley and one of the favorites, Doneraile Court, who
ran last under Jerry Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to think,'' said Nick Zito, who saddled The
Groom Is Red (seventh) and Doneraile Court (10th). ``The Groom Is
Red ran well enough to earn a shot back in the Florida Derby. But I
don't know about Doneraile Court. We tried something different with
him; we took him back. It didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The race followed a strict script. Vicar, breaking from the No.
3 post under Shane Sellers, stepped in front at the start and
stayed there. Cat Thief, with Pat Day riding, broke from No. 7 and
quickly challenged for the lead. Certain, under Kent Desormeaux,
was third after 400 yards and, after giving a little ground to
Doneraile Court in the middle stages of the race, reclaimed third
place in the homestretch. And they were still there as they raced
past the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Vicar paid $11.20 for a $2 bet to win and went home with
$120,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
