The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Feb. 21. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
FERTILITY (Phoenix) _ The ultrasound screen showed one tiny life in
Cathy Cimoch's uterus. Then two, three and four. Her husband became
silent as the reality sank in: Soon, they would become parents of
quadruplets. But the real shock hit them a few moments later. She
and her husband faced an agonizing choice they never knew they'd
have to make: End some of the lives they had sought so hard to
conceive, or have Cathy undergo a harrowing, potentially dangerous
pregnancy that could result in premature children with lifelong
disabilities. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WEBCAM _ There's a high-tech peephole into Pirkko Essen's kitchen
near Stockholm, Sweden. Fire up your computer and you can see her
teen-age children staring longingly at the devil's food cake she
baked Monday. Closer to home, you can get a pretty good view into
the Chandler computer room of Steve and Connie Fannon. In an
intriguing phenomenon sweeping the Internet, people like the Essen
family are broadcasting fragments of their lives into cyberspace
using digital cameras that cost as little as $59. By JONATHAN
SIDENER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GUARD-TURKEY _ Somewhere along the Turkish border, 26,000 feet
above ground, Copperheads from Arizona are fueling the military
campaign against Saddam Hussein. Since the Gulf War ended eight
years ago, Air National Guard members with the 161st Refueling Wing
have been helping patrol the skies of Iraq. Three hundred men and
women, mostly from Arizona, leave behind families and civilian jobs
to serve three-week tours. They are not just pilots and navigators,
but maintenance crews, intelligence officers and others. By DENNIS
WAGNER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) _ Her obituary in the Feb. 15 ``Arizona
Republic`` reported that Adele Coffield, 87, of Phoenix, a retired
school teacher, passed away Feb. 12. Survivors include two
daughters and a brother. Services were held at Westminster
Presbyterian Church on 19th Avenue. In keeping with newspaper
policy, cause of death was not listed. It should have been. It
would have read: Purse snatching. By E.J. MONTINI. Story will move
in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL;
</P>
