<HEADLINE>
RUDD ADAPTS TO REGULATION CHANGES, CAPTURES CUP POLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKINGHAM, N.C. _ For some NASCAR regulars, the 1999 Winston
Cup season did not begin with last Sunday's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   For Ricky Rudd, the real season shifts into gear today at North
Carolina Speedway with the Dura Lube/Big K 400. It is the first of
30 Cup races to be run without carburetor restrictor plates, on the
first of the ``downforce tracks'' that place a premium on handling
over horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I don't think we got started at Daytona,'' said
Rudd, who finished 30th at the 2.5-mile Daytona International
Speedway in a disabled car after getting swept up in a 12-car
restrictor-plate wreck. ``We're just beginning right here, it looks
like.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd celebrated his escape from Daytona, where eventual
race-winner Jeff Gordon nearly drove up his tailpipe while passing
Rusty Wallace for the lead, by bagging the pole position for
today's race. Rudd toured the 1.017-mile oval in 23.284
seconds/157.241 mph for the 24th pole of his career but first since
Oct. 4, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   That was 101 races ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even remember the last time I won a pole,'' said Rudd,
owner/driver of the No. 10 Tide Ford Taurus. ``Going into today, we
weren't good until the final 10 minutes of practice, and we ended
up third-fastest on the speed charts. I was just hoping and praying
I could duplicate that lap, just to get back to third because our
season hasn't started real well. I really didn't expect a pole lap
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, who is running engines supplied by Larry Wallace of
Penske-Kranefuss Racing, failed to better Mark Martin's track
qualifying record of 157.885 mph set on Feb. 21, 1997. But Rudd had
enough steam to knock Jeff Burton (157.180 mph) off the pole and
withstand Gordon's run (157.167) late in the one-lap session. Rudd,
who has won at least one Cup race for 16 consecutive seasons, and
Burton will occupy the front row when the 43-car field takes the
green flag for 393 laps at 11:30 a.m. CST.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the Daytona 500 pole- and race-winner, will start third
and be joined in Row 2 by Jeremy Mayfield (157.018). Mark Martin
(156.931) qualified fifth and will be joined in Row 3 by Wallace
(156.904). Rounding out the top 10 are Mike Skinner (156.864),
Brett Bodine (156.689), Bobby Labonte (156.676) and John Andretti
(156.649).
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying was reduced to one hot lap yesterday after rain
washed out Friday's scheduled two-lap session.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the ``The Rock's'' traditionally abrasive and
tire-chewing surface, teams will be faced with a revised set of
aerodynamic regulations for the first time this season. Gone are
the ``5-and-5'' regulations governing rear-spoiler height and
front-air-dam ground clearance instituted at the beginning of last
year. NASCAR officials had hoped that package would reduce speeds
by making the cars less stable through the corners, theoretically
forcing the drivers to lift off the accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   But the 5-and-5 package not only made the cars less stable, it
also made them almost impossible to run side by side. After a
series of driver complaints and miles of single-file racing, NASCAR
revised the aero package for the season-ending NAPA 500 at Atlanta
Motor Speedway in November. Those specifications, with only a
slight modification, will be in effect today and until further
notice.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Tauruses, like Rudd's and Burton's, will compete with a
rear spoiler 6.25 inches high and 55 inches wide. Chevrolet Monte
Carlos, like Gordon's, will run a rear spoiler that is 6.50 high
and 57 wide. Pontiac Grand Prixs, like those qualified by Labonte
and Andretti, are running with rear spoilers 6.875 high and 57
wide.
</P>
<P>
   In a switch, NASCAR is not requiring a specific rear-spoiler
angle. Last year at AMS, it was 65 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, front air dams on all makes of cars are required to
have a ground clearance of 3.5 inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, the rear spoiler and the air dam has a huge part on
how the handling is,'' said Wallace, driver of the No. 2 Miller
Lite Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have the spoiler back on the car, it's gonna make
for good racing with a lot more people in the mix,'' said Dale
Jarrett, who will start 11th in the No. 88 Quality Care/Ford Credit
Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona 500 runner-up Dale Earnhardt also is forecasting better
racing with the bigger rear blade directing more air _ and creating
more downforce _ on the rear deck lid of the cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tire wear should be better, and I think you're going to see
some side-by-side racing,'' said Earnhardt, who will start 18th in
the No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, winner of a record-tying 13 races last year, said this
race will begin to sort out the title contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the guys you see run well here _ not just here but the
next couple of races _ are really the ones who will be a threat for
the championship,'' said Gordon, winner of both events here last
year in the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevy. ``Every race
is important, but I think the downforce tracks are the ones that
are really important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
