<HEADLINE>
BURTON, MARTIN FINISH 1-2 IN ALLTELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKINGHAM, N.C. _ The mutual admiration Roush Racing teammates
Jeff Burton and Mark Martin share in NASCAR's Winston Cup Series
has spilled over to the Busch Grand National ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Burton and Martin teamed to carve their way from near the rear
of the 43-car field to a 1-2 sweep in the Alltell 200 at North
Carolina Speedway yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The field was set according to 1998 points after rain washed out
qualifying on Friday. That relegated Burton to the 30th starting
spot, two ahead of Martin, a three-time winner of this event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fortunate part of being a bad qualifier,'' said Burton,
driver of the No. 9 Track Gear Ford Taurus, ``is you learn how to
pass a lot of people. I don't get freaked out about where we start.
It sounds silly, but I've gained a lot of experience by starting in
the back in Winston Cup. Those things pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Roush twins began to assert themselves beginning on lap 126
of the 197-lapper, when Burton passed defending race champion Matt
Kenseth. With the exception of lap 155 _ led by Martin _ Burton
paced his teammate and the field home the remainder of the
distance. The winning margin in Burton's 10th career BGN victory
was 2.647 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying hard to live up to the reputation that Mark Martin
has made in Busch Grand National racing,'' Burton said of his
mentor, the series' winningest driver with 34 victories. ``I have
to run so well in my Busch car because Mark runs so good in his.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said his charge to the front was hampered by a
backstretch pit stall, but even that excuse was a bit lame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet we couldn't beat Jeff anyway, but it kind of took our
chance away of having a shot there,'' said Martin, driver of the
No. 60 Winn Dixie Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Burton and Martin's BGN teams are housed in the same shop in
Mooresville, N.C., but separate from their Cup garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team I've got and the team Mark has got is really good,''
said Burton, who averaged 108.599 mph in a race slowed six times by
caution flags. ``They prepare these teams with the intent of
leading every lap and winning every race. That's the mind-set, and
they're good enough to convince the drivers they can do that. I'm
real proud to finish 1-2, starting 30th and 32nd. That says a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Third-place Kenseth led four times for a race-high 108 laps
around the 1.017-mile oval, but none after lap 125.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dominated the first half of the race, but that was the
wrong half to dominate,'' said Kenseth, who started second in the
No. 17 DeWalt Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``The first half of the race
was good, but when Mark and Burton and Randy \RLaJoie\S and all
those guys got their adjustments, they were a little better than
us. I didn't know what else to do to the car. It just didn't have
the grip that we needed to pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth was followed by LaJoie, a two-time series champion, and
18-year-old rookie Casey Atwood, whose car flipped and
barrel-rolled in the late stages of last Saturday's NAPA Auto Parts
300 at Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Reigning series champion Dale Earnhardt Jr. started on the pole
but finished 35th after he was tagged in a five-car accident in
Turn 4. Little E., who was credited with completing 126 laps, is
17th in points.
GORDON STREAKING
</P>
<P>
   Defending Dura Lube/Big Kmart 400 race champion Jeff Gordon will
start a very confident third today in search of his fourth
consecutive victory over two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has won four of the past eight races at The Rock,
including both events in 1998. Gordon scored his 12th victory of
1998 in the ACDelco 400 on Nov. 1, and locked up his third Cup
championship in the process. Gordon closed the 1998 season at
Atlanta Motor Speedway with his record-tying 13th victory on Nov. 8
and won the season-opener at Daytona last Sunday to stretch his
streak to three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But Gordon attempted to downplay his lastest series domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like last season was last season,'' said Gordon, driver
of the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Refinishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
``I feel very good about this racetrack because the last two times
we've been here, we've been very strong _ and we won. But I don't
know about the four-in-a-row thing. We're just trying to put
together a good string of runs.''
JARRETT STUCK IN SECOND
</P>
<P>
   Perennial championship contender Dale Jarrett is winless in 23
Cup starts at Rockingham but has finished second in five of the
past six races here.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett will start 11th after hot lapping at 156.595 mph
yesterday. He is 36th in points after finishing 37th in the Daytona
500, where he was swept up in a 12-car wreck. Jarrett trails Gordon
by 123 points after the first of 34 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him a 100-point lead on us,'' said Jarrett, driver of
the No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit Taurus. ``But as I look
at it, it's only 3 1/2 points per race that I've got to make up on
Gordon, so we can catch him. We have finished second five out of
six races here with this team, so it would be nice to get into
Victory Lane.''
LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to race these guys again. You don't have to hit each
other. You can still race clean. That's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Randy LaJoie, Busch Grand National points leader, after
finishing fourth at The Rock
</P>
</TEXT>
