<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SWAP' STILL HAUNTING MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week marked the two-year anniversary of the largest trade
in NBA history, the nine-player deal in which the Mavericks sent
Sam Cassell, Jim Jackson, George McCloud, Chris Gatling and Eric
Montross to the Nets for Robert Pack, Khalid Reeves, Ed O'Bannon
and Shawn Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as it was then, the swap is a disaster for the Mavericks
and general manager Don Nelson. After just 10 days on the job,
Nelson traded away his starting five for Pack and Bradley, labeling
them ``our point guard and center cornerstones of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, but those cornerstones come off the bench for a
1-7 team that would likely get beat in a seven-game series by the
five players Nelson traded on Feb. 17, 1997. While O'Bannon and
Reeves were released, the Nets start Cassell, give major minutes to
Gatling and parlayed Montross and Jackson into landing Keith Van
Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has 868 wins as an NBA coach and 36 years of experience
as a player, coach and GM. But he also owns a 17-57 record as
Mavericks head coach, better than only Quinn Buckner and Gar Heard.
Jim Cleamons, the coach he fired, was 28-70.
</P>
<P>
   With Nelson in control, the Mavericks have more organizational
stability than at any time in franchise history. They also,
however, have a coach/GM whose hyperbole is the only thing worse
than his transactions:
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 7, 1997: ``I have no intentions of coaching ever again. I'm
finished.'' Less than 10 months on the job as GM, Nelson fires
Cleamons and returns to coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 17, 1997: ``We got our point guard and center cornerstones
of the future.'' The foundation of Dallas' second unit, Bradley and
Pack combine to average only 14 points and 39 minutes per game.
</P>
<P>
   June 25, 1997: ``He'll be the best running big man in the NBA.''
So maybe Chris Anstey should run on Nelson's track team, because
the team's '97 No. 1 draft pick is playing only eight minutes per
game on his basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 18, 1997: ``He's my kind of player. He's the real deal.''
Despite having only 28 games of NBA experience, Erick Strickland
gets a four-year, $14 million contract from Nelson. He averages 4.2
points, 1.8 rebounds and 0.8 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 13, 1999: ``I'd be surprised if he doesn't win Rookie of
the Year. He's got skills that could revolutionize the game, and
we're going to be playing him an awful lot.'' Two weeks into the
season, 20-year-old Dirk Nowitzki averages 8.8 points, 4.8 rebounds
and sat out the entire fourth quarter in consecutive losses to the
Grizzlies and Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 26, 1999: ``I'm not going to put a number on our wins, but
I'll promise we'll play an up-tempo, high-scoring style that is fun
to watch.'' During their 1-7 start, the Mavericks broke 100 just
once and averaged only 90 points per game.
SPOTLIGHT ON ...
IMMENSELY TALENTED LAKERS STILL LACKING MATURITY TO WIN TITLE
</P>
<P>
   Perfect example of why the Lakers aren't mature enough to win a
championship:
</P>
<P>
   Leading the Nuggets by two points in the final minute, guard
Kobe Bryant waves off his teammates for an isolation against
Denver's Bryant Stith. He blows by Stith, elevates and drops in a
soft bank-shot with a foul to seal the win with fist-pumping
theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? When Bryant made his move, there was :16 left on
the shot clock and :23 in the game. Lacking the savvy to match
their immense talent, that's where veteran guard Derek Harper was
supposed to step in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so much physical skills that we fool ourselves,''
Harper said. ``We need to sacrifice a few highlights for the good
of the basketball team, but we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Added forward Rick Fox: ``We haven't matured one bit from last
season. We lose some games to veteran teams before we leave the
locker room because mentally we lag way behind.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS AROUND THE EAST
</P>
<P>
   There's trouble in Detroit, where a 3-0 start has quickly turned
into back-biting among Grant Hill, Jerry Stackhouse and Bison Dele.
Hill constantly rides Dele for a lack of effort, and last week
Stackhouse basically called Hill a ball hog. ``Grant's been scoring
a lot for our team, but I don't think that's exactly what our team
needs,'' Stackhouse said. ``If you're coming down the court and you
haven't touched the ball the last two or three times down, it's
hard to go down and chase a guy and do all the little things you
have to do. I want the ball more.''. ... Just 13 days after signing
a contract extension worth $70.9 million, Cavaliers center Zydrunas
Ilgauskas broke his left foot and will miss the season. ``I must
have killed somebody in a past life,'' he said. ... Hornets coach
Dave Cowens says he doesn't plan to coach next season in Charlotte
without a contract extension, and he doesn't expect to get one.
Cowens has won 50-plus games each of the past two seasons and is
the lowest-paid head coach at just under $700,000 this season. On
top of that, the team lost Vlade Divac and Matt Geiger in free
agency, lost Anthony Mason to a preseason injury and has yet to
suit up star Glen Rice. ``It's just about feeling appreciated,''
Cowens said. ``I'm underpaid and underappreciated.''
AROUND THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   Attention fans of the Clippers, Nuggets and Mavericks _ both of
you: The top four lottery picks should be Duke power forward Elton
Brand, Maryland guard Steve Francis, Connecticut shooting guard
Richard Hamilton and Rhode Island small forward Lamar Odom. ...
It's not yet a sophomore jinx, but Spurs center Tim Duncan is
struggling with aggressive double-teams coming at him in the low
post. ``Tim is just going to have to figure it out,'' said Spurs
coach Gregg Popovich. ``He's holding the ball too long and
everybody on every planet in the universe knows that everybody is
going to come.'' ... Warriors rookie Antawn Jamison had a horrible
start, averaging 13.8 minutes and 4.7 points on 26.8 percent
shooting through six games. ``Honestly, there were times on the
court where I was holding back crying,'' said Jamison, who scored
21 points, hit 7 of 8 shots, grabbed 11 rebounds and tipped in the
game-winning basket with four seconds left against Minnesota last
week. ... Suns guard Jason Kidd had two triple-doubles in three
nights last week, and two quarters to remember. In the third
quarter against the Nuggets, he scored 10 points, grabbed six
rebounds and dished out five assists. In the fourth quarter against
the Spurs, he either scored or assisted on each of the Suns' eight
field goals, and he had a hand in all but two of their 22 points in
the quarter.
INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Bad news for Bulls fans, the Class of '96 is disappearing faster
than David Copperfield's assistants. The Mavericks apparently won't
sign Samaki Walker to a contract extension before the March 13
deadline, but six other players from that draft crop already have.
Chicago is saving its salary-cap money for free-agent runs at
players who won't be available. A look at the players who have
signed the maximum six-year, $70.9 million extension:
</P>
<P>
   Pick Player Current Team 1. Allen Iverson Philadelphia 76ers 2.
Shareef Abdur-Rahim Vancouver Grizzlies 5. Ray Allen Milwaukee
Bucks 6. Antoine Walker Boston Celtics 13. Kobe Bryant Los Angeles
Lakers 20. Zydrunas Ilgauskas Cleveland Cavaliers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
