<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2888 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-BOS &LR;      02-20 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES EXTEND DEADLINE ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMBOUILLET, France _ The Kosovo peace talks were extended
Saturday until Tuesday, and NATO airstrikes against Serbia were
averted, after the Western allies said there had been enough
progress at the talks to set a new deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after a marathon round of all-night negotiations,
representatives of the six-nation Contact Group on the Balkans said
the main sticking point was the refusal of the Yugoslav government
to accept up to 30,000 NATO troops to police a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright was more pointed in
her criticism, saying the Serb delegation representing Yugoslavia
bears ``the lion's share of responsibility'' for not meeting
Saturday's deadline to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Albright praised the ethnic Albanian delegation, saying that
despite hedging at signing an agreement, they had negotiated ``with
unity and discipline of purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, she said, the Serbs ``did not want to engage at
all'' on the deployment of NATO troops, which the Contact Group
says is essential to keeping the warring factions apart while a
settlement is implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said she was ``extremely reluctant to offer extra
time'' because of the refusal by the Serbs to even discuss NATO
ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   But the European powers, and especially the Russians, who are
sympathetic to the Serbs, were more enthusiastic about granting the
three-day extension and postponement ofpossible NATO airstrikes
against Serbian military targets.
</P>
<P>
   While US officials said only the ethnic Albanian delegation had
asked for an extension, the Europeans stressed that both sides had
asked for more time to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In an indirect slap at Albright, the Italian foreign minister,
Lamberto Dini, said it would be wrong to put most of the blame on
the Serbs for missing the deadline, which was set three weeks ago
by the Contact Group, made up of the United States, Britain,
France, Germany, Italy, and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Albright, who was unflinching in her praise of the ethnic
Albanians and her criticism of the Serbs, the European allies were
more discreet in apportioning blame. Hubert Vedrine, the French
foreign minister, who is hosting the talks at a 14th-century castle
35 miles southwest of Paris, said the 75-hour extension was granted
because ``very substantial progress has been made'' on the
framework of an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement would return to Kosovo the autonomy it had
enjoyed until Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic unilaterally
suspended it in 1989. Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of
the 2 million people in Kosovo, would be allowed to police,
educate, and govern themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the ethnic Albanians would agree to remain part of
Serbia for at least three years, a prospect that most of them find
offensive, especially in light of the crackdown that Serb
authorities launched last year to crush an Albanian separatist
movement. Some 2,000 people, most of them ethnic Albanian
civilians, have died in the fighting between Serb forces and Kosovo
Liberation Army separatists.
</P>
<P>
   The slaughter of ethnic Albanian civilians last year by Serb
forces led the US and European allies to intervene in Kosovo, first
by threatening NATO airstrikes last October, then by convening the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The air strikes were postponed after Milosevic accepted a
compromise brokered by US envoy Richard Holbrooke. But the deal
collapsed as ethnic Albanian fighters and Serb forces routinely
flouted the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   A senior US official Saturday said that if the talks end with
the Albanians agreeing to sign a settlement and the Serbs refusing,
NATO would bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what would happen if both sides refuse to sign a
settlement, the official conceded, ``NATO decision-making is not
clear.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``We have no doubt the Serbs understood what
would follow if there is a Kosovar Albanian yes and a Serb no.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said the ethnic Albanians are resisting signing an
agreement because there is no guarantee that there would be a
referendum on independence after three years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, said Albright, wording on what happens then is
purposely being left vague. She said that any agreement would be an
interim settlement that would be reviewed under international
supervision after three years. The vagueness is meant to appease
the Serbs, who refuse to countenance independence for Kosovo, which
is considered the birthplace of Serbian national and spiritual
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Albright suggested that Albanians may alter or defer their
demands for independence after they are allowed to run their own
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years in our very dynamic world can bring different
results,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While Vedrine insisted that both sides had made ``progress in
the right direction'' on political arrangements, he acknowledged
that the Serbs ``will not make concessions that we view as
indispensible.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Contact Group representatives sidestepped
suggestions that one of the compromises being floated is for a
peacekeeping force made up of other than NATO troops. The idea of
putting another, unspecified force on the ground is seen as a
face-saving gesture for Milosevic, who has said he will never allow
NATO troops to occupy a part of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   But the Contact Group cannot agree on the makeup and even the
need of NATO troops to police a settlement. Albright acknowledged
that ``the Russians do not favor such a force.''
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Minister Robin Cook appeared to rule out any
watering-down of the NATO ground forces. When asked if there was
any ``winking room'' between him and the Serbs on the subject,
Cook, who has been nearly as caustic a critic of the Serbs as
Albright, replied, ``I can assure you that the last thing the Serb
delegation did was wink at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, unlike Albright, Cook was generous toward the Serbs,
saying, ``Belgrade has moved quite farther than they had last
night.
</P>
<P>
   There was a palpable difference between the briefings given by
the Europeans and Albright's tough talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not permit Belgrade to create a new humanitarian
catastrophe,'' Albright declared. ``I would hope that President
Milosevic would wake up and smell the coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who briefed President Clinton by telephone, said she
intends to remain in France until Tuesday. She said she had no
plans to fly to Belgrade to meet with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, meanwhile, there was less of the tension that
marked the days before the last NATO deadline in October. The
Yugoslav capital was quiet, and unlike last fall there was no run
on groceries or disruption of services.
</P>
<P>
   A group of rambunctious young people packed a train headed for a
soccer match in Nis, unconcerned that it is one of the areas that
NATO is expected to bomb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
