</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK ACCENT FOR CLEMENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ Roger in pinstripes. What's next, Ted Kennedy delivering
the keynote speech at the Republican National Convention? Seiji
Ozawa conducting the New York Philharmonic?
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket landed at Legends Field in Tampa Saturday and it was
a hideous sight for those who remember the 12 years he toiled for
the Boston Red Sox. It's been two years since he wore carmine hose,
but time cannot dull the pain of seeing Clemens in a Yankee
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-nine years after former Sox hurler Babe Ruth reported to
the Yankees' spring training site in Florida, Clemens retraced the
Bambino's steps on a sun-splashed Saturday afternoon. He claimed to
have some knowledge of how his new status has been received in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to some people back there,'' said the Rocket after
throwing for 20 minutes and running a few miles around the Yankee
complex. ``I heard someone say, `All Red Sox fans report to the
Tobin Bridge.' Hey, it isn't the Red Sox fans I mind. It's just one
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens-the-Yankee hasn't forgotten how he was slighted by
Boston general manager Dan Duquette on his way out the door two
years ago. After Duquette said Clemens was in the ``twilight'' of
his career, the Rocket went to Toronto and won back-to-back Cy
Young Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not keen on him assessing my baseball abilities,'' Clemens
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He also said it would be a thrill to pitch the All-Star Game at
Fenway in Yankee pinstripes, especially if Anaheim Angel Mo Vaughn
is at first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely crazy pitching there the first time in a
Blue Jays uniform,'' he said, ``and I'm sure this will be not much
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee GM Brian Cashman wanted to know how this was playing up
in Boston. Informed that some of the locals were distraught,
Cashman said, ``That's great! It's icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens will wear No. 12, a huge concession for a man who has
worn No. 21 throughout his big-league career. Yankee outfielder
Paul O'Neill wears No. 21, and Clemens observed, ``I think Paul's
even more superstitious than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 12 is the inverse of 21, but it's also the number worn by
Wade Boggs when he played for the Yankees. Boggs was probably
Clemens's least-favorite teammate in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   There's been a lot of speculation about ``special'' treatment
for Clemens, and Yankee manager Joe Torre and Cashman went out of
their way to insist that Clemens is happy to conform to all club
rules. This means no Clemens K-kids on the field or in the
clubhouse before games. In Toronto, Clemens's sons had lockers next
to their dad's, and the boys were almost a daily presence at
SkyDome. Not in New York. And Roger's goatee will have to go. There
are no whiskers allowed in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee beat reporters are already adjusting to Clemens's unique
dialect (``expec-ta-ted'' was Saturday's gem), and it's possible
that George Rose _ the private interpreter hired for Hideki Irabu _
will be retained to translate Rogerspeak.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens dodged the question regarding what cap he would choose
for his Hall of Fame plaque. Clearly, it won't be a Blue Jays cap,
and his antipathy for the Red Sox might be hard to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to accomplish a lot of great things while I was
there,'' he acknowledged. ``Since this deal was made, I've talked
to a lot of people back in Boston and they say they are Yankee fans
now. They're going to come along for the ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are his friends. We all know that rank-and-file Red Sox
fans are not going to jump on the S.S. Steinbrenner just because
the Rocket has landed in the Bronx. A large portion of Red Sox
Nation no doubt believes Clemens went to the Yankees just to stick
it to the Red Sox one more time. That would be truly shameless.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's shameless is the $10 million, four-year offer the Red
Sox gave Roger two years ago,'' countered Clemens's agent, Randy
Hendricks. ``That's what it amounted to, with another $10 million
in nonguaranteed money. They treated him like a rookie with
everything to prove, and at the time I said, `This is Nolan Ryan
leaving the Astros all over again.' And it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think we owe blood to the Boston blood bank? Two years
ago, when Roger didn't go to New York, he talked about how the
people in Boston would have taken it. This is two years later. A
lot has gone on. There's no `in your face' to Boston this time.
This is about winning. And Roger's passion to win is still fueled
by what happened in the 1986 World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Roger Clemens went 24-4, won the Most Valuable Player
award, the Cy Young, and the All-Star Game MVP. The Red Sox took a
3-2 World Series lead, and Clemens led Game Six, 3-2, after seven
innings before John McNamara sent Mike Greenwell up to hit for him.
There has always been debate about Clemens's departure. He had
retired the side in order in the seventh and had a four-hitter with
no walks. He was young and strong, but had a blister on a throwing
finger, which took away his slider. After the game, McNamara told
the national media, ``My pitcher asked out of the game.'' You can
be sure this story will surface if the Rocket gets to the 1999
World Series with the mighty Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was so early in his career,'' said Torre. ``I'm sure at
the time it was no big deal. But when you play for a while, you
realize the impact of winning it, of closing that circle.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens said, ``So much time has gone by, you look back now and
you figure it just wasn't meant to be. Back then I thought it was
going to be pretty easy to get to postseason play. It did happen a
lot early in my career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's still motivation. I've had a great deal of individual
success. But each year when I'm home I see these guys celebrating.
That's what I want now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees come to Fenway May 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
