<SLUG> BC-OLY-U.S.-MEET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL COMMISSION TO FOCUS ON PROCEDURES FOR FUTURE BID CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Shorted)  
 (HLW)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO SPRINGS _ George Mitchell, chairman of the U.S. Olympic
Committee's ethics panel, said Saturday that his commission's
investigation of the Salt Lake City scandal would focus on
recommending procedures for future bid cities.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, the former Senate majority leader, said that his
report was not intended to be an exhaustively detailed laundry list
of allegations of misbehavior. Rather, he said, ``We intend to
place emphasis on recommendations for rules, compliance and
enforcement which we hope, if adopted, will prevent the occurrence
of actions in the future of the type that led to the creation of
the commission.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mitchell did not discount that new improprieties would be
revealed in his commission's report, which will be released on
March 1 in New York, he said that looking ahead was his
commission's primary objective. ``We think that's the most
important aspect of this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One senior USOC official has been implicated in the Salt Lake
City scandal thus far. Alfredo La Mont, the committee's director of
international relations, resigned after it was revealed that he had
carried on secretive business dealings with the Salt Lake City bid
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC has commissioned a review of its practices by the law
firm of Hogan and Hartson.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mitchell and Bill Hybl, the president of the USOC, said
that Mitchell's five-member commission had not discussed details of
its investigation with USOC officials. But based on its own
internal review, Hybl said, ``We have seen nothing that would
indicate any substantive new evidence involving the USOC and Salt
Lake City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
