</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUS DIPLOMACY' RAISES HOPES IN INDIA, PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAHGA BORDER, Pakistan _ Welcomed with applause, flowers, and a
19-gun salute courtesy of his nation's archenemy, India's prime
minister crossed into Pakistan on Saturday and embraced his
counterpart, vowing to resolve differences that have divided the
hostile neighbors since their partition half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The historic visit by Atal Bihari Vajpayee, inaugurating the
first bus service between the two countries, comes just nine months
after he shocked the world by testing nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The blasts prompted Pakistan to follow suit and raised the
stakes in the nations' long-running battle over the disputed
Himalayan territory of Kashmir. Hindu-majority India and Muslim
Pakistan have fought three wars since they were created in 1947,
two over the predominantly Muslim and strategic state of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee is the first Indian leader to set foot in Pakistan
since 1989, and in the last decade, the Kashmir conflict has
escalated with a Muslim insurgency that has claimed as many as
25,000 lives _ including at least 22 in the last two days _ and
fueled bitter anti-Indian sentiment here.
</P>
<P>
   India's Vajpayee heads a Hindu nationalist party and Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif leads a hawkish Muslim party, making
their common bid for peace even more remarkable. Analysts are
divided on whether the scheduled 27-hour visit will yield
substantive agreement on the key stumbling block of Kashmir, but
the symbolic value of the talks is indisputable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time is not so far away when Pakistan and India will be
able to live as the United States and Canada,'' Sharif declared at
a dinner Saturday night in Vajpayee's honor at a 16th-century
Mughal fort in the state capital of Lahore.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee said he was joyful to be ``returning here after 21
years with the message of friendship. My regret is that we have
spent so much time in mutual bitterness. ... I am convinced there
is nothing in our bilateral relations that can ever be solved
through violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee was not uniformly welcomed in Pakistan, however.
</P>
<P>
   Several small groups of anti-Indian hard-liners staged violent
protests in Lahore Saturday that cost the life of at least one
police officer. Still, most Pakistanis interviewed said they want
the talks to yield breakthroughs in trade, travel, and military
confidence-building measures.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides will give a joint statement Sunday that many
observers expect to include economic deals as well as some military
cooperation agreements to reduce the chance of an accidental
nuclear strike.
</P>
<P>
   The summit began at the border with a pomp-filled ceremony heavy
on handshakes and hope. Vajpayee smiled and waved from the window
of the bus, and stepped off onto a red carpet to the roll of drums,
where he was welcomed with a hug by a beaming Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's military honor guard stood at attention, and its band
played India's national anthem before its own. India's and
Pakistan's flags flew side by side for the first time at this
border crossing, while colorful banners of welcome flapped
alongside nationalist slogans _ ``Long live Pakistan'' and ``Our
India is great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most important event ... since the fall of the
Berlin Wall,'' said Saqlain Imam, an editorial writer for
Pakistan's Daily Business Recorder who watched the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bus diplomacy is taking place in an environment preceded
by a series of hostilities, terrorist insurgencies, increasing
fundamentalism on both sides, and of course, the nuclear issue.
Now, after declaring the potential to destroy each other, they are
learning to live with each other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Indian side, folk performers danced in front of
Vajpayee's slow-moving bus until it reached a 15-foot stretch of
no-man's land between huge metal gates on both sides. Garlands of
marigolds _ traditional for festive occasions in India _ were
strung above a barbed wire fence, and villagers and soldiers
strained to see the bus, which bore the Hindi phrase
``Sada-e-Sarhad,'' or ``Call of the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaborately turbaned border guards on both sides marched to the
gates and flung them open for the bus carrying Vajpayee and a
delegation including Indian artists, actors, businessmen,
parliamentarians, and a cricket star. The guards from the Indian
side then marched into Pakistan bearing a basket of candies.
</P>
<P>
   The Delhi-Lahore bus service marks the first time Indians and
Pakistanis can cross at this border. A train and infrequent flights
between the two cities exist, but visa restrictions make travel
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the village of Wahga said they were thrilled about
Vajpayee's visit, but were disappointed when they discovered that
the ceremony did not mean the border wall and fences would now be
removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want peace so we can come and go freely,'' said Rashid
Ahmed, 41, who said the village was divided in 1947, when Pakistan
and India were partitioned.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed said there was more contact with villagers on the other
side until 10 years ago, when a barbed wire fence went up. ``Before
that, their cattle would come over to our side and we would herd
them back. We exchanged gifts, we atttended their marriages.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some members of the border patrol, trained to regard the
other side as a dangerous enemy, seemed moved by the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an extraordinary day. My heart is very happy,'' said a
shyly smiling Gulam Abbas, 25, a Pakistani ranger.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that sentiment will last and spread on both sides of the
border depends largely on what comes out of the leaders' summit
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts say that economic and military realities have
pushed the two sides to the bargaining table. Western nations
outraged at the nuclear tests last year slapped sanctions on both
sides and have pressured them to sign nonproliferation treaties and
make peace.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pakistan is suffering a tremendous
balance-of-payments deficit, and would benefit greatly from
increased trade with India, from whom it could import goods more
cheaply than from the West. Officially, the two sides grant each
other most-favored nation trade status, but in practice, trade is
sparse and cross-border economic deals are difficult to secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade has grown 100 percent between 1993 and last year, and we
feel it can grow even more,'' said Ajay Khanna, senior director of
the Confederation of Indian Industry, and a member of the visiting
Indian delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the issue that remains at the heart of the conflict is
Kashmir, and there is no sign that there will be a breakthough on
that. Yet Khalid Hasan, author of a book on the struggle, said the
difference now is that India seems willing to talk about the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem in the past has been that when there's a strong
government in India, they don't want to talk. When there's a weak
government, they're ineffectual,'' Hasan said. ``Whatever the
reasons, it's an act of courage on Vajpayee's part to come here,
and on Nawaz Sharif's'' to receive him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the Kashmir problem that's intractable; it's the
positions that are intractable,'' Hasan said. India ``needs to
acknowledge there's a problem. . . . I think it's new ballgame
starting today.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone here gives the Indian side that much benefit of the
doubt. Members of the extremist Muslim group Jamaat-i-Islam blocked
Lahore streets and clashed with police, resulting in injuries and
the death of one officer.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters also assaulted the cars of more than a dozen foreign
diplomats, preventing them from attending the dinner at Lahore
Fort. A mob punctured the Turkish ambassador's tire and damaged the
Swedish ambassador's car.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani Senator M. Akram Zaki, chairman of the Senate foreign
affairs committee and a member of Sharif's ruling party, called the
summit ``one of the most important of the year between two men who
will hopefully make a turn in South Asian history.''
</P>
<P>
   But some other politicians said that while they hoped Vajpayee
was sincere, they feared he might have made the journey to divert
attention from anti-Christian violence at home and to woo the
Muslim Indian vote away from the opposition Congress Party. He
might also be trying to soften his image as a hard-liner after
setting off nuclear tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
