<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2895 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-GORDON-     02-20 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON LAID IT ALL ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ray Evernham took all of a nanosecond to reply when asked if
Jeff Gordon's victory in the 41st Daytona 500 was more attributable
to the car than the driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was driver,'' said Evernham, crew chief of Gordon's No. 24
Dupont Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``All driver.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gordon suggested otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some help, but it didn't come from any race driver or
car that was on the track,'' he said. ``I guess the only help I had
was Ray and the guys in the pits. Ray, even after the race was
over, didn't feel like he gave me the fastest car out there. I
believe if it wasn't the fastest, it was one of fastest cars out
there all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was apparent that what carried Gordon to his second
Daytona 500 triumph in three years last Sunday was his enormous
driving talent. It was never more evident than on Lap 190 when
Gordon executed a winning move by hugging a low line through the
start/finish line of the 2.5-mile trioval to draw even with Rusty
Wallace, narrowly averting a rear-end collison with Ricky Rudd's
hobbled car on the apron of Turn 1.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had no intention of letting off his accelerator, as he
held his ground in this game of 190-mile-per-hour brinksmanship and
squeezed between Rudd and Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably in some other races you might not do something like
that, but it's the Daytona 500,'' said Gordon, whose victory paid
him a record $2.1 million and gave him the early lead in the NASCAR
Winston Cup points race heading into Sunday's Dura-Lube/Big Kmart
400 at Rockingham, N.C. ``It's such a big event. Late in the race
like that when you're making a charge, you take every opportunity
you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to see the tape of the closing laps. I knew it
was intense and very exciting from where I was sitting. I'm sure it
was very exciting from where the fans were sitting or standing.''
</P>
<P>
   The finish was so scintillating that CBS drew 900,000 more
viewers than a year ago, earning its highest TV rating ever for the
event, a 9.5 with a 25 share. That was a significant improvement
over last year's race, which earned an 8.6 rating/23 share.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got me on the apron down there and I just couldn't
block him off enough,'' said Wallace. ``I thought I had him blocked
off and he just kept going there and I said, `Man, I'm not going to
wreck a bunch of cars.' So I pulled up and he got me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to drive right into the back of Rudd. I
said, `Man, there's going to be a big wreck, and I'm not going to
wreck a bunch of cars and get somebody hurt,' and that's what
would've happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gordon, with some unlikely drafting support from Dale
Earnhardt, won a three-wide drag race with Wallace and Mike Skinner
down the backstretch and into Turn 3, where he finally pulled ahead
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon then held off Earnhardt's bete noire, the black No. 3
Goodwrench Chevrolet Monte Carlo, keeping it in his rearview mirror
in a pulsating 10-lap shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a great way to get the season started, by
having such a great win in the Daytona 500,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of things that did a lot for us this week. We sat
on the pole, got ourselves back in the Bud Shootout (a race for
Busch Pole Award winners). Then we got the Daytona 500 win and got
the first win of the season out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so important to get that first win. After the previous
season's over, you go, `Do we have what it takes to get to victory
lane next year? Are we going to be a championship contender?' I'm
still not sure about the championship part, but we've definitely
got one win out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, in large part, to the driver's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's hierarchy underwent a subtle yet significant change
last week when president Bill France announced the appointment of
Mike Helton as senior vice president and chief operating officer.
Helton, 45, will oversee day-to-day operations in addition to his
current duties as vice president for competition. It marks the
first time since the France family founded the sanctioning body 51
years ago that the NASCAR helm has been handed to an outsider.
``With the France family controlling the stewardship of the sport,
we can only expect great things to continue,'' Helton said. ``The
best part is that nothing is broken, so there is no urgent mission
for a fix.'' . . . Gordon's record windfall at Daytona, bolstered
by the $1 million bonus paid by the Winston No Bull 5 program, gave
him an incredible jump on matching last year's record earnings of
$9 million. Ray Grimm, a 46-year-old corrections officer from
Hagerstown, Md., who claimed to be a devout Earnhardt fan, also won
a $1 million Winston No Bull 5 bonus. He was one of five lucky fans
paired with a No Bull 5 eligible driver . . . With Indianapolis
Motor Speedway set to host the US Grand Prix Formula One race next
year, construction began last week on the new F1 garages. The
concrete foundation was poured for 36 two-story garages and 12
suites. It marked the second of an eight-phase plan to reconfigure
the garage and infield areas. ``This is the largest construction
project in track history,'' said IMS president Tony George, who
reportedly has agreed to spend upwards of $20 million to make the
alterations. ``It may seem overwhelming, but I am sure that we can
and will accomplish it.'' . . . Jay Leno has been tabbed to drive
the Chevrolet Monte Carlo pace car at the Indianapolis 500 May 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
