<HEADER>
A2897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-PITCHINGCO     02-20 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PITCHINGCOACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRIGAN ARMED AND READY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ The Red Sox will have 28 pitchers in camp: 21
on the roster, seven by invitation.
</P>
<P>
   As improbable as it may seem, there may be exactly one job open,
for a middle reliever.
</P>
<P>
   That could change, of course, because of injury or if a pitcher
or two crashes and burns this spring. But, clearly, these are not
your father's Red Sox, or your grandmother's.
</P>
<P>
   A staff that was second to the Yankees in the American League
last season may be even better this year, and that's without adding
Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most stable we've been coming into spring training
in the three years I've been with the team,'' said Dr. Joe
Kerrigan, pitching M.D., who this spring has added a laptop
computer to the arsenal of charts, videos, and mannequins he
employs in his capacity as pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the personality of the pitching staff was as
faceless as one of Kerrigan's wooden Pitching Pals. No one knew
whether Bret Saberhagen could contribute after shoulder
reconstruction, or whether Tom Gordon could make the conversion
from starter to closer. A rookie, Brian Rose, was an unknown
quantity, and lefthander Butch Henry lasted just two starts before
he was lost for the season with a knee injury. Rose's elbow gave
out soon thereafter. Dennis Eckersley arrived with much fanfare,
but he was merely a ghost of his Cy Young past.
</P>
<P>
   There was a new ace, Pedro Martinez, but he was coming to a new
league, had just signed what was then the game's biggest contract,
and would be facing constant comparisons to the Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast all of that with the present state of affairs:
</P>
<P>
   --The Sox have five veteran starters, all of whom won 10 games
or more last season, and five homegrown starters-in-waiting, all of
whom most likely will begin the season in Pawtucket but may see
Boston by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the newcomers, Mark Portugal or Pat Rapp, fires the
imagination the way a front-line starter would, but both have been
serviceable major league pitchers who should end the
bottom-of-the-rotation roulette that the Sox had to play last
season, when Rose, Jin Ho Cho, Robinson Checo, John Wasdin, and
Derek Lowe all auditioned unsuccessfully for a starting slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be a little more secure in the fourth and fifth hole,''
Kerrigan said. ``Those guys can give you innings, and they'll
protect your bullpen. We should have a rested bullpen. Last year,
we scrambled like a son of a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   --Gordon returns as the league's premier closer, with Lowe
emerging as a potentially first-rate setup man and backup closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flash should remain a dominant closer,'' Kerrigan said. ``I've
seen him make too many good pitches. I've seen it with other guys
who have made that switch, like (John) Wetteland: Once a guy has
it, he usually stays with it.''
</P>
<P>
   --Saberhagen, protected beautifully by Kerrigan and manager Jimy
Williams, is coming off a 15-win season, and while he will continue
to require constant monitoring and special treatment, he matches up
well against any of the top pitchers in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen made 18 starts last season in which he was coming off
more than the usual four days' rest. In those starts, he had a 9-3
record with a 3.33 ERA. Martinez also was given extra rest on 15
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll still be judicious with him,'' Kerrigan said of
Saberhagen. ``He averaged 88 pitches a start last season; we'll
probably bump that up to 95 or 96 pitches, which on the average is
about another two outs per game. That should give him another 20
innings, to around 195.''
</P>
<P>
   --Martinez won 20 games last season, including one in the
playoffs over the Indians, and handled switching leagues and the
added pressures with apparent ease.
</P>
<P>
   And there should be no repeat of the stomach ulcer problems that
caused him to lose a half-dozen pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro's stomach disorder was the only scary part,'' Kerrigan
said. ``He was hurting. You could see it in his face when he was
throwing on the side. He was scared. He got to Detroit and he
couldn't sleep, he was tossing and turning. This wasn't your usual
bellyache. He felt a sharp pain in a big area around his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical part wore him down, but the worrying wore him
down, too. He was really scared. He lost six or seven pounds, which
is like us losing 15 or 20 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   --The Sox have added a veteran lefthanded setup man, Mark
Guthrie, which they did not have last season until Dan Duquette
traded for Greg Swindell.
</P>
<P>
   The negatives? Martinez is the only starter under age 31. There
is no lefthander in the rotation. Pete Schourek, purchased from
Houston last season, pitched ably down the stretch and brilliantly
in his controversial playoff start, but he signed with Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tossed and turned with that,'' Kerrigan said. ``I know he's
a good pitcher and has good stuff, but he needed a lot of
maintenance. Pitch counts, and cutting back on throwing on the
side, and you not only had to worry about his elbow but his
shoulder, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen and Portugal are both health risks, Rapp's wildness
could prove deadly in Fenway Park, and Gordon undoubtedly will have
some slippage from last year's near-perfection.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerrigan, who will oversee his first official workout Sunday
after six days of informal sessions, will gladly take his chances
with this group. He's already well under way in one of his bigger
projects of spring, a makeover of long reliever John Wasdin, who in
96 innings last season gave up 111 hits, 44 for extra bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got too good an arm and too good stuff for that to
happen,'' Kerrigan said. ``We've altered his delivery quite a bit.
He's coming from over his head. He did it on his own, over the
winter. He's added a better turn, and has more deception. You can't
pick up the ball as easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from over the top, he'll get the ball downhill better,
instead of that flat-plane fastball he was throwing for extra-base
hits. We tried subtle changes before, and they didn't work. I like
what I've seen so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The middle reliever will emerge from a group that includes
back-from-Japan import Kip Gross; former Brave Brad Clontz, who had
bone chips removed from his elbow; Bob Wolcott, whose one shining
moment came when he started for the Mariners against the Yankees in
the '95 playoffs; Greg Mix, another former Braves farmhand;
lefthanded holdover Ron Mahay; and El Guapo, Rich Garces, if his
elbow is OK after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The sorting-out process begins Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
