<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-MATCHPLAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD GOLF CHAMPIONSHIPS HAS WINNING FORMAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want a sure bet? There will be some titanium clanging around
Carlsbad, Calif., at the debut of the World Golf Championships this
week. Want another? You'll hear lots of complaints, too, because
this tournament is match play.
</P>
<P>
   The critics will sound their tired battle cries _ that match
play is not a true test of championship golf, that it involves too
much luck, that a guy shooting 66 can go home while a guy shooting
74 can advance. Yeah, yeah, yeah. And a 1-iron is a tough club to
swing.
</P>
<P>
   So what? Our weekends are filled with medal-play tournaments
with leaderboards populated by bright red numbers and birdie
barrages that leave us dizzy. Surely there is room for a match-play
event that will make these millionaires grind.
</P>
<P>
   Match play is a terrific way to determine a golf champion.
Surely, the best player doesn't always win _ not at match play and
not at medal play. But great players will rise to the occasion,
regardless of the format, and you need only turn the pages of time
to appreciate what sort of champion wins at match play.
</P>
<P>
   From 1921-27, for instance, the PGA Championship was won by
either Walter Hagen or Gene Sarazen. You will drive it 450 yards
before you find anyone to argue that those men weren't the premier
players of their time. The fact that each won a pair of US Opens
tells you that they adapted their games quite well for stroke play,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Want more? During the 1940s, Byron Nelson, Ben Hogan, and Sam
Snead each won two PGA Championships at match play. Seems to me
you'll find their names a few times if you look for winners of
stroke-play events, too.
</P>
<P>
   There also was a certain player by the name of Bobby Jones who
somehow managed to beat the opposition at whatever format was
demanded. (Substitute the name Tiger Woods if you prefer hip to
historic.)
</P>
<P>
   Do you get upsets in match play? Most definitely. Long before
the world watched Costantino Rocca defeat Woods in the 1997 Ryder
Cup, a player by the name of Bob Hamilton upended Nelson in the
1944 PGA Championship final. In the 1929 Ryder Cup, both Hagen (by
10 and 8) and Sarazen (by 6 and 4) were dealt stunning defeats.
Fresher in some minds is the memory of Christy O'Connor Jr. beating
Fred Couples in the 1989 Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But to those folks who moan that stroke play delivers a truer
champion, there are entries in the record book that prove
otherwise. The 1969 US Open, for instance. Or the 1971 Masters. Or
the 1973 Masters. Or the 1996 PGA. Orville Moody, Charles Coody,
Tommy Aaron, and Mark Brooks, respectively, won those majors, and
you can still find people shaking their heads in disbelief at that.
</P>
<P>
   Anything short of a final between Woods and David Duval will be
fuel for those who dislike the idea of this match play
championship. So imagine the outcry (not to mention the sound of TV
clickers) if next Sunday's 36-hole finale gives us Bob Estes vs.
Dudley Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Other observations on this match play championship:
</P>
<P>
   --Nick Faldo, barely three years removed from his third Masters
triumph, has fallen to 65th in the world rankings but earned a spot
in the field because Jumbo Ozaki had the good sense to withdraw.
Somehow, Ozaki is ranked 14th in the world, though few observers
would put him in the Top 200. Then again, perhaps Ozaki didn't do
Faldo any favors, for the final spot in the field wins a
first-round matchup with Woods. Admit it, images of 10 and 8 are
dancing in your head.
</P>
<P>
   --When Tom Lehman announced that he would withdraw from this
weekend's Nissan Open, speculation began that he would not play at
Carlsbad, either. Not true, said folks at Signature Sports, the
agency run by Lehman's brother, Jim. The 1996 British Open champ
had surgery on his shoulder late last year but plans to make his
return this week. He draws Scott Verplank in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   --An intriguing first-round matchup is Craig Stadler vs. Colin
Montgomerie. The over/under for scowls has to be 30. On the front
side, that is.
</P>
<P>
   --Ernie Els won three straight select-field world match play
titles, but his first-round foe should give him fits. Paul Azinger
thrives in this sort of competition, as his 2-0-1 Ryder Cup singles
mark proves.
</P>
<P>
   --It's too easy to pick Woods, and Couples speaks for many in
the field when he says of the three-time US Amateur winner: ``He'll
be licking his lips when he gets to LaCosta.'' True enough. But
Couples isn't exactly a weekend hacker when it comes to this (since
that '89 loss to O'Connor, Couples is undefeated in Ryder Cup
singles play), and it says here he will win. He plays well at
LaCosta (six top 10 finishes in the years the Mercedes Championship
was held here), and his laidback reputation overshadows the fire
that often burns inside.
</P>
<P>
   --How ready is Greg Norman? He had a great partner (Steve
Elkington) at the Presidents Cup in December, then looked rusty, at
times tentative, in a few tournaments before taking a six-week
rest. Two weeks ago he missed the cut at his own invitational back
home, but his game was sharp in a runner-up finish last week at the
Australian Masters. Having dropped to 28th in the world rankings,
he draws John Cook as his first opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Think the television folks like to see Woods in the hunt? He
barely made the cut at San Diego last week, so he played too early
for the cameras in Round 3, which means the CBS telecast opened
with news of his scorching 62 at Torrey Pines. Next day, with Woods
stalking his first victory in almost a year, the ratings for the
Buick Invitational were large, and here in Boston it ranked No. 1
with a 7.96 rating, swamping the NBA (reportedly it is back in
business) and college basketball (Duke-Wake Forest reaped an 0.79;
heck, a Duke-Wake Forest chess match would rate an 0.79) . . . Talk
about a finishing kick. In last Sunday's final round of the Buick,
Jason Gore holed out his approach to the par-4 17th, then reached
the par-5 18th in two and drained a 20-foot putt. The eagle-eagle
finish for the former Pepperdine star lifted him into a tie for
26th, good for $20,385. Not bad for a Monday qualifier . . . It
helps to have a little bit of luck, even if you are a world-class
player. At the Australian Masters last weekend, Craig Parry caught
his bunker shot thin, his shot flying the green. But the ball hit a
huge leaderboard and bounced back onto the green. He two-putted for
bogey . . . If it's consistency you like, check out Michael
Campbell at last week's Dubai Desert Classic: 71-71-71-71. He
finished in a tie for 11th at 4 under . . . Alex Cejka, a talented
player on the European PGA Tour who has shown flashes of stardom,
is off to a nice start in 1999 and is tied for ninth in the Ryder
Cup standings. Should he stay in the picture for September's event,
expect to hear more about his family's tale of escaping communist
Czechoslovakia to settle in Germany . . . And there's still a long
way to go, but did you notice that European captain Mark James
threw in three straight 69s in Dubai to finish in a tie for third,
moving him to 21st in the overall Ryder Cup standings? ``I'm very
suspicious of this form,'' James joked with reporters in Qatar
after opening this week's stop with a 67.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After a 19-year run at The Quechee Club in Vermont, the NEPGA is
moving the New England Open to The Woodlands and Portland CC in
Falmouth, Maine, this year (Sept. 13-15). A few weeks before that,
the NEPGA has two gems lined up to host the section's championship
_ Winchester CC and Kernwood CC in Salem . . . Some New England
pros are working successfully in Florida this winter. Gene
Peterson, the former head pro at Cohasset CC, teamed with Tom
Tarsia to win the PGA Senior-Junior title. Larry Startzel of the
Country Club of Vermont finished second with Dan Wilkins. Sal
Ruggiero of Stow Acres earned a victory in the PGA Senior Stroke
Play Championship in the over-60 age group, while Mike San Filippo
of Nashawtuc CC currently leads the PGA Winter Series money list .
. . Looking to purchase something for the coming season? There's a
golf fair Sunday at Stow Acres (9 a.m. to 5 p.m.), and three local
club pros _ Andy Froude of Charles River, Jim Lane of Winchester,
and Bob Carey of Fresh Pond _ will hold a golf equipment sale
Friday-Sunday at Howard Johnson's in Woburn. Part of the proceeds
will benefit the Mass. Golf Association's Inner-City Golf Camps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
