<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-PITTSBURGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST BC LOSS THE PITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The whistles still seemed to be ringing in Kenny Harley's ears
as he stood against a wall outside Boston College's locker room,
explaining the disappointment of Saturday's 67-66 Big East loss to
Pittsburgh before a Conte Forum crowd of 4,347.
</P>
<P>
   With 28 seconds remaining and BC with a 66-63 lead, Harley was
whistled for a foul that put Vonteego Cummings on the line for a
pair of free throws. On the ensuing inbounds play, Harley stepped
out of bounds to relieve guard Dwayne Pina but was whistled for a
5-second violation when he failed to call a timeout. It led to the
go-ahead basket by Stephen Flores, a reserve who came off the bench
to score 8 points, including the winner on an offensive putback
with 8.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little stunned (about the 5-second violation), I
thought I had a clock going in my head, but it might've been a
little too late to call the timeout,'' said Harley, who led the
Eagles (6-18, 3-13) with a career-high 21 points on 9-for-19
shooting. ``Maybe it was a lack of recognition on my part. But what
I was really surprised at was the foul they called on me down the
stretch. I mean, the whole game we'd been playing agressive and I
don't really think that was a foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did BC coach Al Skinner, who jumped up and down to
protest Ed Corbett's touch call against Harley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, by far, is our most difficult loss,'' said Skinner,
whose team was without junior forward Michael Cotton (sprained
right ankle), but still took a 29-24 halftime lead and increased it
to 52-40 in the second half before a 15-0 Pitt run. ``It was there
for us,'' he said. ``We had our opportunities, but, yeah, it was
certainly our most difficult loss all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the officiating didn't help matters. Skinner, whose
frustration over what he sees as his team's lack of respect from
officials has been mounting, wondered how his point guard, Pina,
was unable to get to the line after he was brutalized by Pitt's
defense for 40 minutes and committed seven of BC's 19 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't complain about judgment calls,'' Skinner said. ``I'm
just unhappy about them and I'm disappointed, considering the way
the game was being played. If Dwayne wasn't getting bumped like
that all game long, then I wouldn't have any complaints. If they're
allowed to push up, and reach around and grab, then fine. We should
be allowed to do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, however, found no relief from the officials. So when
Kenny Walls took an inbounds pass from Jonathan Beerbohm with 5.3
seconds left, ``We weren't expecting to get any calls,'' said BC
freshman Brian Ross, who recorded his second double-double of the
season with 16 points, 10 rebounds. ``We just wanted to try and get
it to the goal.'' But Walls let fly of a 3-pointer from the top of
the key that hit the front of the rim and caromed out of bounds as
time expired.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings and Kellii Taylor each had 16 points for Pitt (13-14,
4-12), while Ricardo Greer had 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go back and lick our wounds and come back and live to
fight another day,'' said Skinner, whose team must regroup before
hosting No. 21 Syracuse on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there'd be games like this, but we just have to deal
with it. But we're not going away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 2014EST &QL; 
