<HEADER>
A2904 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-DELAHOYA     02-20 2257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-DELAHOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA STILL PART OF THE FRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Oscar De La Hoya wasn't within 2,500 miles of New
York, but his long shadow hung over Pernell Whitaker and Felix
Trinidad all week.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker and Trinidad were in the final days of preparation for
the biggest fight of their careers, Saturday night's International
Boxing Federation welterweight title clash at Madison Square
Garden, but so much of the talk was about the winner fighting De La
Hoya that Whitaker finally remarked, ``What's wrong with you guys?
This ain't about Oscar De La Hoya. This is a big fight, not some
tuneup. This is for the title.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it was, and a case could be made that the holder of that
title when the first bell rang, Trinidad, was every bit as
dangerous as De La Hoya, if not more so. But such has been the
marketing of De La Hoya that that is the only comparison in which
they are equals.
</P>
<P>
   Other than fight ability, nothing about Trinidad or the
four-time world champion, Whitaker, is close to boxing's new Golden
Boy. After a stirring victory a week ago over undefeated Ike
Quartey, De La Hoya enhanced the perception that he is the new king
of the ring, a point even HBO made by tying its promotion of
Saturday night's telecast into De La Hoya in a two-page
advertisement in Friday's New York Times. The first page hyped the
rebroadcast of De La Hoya-Quartey prior to the IBF title fight,
while the ad for Whitaker-Trinidad was on the following page.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of pairing these fights on back-to-back weekends was to
create a Final Four effect, and the constant talk of De La Hoya all
week made it clear that end of the promotion was working. The plan
(although not yet a promise) is that the winners fight before the
year is out to determine who is the best welterweight in the world.
Such a fight would be good not only for the participants but also
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey could even be on the undercard of such a fight against
either World Boxing Association champion James Page, himself a
fearsome puncher, or Saturday night's loser, thereby setting up a
round robin that could drum up the kind of rooting and gambling
interest that used to exist in boxing's golden days.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad's promoter, Don King, even went so far as to join
forces with one of his sworn enemies among what he calls ``the Boss
scribes.'' King stole a line from New York Daily News boxing writer
Michael Katz and said that if De La Hoya didn't agree to fight the
Whitaker-Trinidad winner, he was indeed ``Chicken De La Hoya.'' And
De La Hoya was only a spectator to this fight.
</P>
<P>
   For some unexplainable reason, Katz has taken to calling De La
Hoya chicken, claiming he is ducking the toughest opponents and
even criticizing him after the final round of the Quartey fight for
allegedly not fighting the full three minutes after nearly knocking
Quartey cold in the first 60 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   There might be some truth to the complaints about some of De La
Hoya's opponents, but certainly not Julio Cesar Chavez the first
time or Whitaker or Quartey, all of whom he defeated. Yet so intent
are some of De La Hoya's few remaining critics that they've begun
demeaning Quartey, who a week ago they said would stop De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   One day Quartey was portrayed as the most dangerous guy in the
division, someone who was going to KO the Golden Boy. Then he gets
knocked flat twice, nearly gets stopped in the final round, and
loses a split decision. Suddenly he had a lousy trainer, spent too
much time in the gym, suffered from too long a layoff, and didn't
have the heart to duke it out down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has learned to laugh about such things, even though
they're no longer funny. Meanwhile, HBO Sports CEO Seth Abraham
remains hopeful that he can work out a major pay-per-view fight
between De La Hoya and the Whitaker-Trinidad winner for the fall,
which would give the division a nearly unified title and perhaps
finally satisfy what's left of De La Hoya's detractors.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, De La Hoya said before Saturday night's fight, ``I
have to fight Trinidad, I have no choice,'' meaning Trinidad
represents the unknown force in the division and eventually will
have to be faced by whoever wants to emerge from this era as the
premier fighter at 147 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   That is because at 35, Whitaker is the past, especially since De
La Hoya already holds a decision over him, albeit a controversial
one that this corner did not agree with.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when asked what he thought of Trinidad insisting he receive
financial parity for such a fight, De La Hoya quickly put on his
new co-promoter's hat and said, ``That's nonsense. If he fights on
pay-per-view he'd have 25,000 people watching. He should just try
to get the biggest payday he can, which we've already offered him.
If he wants to get greedy, there'll be no fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Apprised of that, even Trinidad's father couldn't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parity is not important as long as I am satisfied with what
Tito gets,'' Felix Trinidad Sr. said barely 48 hours before his son
was set to face the toughest and most elusive opponent of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Someone should have reminded the Trinidads and everyone else
associated with the promotion that that opponent was not Oscar De
La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   HBO has closed a deal for Floyd Mayweather Jr., one of boxing's
hottest properties, to defend the World Boxing Council super
featherweight title April 17 on ``Boxing After Dark'' against Goyo
Vargas, with Angel Manfredy-Ivan Robinson the second fight.
Manfredy was originally set to fight IBF junior lightweight
champion Roberto Garcia, but Garcia pulled out last week.
Mayweather defended his title for the second time last week in his
hometown of Grand Rapids, Mich., pushing his record to 20-0 with a
unanimous decision over the resilient Carlos Rios. Mayweather hopes
to break Joe Louis's record of 25 straight title defenses . . .
Former bantamweight champion Wayne McCullough was enraged to learn
that World Boxing Organization featherweight champion Prince Naseem
Hamed's first title defense in his new deal with HBO would not
involve a rematch with McCullough. Instead, Hamed will fight
European champion Peter Ingle at the NYNEX Centre in Manchester,
England, April 10. But the news wasn't all bad for McCullough.
After Erik Morales successfully defended his WBC super bantamweight
title on the De La Hoya-Quartey undercard with a second-round
starching of Angel Chacon, it was announced that McCullough would
be Morales's next opponent on a May 8 card . . . Hamed will next
appear in the US this summer, as HBO Sports senior vice president
Lou DiBella spent three days in England negotiating a deal to give
the network primary status in his career. Time-Warner had to ``buy
the world,'' a source said, meaning it had to buy the worldwide
rights to Hamed's fights. This included buying out SKY-TV, the
British version of HBO. That contract was becoming a programming
problem for HBO because it demanded several fights in prime time in
England, five hours ahead of the US. Hamed will still fight in
England twice in his new deal but at times conducive to US
television . . . America's only gold medalist from the 1996
Olympics, David Reid, tries to win his first world title March 6 on
``Boxing After Dark'' against WBC junior middleweight champion
Laurent Boudouani. Boudouani trained in the Alps, believing the
high altitude would improve his conditioning, so Reid trained in
the Rockies . . . King said Thursday he is still hopeful that an
Evander Holyfield win over Lennox Lewis March 13 will result in a
defense of the WBA heavyweight title against Henry Akinwande in
South Africa this summer, with retiring head of state (and former
boxer) Nelson Mandela the centerpiece of a weeklong celebration . .
. King has gambled his own future making Trinidad-Whitaker and
Holyfield-Lewis knowing that two losses in three weeks would knock
his two top fighters out of world titles. ``It's a gamble but the
worst words a gambler can say are `Oh my, oh my, the deal passed me
by,' '' King cackled. ``I been a gambler all my life.'' . . .
Emanuel Steward reports that Lewis is in his seventh week of
training, the longest stretch of his career. ``His whole career is
based on this one fight,'' said Steward. ``He is hungry, desperate,
and realistic. Everything is on the line.'' If so, that didn't
concern Holyfield's wise veteran trainer, Don Turner. ``How do I
see the fight?'' Turner said. ``Evander hits Lewis and Lewis falls
down. If Lewis fights the fight of his life, he's still no (Mike)
Tyson.'' Steward agreed on the latter point, at least. ``Lewis is
no Tyson,'' Steward said. ``Tyson was never the fighter everyone
thought he was. Evander exposed Tyson. Boxing or toe-to-toe, Lewis
has tremendous punching power and natural strength that Holyfield
has never seen before. Unless you are a consistent fighter you
shouldn't be as cocky as Holyfield is. Lennox has never been an
easy fighter for anyone _ ever. Evander has always been erratic.''
. . . The WBC has ordered light heavyweight champion Roy Jones Jr.
to make a mandatory defense vs. No. 1 contender Graciano
Rocchigiani. It says it will not sanction any other Jones fight and
could strip him of the title if he refuses. Of course, Jones is
again talking of moving up to heavyweight to pursue Holyfield if he
wins next month, which could make it a moot point.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a story that never ends, just the names change.
Three-time junior flyweight champion Michael Carbajal is coming out
of retirement Feb. 27 to fight a 10-round match at junior
bantamweight vs. Jose De Jesus. Money's the reason, of course . . .
Not every heavyweight can boast of what Jeremy Williams can.
Williams (34-2, 31 KOs) speaks three languages (English, Spanish,
and Arabic) and holds a degree in theology from the University of
Michigan. According to his promoters at Main Events, Williams
considered becoming an imam, a Muslim minister, before turning pro
and says he wants to become a doctor when his career is ended . . .
Cuban defector Joel Casamayor recently won the interim North
American Boxing Federation super featherweight title, beating Jose
Luis Noyola (22-2-1). Casamayor is 14-0 and ranked third in the
world by the IBF . . . Here's a note that proves pettiness doesn't
exist only in US boxing. WBO light heavyweight champion Dariusz
Michalczewski was named 1998's Fighter of the Year by readers of a
German boxing magazine, BoxSport. When he learned that 168-pound
champion Sven Ottke finished a close second, he refused to accept
the award and his promoter, Universum, refused to run its annual
full-page Christmas ad in the magazine . . . Oba Carr waits in the
wings for De La Hoya, with a tentative May 22 date at the new Las
Vegas casino, Mandalay Bay. That was the deal he had when he agreed
to fight Frankie Randall on the De La Hoya-Quartey undercard, a
deal he still finds remarkable. ``Who would say a person like Oba
would be fighting a guy like Oscar?'' Carr said. ``Who would say
there would be a possibility of even talking about that a year ago,
after leaving Don King, after being in so much debt I didn't even
know what the heck to do with my life but kill myself?'' At 26,
Carr (48-2-1) already has been managed by four men, promoted by
several more, and lost two shots at the welterweight title. He was
stopped by Trinidad and dropped a majority decision to Quartey
after having 2 points deducted for low blows. So how did Carr get
back on his feet? ``I wasn't going to allow my past to contaminate
my present so I couldn't continue to evolve,'' he said. ``It's all
about evolution.'' Who's this guy been reading, Darwin? . . .
Harold Weston, who promotes NABF junior welterweight champion
Reggie Green, says he will offer WBA 140-pound champion Sharmba
Mitchell $200,000 to get in with Green. But he says he will not
agree to give Mitchell's promoter, King, future rights to Green's
fights. ``I feel Reggie is the hidden jewel of professional
boxing,'' Weston said. Green is not yet ranked No. 1 by any
organization, however, so forcing a title fight at this juncture
seems unlikely . . . Former Ring magazine editor Steve Farhood has
been named executive editor of the first boxing magazine in
cyberspace. Former heavyweight Crawford Grimsley has created
BoxingMag.com, which he calls ``the Internet portal for boxing
enthusiasts.'' The site features not only the usual written fare
but also live and archival press conferences and interviews, plus a
weekly interview with legendary trainer Angelo Dundee . . . Taking
a cue from Foxwoods's move to sanction its own fights rather than
being under the jurisdiction of the state of Connecticut, the
Miccousukee Indian Gaming casino has decided to run its own
commission, independent of the state of Florida. A five-man
commission headed by Don Hazelton, former executive director of the
Florida commission, will run the casino's growing boxing program .
. . In case you missed it, Chelsea heavyweight contender John Ruiz
was named Puerto Rico's boxer of the year at an awards ceremony in
Ponce last month. Ruiz, who holds the NABF title and the WBC's No.
1 ranking, is scheduled to fight on the Holyfield-Lewis undercard
at Madison Square Garden. He is the first New England heavyweight
to be ranked No. 1 in the world since Rocky Marciano in 1952 and is
the highest-rated Latino heavyweight in boxing history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
