<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-KINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS BEST TEAM YOU'LL NEVER SEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people commissioner David Stern refers to as the NBA's
``broadcast partners'' have conspired to perpetrate a mass
injustice on most of the non-dish, basketball-watching public.
</P>
<P>
   Unless there is a late change _ and there should be _ the
Sacramento Kings will not appear on nationwide television this
season. NBC, of course, never even considered them; it'd rather
televise a Lakers shootaround than stoop to do the Kings or the
Bulls. But TNT/TBS omitted Sacramento as well, which is more of a
surprise, because that network tries to show every NBA team,
including the Clippers, at least once.
</P>
<P>
   But with the new season/schedule, the Kings were given the big
doughnut for nationwide exposure, and that is a shame. Though few
NBA fans anticipated they would care, more and more will want to
give Sacramento a look before season's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, we might start getting looked at a little
differently,'' said coach Rick Adelman. ``But you have to earn
respect in this league from everybody. This is a team which can do
a lot of nice things offensively and has some smart players. We're
not quite the team some people think we are, but we may be. And
because of what we do offensively, we are capable of winning any
night.''
</P>
<P>
   There may not be a more enjoyable team to watch than the
reconfigured Kings. They are among the top-scoring teams in the
league, and if you stayed up last Tuesday to watch them play the
Celtics, you saw an entertaining club with a terrific rookie point
guard _ Jason Williams _ and possibly the NBA's best passing front
line, featuring Chris Webber and Vlade Divac.
</P>
<P>
   Reputations are hard to shed, but this team has been overhauled.
Williams, Webber, and Divac were elsewhere last season. So was
Adelman and his staff. Webber still is, er, adjusting to the scene,
but Williams and Divac appear to be feeling at home already.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like here the most,'' Divac said, ``is that the fans
really support the team. That is very important to the players. It
makes you want to give everything you have. And I like all the
young guys. This is the first time I've felt like one of the old
guys. It's a new experience for me. And it's also a challenge for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The poster boy for the Kings, however, is the flashy Williams,
who is being besieged by the national media. He got booted off the
team at Florida last season, but NBA personnel men knew all about
him. His agent, Bill Pollack, got Dennis Johnson to work with
Williams in Orlando prior to the draft. DJ loved what he saw, and
Williams says he's grateful for the attention and teaching he got
from the old pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked me out hard. He killed me,'' Williams said. ``He got
me in great shape. It was a pleasure to be around him. He got the
best out of me, that's for sure. Without him, I don't think I would
have been drafted seventh, that's for sure. No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has been compared to Pete Maravich, but Celtic great
Bob Cousy watched the rookie against Utah and thought he looked a
lot more like another great guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw much more (John) Stockton in him than Maravich,'' Cooz
said. ``Every pass he made was solid, conservative. He's got the
range, he can penetrate, he's solid on his dribble. I love the kid.
I love him without the flair.''
</P>
<P>
   The flair, however, is part of the package. Kings GM Geoff
Petrie noted that Williams is ``a presence'' on the floor, and he's
right. He also knew what he was getting on draft day because the
Kings (a) had done their homework and (b) knew that talent-spotter
extraordinaire Jerry West was slobbering all over him. (If West had
managed to come out of the draft with Williams, we could have ended
the season now and simply given the title to the Lakers.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He was at a position where we had been weak for a very long
time and a position in the NBA that's very, very important,'' said
Petrie. ``After spending a lot of time with him and looking at all
the tape we could, we were as convinced as you can be. On talent,
it wasn't that much of a gamble. He's been terrific for us. All the
things we thought he could do, he's been able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe one of these days people actually will get to see this kid
play without having to buy a ticket or a satellite dish. Then
again, he's probably worth the expense. So, too, is his team.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is crazy. The players aren't in shape. The coaches
are angry that the schedule is crazy and the players aren't in
shape. There's another contingent going through conditioning woes:
the referees. Under normal circumstances, the 57 league officials
would have attended four days of film work, rules discussions, and
medical tests prior to the exhibition season. Included were two
days for a physical, one component of which is a stress test. There
was no such gathering this year. The referees were on their own to
get in shape and get their own physicals. ``So far, we've had two
lost games due to injuries,'' league operations chief Rod Thorn
said. ``One guy missed a game with a bad back and the other was due
to a groin. But they returned for the next game.'' Thorn said the
real killer for the referees is the schedule. They're no more
accustomed to working four games in five days than the players are
to playing them. Unlike the players, they don't have the
conveniences of team travel. ``The trips are coming fast and
furious,'' Thorn said, ``and there isn't quite as much down time.''
. . . Speaking of conditioning, Rick Pitino is making it clear to
his players that he will never tolerate another offseason like the
one he just endured. He used words like ``flabbergasted'' to
describe how he felt about the shape in which his players reported.
(Antoine Walker was the biggest miscreant.) ``I'm just bitterly
disappointed, and I'll tell you this: It will never happen again,''
he said. Pitino is repeating his ``request'' that all Celtics move
to the Boston area year-round. ``They play for the Boston
Celtics,'' he said. ``This should be their home. And now we have a
place where they can work out. And if they don't want to make it
their home, we'll find another home for them.'' He quickly added
that Walker would be allowed to live in Chicago because of his
daughter. ``But he is going to have to hire a personal trainer,''
Pitino said. ``He can afford one. Michael Jordan went to a golf
tournament and brought his trainer with him; Antoine is going to
have to do the same thing.'' . . . And then there's Bryant ``Big
Country'' Reeves. If you watched him on television last Wednesday,
you may have wondered what the fuss was all about. Well, Reeves is
down to his playing weight of around 292 pounds after showing up
for camp around 320. The Grizzlies put him on an intensive workout
regimen, which featured 10 miles on the exercise bike and 2,000
feet on the vertical climber each day. The Grizzlies are going to
demand that Reeves hire a trainer as well, so that mom's home
cooking back in Gans, Okla., doesn't get the better of him again.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   As we continue to be amazed by Paul Pierce, we can also remind
you that one of the reasons he slid to No. 10 was that two teams
that liked him, Toronto and Sacramento, did not appeal to him. ``He
called us the day he was supposed to be here for a workout and said
he was injured,'' Petrie recalled. ``I thought that was interesting
because I had just seen him the night before playing in Los
Angeles. We knew we passed on a terrific prospect in Paul, but
everyone seems happy with the way things turned out.'' As for
Vancouver, which picked second, coach Brian Hill said, ``We were
going to take him, but we felt we had to address our point guard
situation. We're very happy with Mike (Bibby), but Paul is a great
addition to that team.'' . . . It took 73 minutes to play the 15
minutes of overtime in the Celtics-Grizzlies game. Last Sunday's
game between Indiana and the Lakers featured six timeouts and two
20-second timeouts in the final 26.6 seconds. By the way, there is
an extra timeout this season. It comes in the first stoppage of
play after the 10-minute mark in the second and fourth quarters.
The timeout was there for the past few years for NBC and TNT games.
Now it's there for all games . . . The league and the Players
Association have agreed to extend by one month the date to sign
free agents. Under the old rules, teams could sign free agents
starting July 1. That date will now be Aug. 1, although teams can
contact free agents and talk to them on July 1. The reason for the
delay is to enable an actual salary cap figure to be established.
Previously, teams operated under an assumed cap figure; the real
one didn't come out until the auditing was finished in mid-August.
``This time, we're going to rush the accountants a little harder
and they'll have the figure by the first,'' said union attorney Ron
Klempner. It also will give attorneys in both offices some time for
vacation . . . Not to be negative, but if you heard Dennis Rodman
on ESPN Friday, you'd have to think long and hard about signing
him. Asked about the Lakers, Rodman said, ``I'm not nowhere near
close signing with the Lakers.'' (Is that three or four negatives?)
He also said Miami was a possibility and that Chicago was out . . .
The second week of three games in three nights went a lot better
for the tired teams. Miami, for instance, went 3-0 on successive
nights while the Suns and Rockets each won on the road on the third
night. Houston sneaked by New Jersey with Scottie Pippen playing
the entire second half and all of the overtime. By the way, if
you're still uncertain as to why Pippen was so eager to leave
Chicago, read the cover story in the latest ESPN Magazine. One of
the nuggets unearthed was that Chicago GM Jerry Krause, whom Pippen
detests, demanded that he be able to talk to Pippen after the trade
with Houston was completed. Pippen got on the phone and said all
the right things, then hung up and said, ``That was hard to
swallow.'' He also said that if the Bulls had taken care of him and
Jordan the way Houston took care of him, the two would still be in
Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
