<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BLACKHAWKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK CLOUD HOVERS OVER BLACKHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a revoltin' development. The Blackhawks missed the playoffs
last season for the first time since 1969, handed Doug Gilmour an
$18 million promise over the summer when they finished out of the
Brett Hull money chase, and since have established themselves as
the worst thing on double-runners this side of Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Hawks are so bad (16-34-8) that perhaps a bolt of
lightning would be good for what ails 'em. This isn't a team in
need of a makeover. It's in need of a complete overhaul, from front
office to coaching staff to player personnel. They are now on the
fast track to miss the playoffs again, their first back-to-back
flops since 1957 and '58.
</P>
<P>
   They are slow, old, and in severe need of a young star to ignite
them. The closest thing they've got is Tony Amonte, the 28-year-old
former Boston University sniper who jumped out among the league's
top goal scorers early in the season, only to taper off (he still
has a pretty impressive 29 strikes) as the Hawks barreled headlong
into the abyss.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks aren't alone in their Original Six malaise. Only
Toronto and Detroit have winning records among the half-dozen of
the game's ancient elite. The Original Six aren't doing much better
than the NHL's six most recent expansion clubs:
</P>
<P>
   (through Friday) &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Original Six Latest Six &QC; 
Toronto +11 Ottawa +15
</P>
<P>
   Detroit +8 Florida -1
</P>
<P>
   Boston -2 Anaheim -2
</P>
<P>
   Montreal -4 San Jose -4
</P>
<P>
   NY Rangers -5 Nashville -12
</P>
<P>
   Chicago -18 Tampa Bay -27
</P>
<P>
   Total -10 Total -31
</P>
<P>
   Sure makes you wonder about the prestige and mystique of the
game's old guard, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hawks GM Bob Murray sent the fur flying last week
when he said the club's only two untouchables were Amonte and
netminder Jocelyn Thibault. That could mean both Gilmour and Chris
Chelios are up for grabs as the March 23 trading deadline
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Chelios, amid rumors that he will be shoveled
imminently to Philadelphia for Dainius Zubrus. And why not?
Because, he said, the deal he signed with Chicago (through next
season) included a handshake with owner Bill Wirtz pledging that he
would not trade Chelios. When word broke of that private pact last
week, it appeared that Murray was one of two things: (1) out to
lunch or (2) out to move Chelios, no matter what side deal might
have been promised.
</P>
<P>
   Chelios, on the rumor that he'll be dealt to the Flyers: ``I
don't want to go anywhere. You should tell (Flyers GM) Bobby Clarke
to shut his mouth. Just tell Bobby Clarke to leave me alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the continuing case of Alexei Zhamnov, the skilled
28-year-old center whom the Hawks received upon dumping Jeremy
Roenick in a fire sale _ a blunderous deal that ranks up there with
Montreal dumping Patrick Roy. Rather than be held hostage by
Roenick's contract demands, the Hawks showed JR the door (which led
him to paradise in Phoenix) and willingly inherited Zhamnov's,
shall we say, enigmatic approach to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Benched when the Hawks played Phoenix two weeks ago, Zhamnov
developed a bad back 48 hours later and hasn't been in the lineup
since. When the Hawks visited Ottawa Monday _ a week into his bad
back _ they didn't bother bringing him along for the ride. Is he
hurt? Is he healthy? Does anyone care?
</P>
<P>
   All this has been going on with ex-Hawk Dirk Graham making it up
as he goes along behind the bench. His grit as a player hasn't
translated into either motivational or technical prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour, game as he may be, was a skill acquisition for a team
that was more in need of rank-and-file character players. He's a
Picasso, an aging one at that, on a team with a lot of
paint-by-numbers to be done.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Murray, who took over the 3 1/2-decade
rebuilding program from Bob Pulford in the summer of '97. The Hawks
finished nine games under .500 his first year, and this time around
they could finish 25 or more below break even.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, no powerhouse themselves, will be here Sunday for a
first-hand look at the horrible Hawks. It's a grim picture, and an
especially sad one for the league. Bad management. Bad players.
Another of the Original Six gone from riches to rags.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ruslan Salei, the Ducks' tough defenseman, started playing the
game on outside rinks in Minsk. Some days were so cold, he
recalled, that players waited in warm locker rooms between line
changes, braving the cold only in one-minute shifts. He pocketed
about $200 a month, a far cry from his deal in Anaheim that will
bring him $2.25 million over three years. ``It's not fair when I am
making so much money,'' he said, ``driving an expensive car, and
eating in expensive restaurants, and over there people are fighting
for a loaf of bread.'' . . . Phil Housley might never be accused of
playing defense, but he'll bank another $2.5 million behind the
Calgary blue line next season. His contract, originally signed when
he went to the Capitals as a free agent, called for him to make $3
million next season _ at the club's option. The Flames said they
wouldn't bite at that figure, essentially leaving him to become a
free agent again on July 1, at age 35. But for the $2.5 million,
and the opportunity not to uproot his family again, Housley decided
to remain a Flame . . . The Sharks have a new defenseman, Shawn
Heins, who earlier this month unloaded a slap shot that was clocked
at 106 miles per hour _ the fastest one ever recorded (0.8 miles
per hour faster than the missile Al Iafrate launched at the '93
All-Star skills competition). The difference between Canada and the
US: Heins, 6 feet 4 inches and 220 pounds, was featured on Page 1
in Thursday's editions of the Ottawa Citizen the day before he was
to make his NHL debut with the San Jose Sharks. ``I loved the sound
of the tennis ball hitting the door,'' Heins told the Citizen,
recounting his childhood in suburban Ottawa. ``When we missed the
net, mom would hear the thud in the house, and she would yell at us
to stop. The dents in the door are still there.'' . . . A day after
acquiring 6-7 defenseman (and sometimes wing) Chris McAllister from
the Canucks, the Leafs gave up on former first-rounder Jeff Ware
(No. 15 overall in '95) and dished him to the Panthers for right
winger David Nemirovsky (No. 84 in '94). ``The new team policy,''
said a deadpan Mike Smith, the Leafs' associate GM, ``is a trade a
day until the trade deadline.'' . . . Players Association boss Bob
Goodenow last week enumerated the players' lead complaints: (1) bad
ice; (2) seamless glass. Goodenow: ``It's tough enough to stay
healthy and play well, but when you have bad ice conditions and you
have the seamless glass and the injuries that flow from that, it's
a more dangerous environment in which to play.'' . . . Mario
Lemieux acknowledged for the first time last week that he is trying
to round up investors to buy the Penguins and keep them in
Pittsburgh. He'll need a minimum $40 million just to get in the
game. It's a growing belief around the league that Mario Magnifique
won't see the bundle of deferred dough he's owed unless he is part
of a new Penguin ownership package. That's another way of saying
his deal wasn't protected against franchise insolvency, and with
the Penguins now under bankruptcy protection, he could be faced
with settling for pennies on the dollar _ or perhaps less. Roger
Marino, current co-owner, took some heat weeks ago when he began to
look at out-of-town suitors. But don't be surprised to see Lemieux,
if it's the only way he can salvage what he's owed, ultimately go
on the same shopping tour. Get that green carpet ready, Hartford .
. . Uh-oh. The Habs finally are healthy. Witness their 6-3 pasting
of the Rangers Wednesday night. ``They looked like the '79
Canadiens,'' reported eyewitness Gord Kluzak to the Montreal
Gazette. For those who have chosen to forget, those would be the
52-17-11 and Cup-winning Canadiens, who clobbered the Rangers in a
five-game final.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Patrik, who figures to be the top choice in the amateur
draft, June 26 at the FleetCenter, was cleared to return to the
Long Beach Ice Dogs (IHL) this weekend, after missing nearly three
months because of a concussion. He had 23 points in 20 games before
getting dinged . . . The NHL last week requested that the AHL adopt
a four-on-four format, each club playing a man down, for overtime.
The read here: just another gimmick, akin to the shootout. The
Lords of the Boards should be more concerned about what goes on for
the 60 minutes of regulation play. Call penalties. Call more
penalty shots. Make 'em play the puck. Don't allow the team killing
a penalty to ice it. The point of the exercise should be to win in
regulation, not to keep conjuring OT schemes . . . The deal that
didn't get done: Theo Fleury to Los Angeles for Pavel Rosa (RW) and
Yanic Perreault (27). Word is, Fleury wouldn't accept $30 million
over five years to leave Calgary for Los Angeles . . . Bobby Orr
worked the bench at the Prospects Game _ the showcase for the top
amateurs available in the June draft _ in Calgary Tuesday night,
opposed again by ex-Bruins coach Don Cherry on the other bench.
Orr, who works as an agent with Jay Fee at Woolf and Associates
here in Boston, heard the familiar questions about possible
conflict of interest (i.e. an agent wearing a coach's hat, possibly
recruiting clients, influencing ice time). Cherry hurried to his
defense: ``When he walks into the room, it's like God's just walked
in.'' Orr offered a more subtle, ``I won't be passing out business
cards.'' . . . The last goal scored at Maple Leaf Gardens came off
the stick of Chicago tough guy Bob Probert (of all the gin joints
in all the world, he had to walk in . . .). He wasn't sure what
he'd do with the puck, but Gilmour, an ex-Leaf, offered him $100
(Canadian funds). The Hockey Hall of Fame would like to have it,
but as of Friday the Hall still had no confirmation that Probert
would hand over the prized biscuit. Hands off, Home Shopping
Network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
