<HEADLINE>
UCLA FACES KEY TEST AGAINST SYRACUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA and Syracuse meet today in Pauley Pavilion in
a nonconference game that, for the Bruins at least, carries as much
weight as a conference game.
</P>
<P>
   They won't win the Pac-10 and they won't get a top seed in the
NCAA Tournament. But defeating Syracuse _ a top-25 team with a
victory over Connecticut _ could be the difference between, say, a
No.4 seed and a No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a high-level conference game against Stanford,
Arizona or Washington,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``It's on
national TV, with recruiting. There are a lot of factors that make
this special.''
</P>
<P>
   The list starts with seeding. The Bruins and Orangemen, who have
never met, have similar resumes. Both have 18 wins overall and nine
wins in league play. UCLA is ranked 16th, with a victory over
Arizona. Syracuse is 21st, with a victory over Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game can matter, in talking with selection committee
members,'' Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim said. ``When they start to
seed, they say, `Look at this win, look at that win.' When they get
in that room, they look at the schedule and see who you beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like an NCAA Tournament game. This is who we could
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, for both teams, avoid playing.
</P>
<P>
   Road winners: Surprisingly, Syracuse has played better on the
road (6-2) than in the Carrier Dome (9-6). Like UCLA, the Orangemen
have no senior starters and have battled inconsistency: Five days
after winning at Connecticut, they lost at home to Villanova.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no answer,'' Boeheim said. ``You'd figure with a young
team, it'd be the other way around. Maybe our players think they're
supposed to win at home and they try a little too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In a zone? In recent years, the Orangemen have played one of the
best zone defenses in the nation _ a 2-3 alignment that covers the
court, denies passing lanes and intimidates in the post.
</P>
<P>
   Boeheim estimated the Orangemen have played 40 percent zone this
year because their perimeter quickness often makes man-to-man a
better option. But don't be surprised if the 2-3 makes an
appearance today. The Bruins have struggled against zones all
season and they haven't faced one like Syracuse's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only zone I've seen better is Temple's,'' Boeheim said.
</P>
<P>
   Homecoming: Syracuse has two Los Angeles natives, starting point
guard Jason Hart and reserve guard Tony Bland.
</P>
<P>
   Bland, a freshman, was a teammate of UCLA redshirt Billy Knight
at Westchester High. Hart, a junior who played at Inglewood High,
leads Syracuse in scoring (13.8 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get him less excited,'' Boeheim said. ``Jason is
an emotional player.''
</P>
<P>
   Board work: UCLA's rebounding has slipped in recent weeks
because of the injury to forward Jerome Moiso and ineffective play
of center Dan Gadzuric.
</P>
<P>
   Outrebounded in five or their last six games, the Bruins face
one of their biggest, most physical opponents of the season today.
Syracuse's frontline measures 6-9, 6-8 and 6-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to be effective in the tournament, we have to have
collective rebounding,'' Lavin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
