<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS NEED SOME STARR POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I grow up _ with an emphasis on ``when'' _ I want to be
Kenneth Starr, independent counsel. What's not appealing about
unlimited budget, unlimited investigatiive power and a subpoena
hammer that transforms the uncooperative into singing canaries?
</P>
<P>
   But why waste all that on politics? Now that his chores in
Washington are basically done, hopefully Mr. Starr can move on to
more important work.
</P>
<P>
   Ken, we need you in sports. Pronto. Clear it with Janet, and
then report immediately for duty.
</P>
<P>
   Once on board, investigate this:
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones said last week he's planning contract extensions and
fat new raises for quarterback Troy Aikman and cornerback Deion
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   That makes as much sense as the Tarrant County commissioners
voting a hefty salary bump for Sheriff Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Mr. Starr, this smells of a land deal in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman already makes an average of $5 million-plus a season
under an existing contract that has three years remaining. And
those three years will average $8.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offensive production the last two seasons has
resembled Henry Hyde and the House managers' visit to the Senate.
Lot of talk, no points on the board.
</P>
<P>
   As the offensive leader, Aikman takes the hit for the failure.
If anything, he's overpaid at the moment. This is the ultimate team
player, but the team results haven't been good lately.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Nine-Toed Deion.
</P>
<P>
   Ken, you'll definitely need the grand jury for this witness.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of last season, Nine-Toed took six weeks to
limp his way back into the Cowboys' lineup, but a month after the
season ended, he's playing in the Pro Bowl. Legally, how long is
the statute of limitations on medical fraud?
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas Stadium locker room following the Arizona playoff
loss, Sanders hobbled around like a brave warrior who was on his
last leg, or toe. The beach battle in ``Saving Private Ryan''
wasn't this dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Would Deion ever walk again, much less play football?
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, four weeks later Sanders was frolicking in
Hawaii, having a great time at cornerback in a painless and
meaningless performance. Meaningless, that is, except for putting
Deion back in a football spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   And just think, Mr. Starr, you doubted Betty Currie's testimony.
What the heck you gonna do with a Deion?
</P>
<P>
   Just for the record, Sanders is always the first Cowboy to point
fingers when things go wrong _ he's our local Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Deion was running his filibuster mouth loudly after the Arizona
upset, talking about the ``team stars'' who weren't performing up
to standard or salary. This was aimed at Aikman and the offense.
Nice team player, this Deion.
</P>
<P>
   And Ken, in your cross-examination of Jones, also consider the
January testimony of that distinguished football gentleman from New
York, Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he had elevated the Jets so quickly to Super
Bowl-contender status, Parcells said, ``for one thing, I don't pay
a cornerback $35 million.'' He meant Jerry and he meant Deion.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing, Mr. Starr, will apparently change the mind of Jones
on Deion. When on the field, Sanders is the best at what he does,
be it pass coverage or punt returns. The problem, however, is Deion
staying on the field, for whatever weak excuse. What we have here
is a player who doesn't answer the roll call often enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have played 33 games in the past two seasons.
Sanders has missed nine, plus the second half of two others. In 11
of the past 33 games, exactly one-third, he has declared himself
not physically fit for duty.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a guy who will be asking Jones for $10 million a
season and a $15 million signing bonus. He might get it, too.
</P>
<P>
   One obvious question:
</P>
<P>
   How many players with a much better Sunday attendance record
could the Cowboys sign if Jones would dump this prima donna?
</P>
<P>
   Jerry is making a mistake on Sanders. Get him outta here. And
don't bump Aikman's salary either.
</P>
<P>
   That's my testimony, Mr. Starr, but obviously you have much to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Do note, however, that in the on-going salary cap bind for
Jones, he can continue with his theory of
save-now-and-pay-for-it-later on Sanders and Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   With new contracts for both, Jerry will shave immediate cap
dollars, and then worry later about the consequences. Actually,
that's what this bootleg play is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Winning will not return to Valley Ranch without the proper
quarterback in place. Aikman is the only hope. But winning is not
about an overpaid cornerback who plays when he wants to play. See
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Go get 'em, Ken _ investigate like crazy. And maybe this is a
case you can actually win. Maybe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
