</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-VIET-PROTEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPLAY OF HO CHI MINH POSTER SPURS PROTEST AND ARRESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTMINSTER, Calif. _The Vietnamese immigrant who has battled
his former countrymen here for weeks about his right to display a
poster of Ho Chi Minh in his video store rehung the picture on
Saturday, but it took dozens of police officers and sheriff's
deputies to protect him and the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Dodging eggs, oranges and curses, the police hustled the
merchant, Truong Van Tran, and his wife, Kim, into the store
shortly before 10 a.m., as hundreds of protesters screamed ``Down
with Communism'' and threatened to break through a thick line of
officers.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters surged forward at least three times, bending the
line but not breaking it. By 10:15, the police had arrested about a
dozen protesters, including a man who took a swing at the officers
and a woman who rammed into the line with a stroller containing two
children.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the store, Tran, 37, climbed a metal ladder and fastened
the poster and the flag of Vietnam to the wall with colored pins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel happy,'' Tran said after he and his wife bowed their
heads in front of the display that has caused so much debate in
this city south of Los Angeles where tens of thousands of
Vietnamese, most of them refugees from South Vietnam, live in a
neighborhood called Little Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   But minutes later, Tran cried when he tried to explain that he
loved his people here and in Vietnam and that he wanted to help
chase away the ghosts of the Vietnam War that still haunt so many.
</P>
<P>
   To begin the healing, Tran said, his fellow immigrants must
learn to accept different views about their homeland without
resorting to intimidation and violence. In the 1980s, people in
Little Saigon were beaten and sometimes killed if they said
anything remotely positive about normalizing relations with
Vietnam. Stores that did business with Vietnam were burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not afraid to do the right,'' Tran said. ``I want to
communicate with the Vietnamese community. I want to help the
Vietnamese community to live in peace.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese immigrants began arriving here in large numbers in
1975 after the fall of Saigon in the last days of the war. The
memories of the bloodshed and their frightening flight from the
Communists whom Ho Chi Min led until his death in 1969 are never
far away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Bill Lewis of the Westminster Police Department said that
during negotiations with Tran and the protesters over the last few
days, some of the protesters threatened to set themselves on fire
if Tran was allowed to hang the poster.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they were going to do what the monks did in Vietnam
in the mid-'60s,'' Lewis said. ``That's the kind of emotion we've
been dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   No one set himself on fire on Saturday, but numerous people
screamed themselves hoarse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who killed my father?'' a woman chanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ho Chi Minh,'' the crowded shouted back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who killed my brother?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ho Chi Minh.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many here lost a loved one during the war, which killed
millions of Vietnamese from both north and south, including members
of Tran's family. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a communist,'' said Tran, who fled southwest Vietnam
and the communist regime for the United States in 1980. ``I do not
think the communists do well in my country. They have to do more to
change. But who helps them to change?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The protests outside of the store, Hi-Tek, began last month
after Tran put up the poster and the flag and then sent a fax to a
Vietnamese group, daring it to take down the display. Tran said he
was trying to engage the group in debate.
</P>
<P>
   His former countrymen showed up by the hundreds to demand that
the picture of ``Ho, the mass murderer'' be taken down. Tran
refused. But after five days of increasingly tense protests, an
Orange County Superior Court judge ordered the display removed
pending a hearing. Last week, the judge said Tran had the First
Amendment right to hang the items. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the ruling, more than 600 protesters gathered in
front of the store, and were met by more than 100 police officers.
Fearing violence, the authorities ordered Tran to stay away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But at 4:30 a.m. Saturday, the police returned to the store and
caught the handful of protesters there off guard, pushing them
behind a barricade.
</P>
<P>
   The police could not get Tran into the shop as quickly as they
had hoped. A locksmith had to be called in to break a chain that
the protesters had used to lock Tran out.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the door was opened and Tran was driven into the
parking lot in a police van, the ranks of the protesters had grown
to about 300, and more arrived throughout the morning. Tran said he
was going to stay in his shop until noon, but the police whisked
him away by 10:30.
</P>
<P>
   Tran has been served with an eviction notice, but he has vowed
to fight it, reopen his store and continue renting videos like the
two on his display counter: ``Ghosts That Still Walk'' and ``Last
Man Standing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
