<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV MOVIE RESONATES ESSENCE, IF NOT FACTS, OF ALMA MATER'S SAGA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a proud alumnus of New Orleans' Jesuit High School, Class of
1966, there is a lot not to like about tonight's TNT network movie,
``Passing Glory''.
</P>
<P>
   But I'll get over it.
</P>
<P>
   The message is significant, even if my alma mater has been
reduced in the movie to a gullible, misleading, misguided
stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   The time was February 1965, the same week, as it turns out, that
civil rights activist Malcolm X was shot.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1962, Jesuit had become the first all-white high
school in the city to admit black students. It prompted the Ku Klux
Klan to picket our front sidewalk. A year or so later, we arrived
one morning to find that our campus chapel had been painted with
slurs and hate symbols.
</P>
<P>
   To us, it came with the territory. The Jesuit priests and
scholastics (priests-to-be) at our school had preached a gospel of
social justice from the day we walked through the big oaken doors.
</P>
<P>
   Confront the Klan? A good Jesuit would have tried to debate one
into tiny knots.
</P>
<P>
   Our priests marched to their own drummer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, these were the '60s. We were being prepared for a brave new
world not of separate but equal, but of equality and opportunity
for all. Voices were going to be raised, and the Jesuits were
training us to listen.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why so many of my fellow Jesuit alums are going to
have a hard time with ``Passing Glory''. It is a movie about a
basketball game _ a scrimmage, actually. A game played in ringing
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Until Feb. 26, 1965, athletic teams in Louisiana with both white
and black faces had never appeared together on the same basketball
court. But on that day they did _ in my own high school gym, behind
doors that were locked to keep out the media, the curious and the
police who, it was feared by some, might barge in and try to halt
the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   St. Augustine High School, operated by the Josephite Fathers,
was a Catholic, all-boys high school and a perennial basketball
powerhouse. In 1965, the Purple Knights stormed toward the
Louisiana Interscholastic, Athletic and Literary Organization
(LIALO) playoffs with a 30-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   Jesuit also was a Catholic, all-boys high school and was in the
middle of a three-year run of state basketball championships in the
Louisiana High School Athletic Association (LHSAA). The Blue Jays
were 26-1, the lone loss coming early in the season to a team from
Pensacola, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But the bylaws of the white-only LHSAA prohibited its teams from
playing black-only LIALO teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were preparing for a state championship and were concerned
about doing anything that might jeopardize that,'' said the Rev. J.
Donald Pearce, who was Jesuit's athletic director. ``We didn't know
what the LHSAA might do.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Aug principal at the time, the Rev. Robert Grant, pushed
for a game that might eventually pave the way for his school's
acceptance into the LHSAA. Jesuit administration offered, instead,
a scrimmage _ five quarters, no media coverage, with only family
members allowed inside a locked gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, with Hollywood embellishment, the game takes on
grandiose, Rosa Parks-sized proportions. One of the St. Aug
players, Harold Sylvester, wrote the screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   The network's publicity packet for the movie blares, ``Fr.
Joseph Verrett ignites the sparks of the civil rights movement in
New Orleans ... to forever change the established social order.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not really. The script conveniently ignores that black
students had been attending Jesuit for three years. Indeed, it
takes Hollywood liberties with a lot of things about my alma mater
in the movie (red uniforms?) _ reducing us, in a way, to
stool-pigeon stereotypes. African-Americans have been accusing TV
and movies of doing the same thing to them for years.
</P>
<P>
   When we feel that we have to exaggerate history to make our
point, don't we start to sound like our fathers did when they told
tall tales of five-mile uphill walks to school in the snow?
</P>
<P>
   But Sylvester's testament to the times is worth absorbing. In
1965, there were barriers to topple. They fell almost daily _ but
still too slow for some.
</P>
<P>
   Today's high school students will find the St. Aug-Jesuit saga
hard to believe. As Sylvester said by telephone, ``For them, to
think that people as close to them as their parents went through
this is tough to come to terms with.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems ludicrous that these two high-profile teams could meet
and still maintain the veil of silence. Yet they did. More than a
week passed, when finally a St. Augustine source leaked news of the
game to a columnist for the local Catholic weekly newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The Purple Knights had ``won,'' 81-59. Their best player, Isiah
King, had scored 26 points. There was no mention about the
scrimmage or the five quarters or the most disturbing thing, to us,
about the historic meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, two Jesuit starters, Ronnie Britsch and Joe Williamson,
had not played. Britsch said last week that his father wouldn't let
him, because he didn't want his son, now a New Orleans dentist, to
jeopardize a college scholarship. Williamson said he wasn't allowed
to play because he was sick. Between them, the two starting guards
averaged 35 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Jesuit's star player is a fictitious Mike Malone.
In one compelling scene, neck reddening, Malone's father tries to
pull his son off the floor in the middle of the game. Two Jesuit
parents shout at the elder Malone to get off the floor and let the
kids play.
</P>
<P>
   Two more basketball seasons passed before a federal judge
finally forced the LHSAA to change its antediluvian rules and allow
schools like St. Augustine to join its ranks. The LIALO soon
disbanded. Voices were raised _ and people listened.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, that 1965 Jesuit team rolled through its state
playoffs, scoring more than 100 points twice in its final two
games. One week after the scrimmage, St. Augustine lost in the
first round of the LIALO playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Today, St. Aug and Jesuit continue to fight for first place in
the same basketball district.
</P>
<P>
   In its own silent way, my alma mater helped pave a way for that.
The Jesuit fathers who taught us in the '60s would surely approve.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody finally let the kids play. Even if Hollywood hadn't
noticed, there were good reasons to be proud of that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
