<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-CLEMENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS SKIPS TEXAS FOR BETTER SERIES SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Roger Clemens' agent said the chance to win a
World Series was the main reason he accepted a trade to the New
York Yankees rather than hold out for a chance to pitch with the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Hendricks said yesterday the Yankees were three times more
likely to win the World Series than the Rangers and that was more
important than Clemens' desire to pitch in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks, arriving with Clemens yesterday at the Yankees spring
training facility, was reacting to Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin's comments last week when the Toronto Blue Jays traded the
five-time Cy Young Award winner to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who lives outside Houston, had the right to veto any
trade according to an agreement between Clemens and the Blue Jays.
Melvin said he was misled into believing Clemens' No. 1 goal was to
pitch close to home when he originally demanded a trade from the
Blue Jays last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was some frustration on Doug's part because he
had been working hard on this for two months,'' said Hendricks, who
accused the Rangers of whining. ``We have a good relationship with
Doug and a high regard for him, but he's taking into consideration
just one part of the equation. He's not considering the \RWorld
Series\S ring factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger wants to win a World Series. There's a distinction
between being qualified to make the playoffs and being qualified to
win the World Series. The Yankees are the most qualified to win the
World Series. The Yankees have a 60 percent chance of winning the
World Series, the Rangers have a 20 percent chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, reached at the Rangers' camp in Port Charlotte, said,
``That's fine, but say that from the start. Say your No. 1 priority
is to go to New York and if it doesn't work out, get back to us. We
thought he wanted to be closer to home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers thought they had Clemens on Wednesday for outfielder
Ruben Mateo and two other players. But Toronto general manager Gord
Ash made one more call to the Yankees and instead traded Clemens to
the defending world champions for pitchers David Wells and Graeme
Lloyd and second baseman Homer Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, talking before his first workout with the Yankees, said
he had no idea the Rangers had worked out a deal with the Blue
Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week ago I was planning to be \Rwith the Blue Jays\S,''
Clemens said. ``I didn't think anything was happening. It was real
quiet until Randy called late in the evening Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said a trade was imminent, said it was the Yankees and
asked, is it on or isn't it. I said let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his stated desire to pitch in Texas, Clemens said,
``We've talked about that many times. It would have been great.
It's hindsight now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to be here. This is a great opportunity for me. I
have an opportunity to go out there in Yankee Stadium and be a part
of tradition, the monuments ... it's exciting. I can't wait to get
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks also said the Rangers should have been willing to give
up Mateo before Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruben Mateo was asked for by the Blue Jays from December
through February,'' Hendricks said. ``It was not until this week he
was included. If Roger was that important to them, why was Ruben
Mateo not included before so we could have been presented with a
trade in January?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my answer to the Texas Rangers' public whining about
Roger.''
</P>
<P>
   But Melvin said, ``Ruben Mateo earlier wouldn't have gotten the
deal done. We were still talking about Ruben Mateo, plus other
players. For example, Mateo and \RRick\S Helling, which we didn't
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said he has not spoken to Hendricks or his brother Alan
since the trade was completed but will try to call them tomorrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
