<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ASU-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WILL TAKE TIME TO LEARN THE EVANS' WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - A little late, but they finally get it. Finally
they understand why the new coach is in their face all the time,
waking them up to take drug tests, bringing them back for night
practices, demanding the kind of effort that they've never given
before.
</P>
<P>
   When you fly all over the court, when you play Doberman defense,
when you focus for 40 minutes, you thrash inferior basketball
teams. Like Oregon State. A team that, incredibly, beat Arizona
State by 30 earlier in the season.
</P>
<P>
   On a Saturday afternoon where empty seats stuck out like
tombstones, you realize just how far this program has fallen, just
how dysfunctional it has become. Since 1991, they've had a total of
six players stick around for four years. And in the past five
years, only four have played over 100 games, one being the immortal
Hedake Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The point-shaving scandal has drifted away, but what remains is
the reason the Sun Devils have likely blown their chance at an NCAA
berth: Softness. Low expectations. A toleration of failure that has
permeated the walls of Wells Fargo Arena.
</P>
<P>
   People have begun to wonder why ASU can't execute in the waning
moments of close games. It's not the play-calling. It's not really
a lack of talent, either. It's just a bunch of kids who don't win
because they're not winners. Because they're not consumed with the
idea. Because losing has always been acceptable in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Evans, the new coach who is terrorizing the old malaise,
knows what he's fighting. Other people's recruits. The permanent
stain of bad coaching. A party school that attracts kids for
reasons other than discipline and total commitment and banners that
hang from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all said and done, we're going to win some
championships,'' Evans sighed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the rebuilding hit rock bottom. Mike Batiste blew off
an academic session and had to run five miles at 5 a.m. on
successive days, including the morning of a game, just to avoid
suspension. And on Thursday, with an NCAA berth still attainable,
the Sun Devils offered an unforgivable effort in a loss to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Awvee Storey _ a transfer from Illinois who is
sitting out the season _ bolted into the locker room and blasted
his new teammates for their laziness. That night, Evans didn't
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   So. What's it like to run five miles at 5 a.m.?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to know,'' Batiste said. ``It's not so much the
running, but it's the time. It's dark. It's cold. You're in your
sweats.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's what I like about Coach Evans. There's no room for
mistakes in his program. Just look at the way we practice. You're
beat down. You're tired. And he's going to be up in your face,
getting you to compete. And he's going to stay in your face until
he gets it.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday, they never competed like Evans did. Like Evans
wants. At least not for 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some rebellion, of course, because old habits die
hard. Because this team got tired of working as hard as Evans makes
them. Because they never had to before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the first time in my life that I've played defense so
competitively and aggressively,'' Batiste said. ``I wish he was
here when I was a freshman. I wish I had four years being taught
defense and discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he does, maybe he doesn't. But in a couple of years, Evans
will have his kind of kids here. One is Tanner Shell, who scored 27
points for Mountain View on Friday, playing with torn ligaments in
his ankle. Another is Chris Osborne, a kid from Los Angeles who got
so mad following a cheap shot that he punched the opponent in the .
. . uh, groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tone kids down,'' Evans said. ``But you can't tone
them up.''
</P>
<P>
   No, you can't. And that's the reason why ASU can always play
them close, always flirt with the tournament. And the reason why,
in the end, they don't beat Arizona or UCLA. Why they always break
your heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Baron Davis wants a basket, you don't stop him, no matter
who he has to go through, if he has to slit your throat to do it,''
Evans said. ``Same thing with Jason Terry. You need those kind of
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Evans will get them. If he got them to sign with Ole
Miss, he'll get them to sign here. In two years, the Sun Devils
will be worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to take this program to another level,'' Batiste
said. ``Don't be surprised when it happens. He's going to get some
ballplayers up in here. He's going to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, all of the evidence will be gone. The Frieder factor. The
laziness. The nonchalance about losing and the indifference towards
winning. Everything that makes an underachieving program attract
5,000 fans for a weekend matinee.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Sun Devils met Evans' vision. A victory so
complete and thorough that it made you smile with hope. And made
you angry about the timing.
</P>
<P>
   A little late. But they finally get it. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
