<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-OREGON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA WINS BATTLE WITH OREGON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Thanks to another game-winning shot by Jason Terry,
Arizona had just held off the Oregon Ducks, who were more foul than
fowl, in a physical battle Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But thoughts immediately turned to UA's trip to the Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth-ranked Wildcats on Saturday will visit Pac-10 leader
Stanford, where they could move into a share of the lead. First, UA
faces California on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anyone talking about Stanford,'' UA Coach Lute
Olson said. ``Cal has had big wins over North Carolina and UCLA,
and I know how fired-up they will be for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can be thinking, or talking, about Stanford.''
</P>
<P>
   No problem for UA freshman power forward Michael Wright, who had
difficulty talking about anything after the Wildcats outlasted the
Ducks, 92-86, at McKale Center, giving UA (20-4, 11-3) its 12th
straight 20-win season. Wright suffered a deep cut inside his lip
when he was hit by the elbow of Ducks forward A.D. Smith. The wound
required two stitches.
</P>
<P>
   After emerging from the training room, Wright said that Oregon's
big men ``have 25 fouls to give and they give them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They just try to foul, but you've got to stay focused and play
through it,'' Wright said. ``You just work harder to get the
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time I was coming up the floor and Flo Hartenstein just
put his chest into me. They were trying their best to body me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks also tried to body up UA center A.J. Bramlett, who
came away with a small cut on his nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their inside guys are all super-physical,'' Bramlett said.
``They all bang. That's what they're there for, just to beat you
up. Michael was telling me at halftime, `Man, they're beating me
up,' but you can't get frustrated. You have to stay with it. If you
stay aggressive, you keep getting the calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon, with a deep supply of big men, isn't afraid to use its
fouls in an attempt to intimidate, frustrate and pound a foe into
submission. It had some success, outrebounding UA, the Pac-10
rebounding leader, 43-37.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were called for 32 fouls, giving Arizona 40 free
throws. UA made 31, including 8 of 8 by Richard Jefferson, 7 of 8
by Terry and 7 of 9 by Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Olson was irked that even more were not called.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding of the rule is that when the defender puts
both hands in your back, that's a foul,'' Olson said. ``That's the
same as the defender putting his knee in the back of the crotch.
You can't do that. I was concerned that somebody was going to get
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ducks guard Terik Brown said the Wildcats weren't choirboys,
either. They just got away with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to play as hard as we could, but when there are no
fouls being called on the home team on their floor, it makes it
hard,'' Brown said. ``Then it's hard for us to be aggressive when
every time you know you're going to get a foul called on you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Arizona had enough finesse to get through the
hack-a-thon. With the score tied at 84, Terry, the Pac-10 scoring
leader and a candidate for National Player of the Year, caught a
cross-court lob from Jefferson in the left corner and swished a
three-point shot with 1:22 left.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Terry grabbed a fumble by Oregon's Alex Scales that led to
two free throws by Jefferson, giving Arizona a five-point edge with
58.1 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practice, we work on catch-and-shoot, that's all I was
thinking about,'' Terry said. ``If the guy was not on me, I was
going to shoot it right away. Earlier, we had run that same set and
they got a guy out on me. This time, they didn't. It was like, yes,
I'm finally open.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry, who scored a career-high 37 points against the Ducks in
Eugene, Ore., last month, scored 32 this time.
</P>
<P>
   When his shot was shaky early, Bramlett (22 points, eight
rebounds) and Wright (19 points, 13 rebounds) took control inside.
Jefferson added 18 points and five assists.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona seemingly was on the verge of a blowout when Bramlett
posted up Ducks center Mike Carson for a basket and a 12-point lead
with just over 15 minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   But Oregon (14-10, 6-9), which had won four straight and was
battling for an NCAA Tournament bid, did not give in. By spreading
the floor and moving the ball crisply, it managed to keep the UA
defense a step behind. The result was a stunning 26-7 spurt, capped
by a 12-0 run that gave Oregon a seven-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're streaky,''Jefferson said. ``They have three-point
shooters so they can get back in a game in a hurry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
