<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CACTUS-OPENING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CACTUS LEAGUE EXPECTING BIGGER CROWDS THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They are the three tenors of spring training: a
singer, a swinger and the master of the dinger, whose presence in
Arizona could help the Cactus League hit a high note in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The additions of Garth Brooks and Mo Vaughn and the return of
slugger Sammy Sosa have some speculating that the league will
surpass 1 million fans for the first time in its 46-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it will happen,'' Cactus League President Jerry
Geiger said. ``A lot of the early activity this year seems to
indicate we're going to have a banner year.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers and catchers for the 10 league teams have reported.
Position players will arrive this week, and games start March 3 and
4.
</P>
<P>
   Poor weather and the addition of the Diamondbacks contributed to
an attendance drop of nearly 10 percent last season. But with
cooler, rainy days less likely this spring, league officials are
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs, who train at Mesa's HoHoKam Park, said ticket
sales are ``way ahead of last year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to see Sammy,'' said Dawn Berry, HoHoKam Park
ticket manager. ``Even people who don't know who he is. I get calls
saying, `I was told to buy tickets by so-and-so to see that guy who
broke the record.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Berry said ``our phones went crazy'' in January when a snowstorm
hit the Midwest. Tickets are available for all games, although
those against popular opponents, including the Diamondbacks, are
going fast.
</P>
<P>
   Geiger said he believes baseball's strong finish, particularly
the home run derby between Sosa and St. Louis first baseman Mark
McGwire, will lure fans. The Cubs' wild card playoff berth also
left Chicago faithful hungry for more.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres, who train at Peoria Stadium, invited
country music star Brooks to spring training. Whatever the
motivation, it surely will put a few more fans in the seats.
</P>
<P>
   The league gained Vaughn, one of the game's most feared
sluggers. The former Boston first baseman, who has a career .304
average, signed as a free agent with the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The league lost volatile Albert Belle, who left the Chicago
White Sox for the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   And it returns the American and National leagues' rookies of the
year, Oakland outfielder Ben Grieve and Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood.
</P>
<P>
   It may gain at least one more team. The Los Angeles Dodgers are
involved in serious discussions with Fort McDowell Indian Community
officials, who have proposed a $20 million training facility. A
decision is expected by April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're impressed by our discussions,'' said Bob Wymbs, Dodgers
special projects director. `But it's a serious subject and we're
still in the evaluating stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The tribe in November proposed the Fort McDowell Four Peaks
Sports Complex, a 12,000-seat stadium with six practice fields, to
lure the Dodgers from Vero Beach, Fla., where they have trained
since 1948. The tribe believes it could have the practice fields
ready for spring training next year.
</P>
<P>
   Vero Beach residents have put up a fight, and city and county
officials have stepped in to help. But they are concerned because
geographically, the move makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   All four Dodgers rivals in the National League West _ the
Diamondbacks, Padres, Colorado Rockies and San Francisco Giants _
train in Arizona, as do the American League's three West Coast
teams: the Angels, A's and Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Cactus League traditionally deals with far
fewer rainouts than the Grapefruit League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quite honestly think (delaying their decision) bodes well
for us,'' Geiger said. ``There are so many economics working in our
favor. It's not to say they couldn't stay in Florida, but I think
we have some very significant advantages that are going to be very
difficult for Florida to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers already have a strong fan base in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a definitive word on the Dodgers, spring training
should provide the state with a significant economic boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can break 1 million people,'' Geiger said, ``we're
looking at $110 million, $115 million in direct spending coming
from outside the state. That's nothing to lose sight of.''
</P>
<P>
   About 58 percent of the fans at least season's games were from
outside the state, according to a study by the Behavior Research
Center. They averaged 5.4 nights during their stay and spent a
median of $200 per day.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strong statement about how far the league has come from
seven years ago, when it nearly folded after the Cleveland Indians
defected to Florida. It revived itself with $71.5 million in county
funds from a surcharge on rental cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is parallel to the feeling of a spring training
baseball game in Arizona,'' Geiger said. ``Nothing. This is going
to be a great year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
