<HEADLINE>
TRYBA PLAYS THROUGH THE BIG NAMES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN STREGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACIFIC PALISADES, Calif. _ On a historic venue that carries Ben
Hogan's imprint and accordingly is a fitting setting for a Tiger
Woods-David Duval duel, a PGA Tour journeyman intruded.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Tryba flirted with a 59 Saturday, then settled for a Riviera
Country Club-record 10-under-par 61 to open a two-stroke lead at 13
under par entering the final round of the Nissan Open.
</P>
<P>
   The Woods-Duval scenario was not erased, precisely, but the
prospects dimmed in the aftermath of a day rife with low scoring.
Woods, bidding to win for the second week in a row, shot a 65 and
is part of a three-way tie for second at 11 under with Davis Love
3d (68) and Ernie Els (68). Duval, meanwhile, shot a 67 and is tied
for fifth, four behind Tryba.
</P>
<P>
   Riviera is known as Hogan's Alley, a stretch of historic road on
the golf map that previously had not demonstrated such generosity.
Tryba came to the difficult par-4 18th hole needing a birdie to
shoot 59. Instead, his second shot went over the green, leading to
a bogey that still enabled him to eclipse the record of 62 set by
Fred Couples, Larry Mize and Kenny Perry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard he had a chance to shoot 59 I thought, `That's
almost unbelievable,''' Els said. ``I don't know what these guys
have been doing in the off season. Riviera is one of the classic,
tough courses. I don't think you'll ever see 61 here again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tryba has won just once in seven-plus years on the PGA Tour and
is better known for his quantity of golf than his quality. In each
of the last six years, he has played 32 or more events.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of his making a run at history Saturday was
further diminished by a lack of sleep on Friday night. ``I was
really tired,'' he said. ``I was worried about what I was going to
do out there, but when I made a birdie at 6 I started to wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   He turned in a four-under-par 31 on the front nine. He eagled
the 11th hole, then birdied five of the next six holes, moving to
the 18th tee and a possible 59.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was thinking about 59 on the 18th tee. ``I had no
idea what the course record was,'' he said, ``but I knew that
shooting 59 at Riviera would make history.''
</P>
<P>
   He drove it in the fairway at 18, then chose an 8-iron for his
second from 168 yards out. The ball hit near the pin and skidded
over the green, effectively ending his bid, but failing to dampen
his spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Tryba said that he had been telling Ben Bates, his playing
partner, ``that I felt like I was playing a J.C. Goosie event down
in Florida,'' referring to the mini-tour. ``The courses are so easy
down there you've got to shoot seven-under every round to win.''
</P>
<P>
   An equally imposing challenge awaits Tryba in the final round,
when he must fend off challenges from those on this gilded leader
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best players in the world are right there,'' Els said. ``I
think Ted Tryba's going to have an uneasy night tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is perhaps the most serious challenger. He won the Buick
Invitational last week by shooting 62 and 65 on the weekend, and he
already has matched the 65 here. His putter, a nemesis of sorts in
the last year, has become an ally again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the ball probably the best I've hit it all week,'' Woods
said. ``I left a few shots out there, though. I missed four golden
opportunities today, putts from 15 feet and in. But I made some
great par putts, too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
