<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL REUNION PROVES TO BE JOYOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the longest time, it was rumored that they had one of the
most strained father-son relationships in professional sports. But
Hall of Famer  &UR; Bobby Hull and his Hall of Fame-to-be son,  &UR; Brett,
apparently have patched up whatever differences they may have had.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby came to Dallas last week to watch Brett play in person for
the first time this season. He hung around the locker room, joked
around with his son and was mobbed during and after the game by
autograph hounds.
</P>
<P>
   Brett, who is as colorful and as outspoken as his father,
reportedly had tried to distance himself from his dad, especially
after Bobby was accused in August of making racially insensitive
remarks concerning  &UR; Adolf Hitler, which the elder Hull still
emphatically denies.
</P>
<P>
   But the two were all smiles at Reunion Arena on Monday during
their personal reunion of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even seen him on TV,'' said Bobby, who resides in
Chicago. ``All they show up there are Blackhawk games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every guy loves to have his father watch him play,'' Brett
blushed. ``But with me, my dad's a Hall of Famer. I told him this
might be the only arena where he could get in the stands (without
being noticed). Obviously not.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a fun night for the Hulls, the only father and son
in NHL history to have scored 500 goals and 1,000 points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``He realizes the game is different,'' Brett said. ``He said,
`They didn't pay me enough to listen to the coach in my day. But
since you get paid so much, I guess you need to listen to the
coach.' '' &QL; 
Team Turmoil &QL; 
The soap opera continues in Chicago, where it gets stranger by the
day with the dysfunctional Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest episodes involves Coach  &UR; Dirk Graham and
leading scorer  &UR; Tony Amonte, who got into an obscenity-laced
shouting match the other day during practice.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Graham contended it was a ``setup'' aimed at a
``Chicago'' ``Sun-Times'' beat writer for a story suggesting that
Amonte should be traded if his talents aren't going to be fully
utilized by the first-year head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing between Tony and I,'' Graham said, insisting
it was all a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Amonte's reaction was puzzling, however: ``If that's what he
said, then that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it for a moment. Amonte is angry that Graham
removed him off the power play's first unit, replacing him with
underachieving
 &UR; Eric Daze. And Graham's comments in explaining the move prove that
where there is smoke, there usually is fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last four, five games, I don't think the entire first unit
has done the job,'' he said. ``Tony Amonte and the rest of the
first unit should be on the second unit. Same with  &UR; (Chris)
Chelios. My responsibility is not to Tony Amonte to see he gets 30
or 40 goals. My responsibility is to this team.'' &QL; 
Playoff suggestion &QL; 
Edmonton Oilers General Manager  &UR; Glen Sather has an idea about
reformatting the NHL postseason. Instead of 16 teams making the
playoffs (eight from each conference), Sather would increase it to
20 teams and give the two conference regular season champions
first-round byes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe make the first round a best-of-five again, too,'' Sather
said. ``The league's expanded, but we haven't expanded the playoff
picture. I think it would help Canadian teams, and there's only six
of us. Right now, three of them (Vancouver, Calgary and Montreal)
are out, and we're just hanging on.
</P>
<P>
   ``And second, hockey goes to a different level in the playoffs.
How many bad playoff games do you see in Round 1? Hardly any. Lots
of upsets. I don't think it is (a lousy idea).''
</P>
<P>
   But it'll never fly. First of all, if the No. 1 seeds each
receive a bye in Sather's proposed 20-team format, it would create
an unbalanced playoff tree of nine remaining teams in each
conference. Second, owners won't go back to the five-game series
because they'd lose potential revenue. And last, who wants to see
more sub-.500 hockey teams in the playoffs, anyway? &QL; 
Looking back &QL; 
Who got the better end of the  &UR; Petr Nedved-Alexei Kovalev deal
between the Pittsburgh Penguins and New York Rangers earlier this
season?
</P>
<P>
   Entering the weekend, Nedved had 11 goals, 29 points and was a
minus-7 for New York. In two fewer games, Kovalev had 15 goals, 31
points and was a plus 7 for the Penguins. He also had a 10-game
point-scoring streak during Pittsburgh's recent 10-game winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nedved has cooled down quite a bit, and Alexei has gone better
lately,'' Rangers General Manager  &UR; Neil Smith said, ``but I think
it's been a good deal for both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Except the Rangers probably won't make the playoffs. &QL; 
Whiteout scoop &QL; 
The Coyotes haven't announced it yet, but team officials are
planning a major promotion involving the team's popular
``Whiteout'' tradition in which fans all show up to home playoff
games dressed in white.
</P>
<P>
   Details are sketchy, but part of the promotion will involve
giving the Whiteout exposure, apparently at a pre-playoff function
or two in March. Said a team official: ``It's going to be huge.
It's going to take the whole Whiteout concept up many, many
notches.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned. &QL; 
Souvenir pucks &QL; 
There was somewhat of a fiasco over who owns the rights to the last
puck ever scored at Maple Leaf Gardens and the last puck used in
the game between Toronto and Chicago last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Maple Leafs defenseman  &UR; Jason Smith had the game-ending puck
taken out of his hands by an official with the Hockey Hall of Fame.
Someone from the Leafs then snatched it back, saying it belongs in
the team's new arena.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's  &UR; Bob Probert, who scored the last goal in the old
building, said the Hall of Fame wants the puck, but he'd like to
keep it for obvious reasons. He kiddingly wondered how much it
might fetch at an auction, not that it ever would bring as much as
 &UR; Mark McGwire's 70th home run ball, which went for about $3 million
to Ahwatukee resident  &UR; Todd MacFarlane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give you a hundred bucks right now, Canadian,'' teammate
 &UR; Doug Gilmour told Probert with a laugh. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326, or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
