<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON OK WITH BACKUP BACKSTOPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Paul LoDuca has 14 major-league at-bats.
Angel Pena batted 13 times for the Dodgers last season, which is
the depth of his major-league career. They are also the
front-runners to back up Todd Hundley at catcher this season.
</P>
<P>
   And if injury were to saddle Hundley for a prolonged period of
time, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he isn't worried about an
inexperienced replacement handling one of the most talented
pitching staffs in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we could have traded (Charles) Johnson if we
didn't have Angel,'' Johnson said. ``You have to have a backup
plan, which is Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca, 26, is considered the favorite for the backup role, but
the 24-year-old Pena is considered the Dodgers' top prospect. Also
in camp is Encino native Tim Laker, who played in 29 games for
Tampa Bay and Pittsburgh last season, but there's no secret as to
what the Dodgers are thinking long-term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have to be prepared and I want them to know if
something does happen, I can play every day,'' said LoDuca, in his
seventh season in the Dodgers organization. ``But I understand the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the ideal situation would be to send Pena to
Triple-A Albuquerque so he could catch every day, but unforeseen
circumstances could keep him with the Dodgers for the start of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Testing the ankle: Before Dodgers shortstop Jose Vizcaino
worries about whether he'll beat out Mark Grudzielanek for the
starting job, or whether he'll be traded before the season begins,
he had to satisfy his mind that his ankle was fine.
</P>
<P>
   He accomplished that the last few days and now feels as if his
ankle injury, which caused him to miss the final three months of
last season, is healed and healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taking ground balls in L.A. The only thing I wasn't
doing was running straight ahead,'' Vizcaino said. ``When I was
hurt last year I couldn't run straight without it hurting. The last
few days, I ran straight and there wasn't a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been widely speculated that general manager Kevin Malone
will deal either Vizcaino or Grudzielanek before the Dodgers break
camp. Grudzielanek is considered the leader to remain with the
club. However, Vizcaino, who had surgery on his ankle Oct. 2 to
remove scar tissue and a loose body near the deltoid ligament, said
he expects to get a fair shake in the shortstop battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a legitimate shot,'' said Vizcaino, who batted
.262 last season and is considered a defensive shortstop. ``I just
have to prove that I'm healthy. That's what I have to show. They
know I can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and pepper: Right-handed pitcher Luke Prokopec, a
long shot to make the opening day roster, arrived in camp Saturday
after straightening out visa problems in his native Australia. It
leaves closer Jeff Shaw, awaiting the birth of his third child in
Washington Court House, Ohio, as the lone pitcher or catcher not in
camp. At the earliest, Shaw is expected on Wednesday. . . . Dodgers
bullpen catcher Travis Barbary and his wife, Raquel, had their
second son, Colt Travis Barbary (5 pounds, 18.5 inches long)
Friday. Dad is expected at Dodgertown in a few days. . . . The
Dodgers will wear their traditional blue caps and white home
uniforms for the first time today after wearing blue tops and white
caps the first few days as part of a major-league promotion.
</P>
</TEXT>
