<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM NEEDS KIDD'S ATTRIBUTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looks as if Suns guard  &UR; Jason Kidd may not be included among
the first nine players selected to represent the United States at
the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   At least as of Friday night, the selection committee had not
contacted Kidd, who has said on several occasions that he hopes to
represent the United States as a Dream Team member someday.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little hard to believe he has been overlooked every time.
True, the international rules require a lot of shooters, and that
always has been the knock against Kidd. But let's face it, a team
loaded with NBA players is not going to be short on scoring and
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The team is going to need players who are willing to distribute
the ball, and few are better than Kidd in that regard. He wasn't
chosen for the World Championships team that boycotted that
tournament last summer in Greece because of the NBA lockout.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears likely that many of those 12 players will be
among the nine selected for the team that will compete this summer
in Puerto Rico to qualify for the Olympics and, assuming that team
finishes among the top two in qualifying, the team that will
compete at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that players of that caliber obviously are
under consideration,'' said  &UR; Russ Granik, NBA deputy commissioner
and president of USA Basketball. ``It's really a difficult decision
because it's different when you only have nine to pick. Sometimes,
players are picked based on one particular skill. It doesn't mean
they're a better player than somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The three point guards on the World Championships team were
 &UR; Gary
 &UR; Payton of the Seattle SuperSonics,  &UR; Terrell Brandon of the
Milwaukee Bucks and and  &UR; Tim Hardaway of the Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to argue with Payton or Hardaway, who have paid their
dues and deserve to represent the United States. But both are
scoring point guards first, and so is Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   Three players will be added to the team before the Olympics. If
Kidd isn't among the first nine, hopefully the selection committee
will see that Kidd is an entertaining player to watch, and a guy
other players love to be on the court with.
</P>
<P>
   And he'll give them the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There definitely will be three more players picked after we go
qualify, and they'll be NBA players,'' Granik said. ``We usually
end up with at least one player who is injured or can't play for
some reason. That means we'll have at least three or four spots. If
a player hasn't been picked yet and they're one of the top-caliber
players in the league, they're going to have a chance to make the
Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Suns forward  &UR; Tom Gugliotta already has been asked to represent
the United States and has told USA Basketball that he'll give the
two-year commitment to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unbelievable honor,'' said Gugliotta, who worked out
in preparation for the World Championships after missing the second
half of last season because of an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   If Kidd joins Gugliotta, the Suns could have three players in
the Olympics. Center  &UR; Luc Longley has a contract clause that allows
him to compete for the host Australians, who automatically
qualify. &QL; 
Pistol perfect &QL; 
Boston Coach  &UR; Rick Pitino is the lastest to see a little of a
basketball legend in Sacramento rookie guard  &UR; Jason Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take at look at their starting five and their front line of
 &UR; Corliss Williamson, Vlade Divac and  &UR; Chris Webber _ it's as good as
anybody in basketball,'' Pitino said. ``And then you take the
backcourt with  &UR; Pete Maravich and the 6-9 shooting guard  &UR; (Predrag
 &UR; Stojakovic), and you've got yourself a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino isn't the first to draw comparisons between Williams and
Maravich, the late Hall of Fame guard. Pitino had Williams in one
of his camps while coaching at Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   And Williams has heard these Maravich parallels because of his
ballhandling, long-range shooting and flair on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know much about Pete Maravich,'' he said. ``I've only
seen a couple of tapes on him, but I'm glad people compare me to
him because he was such a great player.'' &QL; 
Horrors &QL; 
The Charlotte Hornets lost two centers to free agency, they once
gave up on signing  &UR; Alonzo Mourning, and they may lose  &UR; Glen Rice
next because owner  &UR; George Shinn is too cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Coach  &UR; Dave Cowens has ticked off the front office so much
that he'll probably be gone, too. In the past couple of years,
Cowens has been lauded as one of the league's best new coaches for
the job he has done with the Hornets under tough circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   And he wants a contract extension before agreeing to return for
next season. But he probably isn't going to get one after going
public to say he feels underappreciated by the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the plan?'' Cowens said of the Hornets' problems. ``Do
we have a plan? With all the stuff that's going on, I don't know
what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Management is furious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is already wrecked with injuries,'' General Manager
 &UR; Bob
 &UR; Bass said. ``For your head coach to make statements like this, he's
actually damaged the team further.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many hits can this team take? He's the leader of the team
saying something like that. It's very unfortunate to me. I was
shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Cowens' future, Bass was evasive: ``He's our coach
of record right now.'' &QL; 
Family feud &QL; 
 &UR; Shaquille O'Neal and  &UR; Kobe Bryant of the Lakers got into a shoving
exchange after a hard foul during informal workouts, but both
players insist that no hard feelings have carried over to the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a big deal. That's just competitiveness coming
out,'' O'Neal said. ``We're always going to be good friends. It was
just a hard foul, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Bryant both said that Bryant was slammed to the floor
by O'Neal on a drive to the basket, and Bryant got up to angrily
protest the foul, shoved O'Neal and got shoved back a few times.
</P>
<P>
   No punches landed, and the two were quickly separated.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I guarantee you this, I'll bet you nobody else on another
team will do that to Kobe,'' O'Neal said, ``Especially while I'm
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said: ``When you have two young, enormously high-profile
players together, when you have a team that hasn't yet hit its
stride, when you have a giant hunger for news about the Lakers in a
league famous for intrateam feuds, this stuff is bound to be
stirred up.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob Young can be
reached at 602-444-8271 or at bob.young(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
