<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL CAN'T FEEL NBA'S POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Set aside your anger for just a moment, non-believers, and
embrace the remote control.
</P>
<P>
   Feel the power of David Stern stinging your fingers and bruising
your soul? No? Good, that means you're not insane. OK, power up the
TV and pray that the almighty - your local cable outlet - will
allow these doubts to be washed clean by making the Classic Sports
Network available.
</P>
<P>
   On the Classic Sports Network, there will be visions of
basketball players with tragic hair and shorts that may be judged
pornographic in certain states and Texas. Verily, ignore those. But
check out the defense. Ah, don't see any? Right, most of the guys
you'll see on the Classic Sports Network couldn't guard a lawn
jockey.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to today's NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The custodians of hoop purity - the same citizens who screamed
bloody murder when Jerry West abandoned his crew cut - are howling
about an allegedly disturbing trend.
</P>
<P>
   That trend is insufficient scoring. We're still waiting for
reports from league-sanctioned groupies at our major precincts, but
it's true - scoring IS down. The evidence: In the first two weeks
of the current NBA season, the Sacramento Kings rank as the only
squad averaging more than the magical 100 points per game. Last
season, four teams finished the season above the century mark. The
season before, it was eight. The four seasons prior to that reveal
a back-tracking trend of 13, 16, 20 and, finally (in the 1992-'93
season), 25 teams averaging triple digits.
</P>
<P>
   Should the league pardon Paul Westhead?
</P>
<P>
   No, the league should consider the lead culprit for what is
perceived to be offensive offense: Defense. Most teams actually
play it now.
</P>
<P>
   Just last season, Miami coach Pat Riley - the madman who cooked
up ``Showtime'' - was asked if defense in today's NBA is superior
to the brand played in the '80s. Riley's answer was shocking.
Riley's answer was ... yes.
</P>
<P>
   A second opinion was offered by Clippers vice president of
basketball operations Elgin Baylor, who had to walk 12 miles - each
way - through the snow to achieve the status of old school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense,'' Baylor said, ``gets better every year.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution? Who needs a solution? Basketball with defense is
goooood. In fact, basketball snobs who preach about the superiority
of the college game typically insert the overriding tactic of
defense into debates on why the NBA is too gruesome to behold.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the Chicago Bulls win six championships in eight years?
Michael Jordan. OK, Michael Jordan and defense, at which Jordan
excelled.
</P>
<P>
   So, quit whining about the quality of NBA offense; you're the
same baby who refuses to watch the All-Star Game - because nobody
plays defense.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're disillusioned about poor free-throw shooting, feel
free to keep howling.
</P>
<P>
   Tom's rule of thumb
</P>
<P>
   When Tom Gugliotta was liberated from the Minnesota Timberwolves
by the Phoenix Suns, the All-Star forward reportedly took the
opportunity to compare point guards.
</P>
<P>
   Googs issued a comprehensive thumbs-down to former teammate and
alleged ballhog Stephon Marbury. But new teammate Jason Kidd was
judged as just dandy, the kind of point guard who creates joy from
a simple fast break.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks of marriage in Phoenix, Gugliotta's scoring
average (20 points per game) and shooting percentage (50 percent)
are the same as they were with mean ol' Marbury in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Our days are numbered
</P>
<P>
   Remember how Grant Hill and Tim Duncan became targets for
vigorous fouling by union members who didn't think the young stars
were completely down with the lockout cause?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it could be coincidental, but Hill's free-throw attempts
per game are up to 12 from 8; Duncan's have risen by 5.8 to 8. In
the meantime, Hill is walking toward the light of superstardom by
improving his mid-range jumper. Subsequently, his field-percentage
has elevated from 47 to 53 percent. ...
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned Kidd is threatening to justify his years of
advance hype by improving his shooting accuracy. Kidd, whose career
field-goal percentage is 39 percent, is making 46 percent of his
shots so far this season. ...
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 NBA Draft's first round has provided the league with
seven players who are starting as rookies. That includes ex-Arizona
star Michael Dickerson, selected by Houston at No. 14. ...
</P>
<P>
   The league's worst field-goal shooting team is (ta-da) the
Chicago Bulls, who check in at less than 40 percent. Nothing
against Tex Winter and his lovely triangle offense, but now hear
this: YOU CAN'T WIN IN THE NBA WITHOUT STAR PLAYERS. ...
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Three former UCLA Bruins just happened to get injured Friday,
which also is the same day teams were required to trim their active
rosters from 14 to 12. The wounded (all first-year ex-Bruins) are
Toby Bailey
</P>
<P>
   (Suns), J.R. Henderson
</P>
<P>
   (Grizzlies) and Jelani McCoy
</P>
<P>
   (Sonics). The injury bug also has infected former Long Beach
State standout Lucious Harris,
</P>
<P>
   who was placed on the injured list by the Nets. ... A
double-feature coming to a drive-in theater near the Forum:
``Around The Worm In 80 Days'' and ``West's Side Of The Story.''
... A scientific survey of five NBA scouts reveals that Long Beach
City College star Schea Cotton
</P>
<P>
   should forget pro hoops for a year or two and play college ball
when his thigh bruise finally heals. ... Before Friday's 11-board
effort, Piston followers thought the translation of ``Bison Dele''
was ``Doesn't Rebound.'' The former Brian Williams
</P>
<P>
   was managing just six rebounds per game. ... Now that Marv
Albert
</P>
<P>
   is employed by Ted Turner,
</P>
<P>
   we have decided TNT can be defined as ``Teeth 'N' Toupee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
