<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMBINE-TAIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG, CLUMSY KID GROWS UP _ AND HOW  
 TAIT IS IMPRESSIVE AT NFL COMBINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ His baby fat is gone. John Tait is no longer a
stumbling fool.
</P>
<P>
   Those kids in the Tempe Pop Warner League won't believe that he
has grown up to a chiseled 6 feet 6, 310 pounds. He can bench press
470 pounds and squat 660, run the 40-yard dash in 4.9 seconds and
has only 12 percent body fat.
</P>
<P>
   Tait, the Brigham Young University junior who is considered the
best offensive line prospect in this year's NFL draft, had a strong
showing Friday at the league's scouting combine.
</P>
<P>
   He bench pressed 225 pounds 26 times and wowed NFL scouts during
his interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's big, strong, athletic and we had an impressive meeting
with him,'' New Orleans Saints General Manager Bill Kuharich said.
</P>
<P>
   Tait didn't even get riled when he was asked stupid questions by
teams, including this one: ``If you were an animal, would you be a
cat or dog?'''
</P>
<P>
   Another club asked Tait, a Tempe McClintock High School
graduate, to define success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not usually big on BYU (offensive linemen), but he really
came off well,'' an NFL executive said. ``What a prospect. What a
nice young man.''
</P>
<P>
   Tait is the same guy who says he was terrible at the Pop Warner
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a big, clumsy kid who got beat up in practice,'' he
said. ``I was always big, so I had to play against kids two years
older. I wanted to quit, but my dad wouldn't let me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was even involved in a protest because me and another kid
weren't playing. Each us was supposed to play five plays. We didn't
play.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Tait reached high school, the clumsiness was gone.
Arizona State, Colorado, Texas, UCLA and BYU wanted him, but he
chose the Cougars because he was impressed with offensive line
coach Roger French.
</P>
<P>
   After a redshirt freshman year, Tait was gone. He went on a
Mormon mission for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people go to place like China,'' he said. ``I went to
Knoxville, Tenn., where there was barbecue and pinto beans. I was
one of those guys on bicycles wearing badges. Whenever people there
saw me, the first thing they asked, because of my size, was if I
played football. Football is a religion there. It was a great
icebreaker. We ended up talking about the Vols.''
</P>
<P>
   Tait weighed 270 pounds when he left on his mission. When he
returned to BYU in 1996, he had put on 20 pounds. It wasn't because
of his cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``My cooking was horrible,'' he said. ``Toast was my speciality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an intense learning experience, two years of being on
your own. Your focus was totally on serving other people. But some
people when they come back from their mission are not nearly as
good as players or don't have that desire. I had to relearn how to
play. But none of that desire was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Tait struggled his first few practices after returning. He felt
awkward and uncoordinated. But by the end of spring workouts in
1996, he won the starting job at left offensive tackle that he
never relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   He was a first-team All-Western Athletic Conference selection
his sophomore and junior years. Late last season, he decided he was
going to turn pro with one year of eligibility remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people said, `Stay for the Outland (Trophy),' '' said
Tait, 24. ``I'm not big on that stuff. I was getting good reports
back from the NFL and thought I was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN draft expert Mel Kiper predicts Tait will be the first
lineman chosen and will go 10th overall in the April 17 draft.
``Sports'' ``Illustrated'' has him going 12th.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who need offensive linemen, surely will consider
him with the eighth pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a long way from being out of football three years
ago,'' said Tait, who is 40 credits short of graduating from BYU
with an English degree.
</P>
<P>
   Tait, who is represented by Phoenix agents Eric Metz, Ethan Lock
and Vance Malinovic, knows he will hear a lot of draft rumors
during the next two months. He might even hear some at home.
</P>
<P>
   He has moved in with his parents in Tempe, and his father, Alan,
a Tempe insurance man, has become a draftnik.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become a hobby for him,'' Tait said. ``He looks up
draft boards on the Internet. He likes mock drafts. He likes to
look at all the angles. He has become a pretty good evaluator of
talent. He'll say, `So and so doesn't have good feet.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to enjoy the whole thing, and I'll play anywhere.
They're writing checks. I'm strapping it on.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
