<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWANN THRILLED BY PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals defensive tackle  &UR; Eric Swann thinks he is way ahead of
schedule in recovering from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels good,'' Swann's agent,  &UR; Steve Zucker, said at the NFL
scouting combine in Indianapolis. ``He thinks he can play
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Swann's condition has been the subject of much speculation since
he elected to go to Vail, Colo., in December to have controversial
knee surgery performed by Dr.  &UR; Richard Steadman.
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, Swann had arthroscopic knee surgery done by
Cardinals doctors but decided to have further surgery because he
still felt pain in the knee.
</P>
<P>
   He wound up missing the final 11 games, and with him out of the
lineup, the team's run defense slipped to 20th in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopefully optimistic,'' Cardinals Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin said
when told of Zucker's update on Swann's condition. ``He's a big
part of this football team. We missed him when he wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't just the plays he makes. The attention the other team
places on him allows other guys (on defense) to make plays.'' &QL; 
Procrastinating &QL; 
For the first time, Cardinals officials are acknowledging that if
starting outside linebacker  &UR; Jamir Miller leaves in free agency,
the team will have a hard time replacing him in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The thought has been that if Miller, an unrestricted free agent,
goes elsewhere, the Cardinals will use one of their two first-round
picks on an outside linebacker to fill that hole.
</P>
<P>
   But the best outside linebacker prospect,  &UR; Jevon Kearse of
Florida, is actually an undersized end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The War Room'' draft publication describes Kearse as
``somewhat of a tweener much in the mold of a  &UR; Simeon Rice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals still can find ways to bring back Miller if they
do some creative financing. Other teams do it. Jacksonville
restructured several contracts to add free agents
 &UR; Carnell Lake, Gary Walker and  &UR; Kyle Brady.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom have the Cardinals re-structured contracts because it
requires extending deals and giving new signing bonuses. The
Cardinals aren't a cash-happy team with a wealth of resources.
After all, they spent more than $33 million on bonuses for
quarterback  &UR; Jake Plummer, defensive end  &UR; Andre Wadsworth and Swann
in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Cardinals lose the 25-year-old Miller, they will
catch a lot of public grief for not getting his deal done a year
ago and then putting the franchise tag on wide receiver  &UR; Rob Moore
instead of Miller, who was their leading tackler last season.
</P>
<P>
   All of the criticism will be directed at  &UR; Bill Bidwill Jr., team
vice president who makes the financial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches and players want Miller back. Team executives  &UR; Rod
 &UR; Graves and  &UR; Bob Ferguson have made no secret of their wishes to
re-sign him. Owner  &UR; Bill Bidwill would like to have Miller back if
the team can fit him under the cap. But Bidwill Jr. has failed to
pull the trigger. He's still waiting to see what Miller's price tag
is and whether the team can afford him. &QL; 
Mock draft &QL; 
``The War Room'' has the Cardinals taking North Carolina State wide
receiver  &UR; Torry Holt with the eighth pick overall and mammoth
offensive tackle  &UR; Lonnie Shelton of Eastern Michigan at No. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals would love that scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, 6 feet, 190 pounds, is the best receiver in the draft and
would fill their speed need. He runs the 40-yard dash in 4.4
seconds and is an outstanding return specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, 6-5, 324 pounds, is a terrific athlete with good genes.
He is the son of former NBA forward  &UR; Lonnie Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have the best upside of any offensive lineman in the
draft,'' the ``War Room'' writes. &QL; 
Mighty mite &QL; 
Without a place-kicker on their roster, the Cardinals could take
one in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The best kicker is Kansas State's  &UR; Martin Gramatica, who could
go as high as the third round.
</P>
<P>
   He kicked a 65-yard field goal against Northern Illinois last
season and has kicked a 75-yarder in pregame warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Gramatica, a 5-8, 160-pound native of Argentina, didn't play
football until his senior year of high school near Fort Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a soccer player who didn't know anything about
football,'' Gramatica said. ``Sometimes I would kick an extra point
or field goal and forget about the kickoff. It happened in two or
three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know how to tackle. As kickers, all you can do
is dive at their legs.'' &QL; 
Serious business &QL; 
How badly do the Denver Broncos want to become the first NFL team
to win three consecutive crowns?
</P>
<P>
   Owner  &UR; Pat Bowlen said they spent $22.8 million on free agent
cornerback  &UR; Dale Carter, formerly of Kansas City, because ``as you
can see, we're very serious about a three-peat.''
</P>
<P>
   Broncos linebacker  &UR; Bill Romanowski called Carter the most
complete cornerback in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guy who can cover anybody and knock the
you-know-what out of you,'' Romanowski said. '`He's got a little
nasty in him, and I like to see that.'' &QL; 
Rappin' with Ricky &QL; 
The agent for Heisman Trophy winner  &UR; Ricky Williams is rapper
 &UR; Percy &UR; ``Master P'' Miller, who shares a rap label with  &UR; Silkk the
Shocker,
 &UR; C-Murder, Snoop Doggy Dogg and  &UR; Mystikal.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the Texas running back who is expected to be one of
the first two players picked in the draft, said he has no plans to
become a rap star. He already has a hobby, baseball, and he plans
to report to the Texas Rangers' spring training site in Port
Charlotte, Fla., on March 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play as much baseball as I can without interfering
with football,'' said Williams, an eighth-round pick of the the
Philadelphia Phillies in 1995 who has played four summers in the
minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is Number 1. It's been that way for the past four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the team that drafts him ``will get all of me. You get
paid to play 16 games, and I'm going to be there the whole football
season.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
