<HEADLINE>
DEAL WITH PIRATES NEEDS SELIG'S OK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ From the ``Your Check is in the Mail Dept.'' comes the
trade between the Diamondbacks and Pittsburgh Pirates that is
supposed to send outfielder  &UR; Bernard Gilkey and cash to Pittsburgh
for infielder-outfielder  &UR; Tony Womack and outfielder  &UR; Al Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which has more or less been set for a week, is
contingent upon how much deferred money in Gilkey's contract the
commissioner's office is willing to allow the Diamondbacks to pick
up. The figure could run as high as $6 million. The transaction was
still under review Saturday, despite calls to Commissioner  &UR; Bud
Selig from
 &UR; Jerry Colangelo, Diamondbacks managing general partner, &UR; and Pirates
owner  &UR; Kevin McClatchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd certainly like to get something done before the players
head to Florida and Arizona to their original teams,'' Diamondbacks
General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola Jr. said, ``and then have to turn
around and go back the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the two clubs' equipment managers exchanged uniform
sizes for the players involved. &QL; 
Them's fightin' words &QL; 
Three days into the spring, and the Diamondbacks already have
bulletin board material for motivation.
</P>
<P>
   A quote from Los Angeles Dodgers General Manager  &UR; Kevin Malone
regarding his team's lofty expectations found its way into the
Arizona clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks spent $118.9 million on free agents over the
winter, including $52.4 million over four years for left-hander
 &UR; Randy
 &UR; Johnson. But the Dodgers surpassed that with $142 million,
including a three-year, $17 million contract reconstruction for
closer  &UR; Jeff Shaw; &UR; a three-year, $12.4 million deal for former
Diamondbacks center fielder  &UR; Devon White; and the jaw-dropping,
seven-year, $105 million contract for right-hander  &UR; Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's crystal ball says the Dodgers will reach the World
Series against the defending champion New York Yankees, who
acquired right-hander  &UR; Roger Clemens in a trade with the Toronto
Blue Jays on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll need Roger when they play us in the Fall Classic in
October,'' Malone said. ``It'll be fun. It will be nice to see
Kevin Brown and Roger Clemens matched up in October.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks might as well pack their bags and go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy smoke,'' was Garagiola reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't bragging if you can back it up,'' said Manager  &UR; Buck
 &UR; Showalter, a tinge of sarcasm in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks will be the first to find out whether the
Dodgers can back up Malone's words. The clubs square off in the
season opener April 5 at Dodger Stadium, when Johnson is expected
to duel Brown, and again a week later in Arizona's home opener at
Bank One Ballpark. &QL; 
Eye to eye &QL; 
When the time comes for Showalter to remove the 6-foot-10 Johnson
or 6-6 right-hander  &UR; Andy Benes from games this season, he has some
special instructions for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they'll have to stand at the bottom of the hill
and I'll stand at the top. Otherwise, I'll look kind of dwarfy,''
the 5-10 Showalter said. &QL; 
Say aaahhh &QL; 
Pitchers and catchers will have physicals today beginning at 6:30
a.m., but Showalter and his coaching staff will go first at 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad thing about it is we can't drink any coffee before
coming in,'' Showalter said. &QL; 
Heads up &QL; 
The Diamondbacks and the other 29 major league clubs are wearing
special spring training caps as a marketing ploy by Major League
Baseball Properties to sell more types of merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's caps, which will be worn all spring, are black with a
purple bill and a snake holding a baseball in its mouth. The logo
was part of the club's inaugural patch, although there is no
reference now to the inaugural season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
