<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIN NEVER EASES FOR RED SOX FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big news of the week, at least on the field, centered around
the New York Yankees' acquisition of five-time Cy Young Award
winner
 &UR; Roger Clemens in a trade with Toronto that looks awfully tilted in
favor of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The talk around New England is that the Yankees have once again
shoved a dagger in the backs of Red Sox fans. The fact that a
Boston icon such as Clemens can possibly put on the dreaded Yankee
pinstripes has folks in Beantown wondering whether they're little
more than the butt of jokes for New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   The trade that netted Toronto pitchers  &UR; David Wells and  &UR; Graeme
Lloyd and infielder  &UR; Homer Bush has Red Sox fans feeling as if all
the old wounds from past Boston failures have been opened again.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' move from the Blue Jays to the dreaded Yankees has fans
all over New England recalling the single biggest gaffe in Boston's
storied history, the trade that sent  &UR; Babe Ruth to the Yankees for
cash in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, every Red Sox fan, young and old, has been programmed
to know that Boston has not won a World Series since the Ruth
transaction. But now this? Clemens pitching for the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   This latest move may push many Red Sox fans over the edge. How
much longer can Bostonians remain the punching bag for the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   Even though he had nothing to do with the trade, Boston General
Manager  &UR; Dan Duquette may lose his job over this move. Duquette is
still blamed as the single reason Clemens decided to leave Boston
two years ago when he signed with Toronto as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, one other bit of potential irony to look for this summer: If
he has the chance, Yankees Manager  &UR; Joe Torre might start Clemens
in the All-Star Game. This year's site? Boston's Fenway Park. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who was the last switch-hitter to win the American League Most
Valuable Player award? Answer later. &QL; 
Fun quotes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the Cincinnati Reds reversed a 32-year-old policy to ban
facial hair last week, several Reds players came up with some
beauties last week. Here's a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder  &UR; Dmitri Young: ``Some people are real ugly without
facial hair, and I'm one of them. We can hide behind beards and
mustaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman  &UR; Pokey Reese: ``See what one man can do? A lot of
things might change around here. Maybe earrings are next.'' (The
one man was  &UR; Greg Vaughn, who pleaded through the Cincinnati media
to change the rule).
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Danny Graves: ``No beard for me. It would take me 10
years to grow one, and all you'd see are some wild hairs. Maybe
when I reach puberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Infielder  &UR; Jeff Branson: ``I'm not growing a beard. I'm at the
stage where I want to look younger, not older.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher  &UR; Eddie Taubensee: ``Oh, boy: New uniforms, facial hair .
. . we've got a whole new good look. I wore a goatee every winter,
and my wife says I look meaner and tougher with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager  &UR; Jack McKeon, who wore a full mustache when he managed
in Kansas City and Oakland: ``No, I'm not going to grow one. This
just makes my job easier, one thing less to worry about, although I
only had to say anything to players about not shaving three or four
times last year. All I care about is what they do on the field.'' &QL; 
Out of touch? &QL; 
Kansas City outfielder  &UR; Johnny Damon lost his arbitration hearing
last week and will have to settle for $2.1 million in 1999 instead
of the $3.2 million he was seeking after batting .277 last season.
</P>
<P>
   The loss did not sit right with Damon, who is represented by
 &UR; Scott
 &UR; Boras, known throughout the game as someone who gets the highest
possible salary for his clients. It's a safe bet that Damon will
remember this loss, although his thinking seems a bit off for those
of us who live in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a better player than $2.1 million,'' Damon said.
``I'm going to get ready for another big year, and I'll see them
back at arbitration next year and the following year, and then I'll
get to set my price as a free agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras couldn't have said it better. &QL; 
Bad blood on I-5 &QL; 
Count San Diego General Manager  &UR; Kevin Towers as a non-believer in
the revamped and more expensive Dodgers. Towers last week predicted
that Los Angeles, which will have a major league-record payroll
somewhere near $90 million, will not win the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because a team like the Dodgers spends more money, it
doesn't mean they're going to be a better club,'' Towers said. ``It
just means that the Padres and the Giants need to be a little
wiser. I'll say right now, and I'll go on record with it, that
either the Giants or the Padres will finish in front of the
Dodgers.'' &QL; 
Problems with Pudge &QL; 
The Texas Rangers once again will attempt to get perennial All-Star
catcher  &UR; Ivan Rodriguez to help Rangers pitchers prepare the day of
games.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's pre-game routine does not include going over
opposing hitters, which was said to have angered new Diamondbacks
starter  &UR; Todd
 &UR; Stottlemyre, who started 10 games for Texas last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't something that just developed,'' said Manager
 &UR; Johnny
 &UR; Oates, a former catcher. ``It's something that's been ongoing.
We're trying to incorporate it more. It's something we'll continue
to work with him on, so he can get better at it.'' &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
Oakland Athletics pitcher  &UR; Vida Blue in 1971. Yes, it was a bit of
a trick question. But it is true. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; The fleecing of the smaller markets continues: Say what you want
about the New York Yankees' addition of five-time Cy Young Award
winner  &UR; Roger Clemens, but it seems Toronto should have, and could
have, received more than the three players the Blue Jays got from
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A preview of the lead story on Wednesday nights
 &UR; sports shows: St. Louis first baseman  &UR; Mark McGwire, whose life
will forever be changed after last season, is scheduled to report
to spring training Wednesday, the first day of full workouts for
that club. It should be quite a circus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Barbaro Garbey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Expensive, but worth it?: Texas, which paid Montreal $100,000
for outfielder  &UR; Ricky Williams, the Heisman Trophy winner, learned
last week that the running back/outfielder will report to the
Rangers' spring training camp. Williams, who likely will be the
first or second player picked in the NFL draft, will report March 9
with other position players.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Sesame Street White Sox?: Take away  &UR; Frank Thomas (eight
years and 63 days) and  &UR; Ray Durham (five years), and  &UR; Greg Norton
(1 year, 82 days) is next on the list for the White Sox among
non-pitchers in terms of major league service time. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Philadelphia's projected starters after ace  &UR; Curt Schilling
combined for 16 big league victories last season. In an unrelated
note, the Phillies also have relaxed their policy on players'
wearing earrings. The ban continues on the field but no longer
applies to the clubhouse or travel.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati reliever  &UR; Stan Belinda, who was diagnosed with
multiple sclerosis in August, is in camp and has been cleared to
play. Belinda injects himself once a day with an FDA-approved drug
that decreases the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' everyday lineup, if it remains intact, will have five
players in a row who had at least 90 RBIs last season:  &UR; Rusty
 &UR; Greer,  &UR; Juan Gonzalez,  &UR; Rafael Palmeiro,  &UR; Ivan Rodriguez and  &UR; Todd
Ziele. Only three other clubs this decade could say the same thing:
Toronto in 1993, and Baltimore and Seattle in 1997. By the way, all
those clubs made the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Marlins Manager  &UR; John Boles made it official last week
in declaring that former ace  &UR; Alex Fernandez, who missed all of
last season while rehabilitating a rotator cuff injury, has been
selected as the opening day pitcher April 5 against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sammy Sosa, the reigning NL Most Valuable Player, continued his
whirlwind off-season pace last week by accepting an ESPN award on
Monday and then jetting off to Las Vegas for a promotional stop
before going to Los Angeles on Saturday to shoot a McDonald's
commercial. He is scheduled to get back to baseball this week in
Mesa. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Now that Cleveland has watched the Yankees add  &UR; Roger Clemens, the
Indians have decided to send scouts to watch Oakland's
 &UR; Kenny &UR; Rogers and Kansas City's  &UR; Kevin Appier throughout the spring
for possible trades. Hot prospect  &UR; Richie Sexson could be the bait
used to make a trade. Also, the Indians have signed  &UR; Orel Hershiser
to a minor league deal.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is talking to the agents who represent pitchers  &UR; Jamie
Moyer and  &UR; Jeff Fassero and first baseman  &UR; David Segui, who can
become free agents after this season. Each may receive a two-year
extension with an option for a third season.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh made a three-year offer worth $16.5 million recently
to all-everything first baseman  &UR; Kevin Young. But Young may be
seeking something closer to a five-year deal for $30 million, a
figure he surely will receive if he becomes a free agent after this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is very willing to listen to offers for second baseman
 &UR; Jeff Frye and/or outfielder  &UR; Troy O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   With a burgeoning payroll that is nearing $90 million, Los
Angeles may try to trim some of that by trading the shortstop that
does not win the starting battle between  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Grudzielanek and  &UR; Jose Vizcaino.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego, which still hopes to trade reliever  &UR; Randy
 &UR; Myers, has had interest from the Chicago White Sox and Seattle. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
