<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS TRY TO DESIGN WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Somewhere out there, in a drawer with the second sock
that nobody can ever seem to find, is the answer to the
Diamondbacks' baseball puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   During the team's inaugural season in 1998, there were plenty of
pieces, but only a few seemed to fit. The rest were discarded after
a 65-97 finish.
</P>
<P>
   A new season lies just ahead, and Managing General Partner Jerry
Colangelo has brought home a box full of new pieces, most through
free agency (price tag: $118.9 million) and a few through trades.
</P>
<P>
   Forming a complete picture is the task of Manager Buck
Showalter. He is optimistic about coming closer, yet knows the
remaining pieces won't be available at least for another few years.
</P>
<P>
   That won't, however, stop the process from moving forward. It
began Feb. 17 when pitchers and catchers reported to Tucson
Electric Park and continues Tuesday with the arrival of the
position players.
</P>
<P>
   When he turns the box upside down and allows the pieces to fall
on the table, just what does Showalter have?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, a vastly improved pitching staff with three new
starters _ Randy Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre and Armando Reynoso. A
new key middle reliever _ Greg Swindell. Two new starting
outfielders _ center fielder Steve Finley and left fielder Luis
Gonzalez _ with the possibility of a third _ Tony Womack, coming
aboard via a trade.
</P>
<P>
   With the new players and anticipated improvement of two key
players from last season _ third baseman Matt Williams and Jay
Bell, who is moving from shortstop to second base _ the
expectations have increased considerably. Could the team be good
enough to challenge for a wild-card playoff spot?
</P>
<P>
   Showalter doesn't seem to be worried about added pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody has more expectations than I do,'' he
said. ``Our goal is to get better every year. We want to become
competitive and then stay there. If anybody has a problem with
being in that situation, then they'd better be on their way.''
</P>
<P>
   His primary objectives over the next six weeks are finding a
reliable batting order, solidify the right-handed portion of the
bullpen, increase the on-base percentage and cut down on
strikeouts. The latter area was particuarly frustrating last
season, when Arizona led all of baseball with 1,239.
</P>
<P>
   Depth has improved, both in the outfield and infield. Greg
Colbrunn, another free-agent signee, will be a factor as well as
another strong effort from versatile Andy Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Finley appeared the man most likely to lead off as camp opened,
but likely would drop to No. 2 if Womack joined. If Womack stayed
with Pittsburgh or went elsewhere, Gonzalez likely would bat
second, followed by first baseman Travis Lee, Williams, right
fielder Bernard Gilkey, Bell, catcher Kelly Stinnett and shortstop
Tony Batista.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several times last season when I wanted to give our
starters (position players) a day or two off, but the drop-off (in
talent) was so significant, I couldn't. That wouldn't have been
fair to the fans,'' Showalter said. ``That shouldn't be as much of
a problem this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who is one of baseball's biggest intimidators, has been
under the spotlight since he signed a four-year, $52.4 million
free-agent contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy makes everybody around him better,'' Showalter said.
``It's tough to put together a big inning against him. He's always
three pitches away from getting out of an inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who was a combined 19-10 for Seattle and Houston last
season and led the majors with 329 strikeouts, downplays that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're considered the ace, what does that make the other
four guys in the rotation?'' Johnson said. ``Everybody is No. 1 on
their particular day.''
</P>
<P>
   If the starters and middle men can get to the eighth and ninth
innings with the lead, right-hander Gregg Olson will be called upon
to keep things on course and earn the save, which is what he did on
30 occasions last season to revive his career.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Oly' has got great moxie. He's got a big heart,'' Showalter
said. ``He understands how to evaluate hitters' strengths and
weaknesses and make adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell is making the adjustment from short to second and Williams
will attempt to put a season full of nagging injuries behind him.
He has been a frequent visitor to the weight room at Bank One
Ballpark during the off-season. He appears more muscular and even
has added a small barbed-wire tattoo around a bicep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matty doesn't pay a lot of lip service, but you can tell he's
quietly on a mission,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee looks to have redistributed some of his weight and muscle
and is anxious to improve on last year's finish of .269, 23 home
runs and 71 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bored of being bored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Batista doesn't have the shortstop job locked up, he
probably rates an edge over young Danny Klassen because of a .273
average and 18 home runs in just 293 at-bats last season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
