</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BULLPEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPTH HAS MALONE BULLISH ON BULLPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he wasn't
sure whether he'd bring 10 or 11 pitchers west when the season
begins. He'll decide late in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   That he has viable options is news in Dodgertown. The bullpen
isn't set, but for the first time in a while it should be solid
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an area we knew we had to address and I think we
did,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said. ``When you look
at it, we're going to have a few guys who can close games.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile offseason moves were the trade for catcher Todd
Hundley and the free-agent signing of Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time in a few years the Dodgers have a
legitimate, top-line closer in Jeff Shaw, whom Malone signed to a
three-year, $14.1 million contract to keep him in Los Angeles. In
the past two seasons, he's saved 90 games, including 48 last season
in time split between Cincinnati and L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel very, very confident when you know he's the closer
coming in,'' Dodgers second baseman Eric Young said. ``We've got
the other guys that are set-up guys, and I think the makeup,
overall, is very good. I think they did a good job of mixing not
only ability but personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Dodgers bullpen went 24-22. Its 3.88 ERA ranked
eighth in the National League, below each of the three division
winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone was confident in the guys we had... but I
think when Shaw comes in and gets 25 saves (with the Dodgers), I
think it always eases you when someone like him is on the mound,''
Dodgers starter Darren Dreifort said. ``We started the season last
year and everything seemed in place, and we lost half our team and
half our coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw brings a presence to the bullpen, but its stabilization
isn't about blockbuster moves but rather the discreet acquisitions.
It's about trading Bobby Bonilla to acquire right-hander Mel Rojas
in hopes he regains the form he had with the Montreal Expos, when
he was the best set-up man in baseball. It's acquiring the
hard-throwing Alan Mills from the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Antonio Osuna appears healthy after having a bone
spur removed from his right elbow in September, and there's also
the situation involving Dave Mlicki. He could be traded during the
spring, moved into the rotation or shifted into the bullpen to add
depth.
</P>
<P>
   Malone also covered the left-hander angle, or so he hopes. He
brought in Greg Cadaret to be the situational left-hander who can
turn around a lineup during the middle of the game or get one out
late in the game. And Malone is also keeping an eye on southpaw
Chris Haney, a nonroster invitee to camp who's been impressive in
the early going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mills is a Mike Jackson waiting to happen. Mills is getting
really close,'' Malone said. ``Haney's got a chance. He's a
big-time sleeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll have a quality bullpen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
