</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-LOAIZA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOAIZA FACING MAKE-OR-BREAK SPRING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Rangers general manager Doug Melvin
summoned right-hander Esteban Loaiza into his fourth-floor office
at The Ballpark in Arlington during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The message: Realize your potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitchers with good arms generally fall into one of two
classes,'' Melvin said yesterday morning underneath a bright sun
illuminating the Rangers' Charlotte County Stadium spring training
complex. ``They either rise to the occasion or ... .''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin did not complete the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' Jan. 26 acquisition of veteran right-hander Mike
Morgan, though, completes Melvin's thought sufficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza must produce this spring or risk being banished to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason why he shouldn't be able to do what Rick
Helling and Aaron Sele did and take advantage of being on a good
ballclub,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Helling emerged as the Rangers' first 20-game winner since
right-hander Kevin Brown went 21-11 during 1992, and Sele's 19
victories matched that of Red Sox right-hander Pedro Martinez and
trailed only the 20 posted by Helling and right-handers Roger
Clemens and David Cone among American League pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do that, too,'' Loaiza said confidently.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin extended the challenge to his pitcher this winter, and
Loaiza remembers their conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that he wanted me to be the Jose Lima of last
year,'' Loaiza recalled. ``I can do that. I'm with a good team that
wins a lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima went 16-8 with a 3.70 earned-run average during 33 starts
for the Houston Astros during 1998. Twenty-five of those resulted
in a quality start, defined as an appearance of six or more innings
with three or fewer earned runs surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen plenty from Esteban to know that he can be a very
successful major-league pitcher,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said. ``It's our job _ physically, mentally and emotionally _ to
get him to that level three out of every five starts. If we do
that, he'll be a very successful pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza and Lima share similarities in age and major-league
experience. Loaiza celebrated his 27th birthday Dec. 31, and Lima
turned 26 on Sept. 30. Each enters this season with three years and
52 days of major-league service time.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, though, experienced his breakthrough season during 1998.
Loaiza went 9-11 with a 5.16 ERA during 35 appearances, which
included 28 starts, with the Rangers and Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good arms sometimes develop a little later, but he's at that
age,'' Melvin said. ``He's got good enough stuff, and now he has
the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin acknowledges that Loaiza possesses ``a better arm than
Lima.'' That explains why the Rangers parted with minor-league
second baseman Warren Morris, whom Melvin says will emerge as a
successful major-league hitter, and right-hander Todd Van Poppel to
acquire Loaiza in their July 17 trade with the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers assistant general manager Dan O'Brien describes Loaiza's
fastball and slider as above-average pitches, and Oates calls the
pitcher's sinker ``way above average.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza demonstrated as much during his first start with the
Rangers, and catcher Ivan Rodriguez's response relayed that to
Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Pudge coming back to the duguout with his mouth
open,'' Oates recalled. ``That was the best stuff he had caught all
year with our rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have great stuff,'' Loaiza said. ``I've looked at the
videos. I've talked to other players, and they say the same
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuff,'' though, does not make a pitcher. Command, Oates said,
does.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin introduced Challenge No. 2 for Loaiza by acquiring
Morgan, a 39-year-old veteran with nearly 17 years of major-league
experience, to compete for what likely will be the final berth in
the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting to see how he responds to that,''
Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The time is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe there is a thing such as a late bloomer,''
Oates said. ``There are guys _ for whatever reason _ boom! Who's to
say _ with the stuff he has _ that it won't happen to him?''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers leave Loaiza responsible for the answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
