r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-CASSTEVENS     02-20 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 Showalter eager to get show going for Year 2  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS(at) 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON - He was home for most of three months, enjoying the
off-season with his family. But on Christmas Day, shortly after the
gifts under the tree were exchanged, and the colorful packages
opened, he began to grow restless.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few weeks his wife noticed the change. She
recognized that distant day-dreamy look. At the family dinner table
Angela could see in her husband's eyes that he was somewhere else,
far from hearth and home. Hello? Yoo hoo. Earth to Buck. One night
Mrs. Showalter wondered why she had gone to the trouble to cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might as well have ordered pizza,'' Buck Showalter said,
smiling as he quoted his wife. His mind, he confessed, had been 100
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Time slowed. The days dragged. The Diamondbacks manager mentally
paced the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season's almost here,'' Greg Schulte, the team's radio
play-by-play announcer greeted Showalter one day last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season ``is'' here,'' Showalter replied.
</P>
<P>
   He waited until he could wait no longer. On Feb. 12 the manager
grabbed his suitcase. ``I had it packed for two weeks.'' He
described the two-hour trip to Tucson as one of the most
pleasurable drives he can remember.
</P>
<P>
   Only the equipment men were on the scene when he arrived. Buck
beat the pitchers and catchers to camp by five days.
</P>
<P>
   Buck unlocked his office at Tucson Electric Park. He sat in his
desk chair. He smiled a smile the public rarely sees. He was back
on the job, at home away from home, happy and comfortable in the
familiar surroundings, doing what he loves.
</P>
<P>
   His small office adjoins a meeting room. Directly across the
hall is the laundry and training camp kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen countertop is almost as well stocked with breakfast
cereal, each canister is labeled _ Raisin Bran, Frosted Flakes,
Honey Bunches of Oats and Frosted Mini-Wheats _ as the Diamondbacks
are loaded with quality starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Ten steps away is the carpeted clubhouse. Showalter walked along
the row of empty seats. He read the new nametags above the
cubicles. Randy Johnson. Todd Stottlemyre. Steve Finley. Armando
Reynoso. Greg Colbrunn. Luis Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   When Gregg Olson arrived, and surveyed the neighborhood, the
right-handed closer said aloud what his manager may have been
thinking over the winter months when the organization invested
almost $120 million on free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be pretty good,'' Olson said. ``Just because the
name of the team is `Diamondbacks' doesn't mean we're an expansion
team anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring training is heralded as a rebirth. Baseball is a
butterfly emerging from its cocoon. Hope springs eternal for every
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is upbeat,'' Showalter said. Optimism. That's what
the manager likes most about spring training. At spring training
``everything is a best-case scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks should be a lot better. For the money spent
they ``better'' be. Upgraded pitching. A new improved outfield. A
more experienced Travis Lee. Optimists say this team could contend
for the division title.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter can't wait to start anew. What manager wouldn't get
excited when one corner of his clubhouse is occupied by Andy Benes,
Omar Daal, Johnson and Stottlemyre. In only their second season,
the Diamondbacks have assembled one of the best starting rotations
in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have pressure on us to win, but it's a good pressure,''
Stottlemyre said. ``I'd rather have that kind of pressure than
people saying `Maybe you can win ``next'' year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So forgive Showalter for his preoccupation at the family dinner
table. His mind was on batting orders, lineups, the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Now spring is here, and not a day too soon. Buck swings a bat in
the clubhouse. Huddles with coaches. Zips around the complex in his
golf cart. Blows big pink bubbles with his chewing gum. Showalter
can't hide his eagerness. He feels most at home in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   At his first media gathering, Showalter watched as one, two,
three TV stations positioned their microphones on the conference
table in front of him. Mikes and tape recorders in place, the
signal everyone was ready, Buck folded his arms. Looked around the
room. Waited. Smiled as the silence grew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's that woman (at presidential press conferences) who
always asks the first question?'' Showalter asked playfully,
referring to White House press corps veteran Helen Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   I thought for a second about asking Buck whether losing 97 games
last season is worse punishment than impeachment, but that was
then, and this is now. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
