<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BELL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL MAKING SURE CHANGE 2ND TO NONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ The imprint of a circle in Jay Bell's back pocket isn't
a can of dip. It's a compass.
</P>
<P>
   He will need it, at least for a while, as he adjusts to his move
from shortstop to second base for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Not since his early days with the Cleveland Indians organization
in the mid-1980s, and before that as a high school sophomore in
Florida, has Bell been at second for an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play a position for so long that everything just becomes a
natural movement,'' he said. ``You don't really have to think, you
just go . . . most of the time, you end up in the right place at
the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell probably feels as if he's trying to drive in England. He's
on the opposite side of the car on the opposite side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   He had a two-week indoctrination period in the final 15 games of
last season. The true test will come this week, when he begins
working with infield defensive coach Brian Butterfield and primary
shortstop candidates Tony Batista and Danny Klassen.
</P>
<P>
   Will double plays bring double trouble?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessarily moving across the bag (at second)
differently, more or less away from the play, it's not being able
to see the (base) runner,'' Bell said. ``At shortstop, you usually
can see him all the way. But at second, you kind of have to get a
feel, a sense, of how close the man is.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bell signed a five-year, $34 million free-agent contract
before the club's inaugural season, some around baseball were
stunned. Critics said his range at short was average, and so was
his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who was 32 at the time, was sluggish at times, perhaps not
getting to the ball as quickly as he could have. Yet on similar
plays on other occasions, he would track it down, set himself and
make a crisp throw for the out.
</P>
<P>
   Bell also was struggling at the plate. He began the season
batting second and hit .249 there, striking out more than his
share. A lot of those, he said, came with two outs and with the
team struggling on offense as a whole, ``you try to get something
going by hitting the ball out, overswinging rather than staying
within yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, Bell kept his frustration to himself. Once in
a while, it snuck onto his sleeve. After all, he was only human.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter had a closed-door meeting with Bell to
clear the air, reaffirm Bell's purpose and talk about the future.
</P>
<P>
   The skipper had been toying with the idea of moving Bell. With
his pride at stake, part of Bell wanted to remain where he was.
Another part was open to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood the thought process behind it,'' Bell said. ``It
was good that Buck showed appreciation for me as a player by asking
me about it rather than just going ahead and doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what position you play, you can't really go out and
make excuses. You have to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my goal, and the goal of the organization, to compete
for a championship, and if we can accomplish that within the next
four years that I'm here by me being at second, then that's what I
will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be good for the club and good for Jay,'' he said. ``If
we can do it from the start of the spring, having him and Brian
(Butterfield) work together, they'll find a way to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The club's pursuit of Pittsburgh second baseman Tony Womack
would have no bearing on Bell's switch. Womack would play right
field and only in an emergency play second.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Bell likely will remain in the No. 6 spot in the
order, where he hit during most of the second half of 1998 (.284,
with nine of his 20 home runs).
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of more veterans to aid the cause, particularly
in the pitching department, should enable the offense to relax,
Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   As for 1999, he wants to show leadership as he did last season
with third baseman Matt Williams. Bell attributes a large part of
his inner strength to his faith in God. A trip to Israel shortly
before training camp began and seeing many of the areas described
in the Bible helped Bell gain perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Character means a lot. It's how they deal with other people.
Do they care about their teammates?'' Bell said. ``Despite our
struggles last year, I wouldn't trade it for anything. It may have
been the most enjoyable season I've had. It may be a clichea, but I
think there was chemistry between the older and younger guys. There
was enthusiasm and I think we can have that same thing again this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Having that compass in his back pocket certainly can't hurt,
either. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
