<HEADLINE>
KANSAS DEFENSE WAKES UP, STOPS OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ After Texas Tech's Rayford Young scored 32
points against Kansas in less than nine minutes, the Jayhawks spent
the entire two hours of their next practice working on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was embarrassed after that game,'' Kansas coach Roy
Williams, who recorded his 300th victory, said. ``I told the guys
before the game to be in a frenzy on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Oklahoma needed more than 33 minutes to score its
33rd point against the Jayhawks. The Sooners (19-8, 9-5) were
limited to 26.5 percent from the field yesterday as Kansas (18-8,
10-4) moved into a second-place tie in the Big 12 Conference with a
60-50 victory yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think a team could shoot 26 percent,'' said
Oklahoma's Eric Martin, who contributed to his own disbelief by
making 2-of-14 shots and missing all eight of his 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The game set a Lloyd Noble Center attendance record of 13,219.
The Sooners did their best to send all of the customers home with
their very own missed field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas' defense pushed Oklahoma away from the basket. The
Sooners, the Big 12's best 3-point shooting team, attempted a
season-high 32, but made just seven. In the first half, when OU
shot just 16.1 percent, the Sooners were 1-of-16 on 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can beat anybody if we shoot just 40 percent,'' Oklahoma
coach Kelvin Sampson, whose team had a six-game winning streak end.
``We couldn't throw it in the ocean if we were standing on the
shore.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Oklahoma's poor shooting, Kansas struggled to a 20-14
halftime lead. That's because after the Jayhawks hit eight of their
first 11 shots, they matched OU's inaccuracy. Over the final 11:02
of the first half, the teams combined for 4-of-28 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The game's lone offensive force was Kansas sophomore center Eric
Chenowith. He was scoreless in his previous game, but against the
Sooners he made his first seven shots, scored 24 points and had 12
rebounds and three blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas built a 33-20 lead four minutes into the second half by
hitting five consecutive shots, including two 3-pointers by Ryan
Robertson. The Jayhawks led 44-28 with 8:19 remaining, but the
Sooners found enough offense to close to within 45-39 at 2:55.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks shot 39 percent, were outrebounded 47-43, yet still
had control of the game. And, in a week's time, Kansas has moved
from a tie for fifth into a tie for second in the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a crazy game,'' said Williams, whose 300th victory in his
11th season is an NCAA record. There are four coaches that won 300
in 13 seasons. ``Last Saturday, we were the worst defensive team
I've ever coached. Today, we stuck to 'em like Velcro.''
</P>
</TEXT>
