<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS DECIDE TO GO OUTSIDE FOR WIN OVER AGGIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ After an afternoon of frustration
trying to free its inside strength, Texas finally trapped Texas A&AMP;M
in the Aggies' own defensive net.
</P>
<P>
   UT guards Kris Clack and Will Clay struck for three consecutive
3-point shots against an Aggies defense wrapped around Chris Mihm
and Gabe Muoneke, and that kindled a 13-0 second-half run that
ignited the Longhorns to a 63-54 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns' victory _ before the largest crowd to ever watch
an A&AMP;M home basketball game _ assured them of at least a
mathematical tie for the regular-season Big 12 championship.
</P>
<P>
   At 12-2, the Longhorns (17-10) are poised to clinch an outright
title and the accompanying No. 1 seed in the Big 12 tournament with
a victory Wednesday night at Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a huge win for us,'' said Mihm, who was held to nine
points but had 17 rebounds. ``The way it works out now, we could be
tied as co-champs. But we want to be champs by ourselves. We still
have two games to play, and we're going to come in excited and
ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second game against the Aggies (11-13, 4-10) this
season, Texas pulled away late for an easier-than-it-looked victory
against A&AMP;M. Under new coach Melvin Watkins, the Aggies have gone a
long way toward re-establishing a basketball rivalry with the
Longhorns, despite losing their 12th consecutive game to UT.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I walked off the court today I told \RUT coach Rick
Barnes\S I love this series, and it will be special some day,''
Watkins promised. ``They've got a head start, but we'll get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   As in their 71-59 loss in Austin, the Aggies were in the game
until midway through the second half _ when Clack and Clay took
advantage of room to shoot, burning A&AMP;M's paint-clogging strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Clack tied the game at 40 with 9:47 to play with a 3-pointer
from the deep right corner after a pass from Mihm. Mihm then
rejected two layup attempts at the other end. Clay then followed
with a shot from almost the identical spot on the baseline at 9:08.
</P>
<P>
   A missed A&AMP;M jumper later, Clack again burned the Aggies. This
time, it was from the outside left quadrant _ and the game had
suddenly turned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were sagging all day, not letting us get the ball inside
to Mihm or Gabe,'' said Clack, who scored a game-high 22 points.
``\RMihm\S kicked it back out, and I was wide open and knocked it
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I hit the first one, they left me open again. So I
decided to shoot it again. Once you get a run going, you feel like
you can hit anything you put up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay completed the run with a 12-foot jumper and two free throws
to give Texas a 50-40 lead at 7:10. A&AMP;M got no closer than eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those shots hurt us bad one after the other,'' said Aggie
Shanne Jones. ``We couldn't bounce back from that. With two
all-conference players inside, if they are hitting their outside
shots, they're the best team in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas is on the verge of proving just that.
</P>
</TEXT>
