<HEADER>
A3177 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN--WILLIAMS-HNS &LR;      02-20 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN--WILLIAMS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Williams tooting his horn
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ Running back Ricky Williams, the Heisman Trophy
winner from the University of Texas, did not make the kind of
impression he wanted on the NFL at the annual scouting combine for
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, teams that interviewed Williams were impressed with
his personality, but he didn't participate in the drills. Many top
prospects don't. But he weighed 244 pounds, which is 19 pounds more
than his playing weight.
</P>
<P>
   What worries teams the most is Williams' insistence on playing
baseball even though he hasn't had much success.
</P>
<P>
   Until the combine, there had been speculation Williams was going
to give up baseball to concentrate on the NFL. Not only did
Williams say he was going to play baseball for the Texas Rangers,
he went so far as to say that, because he is going to spring
training, he might not have time to work out for teams like every
other prospect who will be available in the April 17-18 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough with baseball to get some time to work
out,'' said Williams, who reports to the Rangers' spring-training
camp March 9. ``All the teams think I should, but if I'm already
slotted at No. 1 or No. 2, I don't see how it's going to help me to
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   With answers like that, some NFL teams might be less willing to
give extra draft choices to try to trade up with Philadelphia,
which has the second pick. And the cash-strapped Eagles might be
reluctant to draft him and have to compete with Rangers owner Tom
Hicks, one of the wealthiest and most influential University of
Texas exes, for Williams' services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some teams say I should (work out for them), so I haven't
decided yet,'' Williams said. ``I really want to play both sports.
As for baseball, I want to play and have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   The main question for Williams from general managers, coaches
and scouts?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're asking me if I'm going to play baseball,'' he said.
``Obviously, it's been that football is first, and baseball is more
than a hobby. Baseball is literally torture for me. It's so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It was mentioned to Williams it didn't seem fair for a team to
make him one of the first two picks in the draft and have to share
him with baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are getting all of me,'' he said. ``You get paid to play
16 games, and I'm going to be there the whole football season.''
</P>
<P>
   And the offseason?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be there for minicamp,'' he said. ``Like I said, football
comes first, and if I have to take a weekend off for baseball to go
to minicamp, I'm going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Williams came to the combine was to show the teams
interested in him what kind of person he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say (the combine) is good or bad, but I think all the
teams deserve a chance to get to know me and see what I have to
offer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' goal is to be the first pick in the draft, but
Cleveland is expected to select Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely important to me,'' he said about being the
first pick. ``Not to sound cocky or anything, but there's not
really a downside to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a good person. I'm good off the field. I do (good) things
on the field. I've been productive for four years. I'm extremely
versatile. And I'm ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time Williams was interviewed by the media, he hadn't met
with the Browns. He was interviewed by them later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be on my knees like this,'' he said, putting his hands
together as if praying. ``I'll be begging.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Couch had been in Cleveland to accept the Cleveland
Touchdown Club award as the 1998 college player of the year. In his
acceptance speech, Couch talked about how much he wants to play for
the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, honestly, if you have to campaign like that to be
taken, well, hopefully, my playing and how I carry myself speaks
volumes for me,'' Williams said. ``Hopefully, the Browns will see
that and take me with the first pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely important. It's always an honor to be taken No.
1.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch and Williams are expected to be the first two players
selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I hear,'' Williams said. ``Usually in the draft,
there are between one and five (great) players, then the talent
level drops off. This year, they're saying it's only the top two
picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say I'm the best, but there's no one out
there better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports Williams will try to use baseball to
keep Philadelphia from using the second pick on him because the
Eagles are terrible, they need a new stadium and the artificial
surface at Veterans Stadium is the worst in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't worry about that,'' Williams said. ``Once I'm drafted,
that's the way it's going to be, and I'll make the best of it,
regardless of where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Williams changed agents. He dropped the Boston-based
firm of Woolf and Associates for No Limit Sports, which is owned by
Percy Miller, the rap and film impresario who is known as Master P.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't happy with my other agent,'' Williams said. ``It was
the company. Everybody in the organization wanted something
different for me. You'd think if you had the No. 1 or 2 pick that
you would do the little things to make sure you keep him. They
didn't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom didn't really like (them) too much, and that sort of
pushed me over the limit and made my life a lot harder. It wasn't
worth it, upsetting my mom and straining our relationship, so I
decided to choose a new agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who grew up in New Orleans and attended the University
of Houston, has gotten into the sports agent business. Miller,
whose company made $56 million last year, impressed Williams. His
contract will be negotiated by one of Miller's attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a rapper or an actor,'' Williams said. ``I just want
to play football and baseball. I wouldn't do it (act or rap) even
if (Master P) asked me to.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams took some time to mention one of his heroes, former
Chicago Bears running back Walter Payton, who is awaiting a liver
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I met him twice,'' Williams said. ``I made a point
every chance I could to get a VCR, and I'd pop in a Walter Payton
tape and watch him. The way he ran _ his feet never stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant a lot to me, and now this unfortunate disease _ it
really pains me. He was a great person off the field as well as on
the field. Everyone who says anything about Walter Payton says
nothing but good stuff, and that's how I want it to be with me.''
</P>
<P>
   As a senior, Williams was under a lot of pressure to win the
Heisman Trophy, resurrect the University of Texas program and
become the career rushing leader in Division I. That pressure made
him a better player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live for the challenge,'' he said. ``I'm a competitor, and I
love challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I think about it, nothing has been that hard for me.
The way I look at it, I'm so confident that if anything (bad)
happens, I keep looking. The little obstacles I clear without even
trying. I try to stay positive, and little things don't get me
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams got a chuckle out of one question. He was asked who is
the greatest running back in UT history?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an easy one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Campbell?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
