<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEMENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Clemens gets pinstripes, tradition and title chance
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TAMPA, Fla. _ Roger Clemens smiled for the cameras, modeled his
Yankee pinstripes and spoke of feeling right at home with the World
Series champions.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in Texas may have been one of Clemens' aims, but the New
York Yankees offered something he could not pass up: tradition and
the chance for a World Series ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just real exciting to walk in and be a part of the
tradition,'' Clemens said at a packed news conference Saturday
morning, officially introducing him as a New York Yankee. It was
televised live in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees wasted little time in introducing baseball's only
five-time Cy Young Award winner, who arrived carrying a poem his
sister, Janet Johnson, wrote for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's from a sister to a brother,'' Clemens said, declining to
read it aloud. ``It's really neat. It's about pinstripes, and the
tradition, and Yankee Stadium. She knows how I carry that in my
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' agent, Houston-based Randy Hendricks, emphasized his
client's desire to return to the World Series for the first time
since 1986, when he was with the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were the most qualified to fulfill that objective,
Hendricks said.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens turned down a chance to play for the Yankees two years
ago, instead signing with Toronto. The Blue Jays granted his
request for a trade on Thursday, acquiring pitchers David Wells and
Graeme Lloyd and second baseman Homer Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a juggernaut of almost un-parallel proportions,''
Hendricks said of the Yankees. ``Roger's quest is for that ring
more than anything. That is the overriding consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing closer to home was one, winning a World Series was
another. In a perfect world you might do both. But you can't find a
better opportunity than New York I know how much he lusts after
that ring. It's like a big missing piece of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks said the chances of that happening with the Astros or
Rangers were slim in comparison to the Yankees, who have won the
World Series twice in the last three seasons. He suggested the
Yankees were a ``60 percent probability to win a World Series,''
compared to 20 percent for the Rangers and 10 percent for the
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros and Rangers were led to believe, as late as
Wednesday, that a deal that would bring Clemens to them was close.
</P>
<P>
   After pursuing a deal for three months, Rangers general manager
Doug Melvin was particularly frustrated and fuming, accusing
Clemens' agents of misrepresenting their client's interest in
playing closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yankees have a reputation as one of sport's most
storied franchises, Clemens has developed a reputation for himself.
He went 20-6 last season and led the American League in wins,
strikeouts and ERA for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in a way it's his destiny,'' Hendricks said. ``He has
earned the right to be a part of a legendary team. I hope it's a
great long-term relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens got in 15 minutes of throwing to catcher Joe Girardi
after meeting with reporters, then signed autographs for a
half-hour. He wants no special treatment and said he will continue
to do his job as he always has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (manager) Joe (Torre) I'm trying as best I can to slide
in the side door,'' Clemens said. ``This is a great machine.
They've got some great players here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they had never formally met, Yankees lefthander Andy
Pettitte shares several similarities with Clemens: both are from
the Houston area, attended San Jacinto College and have the same
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up he was an idol of mine, along with Nolan Ryan,''
Pettitte said. ``With the career he's had the only thing missing is
a World Series title. This is a great opportunity for him to come
here and get the chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
