u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-CAVALIERS-NY     02-20 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-CAVALIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAVALIERS BEAT NETS, 89-84  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Fans, commentators and players alike have been
riding Shawn Kemp since the Cavaliers star arrived for training
camp bloated and out of shape. But the husky power forward wiped
the smirk off of every face in New Jersey Saturday night by scoring
24 points to lead the Cavaliers to an 89-84 victory over the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to leap as high as usual while still carrying about 15
pounds of extra weight, Kemp, who also grabbed a game-high 11
rebounds, did his damage with toughness and craftiness. At his best
in a critical fourth quarter, he scored 9 points and forced
turnovers by Sam Cassell and Keith Van Horn in the final period to
drop the Nets to their fifth loss in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Now 2-6, the increasingly disappointing Nets head into Sunday's
game against Indiana trying to avoid falling out of the playoff
race before it starts. Cleveland, gaining its fifth straight
victory, improved to 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that shocked everyone but the Nets' coaches and
players, John Calipari started Sam Cassell, the colorful point
guard who had missed the last six games with a sprained right
ankle. Though obviously nowhere near his best, Cassell responded
with 18 points and 5 assists in 23 foul-plagued minutes. Jayson
Williams, on the other hand, had one of his most disappointing
games in a long time, with 2 points and 4 rebounds in 29 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When Cassell fouled out with 3 minutes 24 seconds left to play,
the Nets struggled momentarily, allowing Cleveland to go on an 8-2
spurt that turned the Cavaliers' 2-point deficit into an 84-80 lead
two minutes later. Looking for help, Calipari turned to the ailing
Kendall Gill, who did not play the first 47 minutes because of a
sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   But a cold Gill could not deliver, and with 19 seconds
remaining, he tossed an entry pass wide that forced Van Horn to
step out of bounds to catch it. The turnover sealed the Nets' fate
30 seconds after Van Horn (21 points) had provided hope by hitting
a 22-footer to pull the Nets to within 84-82.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles added 19 points for the Nets, and Derek Anderson
scored 19 for Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The game was close through the first three quarters, as neither
team led by more than 6 points and the lead changed hands 14 times.
The Nets, behind 8 third-quarter points from Cassell, led by 62-61
entering the fourth, and then surged ahead by 72-65 with 7:34 left
behind two baskets, including a 3-pointer, by the reserve point
guard Eric Murdock.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to start Cassell came just moments before tip-off
and caught the Cavaliers off guard. Despite moving gingerly and in
slow motion, he made his first five shots _ four of them jumpers _
and gave out two assists in leading the Nets to an 18-12 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Cassell's presence enlivened the Nets' offense, and they moved
the ball crisply for the first time in what seemed like ages.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets could not shake the Cavaliers, though, and Cleveland
grabbed its first lead at 27-26 on a running jumper by Johnny
Newman. With Van Horn taking control for the Nets and Kemp for the
Cavaliers, the clubs exchanged the lead for the rest of the half.
Van Horn had 15 first-half points, while Kemp had 11.
</P>
<P>
   While Cassell's return sparked the Nets, the club's excitement
was dulled by the sprained left ankle Gill sustained in the second
quarter of Thursday's loss to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   More bad news came when Rony Seikaly said he was ailing at the
morning shoot-around. Seikaly, who missed the first four games with
a sprained left ankle, complained that the plantar fascia in his
right foot was sore. That is the same foot that keep Seikaly out of
all but nine Nets games after joining the club in midseason last
year.
</P>
<P>
   With the Nets refusing to verify Seikaly's diagnosis, Calipari
ignored the center's report and put him in at the start of the
second quarter. After a three-minute stint that included two missed
field goals and a noticeable limp, Seikaly returned five minutes
before the half after Williams and Cleveland center Vitaly
Potapenko began roughhousing inside.
</P>
<P>
   The bumping seemed to take Williams out of his game, and he
grabbed just 1 rebound to go with 3 points in the first half. Both
Williams and Potapenko were playing with noses broken by the
flailing elbows of Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
