u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--Astros-Elarton-H     02-20 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Elarton-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
With trade talk over, Elarton takes aim at Astros' rotation
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
It doesn't take a rocket scientist to figure out how much the
Astros value Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays repeatedly asked for the young righthander
to be included in a deal for Roger Clemens _ The Rocket himself _
and each time Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker told them to
blast off.
</P>
<P>
   It was nothing personal toward the Blue Jays; the Seattle
Mariners got the same response when they tried to entice the Astros
into making Elarton a part of the Randy Johnson trade last July.
</P>
<P>
   By way of simple deduction, one must conclude the Astros believe
Elarton has a chance to be a special pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott Elarton is a very fine person and he handled it (the
trade speculation) with a lot of maturity,'' said Randy Hendricks,
one of Clemens' agents. ``The Astros' management determined at this
time that Scott Elarton was more valuable than Roger Clemens; only
time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, 22, has a long way to go to catch up to Clemens'
credentials. Clemens is a future Hall of Famer and the only pitcher
to win five Cy Young awards. Nevertheless, the Astros have a great
deal of confidence in Elarton's potential. And they have no
intention of holding him up to Clemens' standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the disadvantages of being a high-profile prospect is
that the expectations are often exaggerated,'' Hunsicker said.
``It's tough to live up to those expectations. But Scott has an
advantage because what he did last year should reinforce the
confidence that he has in himself that he can compete at this
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, in fact, he is in the rotation this year, he still has to
prove himself as a starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly think a lot of Scott, but until he establishes
himself in the major leagues, he's still a prospect. Scott is a
very talented young pitcher who has a chance to be a solid major
leaguer for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton got his first taste of the majors when he was promoted
from Class AAA New Orleans last June. He made two starts and then
became a key member of the bullpen, going 2-1 with a 2.42 ERA and
two saves in 26 games.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he will be given every opportunity to win a spot in
the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year gave me an opportunity to get used to the big-league
experience, and I definitely know I can pitch in the big leagues
now,'' Elarton said. ``I don't have any doubts about whether I can
perform at this level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching out of the bullpen was like second nature to me after
the first couple of times, but I definitely don't want to be in the
bullpen again. I want to be the fifth starter, but if they don't
think that's what's best for the team, hopefully they would put me
back into the bullpen (instead of sending him to the minors). I'm
flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner can relate to Elarton because both were first-round
draft picks and highly touted starting-pitcher prospects. The
Astros converted Wagner into a closer _ a role some believe Elarton
would flourish in.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros' crystal ball portrays Elarton as the anchor of
their starting rotation in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Scott's going to have any problems with the
expectations because his maturity level overshadows his talent,''
Wagner said. ``At 22 years old, if you could bottle his maturity,
you'd be rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion _ which doesn't count for much _ trading Elarton
would have been the worst thing we could have done. He has a chance
to be a franchise-type player, and I just don't think you can trade
away someone like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is how Hunsicker and Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. saw
things when the Mariners and Blue Jays came calling. McLane
repeatedly said the Astros would work aggressively toward acquiring
Clemens but that they would not part with Elarton or outfielder
Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   Before learning of McLane's statements during the offseason,
there were times Elarton wasn't sure where he would be reporting to
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the owner says you're not going to be traded, I kind of
felt like I didn't have anything to worry about anymore,'' Elarton
said. ``I think it just shows that they have a lot of confidence in
me. I'm not going to put any more pressure on me than I normally
would.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I want to be. I like Houston, I like the fans,
and I don't want to go anywhere for a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
