r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CACTUS-CAPSULES-A     02-20 3210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CACTUS-CAPSULES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CACTUS LEAGUE CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oakland ATHLETICS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stadium (capacity): Phoenix Municipal Stadium (8,776).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workout times: At Papago Park Complex for two weeks, 9 a.m. to
1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 recap: 74-88 (fourth place, AL West).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Art Howe (fourth season).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: It's usually not fair to pin high
hopes on a rookie, but if the A's are going to surprise anyone in
1999, third baseman Eric Chavez must have a big first season. He
was selected minor league Player of the Year last season by
``Baseball America.'' He is a natural hitter who has worked hard on
improving his defense. The former first-round draft pick is
de)finitely someone to watch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: SS Domingo Cedeno, RHP Doug Jones, OF Tony
Phillips, OF Tim Raines, OF Eric Stuckenschneider.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: 3B Mike Blowers, IF Rafael Bournigal, OF Rickey
Henderson, IF Dave Magadan, LHP Mike Mohler, OF Bip Roberts, 3B Ed
Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Players to watch: Miguel Tejada struggled at times during his
first full season in the bigs. Now that he will come to camp as the
everyday shortstop, more will be expected from Tejada, who likens
himself to a young Barry Larkin. . . . Jay Witasick, a former
reliever, started making the conversion to starter last year. Now
he comes to camp with a golden chance to snag one of the spots in
the rotation. . . . Another starter with a great chance to stick is
last year's first-round pick, Mark Mulder. It would take an
exceptional camp, but by all accounts, Mulder has the tools and
head to step right into a big-league rotation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Will Kenny Rogers, staff ace last year, still
be there Aug. 1, the day after the trading deadline? Rogers is in
the final year of a contract and easily represents the kind of
front-line starter who will receive attention if the A's are out of
the race by then. . . . . Who starts in left field, where veterans
Tony Phillips and Tim Raines will vie for playing time? . . . Who
will own the club next season? Co-owners Steve Schott and Ken
Hofmann put the club up for sale last fall. &QL; 
Colorado ROCKIES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stadium (capacity): Hi Corbett Field (10,000).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workout times: 9:30 a.m. to 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 recap: 77-85 (fourth place, NL West).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Jim Leyland (first season).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Darryl Kile was a tremendous
disappointment last season, posting a 13-17 record with a bloated
5.20 ERA. He did manage to salvage some respect with a late-season
surge, but the damage had been done. As ace of the staff, Kile
needs to jump out of the gate quickly if Colorado is to contend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: LHP Brian Bohanon, IF Lenny Harris.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: RHP Roger Bailey, IF Jason Bates, RHP John Burke,
LHP Mike Munoz, RHP Mark Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Players to watch: SS Neifi Perez played in every game last year
and managed to hit .274. The problem is his on-base percentage was
only .313. If he is going to be leadoff hitter, Perez will need to
do much better than that. . . . Pitcher Pedro Astacio was expected
to make the leap from middle of the pack starter to elite status
last season. Instead, Astacio took a few steps backward. He needs
to build his confidence and return to being a key No. 2 starter. .
. . Finally, there's Dante Bichette. The outfielder enjoyed another
fine offensive season (.331, 22 home runs, 122 RBIs), but there was
a sense he still didn't play up to his level. Bichette tended to
miss easy plays in left field.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: During their six-year existence, the Rockies
never have had a bonafide closer. Will someone finally emerge this
season? . . . Former MVP Larry Walker may have led the league in
hitting last season, but will he be able to return to being one of
the top run-producers in the game (his RBI total dropped from 130
to 67)? . . . Can second baseman Mike Lansing, a virtual bust last
season, especially on defense, rebound and have the kind of season
he enjoyed when there was no pressure to do so in Montreal? &QL; 
Anaheim ANGELS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stadium (capacity): Tempe Diablo Stadium (9,785).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workout times: 9 a.m. to 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 recap: 85-77 (second place, AL West).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Terry Collins (third season).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: There was one reason the Angels again
managed to crawl to the finish line last season and it began and
ended with pitching. Ken Hill, who was injured much of last season,
will be relied on as the ace. He has the best stuff of anyone inthe
rotation but must stay healthy. If he does, the Angels should earn
their first post-season spot since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: RHP Tim Belcher, LHP Mike Magnante, RHP Mark
Petkovsek, IF Luis Rivera, IF Andy Stankiweicz, 1B Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: RHP Mike Fetters, OF Gregg Jefferies, RHP Jeff
Juden, C Chad Kreuter, IF Norberto Martin, LHP Allen Watson, LHP
Trevor Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Players to watch: There are few players in the game as exciting
as Darin Erstad. The Angels stumbled when he was hurt late in the
season. Even though he returned, he was not 100 percent and it
showed. Erstad is a throwback-type of player and worth watching at
all times, even in spring games. . . . He's nearing the end of his
career, but Chuck Finley is still something to watch. Arguably the
second-best left-hander ever to pitch in the Los Angeles area
(behind Sandy Koufax), Finley continually puts out solid efforts. .
. . The club would love youngsters Troy Glaus and Tod Greene to
emerge as every day starters at third base and DH, respectively.
They have backup plans just in case, but with Dave Hollins coming
off rotator surgery, there is also a big question at third base.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Can Jim Edmonds co-habitate with some of his
teammates, especially the ones who questioned how seriously he
takes winning and losing? . . . If there is no trade, how will the
foursome of Erstad, Edmonds, Garrett Anderson and Tim Salmon
co-exist knowing one of them will have to rotate as the designated
hitter most every night? . . . How will Mo Vaughn react when he
gets a first-hand look at how laid-back the fans are? Remember,
he's coming from Boston, where fans live and die with the Red Sox. &QL; 
Seattle MARINERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stadium (capacity): Peoria Stadium (10,000).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workout times: 9 a.m. to 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 recap: 76-85 (third place, AL West).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Lou Piniella (seventh season).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Jose Mesa saved 85 games in 1995 and
'96. He has saved 17 the past two years. Seattle is counting on
Cleveland's former closer to resurrect his career in the Northwest.
It's a big gamble. If it works, though, the Mariners should be in a
position to contend. If it fails, Seattle will be looking at using
a hodge-podge of relievers to close.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: LHP Butch Henry, OF Butch Huskey, C Tom Lampkin RHP
Mark Leiter, IF-OF John Mabry, RHP Jose Mesa, OF Matt Mieske.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: OF Rich Amaral, OF Rob Ducey, C John Marzano, C
Joe Oliver, RHP Heathcliff Slocumb, RHP Paul Spoljaric, RHP Mike
Timlin, RHP Bob Wells.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Players to watch: With two of the top players in the game in
Ken Griffey and Alex Rodriguez, Seattle boasts as great a one-two
punch as there is. Watching these two is always special, the kind
of thing to tell the grandkids one day. . . . Young pitchers Ryan
Anderson and Freddie Garcia, acquired in the Randy Johnson deal
with Houston, promise to be big-league pitchers for years to come.
The club would love to have them spend one more year in the minors,
but if they have fantastic springs, the kids could force the club's
hand. . . . There is no finer defensive first baseman than David
Segui. He's so good in the field that he's the first option to play
outfield if Jay Buhner is not ready to start the season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: A bullpen that resembled a train wreck most of
last season will try to right itself with questionable additions
such as Mesa and Leiter. Are those really the answers to the
bullpen woes? . . . Amazingly, the Mariners were 48-60 while Randy
Johnson was there and 28-25 after he was traded to Houston. Still,
there is no denying how dominant a pitcher he can be. Can the other
starters pick up that slack? . . . Exactly how sound is Buhner's
right throwing arm? He underwent reconstructive surgery last season
and was not expected to return before the end of May. Now he says
he will be ready to start the season, but in left field, not his
customary spot in right. If he's in left, it will be a big boost.
If not, how will the Mariners handle their defense? &QL; 
San Diego PADRES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stadium (capacity): Peoria Stadium (10,000).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workout times: 9:30 a.m. to 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 recap: 98-64 (first place NL West, NL champions).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Bruce Bochy (fifth season).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: George Arias takes over at third base
for the departed Ken Caminiti. Filling the shoes of the former MVP
will be difficult enough, but if the Padres expect Arias to also
fill the clubhouse role Caminiti held, they're crazy. No one can be
to a club what Caminiti was to the Padres the past few years. It's
just not fair. The Padres will need someone to step up, and there
appears to be no clear-cut contender for this role.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: RHP Carlos Almanzar, OF Garth Brooks, IF Damian
Jackson, OF Shane Mack, IF Dave Magadan, RHP Carlos Reyes, OF
Reggie Sanders, RHP Woody Williams.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: RHP Kevin Brown, 3B Ken Caminiti, RHP Joey
Hamilton, OF Steve Finley, OF Mark Sweeney, OF Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Players to watch: Fans have been hearing about the highly
touted Matt Clement for a few years. It seems 1999 will be his
introduction. He figures to land a spot in the rotation and, if
everything we've heard about him is true, he should be here for
good. . . . If Quilvio Veras is unable to start the season because
of his shoulder surgery, then rookie Damian Jackson will be
expected to start at second base. . . . Andy Ashby was walking
around shell-shocked after his World Series experience, when the
Yankees tattooed him good in Game 2 in the Bronx. He must show he's
got a stronger will this season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Exactly who will fill the gap for lost
starters Brown and Hamilton, who combined to win 31 games last
season, or 32 percent of the team's victories? . . . Can Dave
Smith, the former All-Star reliever with Houston, have as
successful a season at pitching coach as Dave Stewart, now an
assistant general manager in Toronto, had last season? . . . How
long before reliever Randy Myers and his hefty salary are traded? &QL; 
San Francisco GIANTS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stadium (capacity): Scottsdale Stadium (10,500).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workout times: At Indian School Park, 10 a.m. to 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 recap: 89-74 (second place, NL West).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Dusty Baker (seventh season).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Shawn Estes is the undisputed ace of
the staff, at least based on his 19 victories from two years ago.
The problem is he slid last season (mostly because of injuries) and
managed just seven wins. If the Giants are to surprise for a third
straight season, Estes will have to have a big season again. With
Orel Hershiser out of the picture, this is Estes' staff now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: LHP Alan Embree, RHP Greg Hansell, RHP Felix
Rodriguez, OF F.P. Santangelo, C Scott Servais, LHP Trevor Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: OF Joe Carter, RHP Danny Darwin, IF Shawon
Dunston, RHP Orel Hershiser, RHP C Brian Johnson, Jose Mesa, LHP
Alvin Morman, OF Dante Powell, SS Rey Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Players to watch: Ellis Burks is coming off knee surgery and
will be expected to take over fulltime duties in right field. He
was one of the biggest run-producers around during most of his
years with Colorado. The Giants are counting on Burks being able to
do the same in the middle of their lineup. . . . Ever so quietly,
Jeff Kent has emerged as one of the top RBI players in the game. He
has 249 combined RBIs the past two years, an amazing fact
considering he plays in the shadow of Barry Bonds. . . . There will
be no other veteran shortstops in camp this time around, meaning
the job is all Rich Aurilia's.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Baker has pulled magic out of his hat two
consecutive seasons as his club has managed to play better than
clubs which, on paper, appeared better built. Is there yet another
season of magic in Baker's cap? . . . There is every reason in the
world to believe Bonds, who turns 35 this year, has not lost a
thing. He remains one of the top players in the game and his
numbers last season indicate the downside of his career has not
begun. Still, one of these years it will start to happen. It's only
natural, right? Is 1999 the time? . . . Will anyone shed any tears
as the Giants prepare for their final season at decrepit and
windswept Candlestick Park? This is it before the club moves to
PacBell Park. &QL; 
Chicago CUBS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stadium (capacity): HoHoKam Park (12,500).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workout times: 9:15 a.m. to 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 recap: 90-73 (second place, NL Central, wild-card
winners).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Jim Riggleman (fifth season).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Strange, but this one belongs to the
Tribune Co., which controls the purse strings. This is definitely a
large-market and large-revenue club that acts more like a
mid-market club. The Cubs are perennial money makers yet ownership
will not allow the baseball people to act like the Braves or
Yankees. If they ever did, watch out. This club could be dangerous
on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: RHP Jon Lieber, C Benito Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: OF Brant Brown, RHP Mike Morgan, C Scott Servais.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Players to watch: Once again, the one to watch in Mesa will be
Sammy Sosa, whose 66 home runs last season is the second-highest
total in the history of the game. Sosa had a jam-packed off-season,
flying to all parts of the globe, and the wonder is whether he will
be exhausted by the time camp opens. . . . Benito Santiago, former
Rookie of the Year and All-Star, is back again to try his hand.
After missing almost all of last season because of a car accident,
Santiago is down to his last chance in ball. If he fails this one,
his once-promising career may very well be over at the tender age
of 33. . . . Lance Johnson used to be one of the top leadoff
hitters in the game. Now he's a mere shadow of that. The wonder
around camp is whether Johnson even cares? If he doesn't it's a
shame. If he does, it's time to show it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Will the Cubs be able to make it through the
season without needing Medicaid? This will be one of the oldest
clubs in the league. Every regular is at least 30, with Gary Gaetti
at the top at 40. . . . How will the Cubs manage to eke out a
playoff spot when everyone else in the division, except for
Milwaukee, has improved? The Cubs appear too willing to rely on
magic this season and it could haunt them by the All-Star break. .
. . The most scrutinized elbow in Chicago will belong to Kerry
Wood. How will his elbow, which became tender last season, hold up
for an entire season? &QL; 
Chicago White SOX
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stadium (capacity): Tucson Electric Park (11,000).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workout times: 9:30 a.m. to 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 recap: 80-82 (second place, AL Central).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Jerry Manuel (second season).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: His teammates can't help but look up
to him. Even so, Frank Thomas seems uninterested in assuming a
leadership role. But With Robin Ventura and Albert Belle gone, the
need for Thomas to step to the front of the class and take over has
never been greater. Is he simply a player capable of amassing great
stats, or is he a great player?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: OF John Cangelosi, OF Darrin Jackson, IF Paul
Konerko, OF Tyrone Pendergrass, OF Chris Singleton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: LHP Jim Abbott, OF Albert Belle, IF Wil Cordero,
3B Robin Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Who to watch: Greg Norton will have first crack at taking over
for Ventura at third base. His hands will be full as his teammates
look for someone to fill those huge shoes. . . . What has happened
to Jaime Navarro? Once considered one of the top up-and-coming
pitchers in the league, Navarro has become an embarrassment. His
6.36 ERA earned a demotion to the bullpen last summer. Many eyes
will be on this strong right-hander, who was supposed to fill the
void left when Alex Fernandez departed. . . . Second-year Manager
Jerry Manuel earned high praise from peers last season. He will be
faced with an even greater challenge this year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: The question of the spring will be finding
someone to replace Ventura. But Ventura, who left for the Mets via
free agency, was so much more than just a third baseman. He was the
only player willing to stand up and be the leader of this group. .
. . Unlike the club that plays on the north side of town, the White
Sox have the opposite age problem. This will be one of the youngest
clubs in the league. Will they have problems finding suitable
babysitters? . . . Now that the Mike Cameron era has failed,
Chicago must find a center fielder from a group that includes
rookies Brian Simmons, Chris Singleton and Tyrone Pendergrass. In
addition, Darrin Jackson might make his way into this battle. Is
there a center fielder among that group? &QL; 
Milwaukee BREWERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stadium (capacity): Maryvale Baseball Park (8,000).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workout times: 9:30 a.m. to 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998 recap: 74-88 (fifth place, NL Central).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Phil Garner (eighth season).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Center fielder Marquis Grissom was
supposed to bring an added dimension last season. All he did was
play well below his standards. If Milwaukee is to surprise anyone
in the Central, Grissom will need to become the catalyst he was on
World Series clubs in Atlanta and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: LHP Jim Abbott, OF Rich Becker, IF Sean Berry, OF
Alex Ochoa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: IF Bob Hamelin, 1B John Jaha, C Mike Matheny, RHP
Jose Mercedes, OF Marc Newfield.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Players to watch: The club tried all winter to trade All-Star
second baseman Fernando Vina, a consummate professional. The bigger
question is whether Vina sticks around through spring training or
the Brewers manage to finally trade him. . . . Injury-prone Dave
Nilsson returns to his original position behind the plate. All eyes
will be on the Australian to see if he can handle the rigorous
chores. . . . Former reliever Bill Campbell takes over as pitching
coach. It will be his duty to try to coax a bunch that had the
13th-worst club ERA in the league last year into a turnaround.
Milwaukee's two complete games was the lowest total in NL history.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Once again, Milwaukee is trying to put
together some semblance of a rotation. At the start of camp, the
rotation looks like this (honest): Scott Karl, Steve Woodard, Bill
Pulsipher and Rafael Roque. They combined for zero complete games
last year. . . . Is the newly acquired Berry capable of playing
first base on an every-day basis? He platooned at third base in
Houston the past few years but the Brewers are looking for some
right-handed power and Berry, they believe, is the answer. . . .
Will new Commissioner Bud Selig honestly be able to keep his hands
out of the daily operation of his former club? Many owners will be
watching this one closely. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
