<HEADLINE>
GRAPEFRUIT LEAGUE CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baltimore ORIOLES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 79-83 (4th place, AL East).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Ray Miller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Brady Anderson must return to being
one of the top leadoff hitters in the game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: OF Albert Belle, RHP Ricky Bones, 1B Will Clark, 2B
Delino DeShields, RHP Mike Fetters, C Charles Johnson, RHP
Heathcliff Slocumb, RHP Mike Timlin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: 2B Roberto Alomar, RHP Armando Benitez, OF Eric
Davis, RHP Alan Mills, 1B Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Will Miller be able to motivate a group that
slumbered last season? Can Timlin become a big-time closer? Is Cal
Ripken ready to sit once in a while? &QL; 
Boston RED SOX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 92-70 (2nd place, AL East).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Since GM Dan Duquette seems to be the
common denominator in star players leaving Beantown, it's
appropriate that his rear is on the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: LHP Mark Guthrie, DH Bob Hamelin, IF Jose Offerman,
RHP Mark Portugal, RHP Pat Rapp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: IF Mike Benjamin, OF Darren Bragg, RHP Robinson
Checo, RHP Dennis Eckersley, 3B Tim Naehring, LHP Greg Swindell, 1B
Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: How long before the fans turn on Offerman, who
is not to blame for the Red Sox offering him a ridiculous four-year
$26 million deal? Is there any way Bret Saberhagen and Tim
Wakefield can team up for 32 victories again? How will Mo Vaughn be
received the first time he visits Fenway as an Angel? &QL; 
Toronto BLUE JAYS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 88-74 (3rd place, AL East).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Tim Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Homer Bush has been a prospect for
more than three years now. Well, it's time to show what you got,
Homer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: DH Geronimo Berroa, 2b Homer Bush, 2B Joey Cora,
DH-1B Cecil Fielder, 3B-OF Willie Greene, RHP Joey Hamilton, LHP
Graeme Lloyd, RHP Eric Ludwick, C Mike Matheny, LHP David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: DH Jose Canseco, RHP Roger Clemens, RHP Woody
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Was the Clemens trade everything it's been
cracked up to be for the Blue Jays? Who will fill Canseco's shoes,
the ones that hit 46 homers? Can Johnson overcome his lying? &QL; 
Tampa Bay DEVIL RAYS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 63-99 (5th place, AL East).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Larry Rothschild.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: This club is so far away from being a
contender, there are no key pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: DH Jose Canseco, LHP Norm Charlton, LHP Steve
Cooke, C Joe Oliver, RHP Bobby Witt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: RHP Dave Eiland, RHP Brad Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Will Canseco manage to stay interested on a
last-place club? Can pitchers begin to have confidence at Tropicana
Field, which plays a lot shorter than it is? Needing just 78 hits
to reach 3,000, will Wade Boggs' eyes and legs manage to hold up
that long? &QL; 
New York YANKEES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 114-48 (1st place, AL East; World Series champions).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Torre has been the vital cog in this
run. As long as he remains the rock that he is, Yanks will continue
winning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: RHP Roger Clemens, RHP Mark Johnson, RHP Jeff
Juden, RHP Todd Noel, LHP Ed Yarnell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: 2b Homer Bush, LHP Graeme Lloyd, 3B Mike Lowell,
OF Tim Raines, LHP David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Will Clemens be able to fit in with this
championship club? What type of rings should the Yankees order for
their second straight championship? Will Derek Jeter get back
together with pop-diva Mariah Carey, or is it really over? &QL; 
Cleveland INDIANS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 89-73 (1st place, AL Central).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Mike Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: If healthy, Steve Karsay could provide
a tremendous boost to this rotation and be the biggest surprise in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: 2B Roberto Alomar, IF Wil Cordero, LHP Ricardo
Rincon, RHP Jerry Spradlin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: C Pat Borders, IF Jeff Branson, 2B Joey Cora, DH
Cecil Fielder, OF Brian Giles, RHP Doug Jones, RHP Chad Ogea, LHP
Jim Poole.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Since he is upset with his contract, where
exactly will SS Omar Vizquel's head be? Is Jaret Wright ready to
work hard toward becoming the dominant pitcher he's capable of
being? Will the Alomar brothers, together for the first time in the
majors, play off each other to have monster seasons? &QL; 
Kansas City ROYALS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 72-89 (3rd place, AL Central).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Tony Muser.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: In short, there are no keys to this
mishmash of players. It's a sad, sad day for baseball in the
Heartland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: RHP Erik Hanson, C Chad Kreuter, 3B Joe Randa, SS
Ray Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: RHP Tim Belcher, RHP Ricky Bones, 1B Hal Morris,
2B Jose Offerman, 3B Dean Palmer, RHP Pat Rapp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: How long before the club dumps Kevin Appier
($4.8 million) and Jeff King ($4 million)? Who will take up the
innings now that Belcher and Rapp are gone? Will this franchise be
sold and finally be able to begin the slow climb back? &QL; 
Minnesota TWINS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 68-94 (4th place, AL Central).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Tom Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Kelly is under no pressure to win.
Still, it's got to eat at him that the Twins are considered a
laughingstock.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: OF Melvin Nieves, RHP Bob Wells, 3B Eddie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: SS Pat Meares, DH Paul Molitor, OF Otis Nixon, OF
Alex Ochoa, RHP Bob Tewksbury.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Is there anything that can keep the Twins from
a losing record for a seventh straight season? Will Brad Radke
return to his 20-game form from 1997? Are they really playing major
league baseball in the Twin Cities? &QL; 
Detroit TIGERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 65-97 (5th place, AL Central).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Larry Parrish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: OF Bobby Higginson and 1B Tony Clark,
both young, appear ready to become club leaders. Their challenge
will be getting other players to follow their examples.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: C Brad Ausmus, RHP Willie Blair, RHP Robinson
Checo, OF Karim Garcia, C Bill Haselman, IF Gregg Jefferies, 3B
Dean Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: OF Luis Gonzalez, 3B Joe Randa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Is minor league sensation Juan Encarnacion
ready to play right field every day? Can SS Deivi Cruz regain the
range he lost after breaking his left ankle last spring? After 88
years there, will fans flock to the final season at venerable Tiger
Stadium? &QL; 
Texas RANGERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 88-74 (1st place, AL West).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Johnny Oates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Juan Gonzalez, MVP two of the last
three years, is once again in phenomenal shape and ready for
another monster season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: RHP Mark Clark, RHP Mike Morgan, LHP Mike Munoz, 1B
Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: 1B Will Clark, C Bill Haselman, RHP Todd
Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Will closer John Wetteland be the same after
undergoing the first arm surgery of his career? Will anything be
able to kick-start the talented but seemingly underachieving
Esteban Loaiza? Can Palmeiro come home again? &QL; 
Atlanta BRAVES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 106-56 (1st place, NL East).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Bobby Cox.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Brought over in part to provide a more
youthful look to the coaching staff, it's Don Baylor's job to get
the Braves to score runs in bunches.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: 2B Bret Boone, OF Brian Jordan, OF Otis Nixon, LHP
Mike Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: IF Greg Colbrunn, RHP Dennis Martinez, LHP Denny
Neagle, OF Michael Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Will reliever Mark Wohlers ever return to his
All-Star form? What's going to happen in left field, where Ryan
Klesko and Otis Nixon will battle? When will Jane Fonda get Ted
Turner to stop wearing a baseball cap with his suits? &QL; 
Florida MARLINS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 54-108 (5th place, NL East).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: John Boles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Cliff Floyd became the first Marlin in
more than two years to receive a multi-year contract. With it,
comes responsibility. It's up to Floyd to lead this kiddy corps
offense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: LHP Armando Almanaza, C Jorge Fabregas, C Guillermo
Garcia, IF Benji Gil, RHP Braden Looper, 3B Mike Lowell, OF Russ
Morman, OF DaRond Stovall, OF Pat Watkins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: RHP Manuel Barrios, IF Josh Booty, OF John
Cangelosi, RHP Oscar Henriquez, C Randy Knorr, Mgr. Jim Leyland,
RHP Eric Ludwick, RHP Donn Pall, SS Edgar Renteria, UT John Wehner,
C Gregg Zaun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Can Alex Fernandez return to being a dominant
starter? Exactly who are these guys? Is there anyone out there who
will honestly miss Wayne Huizenga? &QL; 
Philadelphia PHILLIES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 75-87 (3rd place, NL East).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Terry Francona.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Ron Gant had a spectacular season in
1996. If he can manage to cut down on strikeouts, he is capable of
helping the Phils surprise a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: RHP Jeff Brantley, OF Rob Ducey, OF Ron Gant, OF
David Miller, RHP Chad Ogea, RHP Cliff Politte, C Tom Prince, LHP
Paul Spolgaric.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: OF Ruben Amaro Jr., RHP Ricky Bottalico, OF Lenny
Dykstra, RHP Mark Leiter, IF Mark Lewis, C Mark Parent, RHP Mark
Portugal, RHP Jerry Spradlin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: How long before Curt Schilling demands to be
traded? Is talented but young Marlon Anderson ready to become the
second baseman? Can Brantley, who had an awful season, return to
being a bonafide closer? &QL; 
Montreal EXPOS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 65-97 (4th place, NL East).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Felipe Alou.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: It all starts and ends with talented
right fielder Vladimir Guerrero, who is arguably the best young
player in the game today.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: RHP Danny Bautsita, OF Orlando Merced, OF James
Mouton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost piece: OF F.P. Santangelo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Can a young rotation that features Dustin
Hermanson, Carl Pavano and Javier Vazquez take off without veteran
leadership? Can crumbling Olympic Stadium withstand another year?
If the Expos fall and no one hears them, do they exist? &QL; 
New York METS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 88-74 (2nd place, NL East).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Bobby Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: The Mets made one heck of a financial
commitment to Mike Piazza. Will he carry New York to its first
postseason berth in 11 years?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: RHP Armando Benitez, OF Bobby Bonilla, OF Roger
Cedeno, OF Rickey Henderson, RHP Oscar Henriquez, 3B Robin Ventura,
LHP Allen Watson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: 2B Carlos Baerga, RHP Willie Blair, C Jorge
Fabregas, IF Lenny Harris, C Todd Hundley, OF Butch Huskey, OF Tony
Phillips, RHP Armando Reynoso, RHP Mel Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: At age 40 and back in the Big Apple, can
Henderson squeeze out another stellar season? How will John Franco
react the first time part-time closer Benitez enters to save a game
in the ninth inning? Now that his nemesis, Tim McCarver, is no
longer in the TV booth second-guessing him, will Valentine finally
relax a bit? &QL; 
Houston ASTROS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 102-60 (1st place, NL Central).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Larry Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Ken Caminiti was always thought to be
the heart and soul in San Diego. If he can push the Astros to the
next level, this club could be making its first World Series
appearance ever.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: 3B Ken Caminiti, RHP Dean Crow, RHP Xavier
Hernandez, OF Ryan Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: C Brad Ausmus, 3B Sean Berry, LHP Randy Johnson,
LHP Mike Magnante, LHP C.J. Nitkowski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Can Dierker guide this club to a third
straight playoff appearance? Will Caminiti accept sitting regularly
to save his aching body, as Dierker plans to do? Now that Clemens
will not become an Astro, will Houston's players be able to get
over it? &QL; 
St. Louis CARDINALS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 83-79 (3rd place, NL Central).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Tony La Russa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Pitching coach Dave Duncan will be
asked to pull out yet another miracle. He has a fabulous track
record but showed last year he is no match for injuries. The heat
is on the Cards' coaching staff in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: 2B Carlos Baerga, RHP Ricky Bottalico, OF Darren
Bragg, C Alberto Castillo, OF Eric Davis, LHP Scott Radinsky, LHP
Mike Mohler, SS Edgar Renteria, RHP Garrett Stephenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: RHP Jeff Brantley, 2B Delino DeShields, OF Ron
Gant, OF Brian Jordan, IF/OF John Mabry, C Tom Pagnozzi, RHP Cliff
Politte.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Is Drew ready for the daily grind? Will Juan
Acevedo start or relieve? How many interview requests will Mark
McGwire turn down this spring? &QL; 
Cincinnati REDS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 77-85 (4th place, NL Central).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Jack McKeon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: The fans of Cincinnati. If they show
up in healthy doses, GM Jim Bowden will be able to make moves to
keep the club in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: LHP Steve Avery, OF Mike Cameron, 2B Damian
Jackson, C Brian Johnson, IF Mark Lewis, 1B Hal Morris, LHP Denny
Neagle, OF Mark Sweeney, OF Michael Tucker, OF Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: 2B Bret Boone, OF Melvin Nieves, 1B Eduardo Perez,
LHP Mike Remlinger, OF Reggie Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Between Cameron, Jeffrey Hammonds, Jon
Nunnally and Tucker, who starts in center field? Will Neagle fall
in love with Cincinnati and not demand a trade after the season?
When will Marge Schott finally sell her shares and leave the game
for good? &QL; 
Pittsburgh PIRATES
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 69-93 (6th place, NL Central).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Gene Lamont.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Finally, Kevin Young will have some
help in the middle of the lineup. The arrival of Brian Giles should
help Young reach even better numbers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: IF Mike Benjamin, OF Brant Brown, OF Brian Giles,
LHP Pete Schourek, 3B Ed Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: LHP Jon Lieber, OF Manny Martinez, LHP Ricardo
Rincon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Owner Kevin McClatchy said this club is the
most-improved in the division; can the Pirates live up to that? Is
1996 first-round pick Kris Benson ready to move into the rotation?
Los Angeles DODGERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1998: 83-79 (3rd place, NL West).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manager: Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Key piece to the puzzle: Mike Piazza is gone and Todd Hundley
will be expected to be the big bopper in the middle of the lineup.
If he isn't, the Dodgers have problems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New pieces: LHP Pedro Borbon Jr., RHP Kevin Brown, LHP Greg
Cadaret, LHP Chris Haney, C Todd Hundley, Mgr. Johnson, LHP Ricardo
Jordan, C Tim Laker, IF Scott Livingstone, RHP Alan Mills, RHP Mel
Rojas, OF Devon White.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lost pieces: LHP Brian Bohanon, IF-OF Bobby Bonilla, OF Roger
Cedeno, OF Jim Eisenreich, LHP Mark Guthrie, RHP Darren Hall, C
Charles Johnson, OF Matt Luke, RHP Ramon Martinez, LHP Scott
Radinsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Three questions: Brown has pitched under pressure, but can he
live up to the record $105 million contract? Is Hundley's right
elbow up to the task of catching every day? Is Johnson the one to
inspire the most underachieving club the past five years? &QL;
</P>
