<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3188 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      02-20 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TWO-BIT THEFT OF A PRICELESS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her obituary in the Feb. 15 ``Arizona Republic'' reported that
Adele Coffield, 87, of Phoenix, a retired school teacher, passed
away Feb. 12. Survivors include two daughters and a brother.
Services were held at Westminster Presbyterian Church on 19th
Avenue. In keeping with newspaper policy, cause of death was not
listed.
</P>
<P>
   It should have been.
</P>
<P>
   It would have read: Purse snatching.
</P>
<P>
   One Thursday afternoon in early July 1997, Adele Coffield parked
her new Dodge Stratus in the lot of the Smitty's store at 35th
Avenue and Bethany Home Road. It was just before 4 p.m., and Mrs.
Coffield, as was her habit, planned to eat dinner at the in-store
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   She'd done this most days since the death of her husband, Carl,
in 1993. The couple had moved to Arizona in the mid-'60s, after
selling the family dairy farm outside of Wheeling, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   They knew Arizona well. &QL; 
SHE CAME HERE TO LIVE
</P>
<P>
   Adele's own parents had retired here when Adele's children were
young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every summer, my mother and us kids would catch the train in
Pittsburgh and come out here,'' says Adele's daughter, Karen
Hahacek. ``I can't remember a time we didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Adele earned a master's degree in education at Arizona State
during those summer visits. She taught second and fourth grades in
West Virginia and taught for 10 more years in Phoenix. Carl went to
work for a plant nursery here. Their son, Al, became a collector
and expert on Model A automobiles. Another daughter, Ann, earned an
education degree from Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our father died in 1993, our mother decided she would
stay in the same house,'' Ann said. ``She was very independent. She
had church and friends. She drove.''
</P>
<P>
   She did crossword puzzles in ink. She quilted, and she was
famous for her lemon meringue pies. She bought a new car and drove
it to church and to Smitty's every day for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   That July afternoon in 1997 she had just stepped out of the car
when a man she didn't know approached her and asked if she had the
time. Before she could check her watch the man grabbed Mrs.
Coffield's shoulder bag and tried to tear it away. She was a small
woman, but determined. She didn't let go easily.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, he tore the purse away from her, leaving
Adele on the ground with a broken right arm and a broken shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   SHE BLED ON THE INSIDE
</P>
<P>
   There was internal bleeding in the arm, which concerned doctors.
Mrs. Coffield was taking blood thinning drugs for a heart
condition. In order to stop the hemorrhaging in her arm, physicians
took her off that medication.
</P>
<P>
   About a week later, she had a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It paralyzed her on the right side,'' said her daughter, Ann.
``She never really recovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Adele managed to learn to eat with her left hand, but she
couldn't speak. Her daughters tried to get her to type out her
thoughts, but the stroke left Adele unable to spell even her own
name.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who'd done crosswords in ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got depressed sometimes,'' Ann said, ``but for the most
part she hung in there and did the best she could. She was
strong-willed. And very kind. Very good.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time she passed away of complications from the stroke,
Mrs. Coffield was said officially to have died of ``natural
causes.'' But she didn't.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of unnatural death that only happens in big
cities, where good and gracious people, like her, are so necessary
and so vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   And whose passing too often goes ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The purse snatcher was never caught. About a week after the
attack, a couple returning home from vacation found Mrs. Coffield's
belongings in their back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother never carried any cash,'' Ann Kilbourn said. ``She
wrote checks or used ATM and credit cards. All she kept in her
purse was 25 cents, in case she needed to make a telephone call.''
</P>
<P>
   The purse was undamaged.
</P>
<P>
   Inside it were Adele's car keys and her wallet, her checkbook,
bank card and credit cards. As far as anyone could tell, the only
thing missing was the quarter. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3189 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS     02-20 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Dierker may mull unorthodox move
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The Roger Clemens ordeal is over, the pitching
staff is virtually set and the everyday players soon will be in
town, ready to slide right into their well-secured positions in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   These are indeed wonderful spring days for Astros manager Larry
Dierker. He's got sunshine all day, cool breezes all night, a most
formidable team at his fingertips and even tickets to today's
Rockets-Orlando Magic game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to get my basketball fix,'' Dierker said. ``With the
(NBA) lockout, I didn't get to see much basketball before I got
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is good. And here in Astros camp, it seems the toughest
decisions Dierker will have to make this spring are the stuff of
managers' dreams: Wedge or putter? Spinnerbait or topwater?
Pretzels or peanuts?
</P>
<P>
   ``No question I feel a lot better about this team right now than
I did at this point last year,'' Dierker said. ``We're pretty
set.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty much. But even in these early days of spring training,
when the batters in practice are imaginary and the games
make-believe, there is an interesting decision on the horizon
Dierker and the Astros might make.
</P>
<P>
   It is a decision that goes against every basic big-league
principle, a choice most managers avoid at all costs and one that
few teams have tried.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros are considering it: Outside of closer Billy
Wagner, a completely righthanded bullpen?
</P>
<P>
   Understand, there is little chance Dierker will begin the 1999
season with all righthanded long relief in the bullpen, but the
likes of Scott Elarton, Jose Cabrera, Dean Crow, Chris Holt and
Brian Powell _ all righties _ are making Dierker and the Astros
weigh its advantages and disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   Trever Miller, who is out of options and would have to be waived
if he is not on the big-league lineup on opening day, is penciled
in as the opening-day lefty reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Miller had his moments out of the pen a year ago and finished a
respectable 2-0 with a 3.04 ERA. But Miller was not the
overwhelming force against lefties a year ago that the Astros hoped
he would be. And righthanders Doug Henry and Jay Powell performed
better against lefthanded batters than they did against
righthanders a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The move to go righthanded in the pen would be risky. Basically,
except for his closer, Dierker would have no secrets or cards in
the hole against opposing managers, an option every late-inning
critical moment demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a good thing to have a lefty out there,'' Dierker
said. ``I don't think it's going to happen, but it's a
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The performances by several impressive righthanders this spring
and into the early part of the season might make it even more of a
possibility. Elarton, whose talent and potential were enough for
the Astros to pull out of trade talks for Clemens, figures to only
improve. He must be considered a top prospect for the fifth
starter.
</P>
<P>
   But Holt, coming off surgery to repair a frayed rotator cuff
that made him miss the 1998 season, has been strong throughout
workouts and has showed no ill effects in the elbow. Saturday's
pitching drills proved to be the biggest step yet in Holt's
establishing himself as a candidate to start.
</P>
<P>
   After three days of hard throwing, the Astros expected Holt to
tire or lose pop in his pitches Saturday. He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm particularly pleased with him,'' Dierker said. ``He's
showing all his pitches and throwing hard.''
</P>
<P>
   As things look now, Elarton or Holt will earn the fifth
starter's spot behind Shane Reynolds, Mike Hampton, Sean Bergman
and Jose Lima. If Holt earns the job, Elarton then likely would go
back to the pen and join Henry, Jay Powell, Wagner, Xavier
Hernandez and Miller.
</P>
<P>
   But that's a full complement of 11 pitchers and the Astros like
what they have seen in several others, particularly Crow and Brian
Powell, the relievers acquired from Detroit in the Brad Ausmus
trade. They also like Cabrera, who made the opening-day roster a
year ago before injuries sent him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important not to overreact to what you see in spring
training,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Dierker also often has said the opening-day lineup
isn't what matters most. It's all about getting players set on the
roster when September rolls around and division titles are won.
Between now and then, the Astros likely will be asking themselves
the question about which they are wondering:
</P>
<P>
   Is it better to have a lefty reliever in the pen simply for the
sake of having one? Or is it better to have all righthanders if
those are your best guns, the players who give the team the best
chance of winning?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to have tough decisions, I suppose,'' Dierker said.
``I'm sure it's something that will work itself out.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be the big righthander's call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-20-99 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
