<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3191 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TEXAS-TEXASA&AMP;M-HN     02-20 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-TEXAS </SLUG>
 A&AMP;M-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
UT goes outside to get the best of A&AMP;M
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
COLLEGE STATION _ Texas A&AMP;M did everything it could to keep Chris
Mihm and Nnadubem ``Gabe'' Muoneke from controlling the game in the
paint for Texas, something the two big men for the Longhorns have
done most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was working well until Kris Clack and William Clay
burned the Aggies with 3-point jumpers in the second half that
changed the flow of the game and enabled Texas to claim a 63-54
victory Saturday at Reed Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The 9,424 spectators _ the largest crowd to watch an A&AMP;M
basketball game _ saw the Longhorns clinch at least a tie for the
Big 12 championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas victory at Oklahoma on Saturday means Texas (17-10
overall and 12-2 in the Big 12) can sew up the regular-season title
with a win at Baylor on Wednesday. The Longhorns are 15-3 since
starting the season 2-7 under new coach Rick Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long way from where we were Dec. 18th,'' Barnes said.
``I've really enjoyed watching these guys grow. I trust them and I
believe in them. I don't think there was one time today when I
yelled because I was upset about something. These guys have become
a basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies (11-13, 4-10) looked like a good basketball team most
of the day. Their sagging defense inside helped earn a 40-37 lead
with 10:04 to go.
</P>
<P>
   But the momentum of the game shifted when the Longhorns made
three consecutive 3-point baskets _ two by Clack and one by Clay _
to take a 46-40 lead with 8:39 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were very big shots, but good teams step up and do what
they did,'' A&AMP;M coach Melvin Watkins said. ``I was really pleased
with our defensive effort, but you have to hit some shots. In a
rivalry like this, you have to step up and make a play. They did,
we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Clack, the game's top scorer with 22 points, started the
long-range barrage when he sank a trey from the right baseline.
Then Clay made one from almost the same spot before Clack added
another 3 from the left wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing a sagging defense all night and didn't let
us get it inside to Gabe or Mihm like we wanted to,'' Clack said.
``But we did it in the second half, they kicked it out and we
knocked down the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of Mihm's three assists came in that one-minute sequence
when he tossed the ball outside after he was triple-teamed down
low.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge,'' Mihm said. ``It was the dagger. We had been
trading buckets, but after those 3s, I think (A&AMP;M) might have run a
couple plays too quickly and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas went on a 13-0 run and took a 50-40 lead with 7:10 to play
after two free throws by Clay, a Bryan High product who was playing
in front of family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 45 tickets for this one,'' Clay said. ``I've been
thinking about this game all year. I couldn't wait for it to get
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay came off the bench and scored seven of his eight points
during the 13-0 run that decided the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just playing your role,'' Clay said. ``In this offense,
you never know when your time will come. They sagged on Mihm all
day, then started trying to deny Clack, so it was my time to be
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive is a good way to describe Saturday's game, which at
times looked more like rugby than basketball. Texas shot 35.7
percent (15-of-42), but the Longhorns held the Aggies to 29.6
percent (16-of-54).
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams really went at each other defensively,'' Barnes
said. ``There were no easy baskets on either side.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies surrounded Mihm and Muoneke whenever either player
touched the ball, holding Muoneke to 11 points and Mihm to nine.
</P>
<P>
   But both players still managed to do the job on the boards. Mihm
equaled his career-high with 17 rebounds. Muoneke added nine
boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I barely had room to move down there,'' Mihm said. ``It was
tough, but we knew it was coming. I told Gabe they were going to
try to beat on us, but we're used to it. I told him to keep his
head and we would wear them down eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies did a nice job of fronting Mihm with Joe White or
Paul Jacobs, then collapsed down low whenever Mihm of Muoneke got
their hands on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``At halftime, we said we had to get the ball inside no matter
how good a job they were doing on us down low,'' Barnes said. ``We
had to work the ball from the inside out.''
</P>
<P>
   But the aggressive inside defense caused A&AMP;M's Shanne Jones and
Aaron Jack to get in foul trouble. Jones sat on the bench for seven
crucial minutes of the second half when he had four fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stopping the big guys was our main focus,'' Jones said. ``They
both are great players. But me and A.J. (Jack) got in foul trouble
and that hurt us. We had some silly fouls inside that killed us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
