<HEADER>
A3192 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-SMU-NEVADA-LAS-VE     02-20 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-SMU-NEVADA-LAS-VEGAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESERVE IGNITES SMU WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Late in the first half of a difficult struggle with
Nevada-Las Vegas yesterday, SMU coach Rhonda Rompola scanned the
bench and announced the Mustangs needed a spark.
</P>
<P>
   Obediently, Anika Calvert promptly banged in two 3-point shots
to even the score, and SMU (14-10, 9-3 Western Athletic Conference)
was launched on a 27-4 run that eventually grew into a 74-62
victory against the Rebels (15-9, 6-6).
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it began,'' UNLV coach Regina Miller said, ``we just
couldn't stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory preserved SMU's grip on second place in the Mountain
Division heading into the final week of the season, along with an
opportunity to earn a first-round bye in the WAC tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this means we're peaking at the right time,'' said
Rompola, whose team has won seven of its past eight games, with the
only loss coming to Colorado State on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Once Calvert sparked the Mustangs, this one came easy. The
Mustangs shot 48 percent, forced 26 turnovers and held a commanding
lead throughout the second half.
</P>
<P>
   But after missing 13 of their first 17 shots, they trailed 16-10
when Calvert hit her first shot with seven minutes left in the
half. Her second one pulled the Rebels out of their zone, and
Karlin Kennedy and Claudia Brassard combined for 14 points in the
next five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like we were just taking turns,'' said Brassard, who
finished with 13 points in the final regular-season home game of
her SMU career. ``When they came out of the zone, everything opened
up inside for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and Calvert _ who hit four 3-pointers _ each finished
with 20 points, offsetting a 25-point, 11-rebound performance by
UNLV freshman Linda Froehlich.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into the game all pumped up, because they beat us
earlier out there,'' Calvert said. ``I guess I just kind of got
caught up in the hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Rompola figured the team might have been a little too pumped in
the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes that works against you, and I think we were a little
to tight at the start of the game,'' she said, ``but Anika relaxed
us. Winning two at home this way gives us some good momentum,''
Rompola added, referring to an 82-44 victory against Air Force on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:49 remaining, the Rebels briefly cut a 20-point deficit
in half with a flurry of 3-pointers against the Mustangs reserves,
but it was too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
