<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-ISLES-NYT &LR;      02-20 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-ISLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLES BEAT DEVILS, 3-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ One day after the Devils were humbled by
the defending Stanley Cup champion Red Wings in Detroit, they came
home and were embarrassed by the struggling Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Despite getting Dave Andreychuk back from injury, the Devils
blew a third-period lead and were beaten by 3-2 Saturday night
before 19,040 at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who outshot the Islanders by 26-19, took a 2-1 lead
into the third period but allowed the visiting team to carry the
play. The result was two goals, the second of which was scored in
spectacular fashion by Bryan Smolinski on the power play at 17
minutes 1 second.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski controlled the puck near center ice, and skated
through three Devils, turning defenseman Scott Niedermayer around
en route to the net. Smolinski scored with a high wrist shot that
went over goalie Martin Brodeur's glove.
</P>
<P>
   Zigmund Palffy, the Islanders' crafty wing, tied the game at 2-2
at 7:40 of the third period. Standing behind the net, Palffy threw
the puck in front. It ricocheted off a Devil and dribbled under
Brodeur and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   The only good news for the Devils was that Andreychuk returned
after missing 21 games with a broken right ankle. Having him back
in the lineup figures to help the Devils, whose offense has been
inconsistent over the last month.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's game featured a goal for each team in the
opening two minutes, setting the pace for a fast-paced first
period.
</P>
<P>
   Patrik Elias scored for the Devils and Barry Richter tallied for
the Islanders. On the Devils' second shift, Elias scored just one
minute into the game. Elias was entangled with Islanders defenseman
Rich Pilon in front of the net when the Devils' forward received a
pass from Jason Arnott, who was in the corner. Elias controlled the
puck and chipped it over Tommy Salo's blocker pad.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Continental Arena fans could settle back into their
seats, Richter, an Islanders defenseman, ripped a long shot past
Brodeur 55 seconds later. Richter's shot, which bounced at least
once before entering the net, appeared to fool Brodeur, who managed
only to wave his stick at the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Sykora snapped the tie with a weak snap shot from the top
of the left circle at 9:11 to give the Devils a 2-1 lead. That type
of goal, called a green sector shot by Stefan Lunner, the
Islanders' goalie coach, supports Mike Milbury's decision to trade
for goalie Felix Potvin. While Potvin _ who pulled a groin muscle
and has been out for a week _ has not played well since he was
obtained from Toronto in a Jan. 9 trade, he is seen as an upgrade
over Salo. Especially when Salo allows two goals in the first
period.
</P>
<P>
   In the scoreless second period, both teams had prime scoring
chances. The best belonged to the Islanders, who not only saw
Trevor Linden clank a shot off the post, but watched as Palffy,
alone in front of the net, found Brodeur's chest protector late in
the period. The Islanders took over in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a good welcome back for Andreychuk, whose return had
not been decided until Saturday afternoon. He had been expected to
play on Friday at Detroit, but the coaching staff did not think he
was in game shape, so he had been sent back to New Jersey to
practice on his own at South Mountain Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Without Andreychuk in the lineup, the Devils had gone 10-9-2.
Andreychuk, who played on a line with Randy McKay and Bobby Holik,
had not played since breaking his right ankle on Jan. 5 against San
Jose. He had surgery three days later, sending him to the sideline
with an ankle injury for the second time in three years. The big
left wing had fractured his left ankle in the final game of the
1996-97 season and missed all but one of the Devils' playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to jump right back in,'' Andreychuk said before
Saturday night's game. ``I'm going to have to play my way back into
the lineup. There are going to be some situations where I'll have
to be cautious. You can practice all you want, but you can't
simulate game conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main objective right now is not to be a liability out
there,'' he added. ``I have to get my timing and positioning
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
