NYT-02-20-99 2303EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3201 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUARD-TURKEY-AZR &LR;      02-20 2241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUARD-TURKEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPPERHEADS REFUEL JETS THAT PATROL NO-FLY ZONE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere along the Turkish border, 26,000 feet above ground,
Copperheads from Arizona are fueling the military campaign against
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Gulf War ended eight years ago, Air National Guard mem
bers with the 161st Refueling Wing have been helping patrol the
skies of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred men and women, mostly from the Valley, leave
behind families and civilian jobs to serve three-week tours. They
are not just pilots and navigators, but mainte nance crews,
intelligence officers and others.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Day 1, Phoenix to Spain
</P>
<P>
   They arrive at Sky Harbor Inter national Airport before dawn,
dressed in cammies, passing through the security gate to
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three men and women from Arizona, about to travel 7,000
miles _ halfway around the world _ to play sky cop in northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Before gear is loaded on the plane, a videotape on emergency
procedures is shown.
</P>
<P>
   Crash instructions seem absurd. The KC-135, after all, carries
up to 110,000 pounds of fuel, and would probably blow sky-high in a
crash.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what happened three weeks earlier, when an Air
National Guard tanker from Wash ington state went down along the
German-Dutch border, killing every one aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Crew and passengers line up for chemical suits and gas masks.
They get another briefing on the terrorist threat in Spain _ their
first stop _ and in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   And then a final word: ``Have a safe trip,'' the briefing
officer says.
</P>
<P>
   They board the KC-135 shortly after dawn. It resembles a Boeing
707 passenger jet. On its nose: a phoenix bird rising from scorched
earth. Bart Simpson looks on, declaring, ``Awesome, dude.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it's a cold, dark tunnel with four small windows and a
couple of dim lights. The jet engines roar so loud that, during
flight, crew and passengers wear headsets or plugs to protect their
ears.
</P>
<P>
   Luggage is on the floor; passen gers sit on fold-out canvas
seats along padded walls.
</P>
<P>
   The KC-135 taxis to the runway, hesitates, then rises as Phoenix
shrinks into the past. Next stop, McGwire Air Force Base in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Guard members shout conversa tion over the jet roar, mouth to
ear. Some pace. Others sit near portals to read by the wan light.
</P>
<P>
   Master Sgt. Steve Hanson, a Peoria firefighter, is a 10-year
veteran of the Guard, with experi ence in Operation Southern Watch
out of the United Arab Emirates. He flew refueling missions over
Bosnia from a base in Italy. He's been on hundreds of training
flights out of Sky Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is tension. As the plane levels off, Hanson jokes
about his teenage kids back at their Gilbert home, and how much
they'll miss him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like, `Yeah, Dad, go so we won't have you bothering
us, telling us what to do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mention of his wife draws more dark humor: ``Sure, she worries.
But if anything happens, she's better off with me dead than alive.
She'd be able to pay off the house (with insurance money) and get a
better looking guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson and his crewmates knew for weeks their turn was coming.
They watched the news _ saw that Saddam Hussein had begun taking
potshots at coalition fighters.
</P>
<P>
   In late December, Iraqi forces launched missiles and fired
anti-air craft bursts at coalition jets in the no-fly zone. The
incidents, sporadic and spastic, signaled a change in Iraq's game
plan.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 8, after U.S. jets were targeted by anti-aircraft radar,
a high-ranking Marine Corp officer warned of more to come from
Saddam: ``He's dangerous now. He could become more dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard members begin to relax somewhere over mid-America. A few
crawl into sleeping bags on the floor or atop baggage. One sits
beneath a light, reading The History of the World.
</P>
<P>
   The Guard seems different from other military units, less rigid.
Officers address one another by first name. There is no saluting,
no ``yes sir'' and ``no sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been flying with some of these guys for 25 years,''
explains Col. Joe Smith, the Guard's public affairs officer.
``We're a big fam ily.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech Sgt. Bill Sommers of La veen, an internal auditor for
Arizona Public Service Co., is the prototype. He's been with the
Air National Guard 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the volunteers, Sommers wipes out all of his
vacation time on Guard missions and training exercises.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sense of time or distance in the flying tunnel. It
stops for food and fuel in New Jersey, then takes off across the
Atlantic for Rotta, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gillooly, the navigator, spends most of his life as a
Phoenix cop flying helicopters. This morn ing, he was with his
daughter, Bryanna. Now he's en route to the Iraqi border to police
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Gillooly uses computers, global position systems and charts to
keep the old plane on course, flying at 560 knots into night. He
jots down a a calculation, then grins: ``This is the same way
Magellan did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson eyeballs a sextant in the cockpit ceiling, trying to pick
up stars for a celestial reading as turbulence rocks the plane. &QL; 
 &UR; Day 2, Spanish nights
</P>
<P>
   The flight was uneventful, except for a generator gauge that
went bonkers. Now, for a 24-hour layover in Rotta, a beachfront
resort.
</P>
<P>
   The Guard members know this is their last liberty before
marathon shifts at Incirlik. They march in small groups down narrow
Spanish streets to the ocean. Signs announce that Christopher
Columbus em barked on his new world adventures from this spot.
</P>
<P>
   After snapshots and lunch, they converge on an Irish pub for
another brand of refueling. At Taberna Irlandesa, all fears are
drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some flyers grouse about ``this piddly-ass war.''
</P>
<P>
   Most hate playing sky cop. They spit out the word ``politics''
and wonder aloud why they cannot shoot except in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a low-satisfaction factor,'' one pilot complains. ``We've
turned into a police force.''
</P>
<P>
   They say the Air Force and National Guard have been cut by
one-third, yet they carry the nation's biggest military burden.
Some have been shipped into the no-fly zones and Bosnia more than a
dozen times since 1991. If sky supremacy is the key to modern
warfare, they ask, why are flyers and support crews taxed to
breaking?
</P>
<P>
   Some talk of quitting _ of signing up with airlines for more
money, more time with wives and kids. &QL; 
 &UR; Day 3, Welcome to Turkey
</P>
<P>
   The Mediterranean glitters below, with giant snow-capped
mountains rising from its shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead is Adana, a second-world metropolis of dirt streets and
glitter ing mosques. Two serpentine rivers wind through the
countryside, a geometry of orchards and field crops.
</P>
<P>
   Dead ahead, the runway at Incir lik Air Base rises to greet a
stratotanker from the Grand Canyon State.
</P>
<P>
   Copperheads are shuttled away for briefings and work. AWACS
command ships are lined up on the Tarmack. Concrete and earthen bun
kers house the fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 Air Force personnel are based here, along with
Marine Corp flyers, a U.S. Army detach ment and British and Turkish
forces. As an F-15 Eagle roars skyward, Lt. Col. Joe Smith explains
why report ers were invited on this trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has a right to know,'' he says, ``This is an
incredible thing. We're killing peo ple every day. . . . And
stopping someone else from killing people.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour begins moments later at the office of Brigadier Gen.
Savas Sanliturk, co-commander of Opera tion Northern Watch. Just
outside, a Turkish lieutenant hands out a hand-printed list of
three questions and says, ``This is what you will ask.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a bowl on the coffee table containing a bouquet of ciga
rette packs. It is a formal event, polite conversation in a
military maelstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi forces have just fired on U.S. warplanes in the no-fly
zone. Tariq Aziz, Saddam's deputy prime minister, is in Ankara
telling the Turks to stop supporting coalition forces. Kurdish
rebels are about to riot in European capitals. The Turkish
Parliament, recently dissolved, is jockeying for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Sanliturk speaks of Asia Minor's history, of bonds with America.
</P>
<P>
   The general emphasizes that U.S. and British fighters only fire
if they are attacked. Someone serves Turk ish tea in petite
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop: Patriot missiles. These were installed just weeks
earlier in case of a Scud attack. The Iraqi border is 340 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   The van then heads for a confab with U.S. fighter pilots. They
don't want their names used, just in case they get shot down and
captured.
</P>
<P>
   They say Iraq's anti-aircraft arse nal is pathetic. But they are
not cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes intensely personal when you see Triple A (flak)
going off around your aircraft,'' says a pilot who's seen nine
tours in the no-fly zone since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the van to a munitions depot. Sgt. Leon Mitchell shows
off the latest toy. It's an AGM-130 computer-guided missile with
enough bang to blow up anything within 4,000 feet. There is a
message on the nose: ``Hi, mom.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Days 4 &AMP; 5, Off to Cappadocia
</P>
<P>
   Military personnel at Incirlik usu ally work seven days a week.
When they take a couple of days off, it's classified information.
Iraq's not supposed to know when the fighters are grounded.
</P>
<P>
   This day, more than 140 active Air Force personnel and National
Guard members pile into buses. They head 200 miles north of
Incirlik, through high sierras to a land called Cappadocia.
</P>
<P>
   Here, geology and Mother Nature conspired to create bizarre rock
formations _ a mixture of Sedona and Wilderness of the Rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Here also, there are amazing subterranean cities and ancient
churches sculpted into hillsides of porous, volcanic tufa. One
commu nity, started by the Hittites nearly 4,000 years ago, once
housed 10,000 people. It contains eight levels and descends more
than 200 feet underground _ a bee hive carved in rock.
</P>
<P>
   Saints Paul and Peter wandered these hills. One small valley con
tains more than 250 cave churches with ornate religious murals
painted by monks.
</P>
<P>
   A tour guide points out that Turkey is a historical link between
Asia and Europe, a land criss crossed for military and religious
conquest. The Romans, Greeks, Persians, Hittites, Assyrians, Turks
and crusaders _ all left their mark.
</P>
<P>
   And now American military per sonnel tour the ruins, haggling
for Turkish rugs and pottery along the way. &QL; 
 &UR; Day 6, the mission
</P>
<P>
   The KC-135 has been dubbed ``Ice 1'' for this mission. Arizona
crew members were up at 4, getting briefed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at dawn, they taxi away from the tarmac and head to the
southeast corner of Turkey, escorted by two fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   AWACS airborne command ships are aloft already. The team will be
joined by more fighters and recon naissance planes. In three hours,
they have fueled eight F-16s and F-15s while flying circles on the
edge of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Below is a wasteland of mountain and snow. Aaron Vangelisti of
Scottsdale, the Ice 1 pilot, prepares to head back to Incirlik when
Iraqi anti-aircraft guns open fire, fol lowed by a pair of
surface-to-air missile launchings.
</P>
<P>
   Crew members can see the smoke trails. After a few hairy
moments, it is obvious that the Iraqi gunners have missed again.
Fighter jets move in, blasting away at targets. As Ice 1 turns
back, two more Arizona stratotankers take its place.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the base, Ice 1's crew finishes a debriefing and heads
into The Alley, an off-base shopping area, for a dinner of Turkish
bread, hummus, goat cheese, lamb and beer.
</P>
<P>
   The day's events weigh heavy. One Copperhead says fighter pilots
were so geeked up they came in for refueling ``with their hair on
fire.'' Another says he's never seen so much flak thrown skyward. A
third describes post-flight debriefing ses sions as hell.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, Saddam vows to attack the Turkish air base at
Incirlik. &QL; 
 &UR; Days 6 &AMP; 7, Homeward bound
</P>
<P>
   Anti-terrorism security is elevated at Incirlik. Even The Alley
is off limits.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven Copperheads, done with their three-week tour, climb
aboard a KC-135 for the long ride to Arizona, bearing Turkish
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   They sleep across the Mediterra nean. There is an overnight stop
in Moron, Spain, but few have the energy to party. They just want
to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Garrett is returning to his wife, son and daughter. The
tech sergeant from Avondale seems pained that most of this trip has
been spent on the ground; he made only three sorties.
</P>
<P>
   He struggles to explain the attrac tion, deciding that it's
something akin to the lure of moth to flame.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to do it. It's for real. . . . Heck, maybe so one day
I can look back and tell my grandkids, `Hey, I was there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They cross the Atlantic to New Jersey, coming to life only when
the plane begins its approach to Sky Harbor. They talk about wives
and boyfriends and dogs and cats. Some one sings the chorus line to
Bruce Springsteen's Born in the U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, Staff Sgt. Bryan Parker of Gilbert hugs his three
boys as his wife, Lisa, looks on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never afraid,'' she says. ``I sit back and hold my
breath. When you're dealing with someone like Saddam, you never
know what's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys said their prayers every night: `Please, just get
Daddy home.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dennis Wagner can be reached at
 &UR; 444-8874 or at dennis.wagner &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
