<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-MESSAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS SHOOTING TO GET COLORADO'S ATTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Messages don't come in bottles in the NHL _ unless they're
broken over an opponent's head.
</P>
<P>
   Notes in hockey generally are passed with the butt end of a
stick, a well-placed elbow or a puck slipped squarely between a
goalie's legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think messages can be sent during the regular season,''
Stars center Mike Modano said. ``I think we've done that with
Detroit this year and we'd like to do it with a few more teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Avalanche would be a good start today, when the
Avalanche visits Reunion Arena for the second Sunday in the past 14
days. The Avalanche took a 3-0 victory against the Stars the last
time the teams met, sending a message to the Stars and to the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy came up with 27 saves
in a game in which his team was outshot, 27-12. That dropped at
least one little hint that the Stars should be worried if they have
to face him in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Stars can whisper in a few Avalanche ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychological edges are very important in the business of
winning, and we have chances to earn those edges every day,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I mean, can we beat this team if we
haven't beat them before? Can we beat them four times? things like
that become very important.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars and Avalanche have never played a playoff series. The
Stars and Edmonton Oilers have played two postseason series in the
past two seasons. When the Stars played the Oilers on Monday,
messages were sent all over the ice in a fight-filled game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at games like the Edmonton game and those are playoff
type games,'' Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``I think you learn
a lot about your team in games like that and you can also send
little messages that maybe people around the league will see.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Colorado, for example, the Stars have shut down Peter
Forsberg and Joe Sakic for the past three seasons. If they continue
that trend in the regular season, it can only help if the two teams
meet in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the media the way it is, that'll be something that's
dragged out and talked about and I think that can get into their
heads,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``It's definitely something that could
help us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also can be hurt by messages. Goalie Ed Belfour
struggled in the 3-0 loss to the Avalanche at a time when media
outlets across the country were questioning if he is the weak link
in the Stars' run for the Stanley Cup. So does Belfour try to send
his own message today?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what anybody says in the paper and I don't care
about sending messages to anybody,'' Belfour said defiantly,
perhaps sending a message to his critics. ``I come out and try to
win every game I play, I'm a competitive person and I like to win.
If I don't play well one game out of every 10, there's nothing I
can do about that. I just forget it and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, teams can't forget. The Avalanche and Red
Wings have sent messages since developing the league's most vicious
playoff rivalry. The Stars sent messages to the Red Wings earlier
in the season when they twice won at Joe Louis Arena, breaking a
slump that had reached 1-17-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those games in Detroit were big confidence boosters,''
Hitchcock said. ``I think we knew we could win there, but it makes
a difference to actually go in there and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hitchcock said the Stars have gained just as much
knowledge when they've been sent a message. The Stars lost, 5-2,
against the New Jersey Devils on Nov. 25 and lost, 2-0, against the
Phoenix Coyotes on Nov. 11. In both situations, the Stars needed a
wakeup call, Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's great about games with the top teams is you know you're
going to learn something no matter what happens,'' Hitchcock said.
``After this game, we'll know a little bit more about them, but
we'll also know a little more about ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
