<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OKLAHOMA-CITY-TOURNAMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS, KOURNIKOVA TO PASS CLOSE TO THIS AREA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For fans of professional tennis living in North Texas, the IGA
Superthrift Tennis Classic is as good as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, it's as close as it gets, even if ``close''
is decidedly relative.
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong WTA Tour event, featuring some of the best women's
tennis players in the world, begins play Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that's a lot closer than Leipzig, or Bogota, two of the
other stops on the globetrotting WTA Tour that touches down in
several towns in California, the Southeast and the Northeast during
the year, but not Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The long drive across the border could be well worth the trip
this year. The Oklahoma City tournament, which started in 1986,
features the No. 5 player in the world, Venus Williams of the
United States, and No. 12, Russian Anna Kournikova. Also in the
field of 30 are No. 13 Amanda Coetzer of South Africa and two
Americans in the top 30, No. 25 Lisa Raymond and No. 28 Chanda
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   As the top two seeds this week, Williams and Kournikova receive
first-round byes, meaning they're not expected to see action until
midweek. Quarterfinal action is scheduled for Friday, the
semifinals for Saturday and the finals for next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' return will be special. She won her first professional
singles title at Oklahoma City last year, defeating Joanette Kruger
in the finals after beating then-defending IGA champion Lindsay
Davenport in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Williams went on to win The Lipton Championships and the Grand
Slam Cup later in the year, moving from the rank of potential star
to star.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty exciting since it was my first title,''
Williams said from Hanover, Germany, last week. ``It was our first
title, too,'' she added, referring to her IGA doubles championship,
won with her sister, Serena, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams is skipping the IGA this year, as is Davenport,
now the world's No. 2 player behind Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport said last week she was battling a lingering cold and
was preparing for the upcoming Evert Cup in California and the
Lipton in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had planned to take this whole month off.'' Davenport said.
``The last two years I played in Oklahoma City, and last year I was
pretty tired when I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the presence of Williams and Kournikova, the IGA
won't lack star power, or, possibly, controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Williams drew undesired attention at the Australian Open in
Melbourne in January when the beads she wears in her hair fell out
during a loss to Davenport, causing her to be penalized and leading
to a conflict with the umpire.
</P>
<P>
   Williams downplayed the incident and said she will keep her
hairstyle and composure.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova, who hasn't won a WTA tour singles championship but
did, with Hingis, win the doubles title in Australia, has drawn
attention for her model-like looks as well as for her game.
</P>
<P>
   She was a finalist at the Lipton last year, defeating four top
10 players in four days, after vaulting to prominence in 1997 when
she was a semifinalist at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the Australian Open doubles final to Kournikova and
Hingis, Natasha Zvereva said of Kournikova: ``That's her first
Grand Slam, and I'm sure she's going to have more to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova has had some problems this year, however, with her
serve. At the Australian, in a match she still won, she whacked 31
double faults.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been happening for a while. I'm kind of used to it,'' she
said. ``I'm also kind of frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Offering $180,000 in prize money, the IGA is a Tier III event on
the WTA Tour, the category in which events offering at least
$170,000 but less than $500,000 are ranked.
</P>
<P>
   There are 12 Tier III tournaments on the tour as well as 15 Tier
II events (offering $500,000 to less than $1 million) and nine Tier
I events (more than $1 million). There also are 17 Tier IV events,
which offer at least $110,000 but less than $170,000.
</P>
<P>
   The IGA Superthrift Tennis Classic is being held at The Greens
Country Club. Ticket information can be obtained by calling (405)
297-3000 or (405) 752-7687.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
