<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELS SURVIVES BAD SPELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Through nine holes of the Nissan Open on Saturday,
Ernie Els and Ted Tryba both seemed hellbent on playing through
history. Els made the turn at Riviera Country Club in 5-under par,
one better than Tryba had some 90 minutes earlier.
</P>
<P>
   To scoreboard watchers, it looked less like a PGA Tour event
than a limbo dance. How low could Els and Tryba go?
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, it appeared to be no contest, Tryba
nimbly notching a course-record 10-under-par 61 to Els' strained
68. Ahh, but looks, how they can deceive. If not for one poor putt
and two bad swings, Els might have made up those seven strokes in a
flurry.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for nine-and-a-half holes it looked like nothing could
stop Els except possibly the 19th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going great guns,'' said the South African, who birdied
the first, third, sixth, eighth and ninth holes to go to 13 under
par through 45.
</P>
<P>
   Els was striding toward his ball on the 10th fairway, with not a
care in the world, when someone told him Tryba was one birdie on 18
away from a phenomenal 59.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Els had every reason to believe the bar had been
set impossibly low. Els' subconscious, which had been steering the
golfer to that point, seemed unsettled by the news. That's as good
an explanation as any for why Els proceeded to pull a putt that
looked to all his gallery to be a gimme, especially since he had
drained putts easily twice as long for birdies on three of the
previous four holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unconscious out there for a while,'' Els said. ``I was
hitting it very close for 10 holes. I felt like I really had
something special going. Then I just lost my momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Riviera. She's famous for hypnotizing golfers only to
snap them back to reality really fast. The course is a fickle
temptress, but Els had no one to blame but himself for giving back
three strokes to par on the next three holes.
</P>
<P>
   Two bad swings was all it took. The first was his third shot to
the par-5 11th. Els' second shot landed in a divot, but that was no
excuse for his lackadaisical 80-yard approach, which set up his
bogey-6.
</P>
<P>
   After parring No. 12, Els oscillated on whether to go with his
driver or his 3-wood on the 13th tee. He settled on the more lofted
3-wood, though you never would have guessed it by the
swing-for-the-fences cut he took at the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad swing,'' said Els, who was playing in the final
threesome along with Bob Estes, the second-round leader, and Alan
Bratton.
</P>
<P>
   Then laughing, Els added, ``I should have taken a mulligan
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't kidding about the swing. If there had been a fence in
the foul territory in left, Els surely would have cleared it. As it
was, the ball hit a tree and cowered in a ditch, out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   An agitated Els then went to Plan B, his driver, and smacked it
long and straight. He nearly salvaged a bogey, but his 30-foot putt
slid inches past the hole.
</P>
<P>
   You've never heard such loud applause for a double bogey (well,
outside of Ryder Cup anyway). The fans were firmly behind Els all
day, never more so than at that particular moment when he had the
glazed look of a survivor of a single-car crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big shock,'' Els said of his six. ``There I was, one
shot out of the lead and all of the sudden it's looking like I'm
playing myself out of the tournament. Some strange things go
through your mind after that.''
</P>
<P>
   A logjam at the par-3 14th gave Els more than five minutes to
seethe and suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to think about it slipping away because it
becomes a mind game then,'' Els said. ``You start trying to play
the shot instead of letting it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Els has hit purer 5-irons than his tee shot on 14.
The ball settled on the fringe of the green, above the pin. Els
took out his flatstick and nearly holed the difficult putt. That
tap-in along with the three pars that followed helped Els regain
his equilibrium.
</P>
<P>
   His flair caught up with him on the 18th green. With fans
ringing the green and blanketing the hill and holding their
collective breath, Els sank an 18-foot birdie putt to creep back
into contention. At 11-under par, he is tied for second with Tiger
Woods and Davis Love III, two shots behind Tryba.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of his finish was not lost on Els, who pumped
his fist as though he had won something. Which in a way, he had.
The putt earned him a reprieve and probably a more restful sleep
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real pleased with that birdie,'' Els said. ``I think it's
going to be a wonderful day (today).''
</P>
<P>
   The third-round leader has held on to win each of the past three
weeks on the PGA Tour. But don't be fooled. Sitting in a dentist's
chair for root-canal surgery is more relaxing than sitting atop the
leaderboard as holes are running out.
</P>
<P>
   Els was the bulls-eye briefly during his front nine and look how
boldly Tryba took aim at him. Today, the roles will be reversed and
that's fine with Els.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're leading,'' Els explained, ``it's a different
situation. You won't see the leaders shooting 61.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, in today's final threesome a 68 will be just
great. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
