<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3215 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERTS-DIARY-2NDTAKE     02-20 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERTS-DIARY-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ a wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 7: The first day of proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Very formal. Very impressive. No one is in sport coats. We're
all in blue suits.
</P>
<P>
   We take the oath, then we sign the book. We go down in a
procession....
</P>
<P>
   We keep the pen that we use to sign the book. But it doesn't say
`United States Senate.' It says ``Untied'' States Senate. Everybody
gets to snickering. They say: ``I hope we don't get untied. I hope
we can tie this up.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm in the second row from the back. It is quite a panorama.
From my seat you see the chief justice. You see all the galleries,
which are packed. You see the whole Senate sitting there. You see
the House managers and the White House lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The camera angle on television is terrible. I say to Trent
(Lott, the majority leader), `This does not do justice to these
proceedings.... Every time you walk in, there you get sort of a
jolt of how serious this is. On television, it just looks bland and
rather undistinguished.'
</P>
<P>
   The media literally just surrounds you as you get off the
elevators, on the steps, on the subway. We're talking about scores
of reporters. I just made a decision that I would be taking an oath
as an impartial juror, it's not right to be a talking head on
television.
</P>
<P>
   I came up with a formula: If a senator cannot speak inside the
chamber, there is a natural law that they speak 10 times as much on
television. The formula for that is X-denied equals CNN 10X.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 8: On the verge of a partisan split, both parties meet in
the Old Senate Chamber.
</P>
<P>
   We have the process showdown at the Old Senate Chamber. This is
the first step toward comity. I sit at the desk of (former
President James Knox) Polk, not because of history but because it's
in the back and off to the right, and you can see all the senators
and can leave if you want to.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Gramm gets up and says let's vote on process now and put
off a vote on whether to have witnesses until later on.
</P>
<P>
   Of all people, Ted Kennedy gets up and says: ``It looks to me
it's possible we can get to first base and then second base. I
don't know if we'll ever get home, but we ought to give it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   And nobody can believe it's Gramm and Kennedy working together.
It's just incredible.
</P>
<P>
   Trent jumps up and says, `I think we got a deal.' (Minority
Leader) Tom Daschle said we can work on witnesses down the road,
and I couldn't believe he said that because the White House didn't
want that.
</P>
<P>
   So we avoided a partisan split on process.
</P>
<P>
   I then became convinced of the value of closed sessions where we
talk to one another, rather than at one another in the press. We
never could have done that in an open session.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 10: With opening arguments still a few days off, senators
continue to debate whether witnesses should be called.
</P>
<P>
   I found that the early-in-the-morning thing is the best course
of action for me. That means you're getting up at 6 and getting
home at 8 or 9 o'clock at night....
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time during the mornings you're supposed to be two
places at the same time over half the time.
</P>
<P>
   I'd wake up and think: ``I've got to do some research. Let me
think, there was that asterisk on misleading a witness. Is that the
same thing as threatening a witness and obstruction of justice?
That's Section 1503, OK, I've got to read that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 14: The House managers begin making their case.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, we had a conference. Leadership is worried about
leaks (to the media).... I got to my feet and said, look, ``You're
not going to stop leaks. You're just not going to stop that, so
don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   I think they just finally got over it.
</P>
<P>
   (House manager) Asa Hutchinson's brother, Tim, is a senator from
Arkansas and sits right behind me. Tim was more nervous about
everything than Asa was. He wanted his brother to do a good job.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 15: More prosecution statements.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sitting in the Senate looking at my Democratic
colleagues.... All of a sudden I thought, ``What would I do if the
defendant were Ronald Reagan, and this were Iran-contra? What if it
were Ford? Would I have the same feeling about this?''
</P>
<P>
   ...If I were a friend of Bill, what would I do? I sort of
wrestled with that. You raise up your hand and say I'm impartial,
but is it possible really to divorce yourself from that?''
</P>
<P>
   (House Manager) George Gekas spoke today. He didn't use notes.
His mother was an immigrant. She took the test for citizenship and
George was trying to coach her on her test. And he said, ``Mom,
what are the three branches of government?''
</P>
<P>
   And his mother said, ``There's the executive, the legislative
and there's the (sic) `judish.' '' And then Gekas said my mother
knew that the `judish' was the one thing different from the old
country and why she came to America.
</P>
<P>
   That got me....
</P>
<P>
   Tom Harkin (Iowa Democrat) interrupts the proceedings to insist
we are the `triers of fact,' not `jurors.' I think, `OK, fine.' But
that night, Franki (Roberts' wife) and I went out to dinner late at
a neighborhood restaurant and there's a longtime acquaintance, and
he is just a raging Democrat.... He's leaning over the table, and
he's red-faced. He says this is the most important thing in this
trial: Are you a trier or a juror?
</P>
<P>
   I said, `Well, I'm both.' I said, `Hey, we're going to eat
dinner here. I'll talk to you about it.'
</P>
<P>
   We just decided we wouldn't be going out to dinner after that.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 16: House managers finish their opening arguments.
</P>
<P>
   They generally do a good job. There's no question that they
tended to get to go on a little long....I try to take copious
notes. I always do this, more especially when it gets a little
tedious. There are times I write down: `This is boring. I wonder
when the next break is coming?' MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
