<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-CLEMENS-1     02-20 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-CLEMENS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS THRILLED TO BE A YANKEE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update and rewrite thruout)   By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ By the time Brian Cashman arrived at Tampa
International Airport to pick up the newest Yankee Saturday
morning, Roger Clemens was already at the baggage carousel, waiting
patiently and anonymously to collect his luggage. The pitcher had
already rented a car when the general manager found him. Clemens,
who signed only one autograph, was clearly eager to become a
Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   After Clemens arrived at Legends Field and was escorted into
Manager Joe Torre's office, the two chatted for about 10 minutes
concerning team rules and expectations. Torre said he gave Clemens
his usual spiel about being on time, about working hard, about not
having facial hair and not wearing jewelry during games. Mostly,
Torre simply stared at Clemens. The pitcher looked huge to the
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the chance to see the wall-to-wall man I've admired for
a long time,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   So did the rest of the Yankees, finally. When Clemens pulled on
the blue workout jersey with No. 12 on the back and walked to one
of the fields to simply play catch with the pitching coach, Mel
Stottlemyre, reporters followed him. When Clemens lined up to throw
in the right-field bullpen, dozens of fans stood shoulder to
shoulder to stare at him. Hardly anyone made a sound. It felt like
a tennis match, not a spring workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of strange seeing him in a Yankee uniform,'' Joe
Girardi said. ``It's a good kind of strange.''
</P>
<P>
   The delivery was familiar, the thud in Girardi's glove sounded
powerful, and the expression on his face was typically intense.
Clemens, who has been throwing for over a month, uncorked 59
pitches and was obviously ahead of the pace of most pitchers. The
6-foot-4-inch, 230-pound right-hander tossed two types of
fastballs, sliders, forkballs, and change-ups; most pitchers spend
the first week throwing only fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to have him out there,'' Stottlemyre said.
``I'm the pitching coach and I'll work with him every five days.
But I'm a baseball fan, too, and I get a thrill out of watching
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre, who watched Clemens with Stottlemyre from behind the
mound, pinched himself and admitted it was an exciting day for what
was supposed to be a routine day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He commands that respect and that attention,'' Torre said.
``As much as you like to say he's one player on the team, which he
will be for our purposes, he still perks your ears up a little. He
can't be anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   After Clemens graduated from high school in 1980, he was
anonymous to Torre on one day at Shea Stadium. Torre was managing
the Mets and Clemens worked out for them, but was not signed.
Clemens remembers Torre was unimpressed. Torre did not recall the
tryout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather plead ignorance than insanity,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, was emphatic
in stressing that Clemens would not be given special treatment.
Clemens' four sons had a locker at the Skydome when he was with the
Toronto Blue Jays, and he played on the field with them before some
games. Those privileges will not be extended to Clemens at Yankee
Stadium, at least not to that degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be a problem,'' Torre said. ``We don't allow
kids into the clubhouse before the game. They can come out early
before the game if they want.''
</P>
<P>
   When Clemens was asked if it was possible for a player of his
status to blend in, he said, ``Everything I've done, the team is
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was even more insistent while meeting with Torre. After
Torre finished going over the regulations, Clemens said: ``You
didn't have to read it. Just tell me where to be.''
</P>
<P>
   While the 36-year-old Clemens is also known for following his
own diligent routine as a pitcher, Stottlemyre said Clemens told
him that he would do ``whatever the Yankees want'' in addition to
his extra running. Although the Yankees had difficulty persuading
Hideki Irabu to alter the routine he had used in Japan, Stottlemyre
stressed that there should be no conflict with Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``His routine has been very successful,'' Stottlemyre said. ``It
will be a smooth transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman, who drove from the airport with Clemens, listened to
him gush about how excited he was to be with the Yankees and also
heard how Koby, the pitcher's 12-year-old son, had two hits in a
game on Friday. Before the trade, Clemens planned to stay in Katy,
Texas, until Sunday night to watch Koby play. But once the Yankees
summoned Clemens, he made his flight arrangements, rented a car,
scooped up his luggage, danced around a few questions, threw and,
of course, ran. It was his first day with the Yankees, but there
was a new ace in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' pitcher David Cone said. ``He's the ace of the
league. You could make an All-Star team from around the league and
he'd be the ace of that staff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
