<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE UPSET BY PORTLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU _ This certainly wasn't what Pepperdine seniors Jelani
Gardner and Marc McDowell wanted in their last men's basketball
game at home.
</P>
<P>
   But there it was, a 59-53 loss to West Coast Conference doormat
Portland in the last game of the regular season at Firestone
Fieldhouse on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no reason to allow what happened tonight,''
Pepperdine coach Lorenzo Romar said after the Waves dropped to
18-11, 9-5 in the WCC. ``We were our own worst enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine enters the WCC tournament as the No.2 seed. The Waves
will most likely play San Francisco, which beat Pepperdine in the
teams' last meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves lost three of their last four conference games. Forget
an NCAA Tournament at-large berth; that idea is history. An NIT
invitation is more likely unless the Waves win the conference
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all or nothing now,'' Gardner said. ``I think everybody
realizes that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of what Pepperdine did against the Pilots (9-17, 3-11) was
bad _ 18 turnovers, 42 percent (21 of 50) shooting that included
just three 3-pointers in 20 attempts and a porous defense that
allowed Portland to shoot 55.3 percent (21 of 38).
</P>
<P>
   Portland wisely went to a zone defense in the second half as the
Waves clanked shot after shot and fumbled away the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, who had a team-high 13 points, refused to acknowledge
the team let down after beating WCC regular-season champion Gonzaga
on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's an excuse,'' he said. ``To be an NCAA
Tournament team, you have to bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   Romar tried everything to combat the Waves' ineffectiveness,
trying several lineup combinations. With one exception, when the
Waves took a 52-47 lead with 4 minutes, 20 seconds left, Romar's
revolving door at the check-in table didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose some rhythm with guys shuffling in and out,'' Romar
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, who didn't start Friday for the first time in 55 games
at Pepperdine, started on senior night. But he played only 26
minutes, less than the four other starters and reserve Ross Varner,
who was in for 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like I was out for a long time,'' Gardner said,
``but the team did play well when I was out.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland came in on a six-game losing streak and hadn't won
since Jan. 28, when they beat seventh-place USF.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pilots came out with a swagger, taking an 18-8 lead with
10:47 left in the first half. Nothing came easy for the cold Waves,
who didn't break into double figures until Gardner's 10-footer
bounced around the rim and in with 8:44 left.
</P>
<P>
   Portland went ahead for good on Travis Andrews' 3-pointer that
made it 53-52 with 2:20 left. Andrews had a game-high 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
