</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERTS-DIARY-4TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR'S DIARY PROVIDES INSIGHT INTO IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It was 3 a.m. in Kansas City when Sen. Pat
Roberts was dropped off at his hotel. He was not a happy camper.
</P>
<P>
   The Dec. 30 entry in Roberts' journal shows he had just flown in
from San Antonio, where Kansas State, his alma mater, had played
the worst game of its season in the Alamo Bowl. In just four hours
Roberts was to fly back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm standing there, and it's 13 degrees and snowing,'' Roberts
jotted down, ``and I've got to go back for this impeachment
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yuck. What a bummer.''
</P>
<P>
   What a bummer, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   He had only begun his journal a few days earlier. With history
about to be made, the former journalist began recording
observations and thoughts from his unique vantage point as a
senator-juror in the court that would decide President Clinton's
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually casting his vote in a doomed effort to convict
Clinton on both articles of impeachment, the 62-year-old Kansan did
not go into the trial without his own perceptions about the
president's trustworthiness.
</P>
<P>
   The views of Roberts, one of four Republicans elected to the
U.S. Senate from Kansas and Missouri, coincide with many in his
party who frown on much of what the president has done.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts had come to suspect that the White House had used
foreign policy to deflect attention from legal problems and had
boosted favored programs to cement the loyalty of key Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were the kind of things that were sort of bubbling in my
mind as this thing began,'' Roberts said in an interview, offering
context to his private observations of this momentous period. From
the floor of the Senate to its behind-closed-doors sessions, the
observations in Sen. Pat Roberts' journal provide an inside look at
this century's only impeachment trial of a U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
   His notes reflect the partisanship, and also the personality, of
one of the region's leading Republicans who struggled at times with
boredom, a bad cold and the swirling emotions of this moment in
history.
</P>
<P>
   The journal was compiled in Roberts' Senate office during breaks
in an often hectic schedule. He later read his entries _ which have
been edited for brevity _ to Steve Kraske, political correspondent
for The Star.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 19: The first entry actually comes well before the trial,
on the day the House passed the two articles of impeachment for
perjury and obstruction of justice. Roberts, who was working in his
Senate office that day, walked over to observe the chamber where he
had served 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   The day of infamy.
</P>
<P>
   I had not originally intended on going over to the House. But I
thought this is historic, and I have many good friends over there.
</P>
<P>
   It was emotional chaos. Tears. What's to become of us? What is
going on? We were imploding. This was after Bob Livingston had
announced his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Livingston comes off the floor and sees me, and says,
``Well, Roberts, you won't have me to kick around any more.'' I
give him a big bear hug and I say, ``Bob, we love you. Persevere.''
</P>
<P>
   I mean, there wasn't a dry eye in the place. On both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Gephardt was saying very quietly, ``We need to recess for
15 minutes. I need to change my speech.'' They did not recess. He
got up and spoke from the heart and had tears in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I only stayed for that first vote, and I left. I was
heartsick....
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 6: The Republicans hold their first impeachment conference
as a party.
</P>
<P>
   We have to figure out process first. We have to prevent the
Senate from self-destructing; everybody feels this way.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, we thought maybe the White House would work with the
House managers to shorten the trial. And that was a nonstarter.
They never got back to us.
</P>
<P>
   We agree that we cannot go past February. We agree that we must
stick together or the whole thing would fall apart, and we must
vote on the articles. Everything else is up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   There are constant meetings both official and unofficial with
Republicans and Democrats and people who knew each other from
committees or were friends who would go off into little huddles.
Both Republicans and Democrats, so that atmosphere was different
than the House.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, we were moving on our legislative agenda much
faster than normal, and we have work to do....
</P>
<P>
   Almost every senator spoke. One Western senator said: ``This is
a hung jury. This is not a trial. This is political. We must do our
constitutional responsibilities, we must protect the rule of law.
But let's face reality. The president will be acquitted. So
whatever we do here, let's keep that in the back of our mind and
see if we can expedite this.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought that made a lot of sense.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Burns, my good buddy from Montana, had the most emotional
speech of the day. He said, `What do you think the movie ``Private
Ryan'' is all about? What do you think our veterans died for? What
makes this country special is not elections...the difference in
this country is...no man is above the law. No man is different than
anybody else....'
</P>
<P>
   You could've heard a pin drop....
</P>
<P>
   Some people might think that's a bit much... (but) that made a
big impression on me. It was like a wake-up call. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
