<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3229 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     02-20 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 28)  
(lb) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICA IN BLACK AND WHITE: ONE NATION, INDIVISIBLE &LR;  By Stephan
Thernstrom and Abigail Thernstrom. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$18. Two social scientists argue in language that alternates
between combative and generous that it was World War II and not
civil rights laws and government intervention that led to better
prospects for black America. In 1997 the New York Times reviewer
Nicholas Lemann was not fully persuaded but praised the
``eloquence, toughness and conviction'' of their proposals to
improve race relations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NIGHT TRAIN &LR;  By Martin Amis. Vintage International, $11. The
tough-talking detective Mike Hoolihan is a ``big blond old broad''
assigned to investigate the apparent suicide of the daughter of her
commanding officer, a father figure to both women who saved
Hoolihan from her alcoholism. Last year the reviewer Patrick
McGrath called this ``a police procedural that elegantly defers to
the conventions of the genre while at the same time sinking its
probes deep into the question of human motivation.'' He added that
``this brilliant, painful short novel is ... so profoundly
inflected with grief that it achieves in the end a sort of
melancholy grandeur.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COMMANDING HEIGHTS: THE BATTLE BETWEEN GOVERNMENT AND THE
MARKETPLACE THAT IS REMAKING THE MODERN WORLD &LR;  By Daniel Yergin and
Joseph Stanislaw. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15. This ambitious
study charts an extraordinary revolution in progress: the shift in
the balance of power from big government to market forces, and the
effects of that change on global politics, economics and culture.
The result is ``a colorful and even suspenseful story of how the
world has been transformed over the last half century,'' Jeffrey E.
Garten wrote in the Times Book Review in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPENING AMERICA'S MARKET: U.S. FOREIGN TRADE POLICY SINCE 1776 &LR; 
By Alfred E. Eckes Jr. University of North Carolina, $19.95. A
former trade official in the Bush and Reagan administrations traces
the history of U.S. trade policy to help readers sort through the
arguments of both free-traders and protectionists. In 1995 Michael
Lind called this ``a dispassionate, informed and accessible
account.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A LOVER'S ALMANAC &LR;  By Maureen Howard. Penguin, $12.95. Modeled
on the ``Old Farmer's Almanac,'' this novel strives to demystify
the millennium by following a couple of Generation X'ers and an
extended cast of lively minor characters into the year 2000. It's a
strange brew, but it's also ``rich propaganda'' and ``the product
of obsessive craft,'' Lorna Sage wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFE WITH A STAR &LR;  By Jiri Weil. Northwestern University,
$15.95. The little-known but influential Czech author, who died in
1959, tells the tale of a lonely former bank clerk struggling to
survive in an unnamed city against the tyranny of an unnamed enemy:
It happens that the man is Jewish, the city is Prague and his
tormentors are the Nazis, but the story gains power through its
universality. In 1989 the reviewer Anne Tyler admired this
``stripped, stark, uninflected novel.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued another of Weil's books,
 &UR; MENDELSSOHN IS ON THE ROOF &LR;  ($15.95), in which a Nazi officer
orders the removal of a statue of the Jewish composer from the roof
of Prague's concert hall, with disastrous results. ``This brilliant
novel ... is dominated by a powerful authorial presence,'' Larry
Wolff wrote in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DREAMING OF HITLER: PASSIONS &AMP; PROVOCATIONS &LR;  By Daphne Merkin.
Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13. These strikingly personal essays and
musings take on such hot-button topics as adultery, the thrill of
shoplifting and the author's fondness for sexual spanking. ``Her
tone is a curious blend of girlishness and old-fashioned literary
starchiness,'' Kate Jennings wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DESSA ROSE &LR;  By Sherley Anne Williams. Quill/Morrow, $12. This
novel reshapes two incidents from the antebellum South _ one
involving a pregnant black woman sentenced to death for leading a
slave uprising, the other a lone white woman who gives sanctuary to
fugitive slaves on her farm _ so that the women meet and form an
unlikely bond. The result is an ``emotionally affecting and totally
unforgettable'' book, David Bradley wrote in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JUBILEE &LR;  By Margaret Walker. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $8.95.
This is the story of Vyry, the strong-willed child of a white
plantation owner and his black mistress, who comes of age during
the Civil War years. ```Jubilee' chronicles the triumph of a free
spirit over many kinds of bondages,'' Wilma Dykeman wrote in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A MARCH TO MADNESS: THE VIEW FROM THE FLOOR IN THE ATLANTIC
COAST CONFERENCE &LR;  By John Feinstein. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $14.
This account of the 1996-97 college basketball season unfolds
through the eyes of the nine coaches in the Atlantic Coast
Conference. ``Using his near-unlimited access, Feinstein is able to
describe the highs and lows each coach experiences,'' David Davis
wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NIGHT BEAT: A SHADOW HISTORY OF ROCK &AMP; ROLL &LR;  By Mikal Gilmore.
Anchor/Doubleday, $15.95. A journalist explores the dark side of
rock 'n' roll _ the danger, excess and nihilism that infuse the
work of musicians as varied as Elvis Presley and Kurt Cobain. Last
year the reviewer Michael E. Ross admired these ``witty, accessible
and moving essays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
