<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3231 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERTS-DIARY-4THTAKE     02-20 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERTS-DIARY-4THTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ way it happened.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 2 The Senate begins viewing Monica Lewinsky's videotaped
deposition. With acquittal looming, both sides look for a way to
officially rebuke Clinton for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   The effort for findings of fact against the president, as
opposed to censure, is gaining a little steam. The plan, which I
support, is to try to get at least five Democrats to support it.
Censure to me sets a very bad precedent.
</P>
<P>
   I listen to Monica's deposition. Three and a half hours. Thank
the Lord for fast forward.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 23rd time she has been deposed. She is very poised.
She is a very hostile witness to the House managers. I do not see
the need for Monica on the floor of the Senate and will vote
accordingly....
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 4: A majority of the Senate, including Roberts, votes
against having Lewinsky testify in person.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting between Monica and Vernon Jordan is telling. The
president calls during the actual meeting. Jordan does not tell
Monica. Later at the White House that night, Vernon Jordan meets
with the president following his Christmas party, goes to his
private quarters, then says he believes the president in regards to
the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Sure.
</P>
<P>
   All the way through this, it strikes me that it's not what the
president says, it's what the president does not say that is
important. He is the ultimate chess player, the marionette
master....You can see he is really the only one who knows
everything....
</P>
<P>
   When does he ever own up?
</P>
<P>
   Of all the tapes, the Sidney Blumenthal tape is the most
telling. But the House managers ask only for Monica (to testify on
the floor). Calling her and not the others is strange.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal comes right out and says the president lied, and this
went on for five or six months.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 8: Both sides present closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ...I believe good things have happened in closed session.
Members talk to one another. It's like a retreat, as opposed to us
being at one another in the media. And why should the media cover
jury deliberations to begin with?
</P>
<P>
   (House Manager) Steve Buyer of Indiana made a very good point.
He said there are 182 people serving time for perjury last year,
144 for obstruction of justice. What do you tell them?
</P>
<P>
   (Clinton attorney) Charles Ruff is an outstanding lawyer. He
made a very good defense for the president. He said we could not
get into the president's head in regard to intent.... If you're
coaching Betty Currie, maybe you're coaching her because you know
that Betty Currie talks with the first lady, and maybe that was the
reason he did it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shot.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, I have read and outlined Volume 3, Part II, Pages
450 to 625 of the president's grand jury testimony, and I outlined
them in yellow. There are seven times you can say the president was
misleading or untruthful. In Dodge City language, it was lying....
</P>
<P>
   During a break, I...take a short walk to the front of the
Capitol....I got to thinking about it, and I think, the president's
conduct cannot be a different standard for those he can send to war
or those he appoints to dispense justice. This is not right....
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 9: Senators begin their speeches behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   I'd say 90 percent of the senators were in attendance listening
to those 15-minute speeches for 2 days.
</P>
<P>
   And it is here, our third step, where the Senate came
together....
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people gave their personal background, their history,
why they came to the Senate and their affection for their fellow
senators. About halfway, more and more said here are my prepared
remarks and I'm going to hand them in. I just want to share
something else with you. And it got very emotional. There was an
understanding of tolerance and respect. Some were brought to tears.
It was quite a session.
</P>
<P>
   That could not have happened in open session. And it led, I
think, to a sort of a rebirth of the Senate at the end, why you saw
so many people with their arms around people. It was the best of
times, the worst of times.
</P>
<P>
   And then finally it got down to Trent and to Tom Daschle. There
were tears of joy, that we had come together as a Senate. We had
differences, but it was fair. We did the best we could. Both gave a
lot of credit to each other in language that I'm sure will be
sealed, unless they want to make it public....
</P>
<P>
   The outcome is not going to satisfy some with very strong
feelings on both sides. And there's going to be talk of
retribution. It's going to be interesting to see if this has
changed the dynamic of the Senate and how long it will last....
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 12: The Senate renders its verdict, denying the president's
critics even a simple majority for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``guilty'' did not come from my lips with any sense of
accomplishment. It was a sad day for the president. It was a sad
day for the Congress. It was a sad day for the United States....
</P>
<P>
   I found it necessary to take a little breath before I said
``guilty'' each time. You've been through this thing now for 18
days, and there was a lot of emotion in there.
</P>
<P>
   Then I leave and walk out and...do the obligatory 30 seconds on
television and there's (my wife) Franki and the Love Notes, a
Northern Virginia choral group all decked out in hearts, as a
surprise for me for Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   They sang, ``Let Me Call You Sweetheart,'' and I'm thinking,
``Welcome back to the real world.'' Thanks, honey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
