<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBCAM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB CAMERAS LET SURFERS PEEK INTO EVERYDAY LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN SIDENER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a high-tech peephole into Pirkko Essen's kitchen near
Stockholm, Sweden. Fire up your computer and you can see her
teenage children staring longingly at the devil's food cake she
baked Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the Netherlands, spy holes expose nearly every nook of Alex
van Es' home, including a view of who's ringing his doorbell.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, you can get a pretty good view into the Chandler
computer room of Steve and Connie Fannon.
</P>
<P>
   In an intriguing phenomenon sweeping the Internet, people such
as these are broadcasting fragments of their lives into cyberspace
using digital cameras that cost as little as $59.
</P>
<P>
   This swarm of Web cameras, or Web cams, offers live images of
Rottweilers, ferrets, fish tanks, sushi bars, hair curlers and
computer rooms. Lots of computer rooms.
</P>
<P>
   And in an equally perplexing practice on the other side of the
peephole, thousands of computer users are spending hours watching
fully clothed strangers sitting in their living rooms or at their
keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, the Web cam world seems fueled by a blend of ego
gratification and performance art. But supporters say it's
simplistic to dismiss it as nothing more than exhibitionism,
voyeurism and street theater.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a face personalizes the cold electronic communication of
the Internet, they say. Others say this is a toddling step toward
the science-fiction future we've been reading about for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more personal, more interactive,'' says Sharon Rothe,
owner operator of the Early-Morning-Coffee Cam and the Curler Cam.
``It's not just a Web page anymore. People can see my face. I can
wave to them and say, `Hi'.''
</P>
<P>
   There are already serious applications in the wings. A fledgling
Tucson firm hopes to market virtual quality time with children by
bringing live video from day care centers to working parents.
</P>
<P>
   This whole Web cam thing began with the Trojan Room Coffee
Machine, set up in the Cambridge University computer lab in 1991.
It soon was followed by Netscape's Fish Cam, which offers live
video of a fish tank.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish Cam spawned other fish cams, dog cams and ant-farm
cams. Then Web cams branched out beyond the critters. One site from
an auto body repair shop shows the live restoration of a vintage
Corvette. A California student who lives across the street from his
high school has constant live video of the school grounds during
daylight hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Club in Tucson offers nightly video of the music
acts on its stage.
</P>
<P>
   The Web cam craze has prompted satirical sites, such as several
litter-box cams, a cam cam that shows a purported live shot of
another Web cam and the Continental Drift Cam, which, broadcasting
from the Four Corners area, allegedly offers live video of the
movement of the Earth's tectonic plates.
</P>
<P>
   Many Web cam owners say that the video draws a striking number
of visitors to their sites.
</P>
<P>
   Rothe, a New Hampshire resident, went online with her Web cam
``on a whim.'' Then in an equally frivolous gesture, she launched
The Curler Cam, putting her hair up in rollers live on the Internet
each morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since last fall, I've had 6,000 hits (visitors) on my page,''
Rothe said. ``I did it as a joke. But when I stopped, I got a lot
of e-mail from people saying, `Where's the Curler Cam?' ''
</P>
<P>
   She revived the Curler Cam.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Fuhrman of Avondale doesn't have a curler cam or any
other bells and whistles. The 63-year-old's Web cam just shows him
working at his computer. Still, his camera draws a lot of visitors.
He's had about 7,700 hits in the 18 months that the camera has been
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had people from as far away as China, Turkey and
England nag me about my smoking, as if the smoke was bothering
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I receive comments on what I am wearing, drinking, etc. It
really surprises me as to the number of people who look in daily or
many times.''
</P>
<P>
   While 6,000 or 7,000 hits may sound like a lot, it pales in
comparison with the traffic that clicks through the Essen's site,
one of the most popular cams on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are used to having it here as a member of the kitchen,''
Pirkko says via e-mail. ``I am the only one who is thinking some
days, `to open, or not to open.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Essens are not immune from Web surfers looking for sexual
content. They are frequently asked whether they are naked in their
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmm, we are always dressed in our kitchen, with or without
the camera,'' Pirkko says.
</P>
<P>
   For computer whiz and fish tank enthusiast Jeffery Green of
Boston, the lure of combining the two technologies was
irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it would be neat to have people be able to look
at my fish,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Green's Reef Cam included ``the robot cam,'' which
allowed people to move the camera left and right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also had a camera that was actually in the tank, the sub
cam,'' Green wrote via e-mail. ``My friends have always thought it
was kind of cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Web cam owners run the demographic gamut, from middle-age
Japanese women to young urban American couples to Western ranchers,
though probably the largest number are young, Anglo males.
</P>
<P>
   Many owners tout the lack of purpose behind their Web cams,
calling them useless, goofy and pointless.
</P>
<P>
   But some others have specific objectives, such as the site
posted by 18-year-old Travis Kroh, who attends MacArthur High in
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I originally just wanted to keep in touch with my friends
after I moved (from Wahpeton, N.D.), but I get e-mail from all over
the place.''
</P>
<P>
   A common refrain from Web cam owners is that this technology
allows them to go where no one has been before.
</P>
<P>
   One such pioneering site is the one run by van Es in the
Netherlands. Van Es has several devices wired into the gamepad port
on his computer, including his doorbell, his refrigerator and his
phone. Even his trash can, bathroom and cat's eating area are wired
in, though not all areas have Web cams.
</P>
<P>
   If you take a look at his site, you can see images of anyone who
has rung his doorbell or opened his refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   You can see the numbers of anyone who phones his house or a
photo of his cat each time she eats. A bar scanner tracks anything
he throws in his trash.
</P>
<P>
   Van Es is serious about the electronic fishbowl technology he is
developing and hopes to market it. ``This is the future,'' he
declares on his Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Another person who is serious about making Web cams useful is
Steve Lacy of Tucson. Lacy has developed and is beginning to market
a system using Web cams to allow parents to peek into their
children's day care center from work.
</P>
<P>
   Called Window2Care, the system would be installed without cost
to the day care center. Parents would pay an estimated $19.95 a
month for access to the Web site where the video is displayed.
</P>
<P>
   The system uses passwords to keep prying strangers from viewing
the children. Lacy initially plans to market the service in the
Tucson area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives parents peace of mind,'' he said. ``It adds
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents also feel a little bit guilty about leaving their kids
in day care. This gives them a chance to check in. If they can
watch them play, it gives them the feeling that they didn't leave
them all day. At the end of the day, they can say, `I saw you
playing with little Johnny.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fannon installs high-speed video conferencing equipment as
part of his job as network administrator for a small company with
offices in Tucson and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   He has a simpler Web cam in the computer room of his Chandler
home for friends and relatives to check in and see how he and his
family are doing.
</P>
<P>
   Watching video conferences connect far-flung offices at work
leads Fannon to believe that Web cams are more than a high-tech
toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get to the point where we all have cable modems or
something faster, this is going to be extremely valuable,'' he
said. ``We're talking about a Jetsons scenario.'' &QL; 
Jonathan Sidener can be reached at 444-8169 or at
jon.sidener(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
