<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SABERTOOTH-FOSSIL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSSILS FOUND IN FLORIDA REVEAL DIFFERENT KIND OF SABERTOOTH CAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Amateur fossil hunters stumbled upon a new kind of
sabertooth cat years ago while hunting for fossils of wild pigs in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, they didn't know what they had.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until recently that University of Kansas
paleontologist Larry Martin figured it out. What the amateurs had
found was a third category of sabertooth cat _ one that was the
``biggest, meanest in the world at that time,'' Martin said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a while to realize that this was a different kind
of cat,'' said Martin, curator of vertebrate paleontology at KU's
Museum of Natural History and one of the world's authorities on
sabertooth cats. ``I was shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   The find, detailed in the February issue of Discover magazine,
certainly is one of the most intriguing in decades, said
Christopher Shaw, collection manager for the George C. Page Museum
at the Rancho La Brea in Los Angeles. ``It's a very important
specimen,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Until the discovery, scientists thought there were two kinds of
sabertooths in North America _ dirk-tooth and scimitar-tooth.
Dirk-tooths, which include the genus Smilodon, had narrow upper
canine teeth that were up to 7 inches long. They had short legs and
were built like bears.
</P>
<P>
   Scimitar-tooths, which include the genus Homotherium, had
shorter, broader upper canines. They were long-legged and built
like cheetahs.
</P>
<P>
   The new sabertooth cat combines some of the deadliest features
of the others. It had two short, broad upper canines and short
legs. Its sabers cut parallel slits into its prey, and its serrated
incisors acted like a rotor, cutting a deep groove, allowing a big
strip of meat to roll out.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time it was living, this thing kicked Smilodon anywhere
it wanted to,'' Martin said. ``It's possible that Smilodon didn't
become dominant until the Florida cat became extinct, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin learned about the Florida discovery two years ago when
John Babiarz of Mesa, Ariz., invited him to look at his sabertooth
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Babiarz bought the Florida fossil from the amateurs who found
it. He didn't realize it was a new category of sabertooth; indeed,
it took Martin a while to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe the skeleton he had with it actually went
with the skull,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   When he realized they went together, he said, paleontologists
had to characterize a whole new group of sabertooth cats.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur hunters in north-central Florida found two complete
fossils of the new cat, which could be called ``xenosmilus.''
Martin said the fossils probably were found at least 10 years ago.
They were discovered at a site known as Hog Heaven because dozens
of fossils of wild hogs had been found there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of like a little cave,'' Martin said. ``It had
been occupied by these animals (sabertooths) sometime back in the
Ice Age about a million years ago.... This was probably a den and
the (sabertooths) were catching things and bringing them in, and
the main thing they brought in were some wild pigs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabertooths lived throughout the world. They inhabited North
America for more than 40 million years before becoming extinct
about 11,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Martin says he does not know how long the new variety of cat
lived. Since only two fossils have been found, he said, possibly it
was not around as long as the two other kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, the California expert, said he did not know whether the
Florida cat was the biggest, baddest cat around during its time.
Paleontologists need to look at more fossils to determine whether
that's true.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he had seen a cast of the Florida cat but would like
to look at the fossil. Babiarz still has the fossil he bought; the
other one is in a museum in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   KU has a cast of the cat's skull and all its bones. KU
paleontologists plan to put them together for display.
</P>
</TEXT>
