<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS COMES IN FROM THE COLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Someone asked Bob Burns how he felt after he
strolled off the 18th green Saturday at Riviera Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruddy, cruddy,'' Burns replied.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting response, considering the former Cal State
Northridge All-American golfer had just shot a 69, his third
straight subpar round at the Nissan Open.
</P>
<P>
   Burns wasn't referring to his play, though. He's been bothered
all week by a cold that no amount of decongestants has helped,
especially after finishing his round Friday in the chilly evening
winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt worse than yesterday,'' Burns said, in between
sniffles.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the way Burns is playing, perhaps he should try and
stay stuffy. He is 8-under-par in his last 45 holes at Riviera, and
5-under for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   That's eight strokes off the lead, which is disastrous if your
name is Tiger Woods, but pretty respectable for Burns.
</P>
<P>
   When you are three years removed from losing your PGA Tour
exemption, eight strokes back sounds just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate being back out here because I was playing for
pennies and table scraps on the Nike Tour,'' Burns said. ``I worked
pretty hard to get back here.''
</P>
<P>
   The road back has been longer than Burns expected. After getting
booted off the tour in 1995, he missed earning his '96 tour card by
a single stroke during the PGA qualifying tournament.
</P>
<P>
   So he joined the Nike Tour and struggled to make $31,353 in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty tough,'' Burns said. ``I wrote that year off a
while ago. (But) it's an important part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns took 1997 off to regroup, and rebounded by being the No.1
player on the Nike Tour in 1998 with two tournament victories and
$178,664 in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case it seemed like a fluke, Burns has made $37,800 in
four tournaments this year, and should have another decent payday
at Riviera this weekend. At this pace, he should be able to keep
his PGA card for next season.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns said he doesn't let his precarious status on the tour
affect his play, nor does he worry about losing his exemption
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel scared to tee it up. I come out to play,'' Burns
said. ``I've been out here before.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what Burns shoots today, this Nissan Open already
became special Friday, when he hit a hole-in-one at the 155-yard
16th hole. For a moment at No.16 on Saturday, he thought he might
duplicate the feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 7-iron I hit went right at the hole,'' Burns said. ``I
thought, `Go ahead, two for two.'''
</P>
<P>
   Burns settled for a par. His 69 came with four birdies and two
bogeys, although it looked like he might do better after being
5-under on the front nine. Burns played the back nine even.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played pretty solidly Friday and today,'' Burns said. ``I
felt I shot the highest I could have shot. I just can't get my
putter to come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Burns is staying this weekend with his parents in
Granada Hills, he lives in Knoxville, Tenn., with his wife Hilary.
The slower pace is more to Burns' liking and in his spare time, he
helps his wife breed dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the wide open space. I wouldn't mind 100 acres
surrounded by forest with no people around,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he might be able to afford it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
