<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3245 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      02-20 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THINGS WERE: RELIVING FRAGMENTS OF ONE'S LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Sometimes the feeling of how things were comes back
with a force that nearly takes the breath.
</P>
<P>
   Out driving on some errand yesterday, I passed the sledding hill
where our daughters and their friends, when all of them were small,
used to spend snowy winter afternoons and evenings.
</P>
<P>
   We parents were there, too, huddled close to the barrels that
held the warming fires, and once in a great while sharing a ride to
the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   All those children are grown to men and women now, and we're
20-some years older. I've often passed along that street in the
intervening years, without ever being much affected by memories of
the times we had there.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday was different. Everything came back with a rush:
the bite of frosty air, the smell of burning wood, the excited
cries of those scores of young voices. And it was more than just
remembering. There was the sense, brief but very powerful, of
actually living in that time again.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone, I suppose, there must be places like that _ places
where, in a surprising instant, the past comes completely,
convincingly alive. And while it lasts, you are younger, and
everything around you is as it was.
</P>
<P>
   In an older neighborhood of the city is the street on which I
spent all but the first few of my boyhood years. The houses, mostly
modest bungalows, look a good deal more worn now. But otherwise the
street is little changed.
</P>
<P>
   Standing a bit down the hill from my own house, I am a boy
again, and with me _ all around me _ are the other boys of the
block. We're hurrying to finish some rowdy game, because the light
is going and any moment now our mothers will be appearing on the
porches to call us in for supper.
</P>
<P>
   Another such place for me is the press room of the newspaper, a
great sunken hall below the level of the street, full of enormous
machines.
</P>
<P>
   When the presses are running, there's a world of noise and
activity, and it's exciting then, as you'd expect. A few days after
I first came to work here, in my early 20s and just out of school,
I ventured down there at some off hour _ a Sunday morning, it must
have been.
</P>
<P>
   The place was utterly silent. Not another soul was there. And
yet there was a feeling of keen expectation, as if at any instant
those giant presses might roar to life and give even a beginner's
words the possibility of reaching hearts.
</P>
<P>
   I still go down there sometimes, when nobody's about, to feel
again exactly how it was to be just starting, and to be reminded of
what hope it was that bound me for a lifetime to this work.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from where we now live, only 20 blocks or so to the
south, is the first real house of our married life. Occasionally I
turn there, brake the car, and sit a moment, wrapped in the sense
of beginning.
</P>
<P>
   We are young, both of us. And the girls are in the nursery
upstairs. Parents are alive, and so are all the friends who made
those years so rich. I'm full of the elation of a grand adventure
only just started.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are other places in this world I care about,
some of them a lot. But none with quite the same power those have
to scroll the years backward and let me live fine moments another
time.
</P>
<P>
   One can spend all or nearly all one's years in a single place,
as I've chosen to do, and be thought provincial. Or, propelled by
accident, obligation, or restless ambition, one can be endlessly
starting over among strangers.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that either way is necessarily better than the other.
But how is it possible to travel so fast, so far, without leaving
those earlier pieces of yourself irretrievably behind?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
