<DOCNO> NYT19990220.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-20 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3256 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PA-BLAST-NYT &LR;      02-20 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PA-BLAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENNSYLVANIA EXPLOSION KILLS FIVE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER TOWNSHIP, Pa. _ When he felt an explosion so big that it
shook pictures off his wall and shattered windows in neighboring
houses, Rich Wheeler thought a plane from a nearby airport had
crashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like someone just grabbed the building and shook it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the explosion Wheeler heard about 8:15 p.m. had destroyed a
chemical factory just across the road and up a small hill. Hours
later, rescue workers pulled five dead men from its remains, among
them a father and son.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the men who died worked at Concept Sciences Inc. They
were Anthony Mondello Sr., 55, of Pen Argyl, Pa.; his son Paul
Mondello, 25, of Easton; Paul Wanamaker, 43, of Northampton; and
Rubin Soto, 52, of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth man, Terry Bowers, 48, of Allentown, worked for a
different company in the same building.
</P>
<P>
   The four men, who were working the second shift of the day, were
pronounced dead at the scene. Six other workers were injured, two
critically, in the explosion, and two security officers and six
firefighters who reported to the scene were also injured.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities began investigating n Saturday the explosion at
Concept Sciences, which they said had begun operating in the
building only a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Mark Schweiker, who toured the site, said the ``working
theory'' was that there was an improper mixing of chemicals inside
the building. But Maj. Robert Werts of the Pennsylvania State
Police said, ``It could take days, weeks,'' to pinpoint the cause
of the blast. State and local investigators were scheduled to meet
with officials from the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The company manufactures hydroxylamine which can be used for
cleaning computer chips or etching integrated circuits. Officials
said about one hundred companies in the Lehigh Valley in Eastern
Pennsylvania work with the same chemical. There was no answer to
telephone calls to a nearby Concept Sciences office on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Much as they would do in a plane crash, investigators were
attempting to collect debris from the explosion, but their work was
being slowed because of the presence of potentially hazardous
chemicals. Workers wore protective clothing and had to pass through
several decontamination processes after leaving the factory, which
officials referred to as a ``hot zone.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, hundreds of fire and rescue workers arrived at
the scene of the explosion. But first they had to make sure the
building was structurally safe and test for hazardous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Thorough searching for victims did not begin until midnight,
Marko Bourne, a spokesman for the Pennsylvania Emergency Management
Agency, said Saturday, ``At 4 a.m., it was realized this was not a
rescue _ this was a recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Little remains of the building which sits in a hollow surrounded
by marsh, a highway, and other factories and warehouses. The walls
were blown outward and the roof collapsed. The building looked as
if the center was demolished. The steel framework was bent down and
inward. A 25-foot concrete wall had apparently crumbled in the
blast, leaving a crater four feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion shook houses as far as 13 miles away and sent a
large cloud over the area, local residents said.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler, who lives across the street from the factory said his
well water was so cloudy that it looked ``like someone had put
Alka-Seltzer in it.'' He and a neighbor were drinking bottled
water, he said adding, ``That's what we're worried about _ what was
in there?''
</P>
<P>
   But Bourne said that workers had been taking air, water, and
ground samples and found no contamination.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least four growing industrial parks in the Lehigh
Valley's softly rolling hills, where former blue-collar towns,
farmland, suburbs and service industries coexist.
</P>
<P>
   This area was the home of Bethlehem Steel, but the steel
operation finally closed for good last year. Other major
manufacturers like Mack Trucks that once provided secure jobs and
decent pay checks have left or closed, too.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the laid-off workers from those jobs have been hired for
factory or service work in the industrial park, which helps pay at
least some of the bills. There have been other explosions at
chemical factories in this area, but none, the authorities said,
where they remember such a high toll in human life.
</P>
</TEXT>
